<body>
<h2 align=center><a name="News From October 2, 1996">News From October 2, 1996</a></h2>
<p><a href="#BUCKEYE FOREST COUNCIL ">BUCKEYE FOREST COUNCIL GATHERS SCORES OF WILDLANDS PROTECTORS</a></p>
<p><a href="#CITY OF CLEVELAND ANNOUNCES EXPANSION OF BIKEWAY">CITY OF CLEVELAND ANNOUNCES EXPANSION OF BIKEWAY</a></p>
<p><a href="#ISTEA UP FOR REAUTHORIZATION">ISTEA UP FOR REAUTHORIZATION</a></p>
<p><a href="#CITIZENS ASKED TO CONTRIBUTE">CITIZENS ASKED TO CONTRIBUTE FOR HIKE/BIKE PATH USE</a></p>
<p><a href="#GREENWAY PLAN SEEKS">GREENWAY PLAN SEEKS TO CONNECT WETLANDS IN SOUTHWEST OHIO</a></p>
<p><br>
<a name="BUCKEYE FOREST COUNCIL ">BUCKEYE FOREST COUNCIL </a>GATHERS SCORES OF WILDLANDS PROTECTORS<br>
On September 27-29, on a weekend that promised and produced abundant<br>
rain, over 100 people gathered at Heuston Woods State Park to set the agenda<br>
for rewilding the Western Allegheny Plateau in Ohio. The Buckeye Forest<br>
Council, an organization primarily composed of people under 30 years old, has<br>
called for the protection and restoration of 950,000 acres in the region.<br>
Rivers Unlimited Greenways Coordinator Elaine Marsh made the greenway<br>
connection with wildlands at an energetic workshop. For more information<br>
about the Ohio Wildlands Project, contact BFC at 614/594-6400 or<br>
buckeye@envirolink.org.<br></p>
<p><a href="#News From October 2, 1996" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a><br>
<br>
<a name="CITY OF CLEVELAND ANNOUNCES EXPANSION OF BIKEWAY">CITY OF CLEVELAND ANNOUNCES EXPANSION OF BIKEWAY</a><br>
<br>
After many years of planning and talking, the first phases of a<br>
greenbelt and bikeway that will eventually connect the east side of Cleveland<br>
and its suburbs to the downtown. The plan, which includes a bikepath along<br>
the Cleveland section of Lake Erie, finally got funding for the section that<br>
connects the Inner Harbor with University Circle.<br>
<br>
Running along Martin Luther King Blvd. and North Marginal Rd., the route<br>
will be used both by commuters and recreationists alike. Over 2 million<br>
people every year are expected to use the path. Nearly twenty years in the<br>
making, local cyclists point to momentum created by the opening of the Rock<br>
and Roll Hall of Fame.<br>
<br>
<a href="#News From October 2, 1996" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><br>
<a name="ISTEA UP FOR REAUTHORIZATION">ISTEA UP FOR REAUTHORIZATION</a><br>
<br>
The federal high way program (ISTEA) that has spurred the creation of so<br>
many bike paths in the state will go through its last funding schedule this<br>
year. At that point, the moneys will need to be reauthorized in the next<br>
transportation budget. The &quot;enhancement&quot; portion of that funding is under<br>
siege from the state transportation departments who view these projects as<br>
&quot;frivolous.&quot;<br>
<br>
The battle to renew this funding will need all the hikers and bikers it<br>
can muster. Rivers<br>
Unlimited and its greenway enthusiasts have joined the defense. Recently the<br>
organization<br>
participated in a focus group of pro-ISTEA Ohioans sponsored by the Federal<br>
Highway<br>
Administration.<br>
<br>
<a href="#News From October 2, 1996" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><br>
<a name="CITIZENS ASKED TO CONTRIBUTE">CITIZENS ASKED TO CONTRIBUTE</a> FOR HIKE/BIKE PATH USE<br>
<br>
Beginning in October, the 200,000 people who use the Towpath in the<br>
Cuyahoga Valley<br>
National Recreation Area in Northeast Ohio will be asked to make an annual<br>
contribution of $5 to support the maintenance of the 20-mile trail. An<br>
informal survey of users indicated that most people would be willing to<br>
contribute and that most considered it a bargain (at the cost of one ticket<br>
to one showing in a stuffy movie theater to watch imitation life, &quot;bargain&quot;<br>
is an understatement).<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="GREENWAY PLAN SEEKS">GREENWAY PLAN SEEKS</a> TO CONNECT WETLANDS IN SOUTHWEST OHIO<br>
The B-W Greenway Community in the Dayton area is looking for help in<br>
launching their concept of connecting wetlands in adjacent watersheds. This<br>
process promotes Rivers Unlimited's concept of greenways, which says that<br>
habitat and watershed protection benefit from green connecting corridors.<br>
For more information, contact Bob Jurick at 513/878-6060 or<br>
bjurick@worldnet.att.net<br>
<br>
<a href="#News From October 2, 1996" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><br>
The CANOE system is a project of Rivers Unlimited, made possible by generous<br>
funding from the Hastings Foundation and Recreational Equipment, Inc. (REI).<br>
Feel free to contact us:<br>
<br>
1207 Grandview Ave., Suite 205<br>
