<h3><strong>NEWS FROM SEPTEMBER 18,1996</strong></h3>
<p><a href="#COALITION">COALITION</a> OF HUNTERS, ANGLERS AND ENVIRONMENTALISTS MEETS AGAIN	</p>
<p><a href="#OHIO TAKINGS BILL ">OHIO TAKINGS BILL </a>PASSES SENATE COMMITTEE</p>
<p><a href="#OHIO WETLANDS ASSISTANCE REGISTRY">OHIO WETLANDS </a>ASSISTANCE REGISTRY</p>
<p><a href="#RIVERS UNLIMITED HOSTS ANNUAL DINNER ">RIVERS UNLIMITED HOSTS ANNUAL DINNER</a> OCTOBER 5<br>
</p>
<p><a name="COALITION">COALITION</a> OF HUNTERS, ANGLERS AND ENVIRONMENTALISTS MEETS AGAIN	<br>
<br>
Taken as a group, anglers, environmentalists, hunters and conservationists<br>
comprise amajority of the adult population in this country. Unfortunately,<br>
the groups that represent these constituencies rarely work together on issues<br>
of mutual concern. Thanks to the leadership of the Ohio BASS Federation,<br>
that may be changing. Tonight in Columbus the Ohio Natural Resources<br>
Coalition (ONRC) will hold its third meeting of 1996. This meeting is being<br>
organized by Rivers Unlimited. The coalition was formed to create a forum<br>
for a broad cross section of environmental, conservation, angler and hunting<br>
groups. Topics of interest are discussed and letters of support are<br>
circulated when appropriate. Over thirty organizations belong to ONRC.<br>
Tonight's meeting will feature a presentation by State Representative Bill<br>
Schuck regarding his environmental bond initiative and a discussion with the<br>
Wildlife Legislative Fund concerning their efforts to create a<br>
Wildlife Commission in Ohio. For more information contact Rivers Unlimited.<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="OHIO TAKINGS BILL ">OHIO TAKINGS BILL </a>PASSES SENATE COMMITTEE<br>
<br>
Despite significant opposition from environmental, historic preservation,<br>
local government, planning and other groups, the Ohio Senate, State and Local<br>
Government and Veterans Affairs Committee passed Substitute House Bill 533 by<br>
a vote of 7-1 on September 11. Senator Janet Howard of Cincinnati was the<br>
lone no vote. The bill was further amended from the House passed version to<br>
somewhat minimize the impact of the legislation.<br>
<br>
Proponents call the bill a &quot;Private Property Protection Act.&quot; Opponents<br>
however, including Rivers Unlimited, have noted that the bill is a solution<br>
desperately seeking a problem. The legislation does little to protect the<br>
rights of property owners in Ohio and places a chilling effect on local<br>
government efforts to pass new laws protecting health, safety and the<br>
environment. Opponents have also pointed out that property owners with<br>
legitimate takings claims already have the right to pursue their claims in<br>
court.<br>
<br>
The bill will most likely be considered by the full Senate when it meets<br>
again in December. If it passes the Senate, it will still have to be<br>
reconciled with the House-passed version by a conference committee before<br>
being voted on again by the House and Senate.<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="OHIO WETLANDS ASSISTANCE REGISTRY">OHIO WETLANDS ASSISTANCE REGISTRY</a><br>
<br>
The Great Lakes Regional Office of the National Audubon Society is<br>
initiating a registry of Ohioans with knowledge in one or more aspects of<br>
wetland ecology, natural history, policy or related fields. The Registry<br>
will be used to link community and non-profit groups in need of assistance<br>
with those that have the skills they need.<br>
<br>
Both professionals and amateurs with experience in specific aspects of<br>
wetlands are encouraged to enroll in the registry. All assistance will be<br>
made on a voluntary basis. There is no minimum time committment and registry<br>
members are free to respond to requests for assistance as their schedule<br>
permits. Please contact Julie Sibbing at (614) 224-3303 for a sign-up form<br>
or you may e-mail her at jsibbing@audubon.org<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="RIVERS UNLIMITED HOSTS ANNUAL DINNER ">RIVERS UNLIMITED HOSTS ANNUAL DINNER </a>OCTOBER 5<br>
<br>
Join river advocates from across the state at the Rivers Unlimited Annual<br>
Dinner and Auction on Saturday, October 5. Txe event, which will be held<br>
from 6 - 10 p.m. at the Fawcett Center at Ohio State University, will feature<br>
internationally renowned author Tim Palmer. Mr. Palmer has written several<br>
books about the importance of river protection and has been to hundreds of<br>
rivers and streams in this country. In addition, dinner guests will have the<br>
chance to bid on many great auction items including canoe equipment,<br>
whitewater rafting trips, bed and breakfasts, jewelry, vintage wine and more.<br>
Don't miss this fun-filled and informative event. If youwould like an<br>
invitation simply call Rivers Unlimited at (614) 487-7511 or e-mail us at<br>
riveruoh@aol.com.<br>
<br>
The CANOE system is a project of Rivers Unlimited, made possible by funding<br>
from The Storer Foundation and Recreational Equipment, Inc. (REI) Feel free<br>
to contact us:<br>
<br>
1207 Grandview Ave., Suite 205<br>
Columbus, OH 43212-3449<br>
(614) 487-7511<br>
(614) 487-7513 (fax)<br>
</p>
