<h2 align=center>CITIZEN ACTIVIST NETWORK FOR THE OHIO 
ENVIRONMENT -- <a name="CANOE">CANOE</a> </h2>
<h3 align=center>News From Dec. 12, 1996</h3>
<p align=left><a href="#TWINSBURG CITY COUNCIL">Twinsburg City Council Opposes Plan to Move Tinker's Creek</a></p>
<p align=left><a href="#GOVERNOR SIGNS POLLUTER'S PROTECTION ACT">Governor Signs Polluter's Protection Act</a></p>
<p align=left><a href="#STATE TAKES ACTION TO REMOVE DAM ON LITTLE MIAMI RIVER ">State Takes Action to Remove Dam on Little Miami River</a></p>
<p align=left><a href="#SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME TIME ">Save Money and Support RU at the Same Time</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="TWINSBURG CITY COUNCIL">TWINSBURG CITY COUNCIL</a> OPPOSES PLAN TO MOVE 
TINKER'S CREEK </h3>
<p>The Twinsburg City Council has joined the ever growing chorus of opponents to a proposal to 
move a portion of Tinker's Creek. On November 26, the Council unanimously passed a resolution 
in support of the appeal filed by Rivers Unlimited and the Active Citizens of Twinsburg. The 
appeal, which will be heard at the Environmental Board of Review next Wednesday, seeks to 
overturn the decision of Ohio EPA Director Donald Schregardus. The Ohio EPA director put 
parking lots ahead of people when he approved a proposal by the Whitlatch company to move 
1000 feet of Tinker's Creek so that the company could build a parking lot for a strip mall. </p>
<p>&quot;We are delighted that the city of Twinsburg is supporting our effort to protect this creek,&quot; stated 
Todd Ambs, executive director of Rivers Unlimited. &quot;We believe this is a devastating precedent for 
the 61,000 miles of rivers and streams in Ohio. As far as we know, no where else in the country 
are proposals being seriously considered, let alone approved, to move creeks solely for the benefit 
of a single company.&quot; </p>
<p>When this application was approved, the Ohio EPA said this would not be a precedent for future 
projects. Within three weeks of the decision, Martin Marietta Materials filed a 404 permit with the 
U. S. Army Corps of Engineers to move 1200 feet of Indian Creek, at the confluence with the 
Great Miami River, so that they can expand their gravel mining operation. </p>
<p>The hearing on the Tinker's Creek case will be held at 10:30 a.m. on Wednesday, December 18 at 
the Environmental Board of Review, located at 236 E. Town Street in Columbus. </p>
<h5><a href="#CANOE">Return to top of page</a></h5>
<h3><a name="GOVERNOR SIGNS POLLUTER'S PROTECTION ACT">GOVERNOR SIGNS POLLUTER'S PROTECTION ACT</a> </h3>
<p>Governor George Voinovich today signed the environmental audit privilege bill, better known as the 
Polluter's Protection Act. The bill was vigorously opposed by Rivers Unlimited, a host of other 
environmental and conservation groups, the U. S. EPA and the Ohio Prosecuting Attorney's 
Association. This secrecy measure will now allow companies to conduct voluntary audits of their 
facilities and shield what they find behind a cloak of immunity from civil prosecution. In addition all 
violations, including criminal violations, can be labeled privileged information and kept from 
regulators and the public. This bill is sure to be a green light for unscrupulous companies that want 
to hide their environmental misdeeds behind a wall of immunity provisions, courtesy of the Ohio 
General Assembly and our environmental Governor. The bill passed 62-29 in the House and 
passed on party lines in the Senate with all Democrats opposing the bill. </p>
<h5><a href="#CANOE">Return to top of page</a></h5>
<h3 align=center><a name="STATE TAKES ACTION TO REMOVE DAM ON LITTLE MIAMI RIVER ">STATE TAKES ACTION TO REMOVE DAM ON LITTLE MIAMI 
RIVER </a></h3>
<p>Unfortunately for the rivers of Ohio, actions taken by state government these days usually adversely 
impact a waterway (see story on Tinker's Creek above). So it is especially nice to see the ODNR's 
Division of Natural Areas and Preserves (DNAP) recent application to the U. S. Army Corps of 
Engineers. DNAP is seeking permission to remove a low head dam on the Little Miami River in 
Greene County. The Little Miami is a state and national scenic river and is truly one of the gems of 
Ohio's waterways. Removing the low head dam will return this portion of the Little Miami to a free 
flowing river. </p>
<p>There are many obsolete and unnecessary low head dams in Ohio. They are dangerous, many 
people drowned in the undertow each year, the dams are expensive to maintain and they harm the 
aquatic ecosystem in that section of a waterway. </p>
<p>Rivers Unlimited will file comments in support of DNAP's application to help the Little Miami 
River. </p>
<h5><a href="#CANOE">Return to top of page</a></h5>
<h3 align=center><a name="SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME TIME ">SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME 
TIME </a></h3>
