<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Affinity - Air Quality</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Action Needed to Ensure Strong
Air Quality Standards</font></h2>

<p><font size="2">The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)
revised the National Ambient Air Quality Standards for ozone and
particulates on November 29th. Revision of these standards is one
of the most important public health decisions the EPA will make
this decade. Now is the time to voice public support for
standards that best protect public health and air quality.
Citizens need to weigh in to counteract the enormous political
pressure against tighter standards coming from Capitol Hill, many
Governors, and a well-financed industry coalition led by the
National Association of Manufacturers.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Both ozone and particulates result from burning
fossil fuels in our cars and power plants. The proposed new
particulate standard has resulted from scientific evidence that
particulate matter (airborne microscopic particles that enter our
lungs) is a serious health hazard, particularly to those most
vulnerable: the elderly, children, and individuals suffering from
respiratory ailments. Scientists say particle pollution can
reduce life expectancy by one or two years in cities with serious
pollution problems and particulate pollution is blamed for about
65,000 premature deaths each year in the U.S.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The current standard controls for particulate
matter of a certain size (10 microns); because recent studies
show this standard to be inadequate, the proposed standard will
cover much smaller particles (2.5 microns). In addition, how EPA
resolves issues such as time frame, short-term peak
concentrations, and ways of determining exceedances of the
standard can either strengthen or weaken protection. Therefore,
it is important to urge EPA to maintain the integrity of the
proposed new particulate standard.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Scientists and public health officials have
also documented the serious impacts that result from increased
ozone pollution. Ozone, the main component of smog, is a powerful
lung irritant; it causes breathing problems, reduces lung
function, aggravates asthma, and increases the severity and
incidence of respiratory infections. In addition to impacting
public health, ground level ozone also is a climate change gas
and contributes to global warming.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Again, how the standard is measured is
important. We are urging EPA to maintain the current one-hour
standard of 124 parts per billion which protects against
short-term pollution spikes. We also support the most protective
eight-hour standard under consideration (70 ppb). Not
surprisingly, business and industry are pulling out all the stops
to fight stricter standards, claiming that the costs outweigh the
benefits.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">At least $1.5 million has been spent to date by
the Business Coalition whose members include the American
Petroleum Institute, Dupont, General Electric, and the American
Automobile Manufacturers Association. The Coalition has organized
opposition to the revised standards, sending letters to the
President, lobbying the Departments of Defense, Energy,
Agriculture, Treasury and Transportation, generating letters from
15 Governors, and orchestrating a major press campaign.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">We must counter this highly organized and
well-financed attack in order to prevent public health and clean
air from being compromised. Even after the formal EPA
announcement, there will be a public comment period and your
voice will provide much needed balance in the debate.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">WHAT YOU CAN DO! Write, fax, or e-mail via EPA
website: Administrator Carol Browner, Environmental Protection
Agency, 401 M Street, SW, Washington, D.C. 20460; fax
202-260-0279. Also, please send a copy of the letter to Mary
Nichols, Assistant Administrator for Air and Radiation to the
same address as above. We do not yet have a direct e-mail address
for Administrator Browner, but you can send e-mail to her through
the EPA website at http://www.epa.gov</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Express your support for stricter standards for
particulates and ozone. Urge Administrator Browner to make a
decision based on overwhelming scientific evidence and maintain
the integrity of the new standards to afford maximum protection
to the public¹s health and air quality.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">For more information contact Michelle Robinson
at UCS, 2 Brattle Square, Cambridge, MA 02238 or
mrobinson@ucsusa.org.</font></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

