<body>
<h3 align=center><strong>GREENLines, </strong></h3>
<h3>From <a name="GREEN"><strong>GREEN</strong></a>, the Grassroots Environmental Effectiveness Network, </h3>
<p>A project of Defenders of Wildlife. (202)789-2844x288 or email <a href="mailto:rfeather@clark.net">rfeather@clark.net</a></p>
<p><strong>Articles: </strong><a href="#THOMAS ON SPECIES"><strong>Thomas On Species</strong></a><strong> | </strong><a href="#BOG COURT CASE &quot;BOGGED DOWN&quot;"><strong>Bog Court Case &quot;Bogged Down&quot;</strong></a><strong> | </strong><a href="#CAVIAR HIGH"><strong>Caviar High</strong></a><strong> | 
</strong><a href="#REEFOLUTION"><strong>Reefolution</strong></a></p>
<p><a name="THOMAS ON SPECIES"><strong>THOMAS ON SPECIES</strong></a><strong>:</strong></p>
<p>US Forest Service Chief, Jack Ward Thomas said earlier this week that the ESA should be 
changed to emphasize ecosystem management instead of single-species protection. Greenwire 
reports from an Albuquerque Journal article that Thomas was speaking at a forester's conference in 
Albuquerque, NM. Thomas also said that he regrets the amount of micromanagement that came 
from Washington during his years as Forest Service Chief. &quot;I kept trying to push money and 
authority out, but the pressures in Washington are.[saying] `We want you to control that money. 
We want you to control those decisions.'&quot;</p>
<p><a href="#GREEN">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a name="BOG COURT CASE &quot;BOGGED DOWN&quot;"><strong>BOG COURT CASE &quot;BOGGED DOWN&quot;</strong></a><strong>: </strong></p>
<p>A $200-300 million &quot;takings&quot; lawsuit by the Michigan Peat Company is on hold while MI 
Department of Environmental Quality officials negotiate with the Houston based mining company. 
Michigan Peat is mining the Minden Bog, the last true raised bog in Michigan. The state had 
allowed the mining company to continue mining already disturbed land but would not permit mining 
of the natural part of the bog says Watershed News, the Journal of Defenders of the Great Lakes. 
Fred Fuller, Mayor of the City of Yale says, &quot;What we fear is the Engler administration [Michigan's 
governor] will negotiate away more of the irreplaceable natural bog. This will be a real test of 
whether our wetlands laws mean anything.&quot; Fuller urges supporters of the Minden Bog to contact 
their legislators, the DEQ and the Governor Engler.&quot; For information call (313)389-0029.</p>
<p><a href="#GREEN">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a name="CAVIAR HIGH"><strong>CAVIAR HIGH</strong></a><strong>:</strong></p>
<p>The Boston Globe reports that consumers will be paying much more for their Christmas caviar due 
to overfishing of Caspian Sea sturgeon. The number of adult sturgeon on the Caspian Sea is 
estimated to have dropped from 142 million in 1978 to 43.5 million in 1994. A report written by 
Andrea Gaski, of the World Wildlife Fund, says that &quot;with significant illegal trade, little regulation, 
tremendous profits and increasing demand, sturgeon species are perched precariously on the edge 
of extinction.&quot; Gaski says aggressive fishing by Russian and Iranian trawlers kills all sturgeon, not 
just the egg-bearing females.</p>
<p><a href="#GREEN">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a name="REEFOLUTION"><strong>REEFOLUTION</strong></a><strong>:</strong></p>
<p>An article in the <u>Christian Science Monitor</u> reports that attempts to repair the country's only living 
barrier coral reef are working. Two ships grounded in 1989 severely damaged more than 3,000 
meters of the fragile reef. The groundings prompted Congress to create the Florida Keys National 
Marine Sanctuary and to expand the buffer zone prohibited to ships. The shipping companies 
agreed to pay for reef restoration efforts in an out of court settlement. Bill Causey, superintendent 
of the Marine Sanctuary says, &quot;We are undoing something devastating that humans have done. I 
don't feel we are replacing Mother Nature.&quot;</p>
<p><a href="#GREEN">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
