<TITLE>7/30/96</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>7/30/96</P>
<CENTER>
<P><BR>
 CITIZEN ACTIVIST NETWORK FOR THE OHIO
ENVIRONMENT -- CANOE</P>
<P> BACK ROOM ATTACKS AGAINST WATER QUALITY</P>
</CENTER>
<P ALIGN="LEFT">River advocates across Ohio are anxiously
awaiting a decision by the Franklin County Common Pleas Court
that could protect 96 percent of the state's waterways from
additional pollution discharges. On or about August 1st,
Judge Beverly Pfiefer will render a long-awaited decision on
the validity of the antidegradation rules, a statute slipped
into the massive 1,300-page 1993 budget bill. The new law was
passed without the benefit of legislative hearings or public
review. Most legislators who voted for the budget bill were
unaware they had just approved rules that allow more
pollution into Ohio's waterways.</P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"> <BR>
</P>
<CENTER>
<P>HOW THE RULE WOULD WORK</P>
</CENTER>
<P><BR>
The antidegradation rules were drafted by
the Ohio EPA with the help of wastewater treatment plant
operators and representatives of privately owned electric
power companies, developers and manufacturers. The rules will
reclassify all 61,000 miles of Ohio waterways into five
categories. The top four categories of waterways receive a
variety of protections. In fact, those waterways classified
as &quot;Outstanding National Resource Waters&quot; could
actually benefit from the new rules. However, the fifth
category, &quot;General High Quality Waters,&quot; would
suffer the most if this ruling goes into effect. Rivers
Unlimited has calculated that 97.6 percent of Ohio's rivers
and streams are presently classified as &quot;General High
Quality Waters&quot;-- a figure the Ohio EPA does not
dispute.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<CENTER>
<P>BATTLE TO STOP THIS LAW</P>
<P> </P>
</CENTER>
<P>This winter Rivers Unlimited organized a broad
alliance of environmental, conservation, and recreation
organizations that worked to prevent the rules from being
approved. The alliance, called Citizens for Clean Water in
Ohio, represented nearly one million Ohioans, the largest
cross-section of people ever assembled to fight for clean
water in Ohio. On February 20, 1996 representatives from the
coalition testified for over four hours before the Joint
Committee on Agency Rule Review (JCARR). After four hours of
testimony against the rules, the vote by JCARR members to
overturn the rules failed on a 4-4 vote. </P>
<P>This unprecedented assault on water quality is now being
fought in the courts. Rivers Unlimited, with the help of nine
organizations, has led the legal battle to throw out the
antidegradation statute. The lawsuit charges that the
anti-degradation statute does not comply with the federal
Clean Water Act and that it was passed in violation of the
single-subject rule of the Ohio Constitution.</P>
<P>Keep your fingers crossed and we will update you on the
decision.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><BR>
 The CANOE system is a project of Rivers
Unlimited, made possible by the generous funding from the
Hastings Foundation and Recreational Equipment, Inc. (REI).
Feel free to contact us:</P>
<P>3953 Indianola Avenue</P>
<P>Columbus, OH 43214-3153</P>
<P>(614) 262-3764</P>
