<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Affinity - Bad Meat</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Meat Monoopolies &amp; the
False Promise of Irradiation</font></h2>

<h5><font size="2">Excerpted from &quot;Meat Monopolies: Dirty
Meat and the False Promises of Irradiation,&quot; a report
written by Susan Meeker-Lowry and Jennifer Ferrara</font></h5>

<p><font size="2">Since four children died after eating E. Coli
contaminated hamburgers at a fast food restaurant in 1993,
citizens have been calling on the federal government and the meat
industry to clean up their acts and provide safe meat products.
In an effort to put the public at ease, President Clinton
approved new meat inspection laws this summer, promising stronger
safeguards against contamination. But corporate monopolies
continue to churn out most of this country&#146;s meat supply on
overcrowded farms and in unsanitary processing plants without
regard to public and environmental health, and the new laws do
nothing to stop bacterial contamination at the root of the
problem.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">This country&#146;s large farming and meat
processing operations are breeding grounds for contamination and
disease. Cattle are confined in pens, open and unprotected from
weather, in groups of 100 to 500. Poultry are raised in total
confinement in large floor-pens which hold 10,000 to 20,000
chickens. At the slaughterhouse, animal carcasses are exposed to
hides, feathers, trimming and cleaning equipment, floors, and
buildings contaminated with bacteria-ridden feces and contents of
intestines. At cattle plants, carcasses are inspected for
contamination at an average rate of 360 per hour, not leaving
time for thorough inspections. Poultry processing plants chill
chicken carcasses after slaughter by dipping them in a tank of
cold water. The water in these chill tanks is called &quot;fecal
soup&quot; by some federal inspectors who say that their use is a
primary cause of the high rate of salmonella on chicken
carcasses.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Just three companies control almost 80 percent
of today&#146;s U.S. beef production. Four companies dominate 44
percent of broiler production, and four produce 35 percent of the
nation&#146;s turkeys. While the top meat companies make billions
of dollars yearly, 500 people die and at least 20,000 fall ill as
a result of E. coli contamination. Salmonella causes almost two
million cases of illness and up to 2,000 deaths each year. Time
and again, the meat industry has denied responsibility for the
chronic contamination of the meat supply, calling it a
&quot;natural&quot; occurrence that can best be eradicated in
consumers&#146; kitchens.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">This irresponsible stance leaves doors wide
open for promotion of irradiation, a controversial food
processing technology that exposes food to an equivalent of 30
million chest x-rays, to come along and claim a silver bullet
solution to a deadly problem. The U.S. Food &amp; Drug
Administration (FDA) has already approved irradiation for
poultry, pork, fruits, vegetables, and spices and is close to
giving its approval for red meat. Irradiation does kill
pathogens, but the dangers of the technology far outweigh any
possible benefits.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Food is irradiated with radioactive gamma
sources that break up the molecular structure of the food,
forming free radicals. These free radicals react with the food to
create new chemical substances called radiolytic products, some
of which are known carcinogens (like benzene in irradiated beef).
Others are completely unique to the radiation process and their
effect on human health is unknown. Exposing food to radiation
also causes essential vitamin and nutrient loss, and the process
kills beneficial bacteria that warn citizens when meat has gone
bad. The safety of a long term diet of irradiated foods has never
been proven. In fact, Dr. Marcia Van Gemert, the chair of the FDA
committee that investigated 441 studies on food irradiation
before the approval of the process for some foods in 1982,
testified in 1993 that all 441 studies were flawed.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Irradiation proponents advertise the technology
as the food processing and retail industries&#146; dream solution
to meat contamination, and are hoping to use the coming FDA beef
approval to convince other sectors of the food industry to adopt
irradiation. But citizens have long rejected food irradiation due
to the environmental and health hazards it poses. Because of
strong consumer opposition, no major supermarket will sell
irradiated foods and the country&#146;s top poultry companies
will not use the technology.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Dirty meat will remain a problem, and
irradiation a looming threat, as long as huge corporations that
value profit over health maintain monopolies over meat
production. The new federal meat regulations, the product of
years of compromise between government and industry, only
solidify this monopoly. They allow corporations to perform their
own microbial inspections. Companies&#146; safety records are
considered &quot;trade secrets&quot; and are not subject to
public disclosure. Furthermore, the goal of these laws is not to
eliminate dangerous bacteria, but to keep contamination from
exceeding current average levels. For poultry, that&#146;s one in
five chickens and one in two turkeys contaminated with
salmonella.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The new meat laws and other solutions to the
contamination problem proposed by industry and government
don&#146;t go far enough to address the root causes of meat
contamination. Unsafe meat is only one among many problems caused
by centralized agribusiness. Only by restructuring the current
agricultural system, turning away from meat monopolies and
cleaning up meat production at the source, will the long-term
safety of the food supply be assured.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Excerpted from &quot;Meat Monopolies: Dirty
Meat and the False Promises of Irradiation,&quot; a report
written by Susan Meeker-Lowry and Jennifer Ferrara and published
by Food &amp; Water, Inc., a national non-profit grassroots
environmental and food safety organization. To obtain a copy of
this report or to join activist campaigns to stop food
irradiation, toxic pesticides, and food biotechnology, call Food
&amp; Water at (800) EAT-SAFE.</font></p>

<hr>

