<title>Canoe 111196</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>CITIZEN ACTIVIST NETWORK FOR THE OHIO ENVIRONMENT 
-- <a name="CANOE">CANOE</a></h3>
<p align=left><a href="#DECISION TO MOVE TINKER'S CREEK APPEALED">Decsion to Move Tinker's Creek Appealed</a> | <a href="#RU ASKS OHIO EPA TO ELIMINATE LIMITED RESOURCE WATERS">RU Asks Ohio EPA to Eliminate Limited Resource 
Waters </a>| <a href="#SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME TIME">Save Money and Support the Work of RU at the Same Time</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="DECISION TO MOVE TINKER'S CREEK APPEALED">DECISION TO MOVE TINKER'S CREEK APPEALED</a></h3>
<p>On October 30, 1996, Rivers Unlimited and the Active Citizens of Twinsburg appealed the Ohio 
EPA decision to allow a developer to move Tinker's Creek to the Environmental Board of Review 
(EBR). On September 30, The director of Ohio EPA, Donald Schregardus, had approved the 
controversial proposal to move this creek in Twinsburg so that the Whitlatch Company could build 
a parking lot for a strip mall.</p>
<p>&quot;We have appealed this decision because this case sets a very dangerous precedent for the 
waterways of Ohio,&quot; said RU executive director Todd Ambs. The director of Ohio EPA had the 
legal grounds to deny this permit. The person who developed the stream restoration technigue 
being used to move this creek says it was not intended for this purpose. As a result, we believe 
Tinker's Creek will be permanently degraded by this project.&quot; The EBR has scheduled a 
preliminary prehearing conference on the case on December 10 at 10:30 a.m. in Columbus. </p>
<h5><a href="#CANOE">Return</a></h5>
<h4 align=center><a name="RU ASKS OHIO EPA TO ELIMINATE LIMITED RESOURCE WATERS">RU ASKS OHIO EPA TO ELIMINATE LIMITED RESOURCE WATERS</a></h4>
<p>The Ohio EPA has begun a rulemaking process to update their regulations for surface water quality 
standards in Ohio. Rivers Unlimited filed its preliminary comments today. Ohio EPA plans to 
submit the final rules to The Joint Committee on Agency Rule Review (JCARR) on November 25. 
A public hearing will be scheduled after the first of the year and then the rules will go before 
JCARR sometime in January.</p>
<p>As part of this process, RU has asked Ohio EPA to eliminate its lowest surface water designation 
category, Limited Resource Waters. Waterways with this designation must meet minimal aquatic, 
human health and wildlife criteria. As a result, Limited Resource Waters are little more than open 
sewers. </p>
<p>A summary of the main comments filed with the agency today are listed below: The enclosed 
comments represent the views of Rivers Unlimited regarding the proposed new rulemaking for 
Ohio&#146;s surface water quality standards. The organization will also be presenting testimony at the 
public hearing and on the final rules before the Joint Committee on Agency Rule Review.</p>
<p>&#183; Rivers Unlimited firmly believes that the limited resource waters category should be eliminated. 
There is no requirement that these waters meet chronic aquatic criteria standards. In addition, the 
thresholds for attainment of acute aquatic, human health and wildlife criteria are so low as to make 
these waters little more than open sewers. We believe that limited resource waters are violative of 
the intent of the federal Clean Water Act which is intended to restore and maintain the chemical, 
physical and biological integrity of the nation's waters.</p>
<p>&#183; In general, Rivers Unlimited opposes any downgrades of stream segments to less stringent 
standards. Short of that, any downgrade should only be approved after point source dischargers 
have agreed to take specific steps that in the future would prevent pollution, reduce discharges and 
allow the stream segment to be redesignated at a higher, more protective level within a specified 
amount of time.</p>
<p>&#183; Downgrading stream segments is a self fulfilling prophecy that raises the level of pollutants that 
may be dumped into the receiving waters and triggers a downward spiral that can only result in a 
severely degraded waterway.</p>
<p>&#183; OhioEPA should incorporate the economic and environmental losses of consigning streams to 
greater pollution. When some 50% or more of Ohio's waters are not fishable and swimmable, and 
fishing expenditures in Ohio were $861 million in 1990, is Ohio's economy foregoing up to another 
$861 million because half its streams are too polluted? What other conclusion can one come to? 
Are sewage ratepayers and a few major industrial polluters actually saving that $861 million 
because lax laws and enforcement permit them to externalize their costs of manufacture and waste 
disposal? Downstream economic and environmental costs should be included in any 
decision-making process for use designations of Ohio&#146;s 61,000 miles of rivers and streams.</p>
<p>OhioEPA may indeed be acting in accord with the letter of the law, but certainly not in accord with 
the intent of the Clean Water Act, which says that any additional pollution permitted must be in the 
economic and social interest. True economic benefit/cost analysis has never been used by Ohio 
todetermine the public interest in having clean water in this state.</p>
<h5><a href="#CANOE">Return</a></h5>
<h4 align=center><a name="SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME TIME">SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME TIME</a></h4>
<p>People living in the Columbus area can order Entertainment '97 coupon books through Rivers 
Unlimited. Save up to 50% off dining, travel, shopping, theatre, sports events and more at 
thousands of locations throughout central Ohio. Each book costs only $35 and $7 of every sale 
goes to Rivers Unlimited to support our programs. Don't miss this opportunity to save lots of 
money and help Rivers Unlimited. Contact the RU office for more information.</p>
<p>The CANOE system is a project of Rivers Unlimited, made possible by generous funding from the 
Storer Foundation and Recreational Equipment, Inc. (REI).</p>
