<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>affinity - Meat Contamination</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2><font size="2">Corporate Monopolies and Meat Contamination</font></h2>

<p><font size="2">Food &amp; Water, Inc., a leading national
non-profit grassroots environmental and food safety organization,
released an expose of the highly consolidated U.S meat industry,
detailing the links between industry concentration and chronic
bacterial contamination of the meat supply that continues to
claim thousands of lives every year. In the 37-page illustrated
report, Meat monopolies: Dirty Meat and the False Promises of
Irradiation, Food &amp; Water also discredits proponents of
irradiation who claim that it presents a solution to meat
contamination. The U.S. Food &amp; Drug Administration is
expected to approve red meat irradiation within the next several
months.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">&quot;The chronic plague of microbial
contamination of the food supply is a symptom of the corporate
monopoly over meat production,&quot; reads the report.
&quot;Three companies control 80 percent of U.S. beef production.
Other sectors of the meat industry are also highly consolidated.
As long as such corporate monopolies have control over the U.S.
meat supply and government regulatory agencies, meat safety will
remain a serious public health concern in this country.&quot;</font></p>

<p><font size="2">&quot;Industrial meat production already
exposes citizens to severe and outrageous health risks like
deadly pathogens in meat and toxic pesticides in land and water,
an now the food irradiation industry is looking to make
factory-produced meat even more dangerous by exposing it to
radiation,&quot; said Michael Colby, Executive Director of Food
&amp; Water. &quot;Just as citizen pressure, not government
regulation, has kept the dangers of irradiation at bay for over a
decade, citizens must go directly to meat corporations to demand
a clean and safe meat supply while supporting the development of
safer, sustainable methods of producing meat. This report is an
educational tool for citizens who want to take a critical, active
role in making the food supply safe.&quot;</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The report also features sections on mad cow
disease, the effects of industrial agriculture on workers,
farmers, and the environment, government&#146;s failed attempts
to make the meat supply safe, background&nbsp;on food
irradiation, and the possibilities of regional food systems to
replace disease-ridden monopolies. If you are interested in
receiving a copy of this report, please contact Food &amp; Water
at RR1, Box 68D, Walden, Vermont 05873;(800) EAT-SAFE.</font></p>

