<head>
<title>PCB's Affinity 101196</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>Protect Our Children from PCB'S</h2>
<p>Sierra Club today called on Congress and our national, state and local leaders to protect our 
children from PCBs and other toxic chemicals. </p>
<p>Yesterday's report in the New England Journal of Medicine documents that polychlorinated 
biphenyls (PCBs), chemical pollutants found in our air and water, caused lower learning ability in 
children whose mothers ate PCB-laden fish from Lake Michigan. The children were exposed in 
utero and through their mothers' breast milk.</p>
<p>&quot;This report is heart-breaking,&quot; said Sierra Club Executive Director Carl Pope, &quot;and it is truly 
disgraceful that as we learn more and more about the human consequences of pollution, our 
Congress has been working as hard as it can to weaken the laws that protect our families from 
situations just like this one.&quot; </p>
<p>PCB production was banned in 1977, but according to the U.S. General Accounting Office, 
polluters dumped over 200 pounds of PCBs into the Great Lakes in 1991. That is enough PCBs to 
contaminate over 400 million pounds of fish. In fact, every major harbor in the United States has 
dangerous levels of PCBs or similar toxic chemicals.</p>
<p>&quot;This study is a clear example of the need to strengthen America's environmental safeguards, not 
weaken them, yet that is exactly what this Congress tried to do when it voted to approve HR 961 
'the Dirty Water Act,' and passed the EPA budget riders which would have prohibited the 
Environmental Protection Agency from implementing the Great Lakes Water Quality Initiative,&quot; said 
Brett Hulsey, Sierra Club Midwest Regional Representative and Great Lakes Program Director. </p>
<p>&quot;How many children's bright futures will be lost because of the greed and insensitivity of a Congress 
that responds to polluting industries instead of the American people?&quot; &quot;We call on Congress to stop 
these irresponsible attacks and to start protecting America's environment for our families, for our 
future,&quot; said Carl Pope. Ways to protect yourself from PCB exposure:</p>
<p>- Eat a low-fat diet, especially if you are a woman of child-bearing years. Cut out fat. Take the skin 
off fish and chicken, cut off fat from meat, and eat low-fat cheese and skim milk.</p>
<p>- Buy chlorine free paper and clothing because chlorine tends to lead to the formation of PCBs, 
dioxin and other dangerous pollutants.</p>
<p>- Check with your local community or utility to find out if there are any PCB contaminated 
transformers in your neighborhood, or toxic waste dumps w/PCBs. If there are, tell them to clean 
them up.</p>
<hr>
