<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Affinity - Cuyahoga River Watershed Planning</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Cuyahoga River Watershed
Planning</font></h2>

<h5 align="center"><font size="2">by Janine Rybka, Cuyahoga River
RAP</font></h5>

<p><font size="2">When local residents look into a valley and
wonder what lies on the bottom, when residents within a quarter
of a mile from the second highest waterfall in the county are not
aware of its existence, when local officials are not sure about
the streams that criss-cross their town, you can begin to imagine
how tough watershed planning can be. These are just a few factors
that illustrate the challenges presented to the development of
the Cuyahoga River Remedial Action Plan (RAP). The RAP is an
ecosystem-based plan aimed at restoring the beneficial uses of
the River and nearshore areas of Lake Erie that have been
adversely affected by pollution.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The RAP will address problems in the Cuyahoga
River Area of Concern (AOC). This area falls within the 45 mile
stretch of the River from Akron's Ohio Edison Dam on the south to
the River's mouth in Cleveland's Flats. The nearshore areas from
Edgewater to Euclid Creek are included in the AOC. This is the
most urbanized section of the river and historically the most
polluted. Development patterns are dense and there are large
areas of impervious surfaces that have changed the hydraulics of
local streams which feed into the River and Lake Erie. Poor land
utilization, especially along the stream banks, contributes to a
variety of problems such as erosion and loss of habitat. A
variety of discharges into the river from both point sources and
non-point sources also contribute to the degradation of the water
quality and habitat.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Finding ways to address pollution and
degradation issues has taken significant time and effort. One of
the most important efforts is continually connecting local
stakeholders to their watershed, since their connection leads to
their involvement. Public involvement is the cornerstone of this
community based plan. Continued public involvement will help
ensure the long range success of actions taken to correct the
worst problems affecting the River and Lake Erie.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Cuyahoga RAP planners are continually working
on many levels to develop strategies to correct the worst of the
problems that impact the Cuyahoga River. One strategy is the
Stream Stewardship Project which is intended to provide
opportunities for involvement from local stakeholders.
Stakeholders include everyone who lives and works within the
watershed. Stream stewardship involves getting people to take
responsibility for the streams in their community. Activities can
range from group projects to researching and lobbying for
protective ordinances. The RAP is using stream stewardship as a
means to propel stake holders into developing meaningful local
watershed management plans. These plans would focus the attention
and efforts of the local stakeholders on the stream in their own
backyards.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">According to the Center for Watershed
Protection, a local watershed plan can be the most comprehensive
tool for protection of urban streams. While there are few, if
any, truly successful models on which to draw, the Cuyahoga RAP
believes it has started to build a model that can be used in the
smaller watersheds around the Cuyahoga Basin.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Watershed planning efforts have begun with an
aggressive stream stewardship program in the Big Creek watershed.
The program has been a great example of community based planning.
Local citizens and officials have had the opportunity to learn of
the connection between Big Creek and the Cuyahoga River. Input
from these stake- holders has been useful in further defining
problems and listening to stakeholder's goals for their
watershed. It has also been combined with tools such as
geographic information systems (GIS) mapping, monitoring, and
modeling to offer more opportunities for involvement on all
levels. Volunteers continue to be involved on projects such as
storm drain stenciling, stream side clean ups, and stream bank
restoration which address some of the &quot;simpler&quot;
problems in the watershed. More importantly, these outreach
programs have helped to elevate Big Creek from its partially
invisible status.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">If indeed a local watershed management plan is
to be the best and most comprehensive tool to protect urban
streams, it will need the continued involvement from the stake
holders in the watershed. The Cuyahoga RAP believes a good plan
should focus on a local scale, with an ongoing commitment to
overseeing the plan and monitoring changes in the watershed. When
it comes to the basics of watershed planning, the lack of
excellent watershed plans provides the Cuyahoga RAP with a
challenge to develop the model that will make stream stewardship
a workable goal in each sub-watershed of the Cuyahoga River.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">For more information call Janine Rybka at (216)
443-3700, ext. 610.</font></p>

<hr>

