<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Affinity- Population: An Environmental issue?</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Population: An Environmental
issue?</font></h2>

<h5 align="center"><font size="2">by Alan Kuper</font></h5>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><font size="2">Long before the word &quot;environment&quot;
carried the meaning it does today the concerns of &quot;nature
lovers&quot; were primarily preservation of scenic values. Those
early outdoors people would probably be surprised at the range of
interests today&#146;s nature lovers pursue, particularly, that
some of them rank population among their top priorities. After
all, John Muir, naturalist and founder of the Sierra Club </font></p>

<p><font size="2">said, &quot;When we try to pick out anything by
itself, we find it hitched to everything else in the
Universe.&quot; And surely just about every &quot;environmental
problem&quot; is traceable to people and their consuming ways.
Muir, a keen observer of Nature, would probably have agreed with
the truism that, &quot;the biotic potential of a species exceeds
the carrying capacity of its habitat.&quot; Numerous examples of
overshoot of carrying capacity followed by population crash, like
harsh winter die-off of over-populated deer, were known to him.
One wonders whether he ever noted that the same law applied to
&quot;Lord Man,&quot; as he disparagingly called humans. He
surely knew that the rapidly rising population of Ireland crashed
to a fraction of its pre-1845 number during the Famine.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">There are those who advocate that the Sierra
Club return to little more than protecting and preserving public
lands, return to its roots. Sierra Club population activists
argue that the root cause of threats to our public lands, water
and air is the existence of so many people with their attendant
needs. We, population activists advocate policies that could
stabilize future population. You can&#146;t be more an
environmentalist than that. If you want to walk in the steps of
John Muir with us, call Alan Kuper, committee Chair, of the
Sierra Club Population-Environment Committee at 229-2413; fax
229-9431 or e-mail: AlanKuper@aol.com</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Footnote: Among the many things we publicize to
help people plan their lives and to help improve communities is
&quot;Emergency Contraception &#139; The Nation&#146;s Best Kept
Secret.&quot; You should have EC in your medicine cabinet. Call
(800) 584-9911 for the provider nearest you.</font></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

