<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Affinity -Letter to the Editor</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p><font size="2">Letter to the Editor</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Dear Affinity Personnel:</font></p>

<p><font size="2">I really enjoy your paper and the environmental
issues it explores. Per your request, I wrote a letter to Shell
Oil and got back the enclosed response. My questions to you are:</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Q: Is this just fancy PR; trying to get out of
moral responsibility?</font></p>

<p><font size="2">A: Absolutely. When you read their response
carefully you find many contradicitions. In their response they
mention their concern about many of the grievances felt by the
Nigerian communities effected by the production of oil by Shell.
Then later in the reponse they say &quot;The standard of living
of communities in the oil producing areas is still poor, even
after thirty years of production. Basic amenities are lacking and
opporutinities for employment are few.&quot; So why is it that
now, after 30 years, they are expressing their so called
&quot;concern?&quot; It is obvious that the hugh outcry by
citizens and environmental and human rights groups concerning the
execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight co-defendants have triggered
this response by Shell International Limited.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Q: Is this factual?</font></p>

<p><font size="2">A: I am sure some of what they say if factual.
But they reveal these facts without telling the whole story. They
never express the Ogoni&#146;s, one of the communities severly
effected by Shell&#146;s oil operations, concerns and the
tremendous environmental impact this land has suffered for
decades and how it has affected many communities of Nigeria. They
also neglect to mention what the Ogoni people want. They only
express what they think the Ogoni people need. Other information
they give in their response is definetly stretching the truth.
They had to come up with some response to the many inquires they
have received from citizens all over the world and make sure they
come out looking good. They know there are boycotts on their
products all over the world and they need to be sure their
profits are effected as little as possible.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Q: Is this a combination of the above two
questions?</font></p>

<p><font size="2">A: Yes. I encourage anyone concerned about this
issue to write the president of the Shell Oil Compnay, Philip J.
Carroll, P.O. Box 2463, Houston, TX 77252 or call (800) 248-4257
or fax (713) 241-4044, and express your concerns about this
issue. You will also receive their response and you can read for
yourself their defense on the issue. If readers are unfamiliar
with this issue call the office, (216) 383-9985, and we will send
you the many updates we have run in past issues.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Q: Is this something we truly don&#146;t or
can&#146;t know here in America?</font></p>

<p><font size="2">A: Americans have been very well informed on
this issue. The Sierra Club has taken a major interest in this
issue and would be the best group to contact for more
information. You can visit the Sierra Club&#146;s Web Site at
http://www.sierraclub.org or you can call Stephen Mills at (202)
675-6691.</font></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

