<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Ohio Citizens Protest Against Logging in the Wayne</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1 align="center"><font size="2">Ohio Citizens Protest Against
Logging in the</font></h1>

<h1 align="center"><font size="2">Wayne National Forest</font></h1>

<h5 align="center"><font size="2">by Susan M. Heitker</font></h5>

<blockquote>
    <p align="left"><font size="2">A peaceful protest against
    logging in the Wayne National Forest on Wednesday, November
    13 at the Wayne National Forest Headquarters in Athens, Ohio
    ended with 21 individuals arrested for criminal trespassing,
    two of whom received an additional charge of resisting
    arrest.</font></p>
    <p align="left"><font size="2">At 4:00 p.m. approximately 45
    people from Ohio University&#146;s Campus Greens and the
    Athens community, determined to stop logging of the Wayne
    National Forest in southeastern Ohio, entered the lobby of
    the headquarters and proceeded to the office of Eurial
    Turner, Forest Supervisor. Once everyone was in the office
    Chris Crews of the Campus Greens approached Turner with their
    single demand of zero cut&#151;absolutely no logging in the
    Wayne. Turner explained that the Wayne, as a National Forest,
    is open for multiple use, including timber extraction.
    However, Matt Peters pointed out that &quot;timber extraction
    is an option as a use for the Forest but, the Forest Service
    is not mandated to log the forest. Studies conducted in
    Indiana and Kentucky found 69 percent to 82 percent of the
    people in the Midwest are opposed to logging of National
    Forests,&quot; challenging Turner to explain why the
    interests of the 18 to 31 percent who want logging have
    priority.</font></p>
    <p align="left"><font size="2">At 4:30 p.m. Turner announced
    the office was closing and asked the protesters to leave.
    &quot;We do not want cutting on our public lands and will not
    leave until you concede to our demand of zero cut,&quot; said
    Crews. Turner informed the group that if they did not leave
    the police would be called and they would be arrested.
    Standing their ground, the protesters patiently awaited the
    arrival of the Athens City Police, all the while chanting
    slogans such as &quot;The Wayne is not for sale&quot; and
    &quot;The forest can manage itself&quot; as well as holding
    up signs with similar slogans in the windows so the media and
    other protesters outside could see.</font></p>
    <p align="left"><font size="2">The police arrived shortly
    before 5:00 p.m. and gave the protesters the option of
    leaving the office or being arrested. At this time about half
    of the protesteres opted to join the small group of
    protesters outside the Forest Headquarters while 21 continued
    their occupation of Turner&#146;s office. The police arrested
    the 21 protesters, escorting them to police vehicles via the
    Forest Headquarters garage at the back of the building. For
    the most part the police had little trouble with the arrests.
    However, two individuals passively resisted arrest with one
    actually being carried to the police vehicle. The arrestees
    were taken to the Athens Police Station, charged with
    criminal trespassing, a fourth degree misdemeanor, and
    released. The two individuals who passively resisted arrest
    were given an additional charge of resisting arrest, a second
    degree misdemeanor, and released.</font></p>
    <p align="left"><font size="2">The 21 protesters were
    arraigned on Tuesday, November 19 and Wednesday, November 20.
    One pledguilty and 20 pled not guilty. The pretrial for the
    20 is scheduled for Friday, January 10, 1996.</font></p>
    <p align="left"><font size="2">This protest was by no means
    the first step taken by those opposed to the logging of the
    Wayne National Forest. Previous to this action numerous
    attempts had been made to persuade the Forest Service not to
    log in the Wayne. In addition to letters, petitions, and an
    administrative appeal from individuals and environmental
    groups concerned with the Forest Service&#146;s mismanagement
    of the Wayne, the Buckeye Forest Council (BFC) of Athens,
    Ohio filed a lawsuit against the Forest Service this past
    summer. They staged a rally in early September outside the
    Forest Headquarters in which they presented the Forest
    Service a list of demands and a Rusty Scalpel Award for
    forest health malpractice. In late October the Campus Greens
    organized a rally. Approximately 120 people marched two miles
    from the Ohio University campus to the Forest Headquarters.
    Interspersed throughout these events were numerous meetings
    between the Forest Service and environmental groups. Despite
    these efforts, logging in the Wayne is underway on the
    Bluegrass Ridge Timber Sales near Ironton, Ohio.</font></p>
    <p align="left"><font size="2">The partial select cutting and
    partial thinning of 300 acres of Bluegrass Ridge that has
    begun marks the first time in three years that logging has
    occurred in the Wayne. Originally, the Bluegrass Ridge Timber
    Sales comprised 442 acres, but some of the areas marked for
    cutting did not appear in the Environmental Assessment. The
    BFC&#146;s lawsuit against the Forest Service resulted in the
    150 acres of contested tracts being removed from the timber
    sale.</font></p>
    <p align="left"><font size="2">In addition to the Bluegrasss
    Ridge Timber Sales, the Forest Service has proposed three
    other logging projects, two of which are small scale. The
    third, the Dorr Run Timber Sales in the Athens district, is a
    5000-acre area of which 2000 acres are scheduled for logging.
    The method of logging has not yet been determined but the
    Forest Service preference is select cutting. The objective is
    to thin out the oaks in preparation for the gypsy moth
    invasion in six to twelve years. Gypsy moths defoliate oak
    trees and can cause premature death. The Forest Service
    claims the logging will lessen the impact of the gypsy moths.
    Although there is a newly-introduced fungus, Entomophaga
    maimaiga, that is killing the gypsy moth and could prevent it
    from reaching southeastern Ohio, the Forest Service wants to
    proceed with logging instead of waiting to see what outcome
    the fungus has on the gypsy moths.</font></p>
    <p align="left"><font size="2">To show your opposition to the
    logging of Dorr Run contact Rosemarie Boyle at 219 Columbus
    Rd., Athens, OH 45701. The BFC and other groups will be doing
    whatever is necessary to prevent this area from being logged.
    </font></p>
    <p align="left"><font size="2">For more information contact
    the Buckeye Forest Council at P.O. Box 99, Athens, OH 45701;
    (614) 594-6400; e-mail: buckeye@envirolink.org</font></p>
    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>
</blockquote>

