<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Appalachian Affinity -Restoration Campaign Opens Office in Athens</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Appalachian Restoration
Campaign Opens Office in Athens</font></h2>

<p><font size="2">The Appalachian Restoration Campaign (ARC)
opened its central office in Athens, Ohio this week to coordinate
wilderness recovery efforts throughout the Central Appalachian
region. The purpose of the Campaign is to restore and protect
regional biodiversity by developing and forwarding ecological
proposals for wilderness recovery which are grounded in landscape
ecology and conservation biology.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The Campaign aims to establish an
interconnected system of buffered ecological preserves in the
Central Appalachians in which human activity is compatible with
ecological restoration. The Athens office will coordinate
wilderness recovery efforts of Pennsylvania, Maryland, Ohio,
Kentucky, Virginia, and West Virginia, compiling
locally-generated wilderness proposals into cohesive proposals
for the region. The opening of the Athens office marks the second
year of the Campaign.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The Campaign cites the failure of traditional
efforts to conserve biological integrity through piecemeal
andreactionary attempts at conservation and responds with
landscape approaches to protect biological diversity and natural
evolutionary processes. &quot;If we are interested in preserving
the native biodiversity of the region, we really have no other
choice than to take a landscape approach,&quot; Than Hitt,
coordinator, remarked. &quot;The ecology of the region has been
systematically impacted by large-scale industrial exploitation
which we need to respond to with systematic, large-scale efforts
for preservation.&quot;</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The Appalachian Restoration Campaign is a
project of Heartwood, a coalition of groups, individuals and
businesses dedicated to the health and well-being of the Central
Hardwood region. For more information, contact Than Hitt at P.O.
Box 5541, Athens, Ohio 45701; (614) 592-3968; e-mail:
appalachian@envirolink.org</font></p>

