<head>
<title>Affinity - Letters</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Letters to the Editor</h3>
<p>To the Editor:</p>
<p>Hours after Vice President Al Gore stated on national television that signing the logging rider was 
the Clinton administration's biggest mistake, White Houseofficials were busy negotiating away their 
last chance to the repeal the devastating law. Congress adjourned without taking action to remedy 
this major environmental blunder and California's forests have been left to suffer the consequences.</p>
<p>Under the infamous logging rider, the Forest Service is using the guise of&quot;salvage logging&quot; - the 
removal of supposedly dead and dying trees - to cut perfectly healthy old growth forests. In the 
height of irresponsibility, the Forest Service is moving forward with plans to log some of the state's 
last old growth forests despite numerous law violations and the well documented threats 
theseprojects pose to water quality and wildlife. And because the logging rider suspended 
environmental laws, citizens are almost powerless to halt the onslaught.</p>
<p>Congress has left intact this devastating law. Now, only President Clinton can save California's 
forests by cancelling these reckless timber sales. Conservationists have documented twenty logging 
rider timber sales in California containing old growth that will be offered for sale in the coming 
months. If the President does not act immediately to prevent this needless destruction, the ruination 
of some of the state's most precious Ancient Forests will be his legacy.</p>
<p>Sincerely,</p>
<p>Paul Spitler, Western Ancient Forest Campaign</p>
<p>Dear Editor:</p>
<p>It's a most likely location for a graveyard, between a nightclub and a couple of restaurants, across 
the street from an ultra modern baseball park, smack in the middle of this booming downtown area 
of Cleveland.But the Erie Street graveyard has been in use for most of Cleveland's 200 years and 
was still in use until recently. And quite a few sports fans drawn to Jacobs Field from the suburbs 
spend a few minutes walking among the gravestones and reading what they tell of the people who 
lived and died in this town.</p>
<p>Renate and I passed by on our way to our Habitat II-Revisited/Endangered Spaces Exhibition (the 
United Nation's Second Conference on Human Settlements) located at the Frank J. Lausche State 
Building. And with this exhibition in mind, I came to realize that this graveyard tells much of the 
history of one particular human settlement on the mouth of the Cuyahoga River and, perhaps even 
more forcefully, how the quality of human life has changed for Clevelanders over the past 200 
years.In the 18th, 19th and even the 20th centuries, life in Cleveland was, for most people, short 
and filled with uncertainty. One cannot help but notice the profusion of smaller gravestones 
scattered about the cemetery, each marking the grave of a child who succumbed to some infection 
or other illness.Many of the graves here are filled with the remains of young women who died in 
childbirth. Most of those buried here did not live to see old age. Their lives were cut short by 
sickness or accidents. One tombstone marks the grave of a man who lost his life while working on 
Lake Erie.</p>
<p>Of course, people are still losing their lives on Lake Erie, or to sickness. And maternal mortality 
remains a serious problem in many places. But such premature deaths are no longer commonplace 
in this part of the world. We no longer consider it a special blessing when our children survive into 
adolescence. The death of a young mother is a tragic rarity, not a commonplace occurrence. In this 
prosperous and happy human settlement called Cleveland, at least, life has changed for the better. 
It is longer, more secure, more healthy. And we have every reason to hope that because of 
information obtained from Habitat II-Revisited/Endangered Spaces, quality of life in the upcoming 
21st Century will continue to improve, not only for the people of Cleveland but for people 
everywhere. </p>
<p>David &amp; Renate Jakupca</p>
<p>David and Renate Jakupca are founders of the International Center for Environmental Arts (ICEA). 
David is a noted international environmental artist.</p>
<hr>
