<head>
<title>MILL CREEK RESTORATION PROJECT</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>MILL CREEK RESTORATION 
PROJECT</h1>
<p>Under Rivers Unlimited's leadership, a Watershed Steering Committee was formed and an 
Intergovernmental Agreement has been signed by 17 cities, townships, and counties in Mill Creek's 
watershed. These communities have committed to develop and support a restoration strategy for 
Mill Creek, which includes improved water quality and protection of aquatic life, environmentally 
sound flood damage limitation, remediation of sources of pollution, expansion of public recreational 
access to the creek, and involvement of the public in improvement activities.</p>
<p><br>
In January of 1994 Rivers Unlimited was awarded $360,000 through an industrial pollution 
settlement. This allowed us to form the Mill Creek Restoration Project, which serves to educate 
students in the Cincinnati area about water quality monitoring. Executive Robin Corathers has 
introduced 500 students 12 schools in 6 districts to the fascinations of water quality sampling and 
analysis. We are also been organizing ten of the watershed communities to work toward reclaiing 
Mill Creek.</p>
<p>To learn more about the Rivers Unlimited/Mill Creek Restoration Project, contact:</p>
<p><i>Robin Corathers, Executive DirectorMill Creek Restoration Project805 Central 
AvenueCincinnati, OH 45202513 / 352-1588513 / 352-4970 [fax]</i></p>
<hr>
