<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Affinity -  How to be a Wise Herbal Shopper</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">How to be a Wise Herbal Shopper</font></h2>

<p><font size="2">Greetings! A few thoughts on the &quot;herbal
correctness&quot; of the times. Put aside the limitations of
herbs as folklore, or a witches brew. Herbs are beginning to hit
mainstream America. Look about and see the &quot;gingko-memory
revitalizing herb&quot; packaged right next to the ex-lax on the
shelves of your neighborhood drugstore. What is this? I ask...
Really what is this? A band wagon approach to herbal healing.
Anyone can just jump on and market anything natural with a few
legal disclaimers on the bottom of the package and have it ready
for Jane or John Doe USA to consume.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">A few things to think about when purchasing
herbs or herbal products. First, who are you buying from?
Specifically, do they know their product? Who are their
suppliers? Do you know that the product you are buying is what
the packaging says it is? How fresh is the product? How was the
product packaged? How was it cultivated? And from where? Is it
pure? Read the fine print on packages. Read the labels,
familiarize yourself with the company that is on that label, or
go to a herbalist you trust and let them guide you. If you do
know anyone who is wildcrafting make sure that they are doing it
ethically. A great organization to refer any questions you may
have about wildcrafting is United Plant Savers. Their principles
are solid, and reliable. Their address is at the end of this
column.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Also when purchasing herbs, do you know what to
look for? Color, scent and freshness are the keys. Ask your
friendly herb provider if they can remove a bit of the product so
you can smell it (do not put your nose in the herb jar, it
discourages freshness). As a novice or a veteran herbal user,
questions are always welcomed at point of purchase, or should be.
See if your herb shop has a herbal reference library available.
Remember that the person selling to you is not allowed to
prescribe herbs as medication, or even to make pointed
recommendations. So take the heat off them and be willing to
research a bit on your own. Hopefully, the books available at
your herbal store will add to the information you have already
gathered. Be clear about what it is you are about to ingest and
what your desired results are. It&#146;s your body, mind and
spirit &#139; so learn all that you can about the herbs you are
going to take. It is important to research a recipe for a
specific treatment in a couple different books to be sure that
you are on the right track.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Remember that when using different parts of a
plants there are different ways to prepare the herb. But that is
the start of another topic! Next time we&#146;ll share input on
preparation of herbs. Information is the key to using herbs
properly. If the person who you are buying from has enough
integrity to say &quot;I don&#146;t know,&quot; honor that and
research a bit on your own. Then share with them what you&#146;ve
discovered. That&#146;s a treat for us, all of us, in our
unquenchable desire to learn from the Green world.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">&quot;Going slowly does not stop one from
arriving&quot;- Fulfude proverb</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Herbal Sage column comes to you complements of
the Herbal Sage Tea Company located in The Cleveland Shop at
11606 Detroit Avenue, Cleveland, Ohio 44102; 216-228-9725;
wwww.clevelandshop.com. For more information also contact United
Plant Savers P.O. Box 420, East Barre, VT 05649.</font></p>

<p><font size="2"></font>&nbsp;</p>
</body>
</html>
