<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>affinity - Cow, Water and Cryptosporidium</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Cow, Water and Cryptosporidium</font></h2>

<h5 align="center"><font size="2">by Aaron Lehmer</font></h5>

<p><font size="2">Despite the harsh antiregulatory climate in
Washington, the EPA has embarked on a large-scale project to set
safety standards for cryptosporidium, a potentially deadly
waterborne microbe. In Milwaukee in 1993, a crypto outbreak
caused more than 100 deaths and an estimated 403,000 illnesses.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">While healthy individuals may experience severe
diarrhea and related symptoms for weeks, cryptosporidium
infections can prove fatal for people with compromised immune
systems, such as people with AIDS, transplant patients and
individuals undergoing chemotherapy.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">EPA Administrator Carol Browner has stated that
the agency&#146;s new monitoring effort will &quot;result in more
information than ever about drinking water contaminants that have
thus far defied treatment.&quot; But Browner&#146;s statement
largely ignores what may be the largest culprit lurking in the
background - the livestock industry.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Though it is rarely emphasized, a primary
crypto source is animal waste from cattle production near or
within public watersheds. (Other sources include infectious human
fecal matter deposited in lakes and streams or treated sewage
dumped into public waterways. Waste from calves and human babies
tends to be the most infectious crypto source).</font></p>

<p><font size="2">As early as the 1970s, EPA scientists declared
feedlot wastes to be as much as several hundred times more
concentrated than raw domestic sewage, with soaring rates of
ammonia, nitrates, bacteria and other microbial contaminants.
Frances Moore Lappe, in her landmark book Diet for a Small
Planet, claimed that animal wastes generate more than 10 times
the water pollution produced by human beings.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Crypto is an incredibly resilient microbe,
sometimes evading even the most advanced treatment processes. In
Milwaukee, where scientists linked treatment facilities were
apparently in full compliance with the Clean Water Act, said EPA
toxicologist Bruce Macler.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Massive developments occurring throughout the
animal agriculture industry constitute and ever-expanding threat
to public water supplies. The days of cattle happily grazing in
pastures are all but gone. Today, the vast majority of cattle
spend their lives in crowded industrial feedlots, where they are
fed high-fat diets to ensure maximum weight gain. Such crowded
conditions create a sanitation and waste-disposal nightmare.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Clean Water Action, a 700,000-strong
safe-drinking-water coalition, is urging a ban or sharp
restrictions on grazing around public watersheds. Such a move
would force the cattle industry to internalize some costs (for
cleanup, monitoring and safety research) currently borne by the
public.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">But implementing new restrictions will be a
difficult task - cattle ranchers and animal producers have
enormous political clout, especially at the state levels. Nothing
short of a wholesale downsizing of the animal agriculture
industry is required to ensure a sustainable and healthy
environment. There are not enough resources to accommodate an
ever-expanding nation of meat-eaters, nor are there enough
watersheds or pastures to absorb an ever-expanding reservoir of
animal waste. The U.S. needs a commitment to serious prevention,
not just crisis management.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Aaron Lehmer is a contribution editor to the
San Francisco Green Party Newsletter. This article first ran in
the Earth Island Journal, 300 Broadway, No. 28, San Francisco,
California 94133; (415) 788-3666. Visit their web page at:
http://www.earthisland.org/ei/</font></p>

<hr>

