<head>
<title>Affinity Perry County</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Perry County Fights Chemical Sludge</h3>
<p>In the Fall of 1990 Peabody Coal Company locked their gates, taking with them over 500 jobs in 
Perry County, a mid-size Appalachian county in Southeastern Ohio. Citizens of Perry County felt 
they had been through the worst of what the mine closure could do to their community, until the 
mine gates were reopened for reclamation. In 1992, the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency 
(OEPA) approved Mead Paper Company to distribute what local residents fear was dioxin-laden 
paper by-product waste over former Peabody land now owned by Ohio Mine Reclamation.</p>
<p>In the Spring of 1994, Mead's contract expired and the OEPA approved the City of Lancaster, 
Ohio (Fairfield County) to dump Bio-Gro, a mixture of wastewater sludge and lime, on the 
property. In 1996, the City of Lancaster contracted with the City of Columbus to allow them to 
dump on the property under their OEPA approval. The County Health Department was sent a 
copy of the approval; however, no input from Perry County was pursued.</p>
<p>In the spring of this year residents within two miles of the site complained of headaches, nausea and 
a strong odor that burned their eyes. The OEPA blamed the complaints on a sewer leak in the City 
of New Lexington which has not been found. </p>
<p>The Perry County Commissioners uncovered the OEPA Approval which stated that if the dumping 
was a nuisance it would be terminated. The Commissioners immediately passed a resolution that a 
nuisance existed to the residents and demanded the approval be withdrawn. The OEPA defended 
the sludge, maintaining it was not a nuisance in their terms, and the County had no authority to halt 
the dumping.</p>
<p>&quot;We questioned the OEPA on whether they exist to protect the citizens well-being, or if they 
existed to promote products like Bio-Gro,&quot; stated Commissioner President Larry Householder. 
Previously, Perry County sent a resolution to Governor Voinovich denouncing low level radioactive 
waste being brought into Ohio. &quot;We know that Southeastern Ohio will be a prime candidate for this 
waste. Counties should be granted the authority on what by-products are permissible within it's 
borders, not some agency outside the county. Whenever another community produces something 
they don't want in their backyard, they try to put it in ours,&quot; concluded Householder.</p>
<p>As it now stands the OEPA feels that the sludge is a viable source to promote growth, it is not a 
nuisance to them and the County has no authority to halt its use. The dumping will continue, and so 
the citizens of Perry County will continue to fight to stop it.</p>
<p>For more information contact Larry Householder at (614) 342-7055.</p>
<hr>
