<title>Affinity - Nadar</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>Write-in Nader for President</h2>
<p>On September 6 the Committee to Draft Ralph Nader for President was informed that the petition 
drive to place Nader on the ballot in Ohio was short 373 valid signatures. A search for signatures 
has not turned up enough errors to anticipate a successful challenge, although it has revealed 
patterns of exclusionary practices and policies and no stone will be left unturned. As this paper 
goes to press the committee is filing an application for a write-in candidacy for Ralph Nader for 
President and Winona LaDuke for vice president in Ohio.</p>
<p>On August 29, 1996 Nader announced his choice of running mate, Native American and 
environmental activist, Winona LaDuke. LaDuke, a 37 year-old graduate of Harvard University, is 
an Ojibwe activist from the White Earth Reservation in Northern Minnesota. She is the founder of 
the White Earth Land Recovery Project, the Indigenous Women&#185;s Network and serves on the 
GreenPeace USA Board of Directors. In 1995, Time Magazine nominated Winona LaDuke as one 
of &quot;50 leaders for the future.&quot;</p>
<p>The Nader/LaDuke candidacy is on the ballot in at least 20 states and write-in campaigns will be 
conducted in approximately 20 others. Write-in campaigns are famous for never getting more than 
1% of the vote. It may be that there has never been a serious attempt to teach voters how to cast 
write-in votes. It may also be that no president has pissed off so many voters at the same time that 
such an excellent candidate was willing to run. That we were extremely close to qualifying means 
that we did reach a critical mass as a result of the petition drive.Since filing signatures on August 22, 
we have been flooded with calls from people who want to know how they can become involved in 
the next phase. Some of them have said this is a good chance to see how many votes a really good 
candidate with a grassroots base of committed activists can generate.</p>
<p>There are plenty of things that we can still do to make a difference in this election year. Some of 
them are just getting underway. Sooner or later the grassroots will learn how to get its candidates 
elected without the corporate money, the sold out media and the permission of the election 
establishment at the local, state and federal levels. When we do it will be because we have all 
pitched in when an opportunity like this came up. Remember that Jack (of Beanstalk fame) was not 
a member of the privileged class, nor was he particularly experienced or educated or even overly 
endowed with commonsense. Jack possesed the one important quality that counts when presented 
with an extraordinary opportunity. The courage to act without undue hesitation.</p>
<p>Please, if you think it is time to act, call Daryl Davis at 216-236-5801 or e-mail daryl@igc.apc.org</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
