<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Affinity - Breasticides</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Breasticides</font></h2>

<p><font size="2">In late July, San Francisco newspapers flashed
the grim news that the Bay Area had recorded the world&#146;s
highest incidence of female breast cancer. While county health
professionals were at a loss to explain the alarming report, the
local press already had identified a likely culprit.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">On June 9, San Francisco Examiner environmental
writer Jane Kay reported that over the last 10 years, the city
had dumped &quot;at least 10,000 pounds and 775 gallons of
powerful pesticides on parks and golf courses.&quot; Many common
pesticides - including endosulfan dieldrin, toxaphene and
chlordane - are known to disrupt the function of the hormone
estrogen and have been linked to breast cancer and the
malformation of male sex organs.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">San Francisco uses as many as 32 different
brands of chemicals, including Banvel, Roundup, Ronstar, Trimec,
Turf Supreme and Surflan (all containing 2,4-D, glyphosate,
dicamba and MCPP), Fore, Danconil, Bayleton and Scott&#146;s
Proturf (containing chlorothalonil, mancozeb and PCNB).</font></p>

<p><font size="2">According to a report in the June issue of
Science, pesticides linked to breast cancer and male birth
defects can become more potent when combined with other
pesticides. Tulane University researcher John A. McLachlan
explained that a pesticide&#146;s effects might seem
&quot;inconsequential&quot; when tested alone, but when tested in
combination with other pesticides, their potency can rise
&quot;500- to 1,000-fold.&quot; Instead of one plus one equals
two,&quot; McLachlan observed, &quot;we found, in some cases,
that one plus one equals 1,000.&quot;</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Lynn Goldman, head of the EPA&#146;s Office of
Prevention, Pesticides and Toxic Substances, called the report
&quot;astounding,&quot; adding that &quot;the policy implications
are enormous about how we screen for estrogen effects.&quot;</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Meanwhile, the May issue of the American
Journal of Industrial Medicine reported that golf course
superintendents - individuals who are routinely exposed to common
chemical pesticides and herbicides - showed &quot;significantly
higher&quot; death rates from brain cancer, prostate cancer and
non-Hodgkin&#146;s lymphoma.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">&quot;There&#146;s no reason to use any toxic
chemical inside a park,&quot; Pesticide Education Center founder
Marion Moses told the Examiner. &quot;Product warning labels...
say: &#145;Wait until it&#146;s dry, then your children can play
on the lawn.&#146; But that&#146;s based on no science
whatsoever. I don&#146;t think children should be exposed to any
avoidable toxic.&quot; Pesticide Watch, a Bay Area environmental
group, has called for a 50 percent reduction in the city&#146;s
use of dangerous chemicals.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">This article first ran in the Earth Island
Journal, 300 Broadway, No. 28, San Francisco, California 94133;
(415) 788-3666. Visit their web page at:
http://www.earthisland.org/ei/</font></p>

