<head>
<title>Dishonorable Discharge</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Dishonorable Discharge</h3>
<h4 align=center>Ohio Ranks 7th in the Nation for Toxics to Waterways</h4>
<h6 align=center>By Ohio Public Interest Research Group</h6>
<p>Most Ohio citizens would be surprised to learn that scores of businesses and facilities across the 
state legally dump tons of toxic chemicals into the state's rivers, streams, lakes and bays. Many of 
these same polluters flush millions more pounds of toxic substances down the drain to sewage 
treatment plants that taxpayers pay tooperate and maintain. None of the toxic chemicals sent to 
publicly financed sewage treatment systems are reported as pollution by the Environmental 
Protection Agency (EPA), even though a great deal of the toxic load eventually finds its way to 
Ohio streams and rivers.</p>
<p>The citizens of Ohio have a right to know about any pollution to their water, air or land that may 
pose a risk to human health or the environment. That is why Ohio Public Interest Research Group 
(PIRG) and Environmental Working Group released a report containing first ever river-by-river 
rankings of toxic pollution to Ohio waterways. This report is based on industry generated data and 
contains state rankings and national totals for toxic chemicals released into waterways and sewers. 
It answers the questions of why so many of Ohio's rivers are unsafe to swim or fish in.</p>
<p>Factories and other industrial facilities dumped more than 22.8 million pounds of toxic substances 
directly into Ohio's waters between 1990 and 1994, according to a new analysis of the federal 
Toxics Release Inventory (TRI). Ohio ranked 7th among the states in toxic water pollution 
reported over those five years. In addition, almost 103 million pounds of toxic materials were 
flushed to sewage treatment plants in Ohio from 1990 through 1994, 6th in the nation. Because of 
weaknesses and loopholes in federal pollution laws, most, if not all of these toxic discharges are 
perfectly legal.</p>
<p>As large as they are, these figures substantiallyunderestimate toxic releases to waters and the 
environment because the TRI requires reporting of only about 340 of the 73,000 chemicals in 
commerce. The TRI also exempts certain industries from reporting including utilities, sewage 
treatment plants, municipal incinerators and manufacturing facilities with fewer than ten employees.</p>
<p>The Ohio River received the greatest amount of toxic water pollution in Ohio from 1990-1994, a 
total of 16,000 pounds, followed by the Cuyahoga River, the Black River and the Scioto River 
(see chart #1). The ten most polluted waterways in Ohio received 21,400,000 pounds of toxic 
pollution between 1990 and 1994, 94.0% of the total in the State.</p>
<p>The top three facilities reporting the most toxic pollution of Ohio's waters over this period were 
Elkem Metals Company in Marietta, which dumped 13,800,000 pounds of toxic chemicals, 
followed by LTV Steel Company, Inc., and Monsanto Company in the towns of Cleveland, and 
Addyston, respectively (see chart #2 on page 16). The toxic chemicals dumped in the greatest 
amounts were ammonia, a total of 18,300,000 pounds, followed by ethylene glycol and methanol. </p>
<p>Monsanto Company dumped the most carcinogens into Ohio's waters, a total of 106,000 pounds, 
follwed by AK Steel Corporation and Du Pont. The Ohio River received the greatest amount of 
cancer-causing toxic chemicals in Ohio, a total of 106,000 pounds, followed by Dick's Creek and 
the Scioto River.</p>
<p>Elkem Metals Company dumped the greatest amount of persistent toxic metals in Ohio's waters, a 
total of 540,000 pounds, followed by AK Steel Corporation and USS/Kobe Steel Company. The 
Ohio River received the greatest amount of persistent toxic metals, a total of 610,000 pounds, 
followed by Dick's creek and the Black River.Armco Inc. Doyer Operations dumped the greatest 
amount of toxic chemicals that cause reproductive damage or birth defects into Ohio's waters, a 
total of 45,000 pounds, followed by Hobart Brothers Company and Ford Motor Company. The 
Tuscarawas River recieved the greatest amount of toxic chemicals that cause reproductive damage 
or birth defects, a total of 49,000 pounds, followed by Morgan's Ditch and the Schoewe Ditch.</p>
<p>These discharges to Ohio's waters include only those wastes released by companies physically 
located in Ohio. Many waterways receive additional pollution from sources outside of the state. 
Americans have a right to know about any use, transport or release of toxic substance in their 
communities that might pose a risk to human health or the environment. Required reporting under 
the TRI provides only a small portion of this information. Much more complete reporting is needed. 
Americans also have a right to know about toxic chemicals in the products they buy that may pose 
a risk to them and their children.</p>
<p>Data is available for every region of Ohio. For information specific to your region call (216) 
791-1116, (216) 791-3700 or (614) 421-5815. Ohio PIRG is a nonpartisan, nonprofit 
environmental and consumer watchdog organization with citizens and student members across the 
state.</p>
<hr>
