<html>

<head>
<title>Affinity - wolves</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center><strong>Wolf Recovery</strong></h2>
<p align=left>Wolves flourished in Colorado through the early 1900's, although they were under increasing 
pressure as their habitat was expropriated for livestock. By the late 1800s, most of the native 
ungulates (buffalo, elk and deer) that were the primary prey of wolves had been wiped-out by 
market hunters and settlers; wolves did what they had to to survive -- they turned to domestic 
livestock. Bounties on wolf and coyote pelts were set at fifty cents/ in 1869, and increased to 
nearly two dollars by the turn of the century. However, the bounty laws failed to exterminate 
wolves because bounty hunters let young wolves live so that they'd have more wolves to kill in 
subsequent years, and because wolves soon became savvy to the ways of the wolfers. Ultimately, it 
took the intervention of the federal government on the behalf of ranchers to wipe-out wolves. The 
feds hired hundreds of men with the specific task of killing wolves and sent them west. These 
federal employees had no economic incentive to let any wolves live. They used traps, guns, shovels 
(to dig pups out of their dens and smash them) and they placed thousands of poisoned carcasses all 
over the place. The toll on &quot;non-target&quot; animals from poison was, of course, very high. Colorado's 
last wild wolf was killed in 1945 in the South San Juan Wilderness, near theborder of New 
Mexico.</p>
<p align=left>Sinapu, a grassroots group dedicated to the recovery of the grey wolf in Colorado, recently won 
their campaign to get Congress to appropriate money to the Fish &amp; Wildlife Service (FWS) to 
study the feasibility of returning wolves to the Southern Rockies. The study which concluded that 
Colorado has room for over 1000 wolves, and that 70% of the state's residents want wolves back. 
Unfortunately, the FWS currently refuses to include Colorado in a wolf recovery plan because the 
state's wildlife commission has an official policy renouncing wolf and grizzly recovery. It comes as 
know surprise that four of the eight commissioners are ranchers. Likewise, the FWS appears 
anxious to be done with the whole wolf recovery program.Nearly a year after Sinapu blew the lid 
off of a secret plan to strip gray wolves of their protections under the Endangered Species Act, the 
plan still lurks in the active files of FWS bureaucrats, ready to be molded into public policy. The 
eleven page plan, called A Comprehensive Recovery Strategy for the Gray Wolf in the Contiguous 
48 States, spells doom for the slowly recovering populations of wolves in the lower 48, and 
undermines the chances for wolves to reoccupy more of their ancestral range.Although supposedly 
a scientific document -- the esteemed Dr. L. David Mech has his name emblazoned on the front 
cover -- the strategy is blatantly political in nature. Seeking to wash their hands of the 
controversy-laden responsibility for restoring large carnivores and protecting their habitat, the 
&quot;biologists&quot; and bureaucrats who crafted the strategy came up with a brilliant idea. They decided to 
expand the current recovery plans for Canis lupis that include all of the wolf's former range, but 
mandate that the wolf be de-listed once the current recovery goals are met. For the western U.S., 
that means that once 30 breeding pairs have established themselves in the Northern Rockies (10 
pairs each in Idaho, Montana and Wyoming for three consecutive years), wolves will no longer 
have federal protection under the ESA anywhere in the West. Given that the FWS refuses to 
protect the habitat of wolves under the present recovery plans, 30 breeding pairs hardly constitutes 
a biologically viable founding population. And the situation in the eastern U.S. ultimately could 
degrade to the same level, except for Minnesota where wolf population has finally reached a 
significant size.</p>
<p align=left>What You Can Do: Sinapu and over thirty other organizations across the country have joined 
forces to oppose the FWS plan -- which is why it has not been proposed as official policy yet. 
Sinapu is now laying the foundation for a scientific and legal strategy to put the FWS back on the 
right course. Write to Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt (1849 C Street, NW, Washington D.C. 
20012) and urge him to send the strategy (see title above) back to the drawing board. Ask him to 
set the stage for wolf recovery in other areas of the lower 48 that still have abundant habitat and 
prey for wolves -- places such as Colorado, Utah, and the Dakotas. Finally, emphasize that the 
present recovery goals are not adequate because the FWS refuses to designate &quot;critical habitat&quot; for 
wolves.</p>
<p align=left>Rob Edward is the Outreach Coordinator for Sinapu, a group named after the Ute word for 
wolves, which is dedicated to recovery of the gray wolf in Colorado, and to the restoration of the 
wild habitat in which all species flourish. For more information contact Sinapu, Box 3243 Boulder, 
CO 80307; (303) 447-8655; e-mail: sinapu@sinapu.org and/or web: http://www.sinapu.org/</p>
<hr>
