<head>
<title>camp hi</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p align=center><strong>Canoe at CAMP HI Along Upper Cuyahoga Scenic River</strong></p>
<p>Camp Hi Canoe Livery is nestled along the Upper Cuyahoga Scenic River giving canoers an 
opportunity to meander through this beautifully wooded portion of the river.&quot;We have quite a few 
customers this time of year that take repeat trips just to see the fall foliage,&quot; said Kendra 
Hazlett-Becker, who helps her father, George Hazlett, run his Hiram-based canoe livery. The 
portion of the river along Camp Hi has been designated as a State Scenic River since June 26, 
1974. It extends 25 miles from Burton Township to the state Route 14 bridge in Streetsboro.&quot;The 
water quality has been quite good for at least the past 20 years,&quot; said Steve Roloson, the Upper 
Cuyahoga River coordinator for the Ohio Department of Natural Resources (ODNR). Roloson 
said that low population, sparse development and an abundance of wetlands along the scenic 
portion of the river all contribute to the high water quality.&quot;Anytime you have a lower population 
base, that helps to reduce the effluent that comes into the stream.&quot; Volunteer stream-banking 
projects are also conducted to maintain the water quality. Groups of ODNR's stream team 
volunteers test the water periodically in order to detect changes in the water. Volunteers are trained 
to look for signs of erosion or sources of pollution along the river banks. Camp Hi employees also 
patrol the river. Hazlett-Becker said they go out in canoes periodically to look for changes in the 
river banks and to clean up litter and debris. And for their efforts, Friends of the Crooked River 
recently awarded Camp Hi with a plaque of recognition at the River Day<font size=2> 1</font>996 festivities. Aside 
from stream team efforts a new conservation easement program was implemented by the ODNR in 
order to help preserve the natural state of the Upper Cuyahoga Scenic River.&quot;What the land 
easements do is they allow the land owner to receive some money for keeping the land natural,&quot; 
Roloson said.&quot;The forest zone along the river is some of the best protection for water quality. 
Although they give up the developmental rights of their land, landowners still retain the deed to the 
property but cannot develop the land or do anything that would destroy its natural state. Anyone 
interested in canoeing along the Upper Cuyahoga Scenic River can contact Camp Hi at (330) 
569-7621. They are located at 12274 Abbott Rd. in Hiram, and they will be open weekends 
through October or by reservation during the week. For more information about the land 
easements along the Scenic portion of the river contact Steve Roloson at (330) 527-4184.</p>
