<head>
<title>affinity - National Rivers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>National Rivers Policy Act Gains momentum</h2>
<p>Movement toward developing a National Rivers Policy gained momentum this month when Rivers 
Unlimited founder and President Mike Fremont released a draft policy statement to the national 
rivers community. Fremont stated that the thrust of a national rivers policy would be based on the 
understanding that natural river systems have significant economic value, in addition to the cultural 
and environmental benefits they provide.</p>
<p>Very few rivers in the U. S. today provide more than a fraction of the functions that they 
could--high quality drinking water, a full range of recreational uses, a diverse collection of aquatic 
species, enhanced property values and thus tax base, and attractive park corridors that attract 
tourists, to name a few. Fremont stated that the National Wild and Scenic Rivers Act, protecting 
only one out of every 350 river miles in the country, is symbolic rather than consequential.</p>
<p>&quot;The prospect of a national rivers policy could inspire support of river protection groups, 
environmental organizations, and many of the millions of Americans who fish,&quot; said Fremont. &quot;A 
national policy would permit Congress to legally recognize the practical values of rivers and enact 
laws accordingly.&quot;</p>
<hr>
