<html>

<head>
<title>affinity - urban sprawl</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>Why Worry About Urban Sprawl</h2>
<p>Today, more people in Northeast Ohio drive farther to work than ever before. It's no surprise that 
they often find themselves stuck in traffic. While the overall population of the region declined 
between 1970 and 1990, together we drove 67% more miles. Yet, traffic congestion is only a 
symptom of a larger problem -- urban sprawl. The population of Northeast Ohio is not growing, it's 
spreading. And communities throughout the region are paying a price.</p>
<p>As new homes are built on the urban fringe, people move outward. New suburbs grow and the 
central city declines. As this outmigration process continues, the decline spreads outward, 
weakening the economic health of the region as a whole.</p>
<p>Outmigration is expensive&#160;for everyone -- for communities on the metropolitan fringe and for 
neighborhoods in the urban core. As people move out to newly-developing suburbs, these once 
rural communities struggle to:</p>
<p>&#128; Build new schools, roads and sewer systems.</p>
<p>&#128; Raise tax revenues to provide adequate public services.</p>
<p>&#128; And maintain the rural character that made them attractive in the first place.</p>
<p>At the same time, existing urban areas struggle to:</p>
<p>&#128; Retain population and tax base.</p>
<p>&#128; Maintain existing housing, infrastructure and mass transit systems.</p>
<p>&#128; Redevelop &quot;brownfield&quot; industrial sites.</p>
<p>&#128; Support hospitals, schools, religious and cultural institutions.</p>
<p>&#128; Meet increasing social service demands.</p>
<p>If our goal is healthy , affordable communities where everyone can find gainful employment, breathe 
clean air, and drink clean water, then we need to confront the problem of urban sprawl.</p>
<p>WHAT YOU CAN DO</p>
<p>Each of us can contribute to the solution, both through our personal lifestyle choices and through 
out participation in community affairs. Because most land-use decisions are made at the local level, 
we have a tremendous opportunity to shape the future of our communities. Here are three things 
you can do:</p>
<p>&#128; Become Informed &#139; read local newspapers and learn how communities throughout the region are 
struggling with growth and decline. Obtain a copy of your community's land-use plan and find out 
how your community is changing.</p>
<p>&#128; Get Involved &#139; Sit in on planning and zoning meetings and express your opinions. Vote for 
politicians who support compact, transit-oriented development where people can travel by foot, 
bicycle and public transportation.</p>
<p>&#128; Educate Others &#139; Discuss the issue of sprawl with your friends, relative and neighbors. If they're 
thinking of moving out, ask them why. Encourage them to work to make their community a better 
place instead of leaving.</p>
<p>In the end, we have two choices. We can eithe continue to consume the countryside, at tremendous 
long-term cost to the region, or we can roll up our sleeves together and reclaim our cities. For more 
information call the Sierra Club Urban Sprawl Committee at (216) 521-2434.</p>
<hr>
