<head>
<title>affinity - Philip Enviro</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>Philip Environmental Pollutes the Great Lakes</h2>
<h5 align=center>By David Sharp</h5>
<p><em>we ducked in where the woods meet the parking lot. the full blush of fall was around and 
upon us and simon dove into the wood and i followed the trail that butts the ravine. we 
particularly like this space 'cause he can run free, and i can too.</em></p>
<p>There is a multinational corporation, based in Hamilton, Ontario, Philip Environmental. They are 
one of the fastest growing, award winning, corporations on the continent. Three dump sites that 
they control on the Great Lakes are: the Sarnia, Ont. dump, which flows into the St. Clair River, 
through Lake St. Clair, the Detroit River, Lake Erie and points beyond. The Brantford, Ont. dump 
sits on the Grand River and flows through the Six Nations Indian Reserve directly into Lake Erie, 
and Stoney Creek, a suburb of Hamilton, Ontario on Lake Ontario.</p>
<p><em>i made my way down through the gorge past where the creek is diverted underground and 
past where the tiger lilies bloomed last june along the remnants of the original creekbed. it 
curves around to the left of a large field.</em></p>
<p>Electric Act Furnace (EAF) dust is a hazardous waste generated in significant quantities by the steel 
industry. The U.S. EPA classifies it as a hazardous waste, because, without treatment, it fails the 
toxicity characterizing leaching procedure (tclp) test for lead, cadmium and chromium. Philip 
Environmental had multi-year contracts with several major steel companies in the hamilton area, 
and had been receiving increasing quantities of EAF dust for a number of years. Philip 
Environmental had a recycling program whereby each ton of EAF dust was mixed with two tons of 
BOF dust and one part millscale. This mixture was to be recycled in cement. In December 1993 
Philip Environmental had approximately 65,000 tons of EAF dust. Over the next two years they 
have acknowledged receipt of approximately 75,000 tons. They also acknowledged that during this 
period virtually no recycling had occurred nor was nay disposed of or used in landfills, yet in 
November, 1995, only 70,000 tons could be accounted for. By my math, that&quot;s about half.</p>
<p><em>simon bolts out from under the canopy of fascias, reds and golds that claim the green from 
the trees and heads off to the right where large masonry blocks mix with fallen oak and 
various bramble rising a hundred or so feet to the ballfields above.</em></p>
<p>The Taro West Quarry Landfill site is owned by Taro Aggregates Construction Company, a 
subsidiary of Philip Environmental. According to local residents, Philip had been secretly dumping 
in the quarry for the past fifteen years. The site was filled past capacity, contoured with more waste 
and converted it into a scenic nature trail. The trail was part of a $40,000,000 compensation 
package received by the Stoney Creek city council, which also passed a second landfill site, the 
Taro East Quarry Landfill without the required Environmental Assessment (EA)</p>
<p><em>today i head off towards the old creek bed. water stands in a few deep pockets and i come 
upon a stump standing about twelve feet high. it is pocked and worn from woodpeckers and 
other insect eaters.</em></p>
<p>Regarding the EA process for Taro East, Philip Environmental representatives have often boasted 
that a hearing is unnecessary because they have spent $8,000,000 to ensure that the EA is 
satisfactory. The Taro East site offers no natural protection to the environment. It is a site in a 
residential area adjacent to the Niagra Escarpment, a unique and precious treasure designated as a 
world biosphere. There is already a landfill site that failed right next door leaking toxins into the 
drinking water of millions of people via the Red Hill Creek.</p>
<p><em>across the field, simon wanders in and out of the brush, sniffing out chipmunks or squirrels 
or some other dog that passed this way. he turns to search for me beside an access road that 
i can only describe as steel grey gravel and mud. once satisfied with my presence he moves 
on towards a thicket i wouldn&quot;t even dream of penetrating and disappears.</em></p>
<p>The hydrogeology13 at and near Taro is incomprehensible. That is, there is no way to predict the 
speed or direction of groundwater flow. In addition, the West Quarry is already leaking which 
means there are no clear benchmarks. The result is that if groundwater contamination is detected, it 
may be impossible to determine where and when it originated. Assuming the liners at Taro East 
function properly, there will be a disruption of natural water flow which will impact vegetation, most <br>
notable on the escarpment face.</p>
<p><em>i whistle a couple times and a few moments later, simon emerges and comes over, burr 
covered but happy. we head back through the field where this summer queen anne&quot;s lace 
and chicory scrabbled with buttercup and cattails amidst patches of grass and old tires.</em></p>
<p>It is important to note that nobody should be trusted to manage our environment without the proper 
checks and balances. Philip advertises that it is a fully integrated waste management company. This 
concept may be great for profitability, but is it in the best interest of the public? Philip Environmental 
operates several hazardous and non-hazardous waste facilities in the Hamilton region. It has a 
diverse transportation fleet. It owns a recently closed leaking industrial waste landfill. It manages the 
regions sewage treatment and water supply and owns the engineering company which monitors the 
performance of the contract on behalf of the region. Having one company responsible for all of 
these activities is not in the public interest.</p>
<p><em>last spring, a botanist and his assistant were down here taking samples of the various flora, 
killdeer skreeed about the place and i looked for frogs or tadpoles or minnows or just about 
any sign of life in the creek. as simon and i head up the hill the only signs of life in the water 
are some slippery algae and beer cans.</em></p>
<p>The levels of EAF dust around the Taro dump are ten times the amount found in the industrial core 
of Hamilton. The natives on the Six Nations Indian Reserve have contaminated drinking water and 
cancer rates comparable to Hamilton, the steel capital of Canada.Philip Environmental has been 
cited at least eleven times int he last two years in the U.S., from North Carolina to California. They 
boast about their operation in Brazil, lord knows what damage they&quot;re doing in a third world 
country given the reckless nature of the operations in the U.S. and Canada.</p>
<p><em>we reach the top of the hill and simon sits for a minute and scratches himself, God, i hope 
it&quot;s just fleas.</em></p>
<hr>
