<title>Oberlin College Affinity - Oberlin</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Oberlin College Environmental
Studies Program Earns Award of Excellence </font></h2>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">in Education</font></h2>

<p><font size="2">Oberlin college recently received a $100,000
Award of Excellence in Education from the Consolidated Natural
Gas Company Foundation for its innovative Environmental Studies
Program, which teaches studentshow to apply classroom knowledge
to solve real-world problems.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The Environmental Studies Program has evolved
from a single course 17 years ago into the fastest-growing area
of study at Oberlin, one of the nation&#146;s leading
independent, liberal arts colleges. The program helps students
combine critical thinking and practical know-how to develop
solutions to environmental problems. Local environmental projects
blanket Oberlin&#146;s home region in Northeast Ohio&#146;s
Lorain County, while independent research projects have taken
students around the world. The program&#146;s interdisciplinary
approach includes such areas as politics, economics, science and
ethics.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The CNG Foundation established the Award of
Excellence in Education in 1985 to recognize and encourage the
creativity and innovation inherent in independent colleges. Since
the awards inception, the CNG Foundation has presented more than
$1 million to eligible institutions that serve the same
geographical region encompassed by CNG through some of its
subsidiaries in Ohio, Pennsylvania, West Virginia, New York,
Virginia and Louisiana.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The growth of the Oberlin program culminated in
the planning of a 13,000-square-foot Environmental Studies
Center, a demonstration facility to showcase the latest in
ecological design techniques. Construction is slated to begin in
1997. The center, designed as a zero-emissions facility, will
emphasize energy efficiency, advanced materials and designs that
minimize its impact on the environment.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Other program achievements include:</font></p>

<ul>
    <li><font size="2">Black River Clean-up: In the past six
        years, student-led projects have played key roles in
        cleaning up the Black River, one of 43 toxic hot spots in
        the Great Lakes watershed.</font></li>
    <li><font size="2">Bog Restoration: Students have worked to
        help restore Camden Bog, located eight miles southwest of
        Oberlin. The bog serves as a living laboratory for
        Oberlin students, a feeding area for great egrets and
        their wildlife and a supportive environment for six
        species of endangered plants.</font></li>
    <li><font size="2">Community Outreach: Students have worked
        with local teachers to introduce environmental education
        into local curricula and prepared audits that led to
        proposals for increased resource and energy efficiency
        for the college and City of Oberlin.</font></li>
    <li><font size="2">Encouraging Organic Farming: Beginning in
        1988, student research projects have led to a program
        that links campus dining cooperatives to local farmers.
        Today, students are working with local farmers to
        establish Oberlin&#146;s first community-supported
        organic farm.</font></li>
</ul>

<p><font size="2">&quot;The Environmental Studies Program has
built a model for 21st century education,&quot; said Oberlin
College President Dr. Nancy S. Dye.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Dr. David Orr, the program&#146;s director
added, &quot;If we are to make the transition to a sustainable
and decent future in a world of 10 to 12 billion people in the
next 50 years, the size of the 'human footprint&#146; must be
reduced by 50 to 90 percent. This transition will require broad
changes in our ideas, perceptions and values -- which makes it,
in large part, a challenge to educational institutions.&quot;</font></p>

<p><font size="2">For more information contact Scott Wargo at
(216) 775-8503 or Betty Gabrielli at (216) 775-8474.</font></p>

