<html>

<head>
<title>Affinity - rivers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>State Turns Its Back on Clean Water</h2>
<p>Thanks to a new law that went into effect October 1, 1996 the most pristine waterways in Ohio 
may be subject to more pollution, Rivers Unlimited announced. High quality, scenic waters could all 
get further degraded despite assurances to the contrary by the Ohio EPA. This would include such 
Ohio treasures as the Darby Creeks in central Ohio, the Little Miami River in the Dayton area, the 
Chagrin River near Cleveland and Little Beaver Creek in eastern Ohio. This new law will allow 
more pollutants in the 61,000 miles of rivers and streams in Ohio. It is going into effect today even 
though none of these high quality rivers have been classified under the rules for the new system. 
Furthermore, thanks to the new statute and rules there will no longer be any requirement for public 
hearings for most of the requests to dump more pollution into Ohio water.</p>
<p>&quot;This is a very sad day for people who care about clean water in Ohio,&quot; Rivers Unlimited President 
Mike Fremont said. &quot;We already knew that these rules stole the public's right to have a voice in 
most decisions to increase pollutants into the water they drink. Unfortunately, we have just learned 
that Ohio EPA is moving forward with this plan despite the fact that they have not yet created the 
water classifications needed to protect our most pristine waterways. Every scenic river in Ohio 
could get trashed because Ohio EPA is rushing this process before any of these rivers have been 
classified under the rules for the new system,&quot; Fremont continued.</p>
<p>Under the new law and rules, known as the antidegradation law, all of the waterways in Ohio will 
be reclassified into six categories. Approximately 95% of the waterways in the state will be 
classified into the bottom two categories -- either as general high quality waters or limited resource 
waters. From now on, when wastewater treatment operators or other industrial dischargers apply 
to dump more toxins into these waters there will no longer be any requirement for public hearings 
or testimony. The remaining 5% of the waterways in the state that are in the top four categories 
would receive additional protections, Ohio EPA has repeatedly assured the public. Unfortunately, 
those classifications are not yet completed. As a result, each waterway is still classified under the 
old system. This could subject even the ten rivers in the state scenic river system to more pollution.</p>
<p>&quot;We are doing everything we can to stop this ill-conceived, polluters protection permitting process,&quot; 
stated Rivers Unlimited executive director Todd Ambs. &quot;Our lawsuit to stop this statute is still 
pending at the Franklin County Court of Common Pleas. We plan to demand a public hearing for 
every single permit application regardless of the stream category. At those hearings we will insist 
that a comprehensive cost benefit analysis be conducted and shared with the public. Any time there 
is a proposal to add more pollutants to a stream we want detailed information to justify how the 
benefits of more pollution will outweigh the detriments of lower water quality,&quot; Ambs concluded.</p>
<p>For more information contact Rivers Unlimited at 1207 Grandview Ave., Columbus, Ohio 43212; 
(614) 487-7511; e-mail: riveruoh@aol.com</p>
<hr>
