<html>

<head>
<title>Affinity - Great Lakes Water</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Great Lakes Water Safety Standard Should Be Set Higher</h3>
<p>Ohio Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) should set high standards to protect children and 
wildlife fromcancer-causing and endocrine-disrupting chemicals dumped into the Lake Erie 
watershed. By March 1997 the agency must finalize regulations to implement the Great Lakes 
Water Quality Initiative, a federal law passed in 1995 that aims to reduce toxic dumping into the 
Great Lakes.</p>
<p>&quot;All eight Great Lake states are currently working together to upgrade their water quality 
standards,&quot;said Edith Chase, president of the Ohio Coastal Resource Management Project and 
member of an Ohio EPA advisory committee helping to develop the new regulations. &quot;It started 
back in 1988 with the Council of Great Lakes Governors. It was their idea to say, 'Let's work 
together instead of competing for industry among ourselves. If we have consistent standards, then 
industry won't go pollution shopping'.&quot; Toxic chemicals regulated in the new program persist in the 
environment and can cause decreased fertility, birth defects, thyroid problems, and immune system 
damage in birds, fish, shellfish or mammals, according to the International Joint Commission on the 
Great Lakes. The Commission is a U.S.-Canadian agency overseeing Great Lakes protection.</p>
<p>&quot;The particular contaminants they worry about are called bioaccumulative chemicals of 
concern,&quot;Chase said. &quot;These are not only toxic in themselves, but when they are discharged into 
rivers and Lake Erie from a variety of sources, they end up in the sediments. Then the little 
creatures in the sediments munch on them. The bigger creatures, like crayfish and invertebrates, 
munch on the little ones and the fish munch on the invertebrates and it goes on up the food chain. At 
the top of the food web are two, the eagles and humans.&quot; Most eaglets born in the Lake Erie region 
still fail to thrive and live to maturity, according to Ohio EPA sources.</p>
<p>&quot;Mounting published evidence indicates that harm to humans from persistent toxic substances is 
similar to that caused in wildlife...Harm is being caused, at least in part, by in utero exposure to 
elevated levels of environmental estrogens,&quot; according to the International Joint Commission's 
Eighth Biennial Report on the Great Lakes. Children whose mothers consumed Great Lakes 
fishwhile pregnant were found to suffer developmental and behavioral problems. Men may suffer 
testicular cancer, genital tract disorders and lower fertility rates.Ohio EPA Director Donald 
Schregardus could set stringent rules protecting children from exposureto carcinogens in the water 
and fish. Chase and environmental representatives on the advisory committee are urging 
Schregardus to select a protective standard used in many federal programs that limits cancer risks 
to one additional cancer per million people exposed.</p>
<p>Kieth Linn, environmental specialist with the Northeast Ohio Regional Sewer District, and 
municipal and industry representatives on the committee are urging Ohio EPA to select a less 
restrictive one in 100,000 risk level .&quot; Society needs to ask itself what risk is acceptable. We 
encounter risks every day in our lives which are much greater than that,&quot;Linn said. &quot;I think the 
average risk of a person driving a car being in a fatal automobile accident is one in 70. You need to 
put it all into perspective. There really is no scientific basis for choosing an acceptable risk level. It 
is what society deems is acceptable.&quot;Pollution in the sediment, traveling in the atmosphere and 
non-point sources [such as agricultural runoff] contribute more pollutants than discharges do,&quot; Linn 
said.</p>
<p>Industrial discharges of&#160;cancer-causing&#160;and endocrine-disrupting chemicals should be strictly 
regulated while society&#160;tries&#160;to reduce other sources, Chase said. &quot;For years U.S. EPA used to 
consider cancer the most significant endpoint for risk. If they could get the cancer-risk down then 
they figured they could protect the population from other health effects,&quot; Chase said. &quot;The 
developmental and reproductive effects are apparent at much lower concentrations than cause 
cancer. We don't have the numbers to set for these non-cancer effects. If we set the risk level at 
one in a million, hopefully it will be protective of the reproductive and development effects. It is a 
safety margin.&quot;</p>
<p>Laura Yeomans is the research director for Citizen Action. Write to her at P.O. Box 8, Dover, 
Ohio 44622-0008.</p>
<hr>
