<title>Editor Letter</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Letter From the Editor</h3>
<h5 align=center>By Stefanie Mugridge</h5>
<p>Citizens should have the RIGHT TO KNOW about all of the chemicals that are discharged into 
their communities. This Mid Fall issue of Affinity informs readers about the Right-To-Know Act 
and the ways in which citizens can obtain records indicating some of the pollutants in their area.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, the Right-To-Know Act is one of the many environmental laws the Republican 
Congress has tried to deregulate. Currently, only 1% of the 72,000 chemicals that are in use today 
in the U.S. have to be reported by industry under the Right-To-Know Act. Citizens need to speak 
up and let the government know they want to be informed on anything happening in their 
community that may effect their health and that of their children or the environment.</p>
<p>The cover story &quot;Dishonorable Discharge&quot; reveals the rivers in Ohio that are the most polluted and 
the company&#185;s that are responsible for polluting them. Ohio Public Interest Research Group 
(PIRG) has done an extensive job in pin pointing the sources of chemical discharges into our 
waters. The full report, which is available to those interested by calling the Affinity office, goes into 
great detail about all the streams, river and lakes in Ohio that are being polluted by chemicals.</p>
<p>The Great Lakes article on page 3 talks about the need to come up with stronger regulations in 
protecting the Great Lakes ecosystem. The article on page 13 gives information into a specific 
problem on Lake Ontario which is affecting all of the Great Lakes. I learned about this issue while I 
was in the middle of my radio show (Earth Watch Radio, 89.3 fm, WCSB, Friday, 5:00-5:30 pm) 
and a woman came into the station and asked if she could have a few minutes of air time to explain 
what is happening in her home town. She spoke about the cancer rates that have skyrocketed in 
her town ever since Philip Environmental has come to Stoney Creek, Ontario. </p>
<p>She told of how her mom and dad had died of cancer and of her need to tour the Great Lakes in 
Canada and the U.S. to let people know what is happening to the health of her community and the 
Great Lakes Basin.I hope readers enjoy this issue of Affinity.</p>
<hr>
