<title>Affinity Sludge farming</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Sludge Farming Threatens Cuyahoga Valley</h3>
<h5 align=center>by Marilyn Christian</h5>
<p>This article will come as a shock to some people. For the communities of Boston and Richfield 
Townships, located in the Cuyahoga Valley National Park, this article reveals a nightmare come 
true. </p>
<p>Sludge is a black mud which is left over after the liquids have been removed from raw sewage. It 
contains levels of heavy metal, including lead, cadmium, arsenic, chromium, copper, nickel and zinc, 
along with bacteria, dioxins, polychlorinated&#160;biphenyls, pesticides, asbestos and other 
contaminants. </p>
<p>A sludge farm, recently purchased by Kurtz Bros. Compost Services, Inc., has begun operation on 
Major Road in Richfield. Major Road is south off of Streetsboro Road just east of I-271. 
Approximately 1 1/2 miles down Major, at the sharp left turn, you can see and smell the beginning 
of the sludge operation. On the right side of the road is a field where people frequently watch deer 
herds and sun sets. This field has been spoiled by a dirt/gravel road and a gate with an 
unwelcoming sign. This dirt road leads back behind the trees to the now operating Richfield 
Township sludge site.</p>
<p>The 49.9 acres across the street on the left side of Major Road, as well as the 20.7 acres on the 
south side of Major just west of Oakhill Road, are located in Boston Township. The Ohio 
Environmental Protection Agency (OEPA) has placed their rubber stamp of approval on all of 
these sites. The sludge that is stored on these lands is from the City of Kent&#185;s Wastewater 
Treatment Plant.</p>
<p>On November 13, 1995, Mr. Dean Stoll, Environmental Engineer for Division of Surface Water at 
the OEPA, wrote a letter to Mr. Bruce Bailey, the environmental coordinator at Kurtz Bros. 
Compost Services, Inc., stating that the Boston Township sites are acceptable locations for land 
application of sludge. He said, &quot;The sites are well isolated from neighboring properties and have 
acceptable soils.&quot;</p>
<p>Well guess what Mr. Stoll, Mr. Bailey and most of all Mr. Kurtz, there are neighboring properties 
and you are not isolated far enough away from us. The properties where these sludge farms exist 
are the headwaters for numerous creeks, streams, ponds and lakes. The fields are at the top of a 
hill with a community down stream that gets their drinking water from wells. </p>
<p>In a society where citizens are more aware of potential health risks and educated on how to avoid 
them, the allowance of sludge farming is not acceptable.</p>
<p>After hours of phone calls to neighbors, the Cuyahoga Valley National Park, local and national 
environmental groups, town officials and biologists, to find out more information concerning sludge, 
the result was overwhelming: &quot;Sludge is not risk free.&quot; There is no guarantee that our health and the 
health of future generations is not being jeopardized. </p>
<p>We were not given a choice in this matter. The OEPA and Mr. Kurtz made our choice for us. Now 
we are forced to live with their mistakes. If they would have asked us whether we wanted this 
sludge in our neighborhood they would have found a community of people who desire a clean and 
healthy environment in a sustainable balance with nature. We will have no tolerance for sludge! </p>
<p>For more information contact Marilyn Christian at (216) 657-2056. Marilyn wrote this article with 
the support of her husband Joe, family, community of people and most of all Mother Earth.</p>
<hr>
