<h2 align=center><a href="#Return to Top of Page" name="Community Activities">Community Activities</a></h2>
<p><a href="#A BENEFIT FOR LEONARD PELTIER">A BENEFIT FOR LEONARD PELTIER</a></p>
<p><a href="#EARTH WATCH RADIO">EARTH WATCH RADIO</a></p>
<p><a href="#FALL COLORS BACKPACKING">FALL COLORS BACKPACKING</a></p>
<p><a href="#EXPLORER LECTURE SERIES CLEVELAND MUSEUM OF NATURAL HISTORY">EXPLORER LECTURE SERIES</a></p>
<p><a href="#NORTH ROYALTON RESIDENTS' INVOLVEMENT COMMITTEE ">NORTH ROYALTON RESIDENTS' INVOLVEMENT COMMITTEE</a></p>
<p><a href="#CUYAHOGA COUNTY SOLID WASTE DISTRICT ">CUYAHOGA COUNTY SOLID WASTE DISTRICT </a></p>
<p><a href="#AMERICAN INDIAN CULTURAL APPRECIATION FESTIVAL">AMERICAN INDIAN CULTURAL APPRECIATION FESTIVAL</a></p>
<p><a href="#CUYAHOGA VALLEY ENVIRONMENTAL EDUCATION CENTER">CUYAHOGA VALLEY ENVIRONMENTAL EDUCATION CENTER</a></p>
<p><a href="#GREEN PARTY MEETINGS IN OHIO">GREEN PARTY MEETINGS IN OHIO</a></p>
<p><a name="A BENEFIT FOR LEONARD PELTIER">A BENEFIT FOR LEONARD PELTIER</a> October 13 - Peabody's Down Under - 8 pm This 
benefit is being held to raise consciousness and funds for the legal defense of jailed Native 
American activist LEONARD PELTIER. Peltier is serving two life sentences for the deaths of two 
FBI agents during a shoot out on the Pine Ridge reservation in 1975. The U.S. government has 
come out and said even they do not know who killed the agents. Witnesses were coerced, 
evidence fabricated, exculpatory evidence withheld, and perjury committed. Twenty years of 
LEONARD PELTIER'S life have been spent in prison. Come to Peabody's Down Under where 
local music will be played by Carlos Jones and the Peace Love and Unity Syndicate, Jim Miller of 
Oroboros, Eric Meany and the Diatribe, Shouting Mountain, and David and Marty. There will also 
be special guest speakers, information table and raffle. Tickets are $5.00 in advance and $7.00 day 
of show. For more information call (216) 721-4165 and leave a message and your call will be 
returned promptly.</p>
<p><a href="#Community Activities" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a name="EARTH WATCH RADIO">EARTH WATCH RADIO</a> Every Friday at 5:00 - 5:30 p.m. is Earth Watch Radio on 89.3 
WCSB. Tune in to learn about current environmental issues. Also, listeners can call in and ask their 
environmental questions. For more information call (216) 383-9985.</p>
<p><a href="#Community Activities" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a name="FALL COLORS BACKPACKING">FALL COLORS BACKPACKING</a> This program involves two evening classes and a 
moderately-paced weekend trip to Pennsylvania's Allegheny National Forest. It is for people with 
some experience day hiking, camping or backpacking. Newcomers to backpacking, however, are 
welcome. Our weekend trip will cover about eight miles with some &#179;off-trail&#178; map and compass 
travel. Pre-trip classes will cover basic skills including equipment choices and uses and menu 
planning. There are three sessions: Session A &#139; September 24 &amp; October 8; Session B &#139;September 
25 &amp; October 9; Session C &#139;September 30 &amp; October 14. For more information call (216) 
341-1704. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERNET Wednesday, October 23 North Chagrin Nature 
Center Lee Batdorff, a local internet consultant, will discuss using the internet and other on-line 
services for environmental research and networking. He will demonstrate actual sites such as RTK 
(Right to Know Net). Beginners as well as experienced users will benefit from this discussion. 
Plenty of opportunity for questions.</p>
<p><a href="#Community Activities" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a name="EXPLORER LECTURE SERIES CLEVELAND MUSEUM OF NATURAL HISTORY">EXPLORER LECTURE SERIES CLEVELAND MUSEUM OF NATURAL HISTORY</a> The 
Explorer Lecture Series features acclaimed scientists, environmentalists and adventurers from 
around the world. This year's topics range from monkey conservation and the wolves of 
Yellowstone to the great dinosaur egg hunt, biodiversity and exploring space with the Hubble 
Telescope. Two up coming events are: FRIDAY, OCTOBER 11 at 8 p.m. Dr. Elanor F. Helin 
from NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory will speak about Asteroid Cleveland, named in honor of 
the Bicentennial, and the hundreds of asteroids capable of approaching Earth or crossing its orbit. 
FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 8 AT 8 p.m. Douglas Smith, the lead biologist working to restore gray 
wolves to Yellowstone National Park, will discuss the history and politics of this controversial 
effort. He'll also share his personal experiences with wolves in the wild in this talk titled The Wolves 
of Yellowstone. For more information, call (216) 231-4600, ext. 218. </p>
<p><a href="#Community Activities" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a href="#NORTH ROYALTON RESIDENTS' INVOLVEMENT COMMITTEE " name="NORTH ROYALTON RESIDENTS' INVOLVEMENT COMMITTEE ">NORTH ROYALTON RESIDENTS' INVOLVEMENT COMMITTEE </a>September 27 at 7:30 
pm at Crown Point in Bath The North Royalton Residents' involvement committee is a grassroots 
citizens organization that started a few years ago in North Royalton by residents who were 
concerned about the uncontrolled growth facing our community. They have scheduled a preliminary 
get-acquainted, get-organized meeting for September 27. For more information call (216) 
237-4541. </p>
<p><a href="#Community Activities" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a name="AMERICAN INDIAN CULTURAL APPRECIATION FESTIVAL">AMERICAN INDIAN CULTURAL APPRECIATION FESTIVAL</a> OCTOBER 14 - 10 am - 6 
pm - Public Square Learn about and experience Native American dance, music, food and 
traditions. </p>
<p><a href="#Community Activities" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a name="CUYAHOGA VALLEY ENVIRONMENTAL EDUCATION CENTER">CUYAHOGA VALLEY ENVIRONMENTAL EDUCATION CENTER</a> (CVEEC) is nestled in 
scenic Cuyahoga Valley National Recreation Area. The center has laboratories, dining halls, 
dormitories (138 beds), meeting spaces and 500 acres of natural habitat. The CVEEC is jointly 
operated by the National Park Service and its non-profit partner, the Cuyahoga Valley 
Association. The CVEEC provides residents of northeast Ohio with hands-on programs that blend 
environmental problem solving, natural history and artistic expression. These programs explore 
conservation of regional water, land and air resources. The CVEEC is located 15 minutes north of 
Akron, or 25 minutes south of Cleveland in Peninsula, Ohio. For more information contact CVEEC 
at (216) 657-2796. </p>
<p><a href="#Community Activities" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a name="CUYAHOGA COUNTY SOLID WASTE DISTRICT ">CUYAHOGA COUNTY SOLID WASTE DISTRICT </a>A Guide to Used Motor Oil Recycling in 
Cuyahoga County is now available through the Cuyahoga County Solid Waste District. The guide 
lists service stations and cities that accept used motor oil for recycling from the general public at no 
charge. Every year in Cuyahoga County, an estimated 300,000 people change their own motor oil. 
While this can save the &#179;do it yourselfer&#178; money, this practice can come at the expense of our 
environment if the used oil is poured on the ground, down storm drains, or in the trash. This oil 
migrates into our ground water, streams, even Lake Erie. Just one gallon of used motor oil can 
contaminate one million gallons of drinking water when disposed improperly! This guide will make 
citizens aware of the proper way to recycle used motor oil. To receive a copy of the guide, call the 
Cuyahoga County Solid Waste District at (216) 443-3749. </p>
<p><a href="#Community Activities" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<p><a name="GREEN PARTY MEETINGS IN OHIO">GREEN PARTY MEETINGS IN OHIO</a>: Northeast Ohio Greens, alternate Thursdays, 9/26, 
10/10, etc. 3118 Carroll St, Cleveland, for info call (216) 631-0557. Northwest Ohio Greens, 
every Wed., call Mike Leonardi at (419) 242-2433 for info. For Green Party meetings in Athens 
call Bill Safranek at (614) 592-5025 and for meetings in Dayton area call Logan Martinez at (513) 
274-7003. Other locals are mobilizing around the state. For contacts in your area call David Ellison 
at 216-631-0557.</p>
