<body>
<h3 align=center>AFFINITY NEWS - October 3, 1996</h3>
<p align=left><a href="#Logging the Wayne National Forest "><strong>Logging the Wayne National Forest</strong></a></p>
<p align=left><a href="#Buckeye Forest Council Stages Rally to Protest Logging "><strong>Buckeye Forest Coucil Stages Rally to Protest Logging</strong></a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="Logging the Wayne National Forest ">Logging the Wayne National Forest </a></h3>
<p>After four years of virtually no logging on the Wayne National Forest in southeast Ohio, the U.S. 
Forest Service has recently proposed four new logging projects in an effort to jump-start a major 
timber program on the Wayne. One of these logging projects, the Bluegrass Ridge Timber Sale, 
was fought in federal court earlier this summer when the Buckeye Forest Council filed a lawsuit for 
Forest Service violations of the National Environmental Policy Act. Although over 100 acres were 
dropped from the logging project as a result of the suit, more than 300 acres are scheduled to be 
cut sometime this fall. </p>
<p>Another of the four sales, along Dorr Run, is still in the early stages of planning and public 
comment. These sales would allow logging on over 2,000 acres of the Wayne over the next five to 
seven years. These timber sales are being conducted in the name of forest health, although none are 
currently being painted as 'salvage sales' under the Salvage Logging rider. To propose that the 
forests need to be cut in order to save them is like proposing to put someone to death to prevent 
the flu. 'Forest health' is affected by a multitude of stresses, including air pollution, forest 
fragmentation, logging, and other effects, which combine to weaken the 'immune system' of forest 
ecosystems. This makes trees more susceptible to pathogen or insect attacks they normally would 
have resisted. The science behind the solution proposed by the Forest Service (increased logging) 
has been debunked by biologists nationwide.</p>
<h3 align=center><a name="Buckeye Forest Council Stages Rally to Protest Logging ">Buckeye Forest Council Stages Rally to Protest Logging </a></h3>
<p>Continuing the pressure on the Forest Service, the Buckeye Forest Council staged a protest at the 
Wayne Forest Service office in Athens, Ohio on September 12. A black bear presented the first 
annual &quot;Rusty Scapel Award&quot; for forest health malpractice to the U.S. Forest Service. The award 
will be given annually to agencies, corporations or individuals who demonstrate that quack science 
is not dead. &quot;The area where they want to log [Dorr Run] already has 30 miles of ORV trails, 36 
active oil and gas wells, 9.8 miles of oil and gas roads, and 4.7 miles of Forest Development 
Roads,&quot; said Daria Gere of the Buckeye Forest Council at the rally. &quot;In addition, the Dorr Run area 
has been logged, strip mined and deep mined. This is not a healthy forest. It needs time to heal and 
restore to a healthy, wild state. The last thing this forest needs is to be logged! The forest service 
talks about 'forest health.' But this timber sale, and all the others, are really about getting the cut out 
and subsidizing big timber industries.&quot; </p>
<p>Also at the rally, a petition with over 5,000 signatures was presented to the Forest Service, 
demanting that logging end on the Wayne. Six demands were given to Sharon Nyggard-Scott, 
District Ranger for the Athens unit. These demands included zero cutting on the Wayne, more 
wilderness, no new roads/close existing roads, increase land acquisition, stop breaking the law and 
tell the truth. One of the biggest problems with the logging industry, on both public and private lands 
in Ohio, is the waste. To illustrate this, speakers at the rally stood on a makeshift stage constructed 
from pallets. They explained that 84% of the tress cut in the state of Ohio are made into shipping 
pallets. Over two-thirds of these pallets are landfilled after a single use, representing the wholesale 
trashing of Ohio&#185;s forests. Another point that was emphasized was that most timber sales on public 
lands lose money. The U.S Forest Service loses over half a billion dollars annually from below cost 
timber sales, which represents a tremendous waste of taxpayer money. The rally concluded with 
Matt Peters and Than Hitt singing eco-tunes to the crowd, who participated in a rousing sing-along. 
For more information about logging on the Wayne, and other forest issues, contact the Buckeye 
Forest Council at P.O. Box 99, Athens, OH 45701; (614) 594-6400; e-mail: 
<a href="mailto:buckeye@envirolink.org">buckeye@envirolink.org</a></p>
<hr>
