<head>
<title>Affinity - Recycling</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>Closing the Loop of Recycling</h2>
<p>Despite some progress made by cities and towns in recycling, over 78% of the trash in our country 
is still headed to landfills and incinerators. Burying and Burning trash causes air and water pollution 
and other environmental and public health problems besides wasting natural resources. Clearly, the 
need to improve the nation's recycling cannot be overemphasized.</p>
<p>Successful recycling is hampered due to a marked absence of strong markets for materials 
collected in local recycling programs. Manufacturers need to therefore buy recyclables and turn 
them into new recycled products. However, only when there is a strong demand for these new 
products, can the market for recyclables improve. The federal government has already taken the 
first significant step towards &quot;closing this loop&quot; on recycling by passing the &quot;Buy Recycled&quot; 
Executive Order in 1993. The federal offices are now committed to purchasing printing and writing 
paper made of a minimum 20% post-consumer recycled content, which means made of materials 
from local recycling programs. Given the large purchasing power of State and local governments 
and large institutions such as universities, they too need to adopt similar mechanisms to make 
critical and significant improvements to the market for recycled products.</p>
<p>The Ohio Public Interest Research Group (Ohio PIRG) just completed a &quot;BUY RECYCLED&quot; 
campaign in the state of Ohio. Efforts of Ohio PIRG were directed towards urging cities and 
counties within Ohio to adopt a resolution that would mandate buying of recycled paper containing 
20% post-consumer material as long as the price of recycled paper was within 10% of the cost of 
virgin paper. Extensive research during the campaign revealed that good quality recycled paper is 
now available locally and at competitive prices. Scores of cities and counties across the country as 
well as the cities of Mansfield, Lakewood and Cincinnati in Ohio already have a working &quot;Buy 
Recycled Paper&quot; resolution. Last month, Cuyahoga County and Medina County adopted the 
proposed resolution thereby providing a boost to a recycling economy, conservation of resources, 
waste reduction and a cleaner environment.</p>
<p>While these initiatives are exemplary and encouraging, it is imperative for other local governments 
to follow suit and reaffirm their commitment to the environment. Concerned citizens of Ohio can 
play an important role in bringing about this change. One mechanism would be to call local 
governments and urge them to adopt a &quot;Buy Recycled Paper&quot; policy that is as strong as the federal 
government's. Another would be to write a letter-to-the-editor for local newspapers calling for 
&quot;Buy Recycled Paper&quot; policies locally and statewide.</p>
<p>For more information call Ohio PIRG at (216) 791-1116.</p>
</body>

</html>
