<head>
<title>Affinity letter from editor</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>I am happy to announce that AFFINITY has reached the goals it set out to achieve. The purpose 
of this publication is to provide information that helps citizens take a more active role in protecting 
their environment. In addition, AFFINITY serves as a forum for citizens and environmental activists 
to voice their concerns. </p>
<p>Citizens call in from all over the state to tell their stories. From urban sprawl to sludge farming, 
people are reaching out to AFFINITY for help. They need exposure on their issues and 
information on how to organize in their communities to stop the destruction to the environment and 
their health.</p>
<p>In this issue of AFFINITY, readers will find articles that focus on human health problems resulting 
from chemicals. The cover story focuses on the Multiple Chemical Sensitivity (MSC) issue. There 
are countless people suffering from this disorder all over the world. As society continues to 
encourage the use of chemicals we will see tremendous increases in cancer rates and other chronic 
disorders such as MCS.</p>
<p>The article on biotechnology on page three discusses the implications of genetically engineered 
foods. After reading this article, it is impossible not to question whether this world is headed in the 
wrong direction. </p>
<p>On page six of this issue, readers can learn about the struggle of two communities in Ohio fighting 
sludge farming. These articles are perfect examples of citizens fighting to protect their homes. The 
problem now exists in their backyards and they are ready to fight. </p>
<p>Nearing six years of publishing AFFINITY, I am proud of what it has become. Thanks to the 
advertisers who have made publishing possible and to the readers who have expressed their 
appreciation for the paper. </p>
<p>Special thanks to my family who has always been very supportive of my efforts&#139; and to my husband 
who helps out more than I can express. How did I do it all those years without him? He is the best! </p>
<p>I hope readers enjoy this Early Fall issue of AFFINITY. If readers are interested in receiving 
AFFINITY by mail or making a donation to the paper, see the form on page 15.</p>
<p>It's hard to believe the summer has passed and fall is here. until next time,</p>
<hr>
