<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Affinity - clear cutting in NW</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Clear-Cuts Causing Landslides
in the Pacific Northwest</font></h2>

<p><font size="2">A landslide, originating in a 1987 clear-cut
unit, brought four hard working Douglas County citizens to a
violent, tragic death last week. The Oregon Department of
Forestry claims that the timber company who clear-cut the land
above the destroyed home had followed the regulations under the
Forest Practices Act. If this is true, then the Forest Practices
Act is failing to safeguard the lives of many rural residents.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">All over Oregon, landslides occurring in
clear-cuts logged under the Forest Practices Act have damaged
adjoining private property, degraded fish habitat, and fouled the
state&#146;s water. The 1975 US Forest Service study of
clear-cutting in the western Cascade Range in Oregon concludes
that non-road related landslides occur almost 3 times more often
in clearcuts than forested areas. It also concludes that
&quot;most hillslope failures in clearcut areas occurred in the
first 12 years after cutting.&quot; (See USFS study referenced
below.) Other recent surveys of landslides caused by last
year&#146;s heavy rains show an even greater correlation between
clear-cuts and landslides. It is unconscionable that the law
still allows logging practices that are known to increase the
likelihood of landslides.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Now that it&#146;s dramatically clear that our
rural neighbors&#146; lives are in danger, we must immediately
re-examine and strengthen the rules that regulate the logging of
timber land. Moreover, we must move quickly to assess existing
clear-cut units for potential slope failure. To prevent any
further danger to human lives, all clear-cut units harvested
under the rules of the Forest Practices Act for the past 12 years
should be immediately examined for indications of possible slope
failure. Where indications of possible failure occur, all
downstream residents must be immediately warned so they can take
measures to prevent loss of life and property. Countless rural
residents live down stream from clearcuts less than 12 years old.
It is imperative that we take immediate action to prevent any
further loss of life.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The clear-cut that produced the fatal landslide
was on rocky, unstable soil with steep slopes that ranged from 60
percent to 120 percent. In addition, the law allowed the
clear-cutting of the entire riparian buffer on the creek that was
the course for the slide. In light of these facts, we call upon
the Oregon Department of Forestry to place an immediate
moratorium on clear-cutting timber on slopes until the current
laws have been reviewed and modified to eliminate landslide
danger and adequately prevent soil disturbance.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">The people who died from this landslide had
been living in their rural home for many years before industry
clear-cut their watershed. All over the state, large numbers of
rural residents live below industrial forest land. We must take
these tragic deaths as a warning that our forestry laws and
regulations need to be strengthened. It is time for a complete
overhaul of the state Forest Practices Act. We must act now to
prevent any further loss of life.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">References: &quot;Impact of clear-cutting and
road construction on soil erosion by landslides in the western
Cascade Range, Oregon,&quot; 1975 F.J. Swanson, Department of
Geology, University of Oregon, Eugene, Oregon C.T. Dryness, USDA
Forest Service, Pacific Northwest Forest and Range Experiment
Station, Corvallis, Oregon. Published in Geology, July, 1975. For
more information contact Bob Allen at (541) 672-5239 or Francis
Eatherington at (541) 673-7649.</font></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

