<head>
<title>affinity - Earth Watch</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>EARTH WATCH</h2>
<p><strong>EXTINCTION?</strong></p>
<p>&quot;Nearly one quarter of the world's mammal species are threatened with extinction and about half of 
those may be gone in as little as a decade,&quot; says a report from the IUCN-World Conservation 
Union. An article in the Washington Post says that conservationists called the report &quot;surprising and 
frightening.&quot; Of 4,600 known species of mammals, the report finds 1096 at risk.</p>
<p><strong>MT. SELLMORE</strong></p>
<p>A &quot;late blooming&quot; bill before the House Resources Committee to allow corporations to become 
official sponsors of national parks is a contender for &quot;worst idea of the year,&quot; says the Washington 
Post. The measure would allow sponsors &quot;limited recognition&quot; in the parks and mention of their 
sponsorship in advertisements in return for their financial contributions. &quot;It's precisely to escape the 
world of corporate logos that people go to the parks,&quot; the Post argues. &quot;These are public parks, 
not private billboards, and they ought to stay that way.&quot;</p>
<p><strong>ROAD TO RUIN </strong></p>
<p>A taxpayer-conservationist coalition wants to halt 22 &quot;wasteful and environmentally destructive&quot; 
highways, says a release from Taxpayers for Common $ense and Friends of the Earth. &quot;It's time for 
the government to pull over for directions,&quot; says TC$'s Ralph De Gennaro. A national campaign to 
kill unnecessary road projects is planned; among the targets are a $288 million highway &quot;designed 
to ease traffic jams after Penn State football games&quot; and a $750 million road project that would 
&quot;pave through some of South Carolina's last bottomland hardwood forests.&quot;</p>
<p><strong>OCEAN PERIL</strong></p>
<p>&quot;For the first time, some scientists are saying that some species of ocean fish and invertebrates are 
reaching the perilously low levels where extinction becomes a real possibility,&quot; the New York 
Times reported Tuesday. Next month more than 100 species of oceanic fish will be added to the 
World Conservation Union's &quot;red list&quot; of endangered creatures.</p>
<p><strong>EVERY AMERICAN</strong></p>
<p>All citizens have a stake in protecting Utah's wildlands, &quot;since the land in question belongs to the 
people of this nation, not the politicians in Utah,&quot; actor Robert Redford writes in the LA Times. 
Redford defends the designation of the Staircase-Escalante National Monument by President 
Clinton under the Antiquities Act for both economic and environmental reasons. Business comes to 
Utah &quot;because employees want to raise their families in proximity to the region's pure, open 
spaces,&quot; Redford argues. And rural economic growth in Utah is related to &quot;an unprecedented 
increase of tourism,&quot; not extractive industries.</p>
<p><strong>NO REPEAL</strong></p>
<p>Hours avter Vice President Al Gore told a PBS audience that the &quot;salvage&quot; rider was the &quot;biggest 
mistake&quot; of the Clinton administration's four years, the White House abandoned efforts to seek 
repeal of both the logging and the Mt. Graham riders in the Omnibus spending bill. The House 
passed the measure Saturday; the Senate votes today. The Washington Post reports that the White 
House &quot;succeeded in getting practically all of its demands&quot; in the negotiations. &quot;The White House 
tried, but not very hard,&quot; says Connie Stewart of the Western Ancient Forest Campaign. &quot;Now 
everyone can go out and campaign on protecting the environment while the worst law of the 104th 
Congress remains in full force.&quot;</p>
<p><strong>ANIMAL LOVE CANAL?</strong></p>
<p>Robert McKinnell, a geneticist and cancer expert at the University of MN, concludes that &quot;we 
should be alarmed&quot; because of the widespread deformities found in frogs at more than 100 sites in 
MN. The Washington Post reported on a conference of scientists held in Duluth MN to study the 
phenomenon. Environmental degradation is considered by many of the scientists to be the reason 
for the deformities, with &quot;some kind of chemical pollutant&quot; the most &quot;probable cause of that 
degradation.&quot; McKinnell says that frogs serve as a &quot;sentinel species&quot; because many of their 
metabolic functions, notably in the liver, &quot;are similar to the same processes in humans.&quot;</p>
<p><strong>ALAR COVERAGE</strong></p>
<p>Greenwire reports that a Columbia Journalism Review article about how the news media covered 
the pesticide Alar concludes that mistaken media coverage &quot;has contributed to the public &#140;myth' 
that the pesticide Alar poses no health threat.&quot; Although Alar &quot;has become a favorite media symbol 
for a false alarm,&quot; studies have confirmed that Alar is an animal and &quot;probable human&quot; carcinogen, 
according to EPA sources. A &quot;sophisticated public relations counterattack&quot; mounted by the food 
industry was responsible for erroneous reporting on Alar by major newspapers, says John Stauber 
of the newsletter PR Watch</p>
<p><strong>COLLECT AND PROTECT</strong></p>
<p>New endangered species postage stamps went on sale last week, &quot;intended to promote awareness 
of the hundreds of North American animals currently in danger of becoming extinct,&quot; reports 
Greenwire based on a San Diego Union-Tribune article and a USPS release. Among the 15 
species featured are the black-footed ferret, the ocelot, the Gila trout, the piping plover, the 
California condor, and the Florida manatee. The stamps were unveiled in a ceremony at the San 
Diego zoo.</p>
<p><strong>CORPORATE CLEANUP</strong></p>
<p>December 3 will be observed as &quot;Corporate Cleanup Day&quot; to commemorate the victims of the 
Bhopal tragedy and &quot;bring to the attention of the world the wrongs and injustices being committed 
by powerful corporations all the time.&quot; The event, on the anniversary of the Bhopal incident, is a <br>
&quot;national day of corporate accountability,&quot; says Communities Concerned About Corporations, its 
sponsor. For an information packet write to Nan Hardin, 210 W. Jennings St., Newburgh IN 
47630.</p>
<p><strong>LAX LOGGING</strong></p>
<p>A survey of more than 200 logging operations in Washington state found 68% of them violated fish 
and wildlife rules, and &quot;few violators were cited by regulators,&quot; the AP reports. &quot;It's alarming,&quot; said 
Joseph Pavel from the Northwest Indian Fish Commission and a member of the Timber, Fish, and 
Wildlife group that conducted the survey. &quot;We have regulations on the books . . Basically, they're 
not being enforced.&quot;</p>
<p>PERILOUS WATER</p>
<p>&quot;Without drastic change, the nation's tap water faces an increasingly perilous future,&quot; a Houston 
Chronicle series concludes according to an article in Greenwire. The series reports that one of 
every five water systems in the U.S. violates a health standard, with aging water distribution pipes 
and treatment plants &quot;a large part of the problem. &quot; Legislation passed by Congress this year 
&quot;focuses resources on the most serious water contaminants but is too limited in its scope and 
funding to address many other problems,&quot; the report says.</p>
<p><strong>FROG SLEUTHING</strong></p>
<p>Minnesota scientists are still puzzled by a outbreak of malformed frogs in the upper Midwest. The 
Minneapolis Star Tribune reports that scientists analyzing the frog malformations remain convinced 
that the cause is at least partially environmental, not due to a snake parasite as reported earlier in 
the week. A biologist with the Minnesota Pollution Control agency, Mark Gernes said, &quot;Parasites 
might be one of the contributors.[b]ut I think there might be more than one cause. [Frogs] are fairly 
significant indicators of health in our environment.We ask ourselves what has changed in the 
environment in the last two years.&quot;</p>
<hr>
