<tr><td width=50%></td><td width=50%></td></tr>
</table>
<h4 align=left><a name="DIOXINS AND EAGLES">DIOXINS AND EAGLES</a></h4>
<p>The loss of six bald eagles would likely result from dioxin discharges from a Maine paper mill into 
the Penobscot River, according to a Fish &amp; Wildlife Service (FWS) biological opinion issued in late 
August. An article in &quot;Greenwire&quot; from several sources says the FWS &quot;will study the effects of 
dioxin on bald eagles that eat contaminated fish from the river&quot; to determine if the EPA should 
reduce Lincoln Pulp &amp; Paper Co.'s dioxin limit. &quot;Some enviros are demanding that Marine paper 
mill not be allowed to discharge any dioxin into rivers,&quot; the article reports. &quot;These eagles need more 
study of dioxin like they need a hole in the head,&quot;says Peter Washburn of the Natural Resources 
Council in Maine. </p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="TAKE THE MONEY:">TAKE THE MONEY:</a></h3>
<p>A Sierra Club report shows that current Members of Congress took nearly $50 million from 
&quot;polluter PACs&quot;(Political Action Committees) and then voted to weaken key environmental 
protections. The report &quot;confirms a strong and deeply disturbing relationship between 
anti-environmental PAC giving and voting records,&quot; says the Club. The Club's study of Federal 
Election Commission records shows that 660 political action committees associated with anti- 
environmental causes or legislation donated a &quot;whopping&quot;$46 million to Members of the 104th 
Congress since December 1993.</p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="MORE FIRES ">MORE FIRES </a></h3>
<p>Experts say the great forests of the West &quot;need more fire rather than less,&quot;reports the Washington 
Post this September. Some scientists argue that this year's &quot;explosion&quot;of fire is the inevitable result 
of &quot;decades of well-intended but misguided fire suppression practices&quot;as well as poor logging 
practices. But in Washington DC, the fires &quot;are also igniting a political debate&quot;with the timber 
industry arguing for more cutting in spite of a recent study of Sierra Nevada forests concluding that 
logging &quot;increased fire severity more than any other human activity.</p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="NO FORESTS, NO FIRES ">NO FORESTS, NO FIRES </a></h3>
<p>An ad in &quot;Roll Call&quot;from the National Forest Protection Campaign takes on logging industry 
arguments that &quot;if we just let them cut down our National Forests, we won't have to worry about 
forest fires.&quot;The ad attacks S. 391, the Craig &quot;forest health&quot;bill, calling it &quot;another example of this 
Congress's assault on the American people's right to a safe and healthy environment.&quot;The timber 
industry has claimed that &quot;salvage&quot;logging is necessary to reduce forest fire danger; a hearing by a 
House Resources subcommittee will look at Forest Service fire management policy this September.</p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="ESTUARY PLANS">ESTUARY PLANS</a></h3>
<p>A national grassroots campaign and legislation aimed at restoring one million acres of estuary 
habitat by the year 2010 will be the subject of a briefing and press conference in September in 
Washington D.C. &quot;Estuary habitats -- salt marshes, wetlands, river deltas and shellfish beds -- are 
under great threat,&quot;says the group Restore America's Estuaries, the event's sponsor. &quot;If we do 
nothing to halt their destruction, we could lose up to 600,000 more acres ... by 2010.&quot;For more 
information call (202) 289-2380. </p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="WOLF CONFERENCE ">WOLF CONFERENCE </a></h3>
<p>Scientists, wolf activists, agency personnel and the public will consider &quot;wolf biology, management 
and recovery&quot;at a Defenders of Wildlife conference on the &quot;Wolves of America.&quot;The event will be 
held November 14-16 in Albany NY; live &quot;ambassador wolves&quot;will be a part of the program, as 
will workshops, technical sessions and &quot;forums on the status of wolf recovery efforts in the U.S. To 
register by phone or for more information call Defenders at (202) 789-2844 x-334.</p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="&quot;GRAVY TRAIN&quot;">&quot;GRAVY TRAIN&quot;</a></h3>
<p>American taxpayers &quot;are being fleeced by the federal grazing fee system,&quot;says an op-ed in the 
Washington Times by Sens. Judd Gregg (R-NH) and Dale Bumpers (D-AR). They say that the 
Domenici grazing bill that passed the Senate in March would set grazing fees at $1.63 per animal 
unit month (AUM), &quot;lower than the lowest federal fee charged between the years 1989-1994.&quot;The 
Senators argue that the current grazing fees, and those proposed in the Domenici bill, &quot;contain 
stewardship disincentives that promote overgrazing and degradation of public land while stripping 
the public of its right to protest federal grazing decisions and allowing private ranchers to sublease 
public lands at high profits.&quot;</p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="STEWARDSHIP UNDER SIEGE SAYS DEFENDERS">STEWARDSHIP UNDER SIEGE SAYS DEFENDERS</a></h3>
<p>A report released by Defenders of Wildlife over the Labor Day weekend cautions Americans 
against thinking their public lands are safe. The report concludes that a &quot;September Surprise&quot;of at 
least 18 public lands attacks will be taken up by Congress, now back in session. Defenders' 
President Rodger Schlickeisen says, &quot;Although the public may think that Congress is turning green 
before the election, we're seeing red for danger ahead.&quot;The report, called Stewardship Under 
Siege: The Coming Attack on Our Public Lands, is available by calling Ken Goldman at (202) 
682-9400 x-221.</p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="RED TIDES ">RED TIDES </a></h3>
<p>Links between algal blooms, threatened wildlife, sewage and hog farms are discussed in an article 
in the New York Times. Reporting that some scientists believe there is a &quot;serious global 
epidemic&quot;of marine microorganisms that cause dangerous red tides, the Times says these scientists 
are &quot;urging action to reduce the runoff of sewage and other nutritive substances that seem to 
promote the poisonous blooms.&quot;Reporting research in North Carolina that seems to link phosphate 
enrichment from hog farm sewage to fish kills, the article says that &quot;a growing fear, intriguing but 
unconfirmed, is that nutrient runoff . . is feeding the growth of the marauding [microorganism] 
swarms. Algal blooms affect not just NC: &quot;Every single coastal state has this problem in one form 
or another,&quot; says Dr. Donald Anderson.</p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="OPPOSE CLEARCUTS">OPPOSE CLEARCUTS</a></h3>
<p>A letter from the Sporting Goods Manufacturers Association says the group is &quot;shocked to find that 
abuses from last year's salvage rider have led to the clearcutting of significant stands of live green 
trees.&quot;The group is asking Senators to oppose &quot;new timber clearcut legislation&quot;such as Sen. Larry 
Craig's S. 391. &quot;When the facts are known, it is clear that the clearcut logging proposals in this 
Congress are anti-jobs as well as anti-environment and fiscally unsound.</p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="&quot;ENVIRONMENT &quot;AT RISK&quot;">&quot;ENVIRONMENT &quot;AT RISK&quot;</a></h3>
<p>The &quot;fevered atmosphere&quot;of the last month of the 104th Congress puts the environment at risk from 
&quot;a score of proposals that threaten national forests, rangelands and other public spaces,&quot;says the 
New York Times. &quot;Most of these bills are too controversial to survive as freestanding 
measures,&quot;the Times says, but they could be attached &quot;like so many freight cars&quot;to various 
legislative &quot;trains.&quot;The Domenici grazing bill, anti-Tongass provisions, and Sen. Larry Craig's &quot;forest 
health&quot;bill are among the threats that the Times cites.</p>
<p><a href="#Articales" name="Return to Top of Page">Return to Top of Page </a></p>
<hr>
