<title>Air breathe affinity Oct 15</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>The Air I Breathe Makes Me Sick</h2>
<h5 align=center>by Amy Simpson</h5>
<p>Toni Temple suffers from Multiple Chemical Sensitivity (MCS). MCS is a disorder triggered by 
exposure to chemicals in the environment. Synthetic chemicals are all around us. They are in the 
products we use, clothes we wear, food we ear and air we breathe. Because chemicals are 
everywhere, it is not possible to escape exposure. It is no wonder, then, that many people have 
become sensitized to the chemicals around them. In fact, it is estimated that 15% of the population 
has become sensitized to common household and commercial products. </p>
<p>Toni's illness resulted from her malfunctioning water softner and furnace that releasec zinc chloride 
into the air in her home. Once leading a normal, healthy life - Toni is now legally disabled and on 
social security disability. She suffers from extreme chemical sensitivity, anemia and chronic bolld 
clotting problems as a result of her exposure to chemicals. When Toni ventures outside her home, 
she often wears a respirator with special filters to reduce the amount of chemicals reaching her nose 
and mouth. MCS may result from a single massive exposure to one or more toxic substances or 
repeated exposures to lower doses. On one hand, some people may become chemically sensitive 
following a toxic chemical spill at work or in their community or after being sprayed directly with 
pesticides. On the other hand, individuals may develop this condition from spending forty hours 
each week in a poorly ventilated building where they breathe a mixture of chemicals common to our 
modern way of life. </p>
<p>MCS affects the overall health and feeling of those with the disorder. It typically impairs many 
bodily functions including the nervous system and digestion. People with MCS experience a 
number of symptoms: headaches, asthma, increased sensitivity to odors, bloating short and 
long-term memory loss, dizziness and chronic exhaustion. These symptoms may, at times, seem like 
allergies because they tend to come and go with exposure to chemicals. </p>
<p>WHAT CAUSES MCS? In non-industrial workplaces, a number of common products and 
processes are often identified as contributing to the onset of MCS. These are off gassing of new 
carpets, cleaning supplies, pesticides and wood preservatives, new building materials and 
furnishings, toxic chemicals used in art, photography, printing, etc., formaldehyde in new clothes, 
inks, laser printer toner, house paints and vehicle exhaust fumes, perfumes, detergents, artificial 
colors, flavors and preservatives in food, drink and medicines.</p>
<p>When our bodies are assaulted with levels of toxic chemicals our system cannot safely process, it is 
likely that at some point in our life we will become sick due to the chemicals we are exposed to. 
For some, the result could be cancer or reproductive damage. Others may become hypersensitive 
to these chemicals or devlop other chronic disorders. Some people may not experience any 
noticeable negative health effects. The threshold for toxic injury is not the ame for everyone 
because sensitivity varies greatly among individuals. Most chemcials in consumer products are not 
tested for negative health effects such as cancer and reproductive problems nor for the impact of 
long-term low level exposure. The effects of these substances on women, children and people with 
existing conditions is also untested.</p>
<p>IS THERE A CURE FOR MCS? Though there is no cure for MCS, there are, at the present time, 
several treatment available that seem to improve the baseline health status of some patients. With 
the onset of MCS, a person's health generally continues to deteriorate. Signs of improvement 
usually occur only after the chemical sensitivity condition is uncovered and action is taken to avoid 
the chemical toxins at fault. </p>
<p>THE MCS CONTROVERSY Many traditional allergists and other physicians discount the MCS 
diagnosis. They claim that there is not yet sufficient evidence to substantiate that MCS exists. 
Research efforts regarding the mechanisms that cause MCS have been inadequate and 
unfortunately are often financed and supported by the industries which benefit from chemical 
proliferation. Generally, medical doctors have not yet been trained to understand nor have tehy 
seriously investigated MCS. </p>
<p>Fortunately for those afflicted with MCS, Toni Temple recently published, Healthier Hospitals, an 
MCS disability access manual. It was produced primarily to educate hospital administration, staff 
and medical personnel on proper care and consideration regarding the special needs of MCS 
patients. The 28-page manual is the direct result of the combined efforts of its author, Toni Temple 
and two local hospitals. It is hoped that Healthier Hospitals will improve access issues for those 
hospital patients who suffer from this widespread disability. Patients with MCS may have 
sensitivities to common chemicals. They can experience problems ranging from mild discomfort to 
severe, life-threatening reactions. &quot;This book was written,&#178; said Temple, &quot;because the needs of 
MCS patients were not being met simply because hospitals did not know what those needs were 
or how to accommodate them. This manual simplifies what can be done, how to make it work and 
creates good will and benefits for both the patient and the medical facility at very little or no cost. I 
feel this educational tool will help prevent further misunderstanding of chemical sensitivity disability 
and provide better health care for those with MCS.&quot; People who suffer from MCS typically spend 
most of their time in a &quot;sanctuary&quot; they create in their home which is free of chemical emissions. The 
amount of chemicals in our society is ever increasing. It is time people start using natural alternatives 
to these chemicals that are making people sick. For more information on MCS or to request a 
copy of the Healthier Hospitals manual contact Toni Temple at (216) 230-1985. Some of the 
information in this article was obtained from a booklet written by Tracy Frisch and published by the 
Multiple Chemical Sensitivity in the Workplace Taskforce, 33 Central Ave., Albany, NY 12210; 
(518) 426-8246. </p>
<hr>
