<title>Metroparks affinity 101196</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>Clearcutting and Poisoning the Metroparks</h2>
<h5 align=center>by Kim Wendel</h5>
<p>The battle may be over, but can the war be won?</p>
<p>A group of Cleveland Metroparks users is concerned over the park's new guidelines over trimming 
and vegetative maintenance. Yes, the district's Board of Park Commissioners accepted the 
first-ever written guidelines for such matters, on Aug. 13. However, the commissioners did not vote 
to adopt them and have no plans to do so. </p>
<p>The Metroparks golf courses and the Cleveland Metroparks zoo are exempted from the guidelines, 
and they allow the use of herbicides and pesticides throughout the district. This bothers the park 
users. </p>
<p>&quot;Why should we [vote to adopt them]?&quot; Board President Fred Rzepka said Tuesday. &quot;First of all, I 
do not understand the total story because I am not a scientist. A group of people next year might 
decide that the guidelines are wrong, and I am not going to vote on an issue that may change next 
year. </p>
<p>&quot;Just let it [the guidelines] be there. As long as the staff is happy with it, we don't need to vote on 
it.&quot; </p>
<p>However, the users fear that the new guidelines are too broad to address specific issues&#139;such as 
why areas severely damaged by prior trimming are not being allowed to grow back naturally.</p>
<p>The new guidelines were developed with input from citizens, as well as Tom Stanley, the 
Metroparks' chief of natural resources, and Park Forestry managers. They were developed in the 
aftermath of a protest last March, over Executive Director Vern J. Hartenburg's clearcutting and 
trimming program in several Metroparks reservations, including Rocky River, Mill Stream and 
South Chagrin.</p>
<p>That program eradicated much undergrowth in some forested areas. Hartenburg said he ordered it 
in the name of safety, but the park users said it ruined the parks' natural look and robbed small 
animals of their habitat. As a result of the protests, Hartenburg immediately declared a 30-day 
moratorium on the trimming. The moratorium became permanent in May. </p>
<p>Also, park district commissioners removed Hartenburg from the trimming program and assigned it 
to Stanley. New guidelines were drawn up and accepted Aug. 13. In general, the new trimming 
guidelines give more power to each park reservation manager, who are best able to determine the 
needs of each reservation, commissioners said. The guidelines stress conservation and &quot;the natural 
system&quot; as the main considerations in making vegetative maintenance decisions. </p>
<p>But the angry park users from the South Chagrin Reservation, who launched the protest last 
March, fear that the work orders issued under the new guidelines will &quot;stretch the bounds&quot; of the 
guidelines.</p>
<p>Last month, three of the original 10 who had objected to Hartenburg's program voiced specific 
concerns. Among them, that the previously cleared areas in the South Chagrin Reservation, most 
notable the arboretum, were not being allowed to grow back to their natural state as promised. 
Instead, they continue to be mowed flush to the ground.</p>
<p>Moreland Hills residents Barbara Jung and Hobie Cleminshaw and Solon resident Pat Marshall cite 
loopholes and omissions in the guidelines that might provide a way to circumvent their usefulness. 
They also believe the use of herbicides and pesticides, which is deliberately not addressed in the 
guidelines, may be the next obstacle they have to surmount. </p>
<p>&quot;As the guidelines went through several drafts and revisions, the references to the use of herbicides 
were totally removed,&quot; Marshall said. &quot;They said the reason was because herbicides are too big of 
an issue to deal with in a guideline rundown. But we are seeing them use herbicides where they 
once were cutting underbrush or trimming around posts and trees. So, technically, they aren't 
trimming. </p>
<p>&quot;Although there are general signs posted at the entrances that herbicides are used in the 
reservations, I have never seen any signs to let the public know exactly when the area was last 
sprayed. Your kids and dogs could be rolling around in grass that was treated a half hour earlier 
with herbicides and you wouldn't know it. </p>
<p>&quot;They use it around picnic tables and rest rooms continually. &quot;That's a huge concern in my mind 
because they have been using herbicides in the parks for the past two years,&quot; she said. Marshall is 
strongly against the use of chemical management for control. &quot;The use of herbicides and pesticides 
should be closely examined, whether it is used in a reservation or a golf course,&quot; she said. </p>
<p>Stanley is working on the herbicide issue in each reservation. One suggestion would require park 
personnel to post small white signs after spraying, similar to those used by landscaping companies 
in residential neighborhoods. There is a reason why Stanley is addressing the herbicide issue 
separately. </p>
<p>Two of the areas where herbicides are used extensively are the park district's golf courses and the 
Cleveland Metropark Zoo. Those are also the two areas where extensive trimming and manicuring 
of the facilities are, by his own earlier admissions in April, most desired by Hartenburg. </p>
<p>Between the second draft of the guidelines, dated June 1, and the third draft, dated June 19, a 
section was inserted which stated that the guidelines were for all areas of all reservations, &quot;with the 
exception of golf courses and Cleveland Metroparks zoo.&quot; It is also between those two drafts that 
the reference to herbicide use was removed. </p>
<p>The park users vow to continue to monitor the district. They attend every board meeting and they 
hope they can affect changes in park district policies. They said at least one commissioner seemed 
to take their concerns seriously at the Aug. 13 board meeting. After a short discussion on the 
guidelines spearheaded by Vice President David W. Whitehead, he and the other two 
commissioners&#139;Rzepka and Vice President John K. O'Toole&#139;verbally agreed to &quot;see that the 
guidelines are at least implemented and followed.&quot; For more information call Barbara Jung at (216) 
247-7985. </p>
<hr>
