<!--header ends here-->	

<h5>Contact: <A HREF="/media/contacts/cummins.htm">Lin Cummins</A>

(<a href="mailto:lcummins@uta.com">lcummins@uta.com</a>)<br>
(313) 593-9475</h5>


<H2>Reaching the global marketplace</H2>

<EM>The following remarks were prepared for delivery by <A HREF="/general/people/norm.htm">Norman R. Bodine</A>, president and CEO of UT Automotive, at the SAE Global Vehicle Development Conference in Detroit on Thursday, Dec. 5, 1996.
</EM><p>

I'm very happy that UT Automotive was invited to be a part of this conference, and that I can be with you today. <p>
UT Automotive is just one piece of a very dynamic corporation. While most of you know about <A HREF="http://www.uta.com">UT Automotive</A>, I suspect that many of you aren't aware of the worldwide resources that stand behind our company.
Our company builds jet engines by <A HREF="http://www.pratt-whitney.com">Pratt & Whitney</A>, helicopters  by <A HREF="http://www.sikorsky.com">Sikorsky</A>, <A HREF="http://www.otis.com">Otis</A> elevators, <A HREF="http://www.carrier.com">Carrier</A> heating and air conditioning units, and UT Automotive systems.<p>
United Technologies is a company that operates on every continent of the world; a company whose vast global resources provide the service, experience and technology so much in demand by OEMs today. And UTC has products in every country in the world, except one -- North Korea.
<p>Speaking of global reach, more than half of UTC's revenues -- totaling more than $23 billion last year -- are generated outside of the United States.
The reason I'm telling you this is because our connection to United Technologies gives us a huge advantage over most other companies when moving into new markets. In most areas of the world where we want to expand our automotive business, our parent company has already paved the way.<p>
The building industry, for example, is one of the first industries to boom in a developing country. In fact, it's estimated that 30 percent of the world's high-rise building cranes are in China. And Otis and Carrier are building industry leaders.
Fifteen percent of UTC's work force -- or more than 25,000 employees -- are located in the Asia Pacific region. Last year, the company's revenues from that region were $2.7 billion. <p>
Let me use Otis' presence in China as an example. Otis, which entered China in 1900 with the sale of two elevators, established its first joint venture in the People's Republic of China in 1984. Today, Otis has four such ventures and employs more than 4,000 people in China.<p>
The Orient Pearl Television tower in Shanghai is one of Otis' major installations in China. At 1,509 feet, it's the third-tallest structure in the world.<p>
Otis also won the largest contract in China's elevator industry -- a project that involves 54 elevators and escalators and is worth nearly $9 million.<p>UTC as a whole has 16 joint ventures under way in China. Over the last five years company revenues there have totaled nearly $2 billion. In China alone, UTC is forecasting sales of more than $700 million in 1996.<p>
And UT Automotive reaps the benefits of these global resources by hitchhiking off their capabilities, knowledge and experiences.<p>
It's no secret that the greatest incremental growth potential for the automotive industry is in China and other Asia countries -- outside of Japan. Our  OEM customers are focusing on these opportunities.<p>
UT Automotive is moving aggressively into these emerging markets and, whenever possible, we are taking advantage of our position as a member of the UTC family to speed the process.<p>
UT Automotive sales to Asian-based automakers alone have more than tripled over the past four years -- from $70 million to nearly $250 million.
In Asia, we're taking steps to expand our operations through a number of joint ventures and partnerships.<p>

We've signed four such agreements with Asian companies over the past two years, including two in China -- one  to produce electrical distribution systems and engine cooling modules, and the other to produce automotive electrical distribution systems.<p>

And you can bet that United Technologies' past ventures in China and the relationship that has been already established with their government helped smooth our entry into the country.<p>

Our presence in Asia extends far beyond China, however. We're also very proud and excited about our main Asian operation in Cebu, the Philippines.<p>
We began operations in Cebu in May 1990 with only 190 employees. Today, we have 2,500 people in three manufacturing facilities and ship products to customers in Asia, Europe and North America.<p>

I've just returned from the Asia, where we announced plans to invest $5 million to open a new, 60,000-square-foot Engineering and Technology Center in Cebu. The new center will serve the entire Asian region, and will also support our efforts in North America and Europe. The new Philippine Engineering and Technology Center will provide all of our business units with a tremendous opportunity for new ventures in Asia.<p>

Another area of great interest to us is South America, where 30 percent growth in production is expected by the year 2000. To meet our customers' requirements and to successfully continue our global expansion process, we recently acquired a supplier of automotive wire harnesses based in Buenos Aires.<p>

As automakers increase their production of global vehicles, we want our products to be part of what they produce whether it's in North or South America, Europe or Asia. <p>

Our automotive operation is already a global player on its own. UT Automotive has more than 40,000 associates, 90 plants in 18 countries.<p>

And with the worldwide resources of UTC behind us, we're especially well-suited to partner with our customers in China, South America or anywhere else in the world.<p>

In addition to our North American operation, we have an organization in place in Europe that produced about $1 billion in sales last year.<p>
Our headquarters for Europe is in Paris. We have technical centers and sales offices in France, Germany, Italy, Sweden and Spain; and manufacturing plants in nine European countries that serve OEMs such as PSA, Renault, Volvo, Fiat and GM-Opel. <p>
One of our newest European facilities is in Hungary, which opened in 1991 and doubled its capacity in 1996.<p>

So, when people ask how we're going to execute a product development process outside of North America, I tell them we're already there.<p>

Today, for example, we are designing the wiring system for a  North American global platform vehicle.  That car, however, is being designed in Europe. So, to best service and support our customer's needs, we're designing the wiring system at our European facility in Germany.<p>
That vehicle will be produced in  North America, Europe, Asia and South America. And we're already gearing up to support the customer with wiring systems produced at our facilities in Mexico, Honduras, the Philippines, Portugal, Hungary, Poland and now Argentina.<p>

From our experiences, I can say that growing globally has many challenges. 
The biggest challenge is developing a management team, comprised of people from around the world who are capable of dealing with diverse cultures and are able to treat each individual equally and with dignity.<p>

But with every decision we've had to make, we've reminded ourselves of our goal, which is not necessarily to be the biggest in the world, but to be the best at what we do -- on a global basis.<p>

That means providing our customers with the best technology, the best products and at the lowest possible cost -- anywhere in the world.<p>
Clearly, our industry is faced with major challenges. And it will be interesting to see what additional changes and challenges we'll be facing in the year 2000.
But we at UT Automotive are looking forward to the journey.<p>
Again, thank you for inviting me to be a part of this morning's session. I'm looking forward to our roundtable discussion, and I hope you enjoy the rest of the conference.

<!--footer begins here-->
