</map>
<IMG SRC="/media/medi.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="68" usemap="#media" border="0">
</center>
<!--header ends here-->

<H2>Managing the supply chain<p></H2><BLOCKQUOTE><EM>Following is the text of remarks prepared for delivery by <A HREF="/general/people/norm.htm">Norman R. Bodine</A>, president and CEO of <A HREF="http://www.uta.com">United Technologies Automotive, Inc.</a> at the Automotive Industries  Executive Management Conference in Detroit on Tuesday, Oct. 29, 1996:
</EM></BLOCKQUOTE><p>
<p>Good afternoon ladies and gentleman and thank you David for that fine introduction.
<p>I appreciate the opportunity to speak to you this afternoon. We are seeing a dramatic change in the way our industry interacts with both its customers and its suppliers.
<p>Historically we've been an industry of evolutionary change . . . But what we are seeing today is not evolutionary . . . it is revolutionary . . . and will have a profound effect on the way we do business from now on.

<p>This revolution is being driven by two things: One, our customers, who are responding to the wants and needs of their customers; and two, by increased competition.
<p>This creates intense pressure on OEMs to develop new models faster, with higher quality and at lower costs than the competition.

<p>As a supplier we are under the same pressure to improve quality . . . reduce product development time . . . increase the services we provide to our customers    . . . and continually lower our costs.

<p>At UT Automotive we understand the ever increasing competitive environment we're in.
It's our intent to work harder and closer with the car companies, as well as our suppliers, to ensure future prosperity for all of us.

<p>Managing the supply chain means that as a Tier 1 supplier we no longer can mind only our own business -- we now need to have an understanding and knowledge of the process improvement actions of our suppliers.
How do we do that?

<p>We can't run their businesses for them . . . and we don't want to.

<p>The solution is in managing the process.

<p>At UT Automotive we intend to accomplish this task by building stronger relationships with, and becoming closer to our suppliers than ever before. And the reason is simple.
We cannot expect to operate effectively if we work independent of each other. We have to remember that our parts do not stand alone, they're all inter-related.

<p>We're much more interdependent than we are independent. The products we build interface with each other. We're all participating in putting the chunks of a vehicle together.  
For example, our company's electrical system is linked to other Tier 1's safety systems . . . to air conditioning and heating units . . . to the drive train and instrument panel . . . to interior trim    . . . and to braking systems.

<p>Our electrical system is linked to all other electrical components on a car or truck today.
All of these linkages require suppliers to interface with each other. Therefore, if we intend to provide our customers with the quality they're looking for, we will need to understand how our systems work together.    

<p>We'll only accomplish this task by building and establishing strong relationships with each other.
It will be through these relationships that we'll be able to talk to each other and share quality information . . . as well as acquire the knowledge necessary to become the world's best producers.					


<p>We all know our own products, designs and processes better than anyone else in the industry. Therefore, we need to share this information and make sure it flows through the system.

 <p>	So how are we going to do this? We have to work more openly and truly become partners with our suppliers.
We need first to build trust and a mutual understanding so that we both know where we are now . . . where we want to be in the future . . . and what we need to do to get there.

<p>We must change from the  past . . . change from the traditional way of managing suppliers to managing the process.

<p>And managing that process takes, again, trust, understanding, strong communications and training. But most of all, it takes time.

<p>We must learn to work out our problems as a team, not as adversaries searching for blame.
We must create an open environment where we all feel free to tell each other what's wrong . . . this is the only way we're going to understand problems and figure out solutions.
And the way to do this is to start communicating. The communications channel is the key to getting the quality our customers want. It will allow us to focus on getting the job done. 
It will help us to get accurate information . . . get the truth, even if it's painful . . . so we can make high quality decisions.

<p>At UT Automotive we are working hard to create an open communications environment with our suppliers.

<p>We're  asking our suppliers to take a chance with us. We want them to challenge us . . . to test us . . . to see if our word is good.
At our company we're really trying to do this. We've recognized this issue . . . we understand how important it is . . . and we're doing something about it.

<p>The following are just some of the programs we're putting in place to support our efforts: 

<p>First, we're training our management . . . we're teaching them to be responsible for creating an environment that encourages trust and open communications.

<p>So far, we've put about 1,500 people from our organization through this training session. And I personally participate for two hours in every training session we conduct.
In these training sessions, we're instructing our managers how to communicate to our suppliers . . . and how to get feedback from them that will help improve our products.

<p>We believe it's our responsibility as a Tier 1 supplier to make this happen. It's not the responsibility of our Tier 2 or 3's. We, as Tier 1 suppliers, need to take the lead on this.

<p>A second initiative, which our company introduced earlier this year, is our new product development launch process.

<p>One of our objectives is to bring our suppliers in on the ground floor. We believe it's very important to get them involved in the process right from the beginning.
We want to make sure that necessary changes and fixes are made early in the process . . . at little or no cost . . . rather than later at a higher cost.  

<p>This means we have to be able to share process information with our suppliers. 
This is one of the things we do differently than other Tier 1's. We share our product development process details with our suppliers. Our manual is at their disposal. We did this because we value the communication opportunity more than we value the secrecy of the process.
In order to get the quality we want, we must share information.  Our suppliers have to know everything we know.  

<p>Third, we've developed the UT Automotive Road Show program, where we visit a number of our suppliers and provide them with an opportunity to hear directly from their customer -- us --what's expected of them. 	

<p>At these Road Shows we present a basic message: If our suppliers don't have quality products, we won't have quality products . . . and if we don't have quality products, neither will our customers.

<p>The message is simple: Produce high quality products or we will find someone else who can.	
Fourth, we implemented a Partners in Excellence program, which we started in 1992, and is worldwide.

<p>This program identifies basic standardized principles, guidelines and performance expectations of UT Automotive suppliers.
It challenges our suppliers to be the best they can be . . . and it helps us recognize those suppliers who help us attain our goals.
In order for our suppliers to qualify for a Partners in Excellence Award, they must achieve quality levels equal to or less than 50 parts per million for a minimum of six months . . . a continuous delivery rating equal to 100 percent . . . and commercial, technological and system ratings of 85 percent or better.

<p>And fifth, we're inviting suppliers to attend our Kaizen programs, so together we can find new ways to improve our processes and our performance.
The programs I mentioned are just some of the processes we're implementing at UT Automotive to ensure that our customers receive products that are high quality, exciting and add value.
The suppliers who help us reach our aggressive goals will be the ones with whom we'll build our future relationships.

<p>We want suppliers who will take on the responsibility of bringing ideas to the table . . . who design and build products that work . . . have zero defects . . . and are inexpensive.
The suppliers that can do this will be the suppliers that will be with us for many years to come.
One thing is clear -- the playing field is much larger, it's global, it's more competitive, faster changing, and more complex than businesses have ever had to play on.
Playing successfully on such a field will not be easy.  It will require OEMs and the total supply chain to work effectively together as a team. 

<p>Again, this means cleaner lines of communications, higher quality products and trust.	

We must not be afraid to change . . . and we must not be afraid to do the things we need to do to assure we're one of the players in the future. 

Remember what FDR said: "The only thing we have to fear is fear itself."

Thank you very much.
