<H2>Conference on Improving Trade Relations
Between Italy and Michigan
</H2>
<BLOCKQUOTE><EM>Following is the text of remarks prepared for delivery by <A HREF="/general/people/norm.htm">Norman R. Bodine</A>, president and CEO of <A HREF="http://www.uta.com">United Technologies Automotive, Inc.</a> at the Conference on Improving Trade Relations
Between Italy and Michigan on Monday, September 23, 1996:


</EM></BLOCKQUOTE><p>




Grazie Signore Infusino, per la gentile presentazione.<p>

E buonigiorno Signore e Signori. Un rigraziamento particolare al Dottor Quaroni, il nostro Console Italiano, e all'lngegner Alberto Negro, dal Fiat, che risiedono entrambi qui a Detroit. Vorrei dare inoltre un benvenuto specials a tutti I visitatori italiani present) in sale . . .<p>

and good morning ladies and gentleman. My special thanks to Dr. Quaroni, our Italian Consul, and to Mr. Alberto Negro who are both located here in Detroit. I'd also like to extend a special welcome to all of the Italian visitors in our audience. <p>



Our thanks also to Mr. Wagner of Macomb Community College, and Congressman Bonier for putting this program together.<p>

Italy is an important cornerstone in the global business operations of both United Technologies and UT Automotive. And you'll frequently hear Italian spoken at UT Automotive facilities in Dearborn and throughout our operations in European.<p>

And I'm pleased United Technologies could be part of today's program.<p>


In fact, worldwide Italian is the fourth most widely used language among UT Automotive employeesafter Spanish, English and Portuguese. <p>





Before going any farther I'd like to give you a brief overview of UTC and UT Automotive. UTC:<p>

Ranks among the top 150 companies on Fortune Magazine's Global 500 list.

 We operate on every continent of the world.<p>

 And UTC generates more than half of its $23 billion in annual revenue outside of the United States. Very few U.S. companies can make that claim today.<p>



Some of the exciting products UTC builds include:

<ul><li>Jet engines


<li>Helicopters


<li>Elevators


<li>Heating and air conditioning units


<li>and, automotive systems</ul>


 



In terms of global reach, UTC has products in every single country in the world, but one.<p>

Now let's turn to UT Automotive. Our company has $3 billion in revenues or 14% of UTC. We have more than 40,000 employees worldwide, located in more than 90 plants in 17 countries. And we are among the world's 25 largest suppliers of systems and components for the auto industry.<p>

We deal in huge volumes....for example, we deliver more than 200,000 wiring harnesses with more than 7 million terminals per day to our OEM customers.<p>




We supply components for seven of the world's 10 best-selling vehicle platforms.<p>

In Europe, which accounts for 30 percent of our business, we employee about 11,000 people and have 21 manufacturing plants in nine countries.<p>

Our European operations is a leader in motors and electrical systems.<p>



Our electric motors are an important and growing part of our business, especially in Italy. Our motors business:<p>

 Increased 50% in North America in the last five years<p>

		Is expected to increase 10-15% by year 
2000<p>

 Accounts for 25% of our European sales, and is
expected to increase significantly by the end of the
decade.<p>


Fiat and PSA are UT Automotive's largest motors customers in Europe.<p>



Now let's talk just about Italy. In Italy alone, UT Automotive, together with the other divisions of UTC generate more than $650 million...or 991.6 billion lira...and we employ more than 5,300 people.<p>


Our company does many things in Italy, but one of the most significant is the Sistine Chapel, where our Carrier division installed and maintains the air conditioning and air handling system that protects Michelangelo's frescoes.<p>



Our relationship with the Italian automotive industry is mutually beneficial. Our Pratt & Whitney division's PW4000 engines . . .<p>

. . . and Boeing's new 777 uses a gear box made in Italy by Fiat.<p>


Located in Asti, Italy is UT Automotive's motor operations, called Gate. They are a leading European manufacturer of:<p>

 Electric motors and<p>
 Electromechanical components for the auto industry<p>





Gate was acquired by UT Automotive in 1983, and has more than 1,000 employees and generates nearly $200 million ...or 305.1 billion lira...in revenue annually.<p>
On Fiat's new Bravo. . .<p>

. . . and Brava car lines, we supply 100% of the:  Washer assemblies  Wiper motors  And radiator cooling modules<p>





We've been very successful and have had a wonderful experience working with the Italian people. We have found them to be: Team-oriented Cooperative Highly skilled, and Easy to build relationships with.

In summary, gliItaliani sono molto sinpatico.<p>
In the future, our primary competitive challenge as a Tier One supplier is becoming global, capable of supporting vehicle platforms like the Fiat Brava and Bravo worldwide.<p>




We at UT Automotive are moving aggressively into emerging markets to meet this challenge. Last year, we established two new joint ventures in China, and this year we announced entries into Thailand and Argentina.<p>


As we continue to grow, we look forward to supporting and building stronger relationships with our Italian partners in Italy, here in Michigan as well as around the world.<p>

Grazie, and I'm looking forward to your questions later in the program.

<!--footer begins here-->
