<!--header ends here-->

<H2>Challenges for Success
</H2><p>
	
<IMG SRC="/media/1996/sep_oct/aiag2.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH="226" HEIGHT="286" BORDER="0" HSPACE="2" VSPACE="2"> 
<EM>Following is the text of remarks as prepared for delivery by <A HREF="/general/people/norm.htm">Norman R. Bodine</A>, president and CEO of United Technologies Automotive, Inc. at the <A HREF="http://www.aiag.org/">Automotive Industry Action Group's (AIAG)</A> annual Achievement Awards dinner in Detroit on Tuesday, Sept. 17, 1996:
</EM><p>

	<p>Thank you Derryl, and good evening ladies and gentlemen.
	<p>It's a real honor for me and for United Technologies to have a part in tonight's tenth annual AIAG Outstanding Achievement Awards program.
	<p>As many of you know, Derryl is one of the chief architects of  AIAG's new strategic plan. He's been active in AIAG for a number of years and has been instrumental in marshaling the resources of <A HREF="http://www.gm.com/">General Motors</A> behind the organization.	
	<p>Tonight's a special night for AIAG and the winners of the organizations Outstanding Achievement Award.
	<p>Like the industry it serves,  AIAG has undergone a tremendous amount of change and growth in the past several years. 
	<p>Change brings challenge and tonight I'd like to discuss some of the challenges that I see facing our industry ... and  AIAG and Tier One suppliers like UT Automotive.
	<p>Most of you know about UT Automotive, but I suspect that many of you arent aware of the worldwide resources that stand behind our company.
	<p>As you saw in the video, our company builds jet engines ... helicopters ... elevators ... heating and air conditioning units ... and automotive systems.
	<p><A HREF="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies</A> is a company that operates on every continent of the world ... a company whose vast global resources provide the service, experience and technology so much in demand by OEM manufacturers today.
	<p>Speaking of global reach, did you know that more than half of UTC's revenue,  totaling more than &#36;23 billion, is generated outside of the United States&#63;  Very few U.S. companies can make that claim today.
	<p>UTC also has product in every country in the world, but one.
	<p>UTCs <A HREF="http://www.otis.com/">Otis</A> operation alone has offices in nearly 2,000 cities around the world. And they have the largest number of employees in the former Soviet Union of any foreign company, with nearly 14,000 in Russia and the Ukraine.
	<p>In fact, the majority of Otis employees speak Russian, not English.
	<p>Our automotive operation is a global player on its own, and with the worldwide resources of UTC behind us, we're especially well-suited to partner with our customers anywhere in the world.
	<p>To point out just how truly international we are,  the most commonly spoken language by the people of UT Automotive isn't  English . . . it's Spanish.
	<p>UT Automotive has more than 40,000 associates, 90 plants in 17 countries around the world. About 30 percent of our business in Europe.
	<p>Last year our revenues topped the &#36;3 billion mark for the first time -- up 14 percent  from the previous year.  
	<p>Our people, however, are our most important assets. I'd like to take a minute to tell you about what were doing to invest in our people right here in the United States.  We offer our employees a scholar program that:
	<UL>
<LI>Covers 100 percent of all tuition costs.
<LI>Pays for 100 percent of all course-required books and fees.
<LI>Grants 50 percent of all classroom hours as paid time off for degree courses.
<LI>Places no limits on the number of courses taken or what courses are taken . . . it can be in any field. And,
<LI>Awards employees with 50 shares of Company stock, currently selling at about &#36;115 a share, for the completion of any undergraduate or graduate degree program.
</UL>
<p>	UT Automotive's primary products are electrical systems and automotive interior components and systems. We supply parts for seven of the world's 10 best-selling vehicle platforms.
	<p>And as you might suspect, we deal in huge volumes.
	<p>For example, we deliver more than 200,000 wiring harnesses with a total of more than 7 million terminals to our OEM customers on a daily basis.
 <p>	If stretched end to end, the wiring harnesses we produce each day would circle more than 75 percent of the world. 
	<p>We're also optimistic about our future ... as well as the future of our industry.
	<p>We expect light vehicle production and sales in both North America and Europe to remain relatively stable over the next two to three years, though we expect some moderate slowdown in U.S. vehicle sales as we move into 1997.
	<p>At the same time, we expect trucks -- thank goodness for those minivans and SUVs -- to continue their record sales pace.
	<p>New vehicles planned by Japanese automakers in North America will provide some of us with additional growth opportunities as well. Our sales to the Japanese now account for more than 10 percent of our U.S. revenue and those sales will continue to grow.
	<p>In a relatively flat market with some incremental vehicle capacity, OEMs will place more and more emphasis on cost-cutting ... which in turn will place added pressure on all of us who are Tier One suppliers.
	<p>Vehicle production in emerging markets such as China, Thailand and South America, on the other hand, is growing at a relatively strong pace of about 16 to 20 percent annually.
	<p>With that in mind, we're moving aggressively into emerging markets.  Last year, for example, we established two new joint ventures in China, and  we recently announced entries into Thailand and Argentina.
	<p>Our sales to Asian-based automakers alone have more than tripled over the past four years, from &#36;70 million to nearly &#36;250 million last year.
	<p>One of the biggest unknowns facing our industry today, of course, is the outcome of the UAW negotiations, especially as those talks relate to outsourcing.  
	<p>Outsourcing decisions will have a major impact on our entire industry.  We're all hopeful that contract issues can be resolved without a major shutdown. With today's reliance on just-in-time delivery systems,  a labor dispute could have a serious impact on all of us.
	<p>But outsourcing and labor disputes aren't the only challenges facing our industry today.
	<p>Its no secret to any of you that our industry is undergoing dramatic change ... especially as it relates to the cost and capital structure of Tier One suppliers.  
	<p>Some of that change may not be for the best.  Stock analysts are warning investors about companies:
	<ul><li>That increase revenue without regard to prudent capital utilization.
		<li>	That show rapid revenue growth that might mask internal cost problems. Or
	<li>	That fail to fully integrate new business or acquisitions into day-to-day operations.</ul>
	<p>As suppliers and OEM manufacturers, we need to ask ourselves some fairly tough questions in todays rapidly changing business environment.  Here are some at the top of my list
	<p>For starters, there's a feeling that we need to be "big" to survive.  But, do we really believe that growth by merger or acquisition is the best course of action for Tier One suppliers&#34;  
	<p>For the past several years, the news has been filled with stories about automotive-related acquisitions and mergers ... and you can be sure more are in the works.  
	<p>But interest in mergers seems to run in cycles and this particular cycle may run its course sooner than we think. Some analysts already have pulled out their yellow caution flags.
	<p>At UT Automotive our goal is not necessarily to be the biggest, but to be the very best at what we do ... on a global basis.
	<p>That means providing our customers with the best technology, the best products, at the lowest possible cost ... anywhere in the world.
	<p>We're also asking ourselves what the OEMs will want or need in an "integrated systems" supplier. And, perhaps more importantly, what is the definition of an integrated system&#63; We think
each OEM customer describes it differently. UT Automotive was one of the first suppliers to provide its OEM customers with integrated systems in the early 1990s.
	<p>But I believe our customers will be better served if we offer quality systems that perhaps dont provide everything in one bundle, but are better suited to their special product wants and needs.
	<p>We're now doing market research, providing design support and developing new technologies and products.
	<p>In addition, Tier Two and Tier Three suppliers will have to assume some of that responsibility in the relatively near future, particularly for product quality.  And that will be a major challenge for all of us.
	<p>Along with the challenge of providing full systems support come the issues of accountability, product reliability and warranty costs.  We have a tremendous opportunity here. 
	<p>I believe the first step in being responsible and improving vehicle quality is to improve communications on the performance of vehicles in the field.
	<p>We must set up systems and processes between OEMs and suppliers that will provide this information exchange. 
	<p>Our company has taken the lead on this in many respects. We were the first supplier to deliver report cards on ourselves to our customers on field reliability.
	<p>This is one of the biggest opportunities we have to improve quality and cost.
	<p>Our plates are fuller than they've ever been before.  We have more responsibilities.
	<p>Our programs are more complex and they're becoming more difficult to manage. And we're being held more and more accountable for the final product.
	<p>And make no mistake, OEM pressure to reduce cost will continue and even increase in years to come.
	<p><A HREF="http://www.chryslercorp.com/">Chrysler</A>, for example, recently announced that its SCORE -- Supplier Cost Reduction Effort -- had shaved &#36;1 billion off the company's 1996-model &#36;35 billion parts bill.
	<p>And both <A HREF="http://www.ford.com/">Ford</A> and Chrysler are on record with plans to reduce their parts costs five percent annually over the next several years.
	<p>That brings me to our final challenge -- the challenge of going global.  For Tier One, Two and Three suppliers, the ability to support global OEM sourcing requirements is becoming the "price of entry" for some, if not all, OEM business.  
	<p>But should or can every Tier Two or Three supplier develop an international presence&#63;  It's not really a question of desire or interest.  Its a question of financial ability. 
	<p>In many cases, "going global" can stretch a companys financial and human resources to the breaking point.
	<p>Clearly our industry is faced with major challenges.  Were fortunate, therefore, to be part of an organization like AIAG ... and organization that helps each of us meet and manage those challenges.
	<p>And by the way, don't think of AIAG as a separate staff or organization. As Ray Mitzel likes to point out ... the members <EM>are</EM> the organization. We ... you and me ... are AIAG.
	<p>During any given month of the year, more than 1,000 volunteers from 1,200 member companies are involved in meetings aimed at improving the efficiency and competitiveness of our industry.
	<p>As our industry changes, I see new challenges for AIAG as well. First, as we go global,  we'll need to have AIAG go global with us.  
	<p>The entire industry, car makers and suppliers, need AIAG's support more than ever to establish standardization and put systems and processes in place as we enter overseas markets that will help us to be more effective and meet our just-in-time objectives.
	<p>I also challenge AIAG to place more emphasis on computer standardization.
	<p>Today,  processing an order or exchanging product information can be a needlessly complicated process.
	<p>For example, the person at the parts plant who is processing a shipment for Ford enters the information into his computer using one process. If the next order is for a GM or Chrysler customer,  he has to use a totally different process to enter the same basic information. That means he has to start from scratch. All of that takes time, and it also increases the possibility of error.
	<p>Earlier this summer, AIAG sent out a survey to the CEOs of nearly 700 companies that manufacture automotive parts. Only 32 percent responded.  And that's clearly not enough.
	<p>UT Automotive was one of the companies that is involved. <A HREF="/general/people/lloyd.htm">Jim Lloyd</A>, our vice president for Information and Network Resources, recently was elected to AIAGs Board of Directors.
	<p>And Jack Tyson,  a UT Automotive manager for business improvement systems and process management, co-chairs AIAG's QS-9000 Sub-Tier Deployment effort.
	<p>If you and your company aren't actively involved in AIAG's day-to-day business, you should be.  Here are four AIAG initiatives that warrant your immediate attention:
	<ul><li>AutoSTEP is a program that you should know about by concept if not by name. Its mission is to eliminate redundant CAD systems along with associated maintenance and training costs. If successful, the program could  save our industry hundreds of millions of dollars.
	<li>	The QS-9000 Sub-Tier Deployment project is designed to extend QS-9000 beyond Tier One to Tier Two and Three suppliers. A number of UT Automotive associates are involved in this  effort. Is there a need?  </ul>
	<p>AIAG surveyed  Tier  Two and Three suppliers in Michigan earlier this year and 61 percent said they needed QS-9000 training and 47 percent said they were operating without a QS-9000 quality manual.
	<ul><li>	MAP, which I referred to earlier, is another program that deserves your attention. The Manufacturing Assembly Pilot is an effort to develop EDI (electronic data interchange), e-mail and standardized business processes to move scheduling information through the supply chain, from OEMs down through Tier 4. The estimated savings for North American OEMs and their suppliers could exceed &#36;1 billion per year, or more than &#36;70 per car when fully implemented.
	<li>ANX, or the Automotive Network eXchange project, is a fourth program that deserves your attention.  Its goal is to develop a single electronic network and standard for supply chain communications.  A pilot program will begin shortly with a full rollout planned for 1997.  As suppliers, however,  we each need to ask ourselves:
	<li>	Does my company have the ability to connect to the new Auto Industry Internet when the time comes. And,
	<li>	Does my company have the skilled personnel and technology to support access to the new network? </ul>
<p>As OEMs outsource more, links needed to exchange data become more and more critical. To succeed in these initiatives, AIAG needs your active participation.  Tonight's program honors companies and individuals who have made exceptional contributions to AIAG and to its programs -- programs which each and every one of us benefits from.
	<p>So if your company and its employees aren't already involved, decide to do something about it tonight.  
	<p>A lot still needs to be done. Despite the fine work AIAG has done to develop standards for our industry, there are far too many exceptions to standards that already exist.
	<p>AIAG needs to revisit and tighten those standards. And AIAG needs to help us go global with them as well.
	<p>In just the last four years.  AIAG has grown by nearly 75 percent. With your active participation we can continue that growth rate through the year 2000 ... put life into important projects like AutoSTEP, MAP, ANX and QS-9000 Deployment ... and meet the new challenges of a global marketplace. 
	<p>It will be interesting to see what the future holds ... and what additional changes and challenges we'll be facing in the Year 2000.
	<p>We at UT Automotive look forward to the journey ... and hope that all of you in this room will be there with us.
	<p>Thank you, and now let's get on with the Outstanding Achievement Awards program.


<!--footer begins here-->
