<h2>UT Automotive pushes flat screen, smart box

 </h2>
<strong> 

October 23, 1996<br>

<CITE>Ward's Auto World 
</CITE></strong><br>
</p>


United Technology Automotive and Planar Systems Inc. have jointly developed a prototype electroluminescent display (ELD) for automotive applications.</p>

ELD, unlike liquid crystal display, does not require a supplemental light source. It also has a wider viewing range and a broader temperate range for operation.</p>

Applications range from dashboard display to radio/CD tuner readouts.</p>

The technology was developed from military technology. A spokeswoman says in the military application the screens could literally be hosed down along with the vehicle without ill effect.</p>

UTA also has developed a new concept called "Smart" Junction Box (SJB) technology.</p>

The SJB concept integrates electronic functions and existing power functions into a single unit. The SJB requires fewer interconnections, smaller packaging, fewer parts, faster design and other advantages, the company says.
In another consolidation, UTA also unveiled its new integrated liftgate multiplexed module.</p>

The module incorporates controls for liftgate lock/unlock, release, wiper, heated backlight, license plate lamps and center, high mounted stop light. The six operations previously required three motors and a series of wires, relays and electronics.</p>

The Geneva mechanism, the heart of the new liftgate module, consists of a central cam and three shafts that turn using a series of cam followers. Each shaft controls one of three mechanical functions. The mechanism is driven by a single, permanent-magnet DC motor. 	Jeff Green<!--footer begins here-->
