<h2>He's UT Automotive's efficiency expert

</h2>
<strong> 

October 29, 1996<br>

<CITE>Detroit Free Press 
</CITE></strong><br>
</p>


                           

                            By TED EVANOFF</p>

<img src="ed.jpg" align=right align=middle>

                             
		    	

                            IOWA CITY, Iowa -- One day last winter Bill
                            Kubik parked outside the guard shack, passed
                            through the gate in the barbed wire fence, walked to
                            his big office and sat at the desk under the framed
                            sign that said Sweat the Details.</p>


                            He was on edge. Understandably so.</p>


                            The new boss was coming. Direct from Dearborn.
                            And Kubik, general manager of a United
                            Technologies Corp. plastic auto parts plant
                            supplying Chrysler Corp. and Toyota Motor Co.,
                            knew the new boss' reputation:</p>


                            Turnaround expert. A regular Mr. Fix-it. Full of
                            Japanese business buzzwords. Harvard Business
                            Review even had praised the guy as an efficiency
                            expert when he ran UTC's Pratt & Whitney turbine
                            airfoil plant.</p>


                            Now he was Kubik's boss. His name was Ed
                            Northern. A short block of a man with thick black
                            hair and a trace of native Kentucky in his accent, he
                            walked into the Iowa City plant and asked a blunt
                            question.</p>


                            "What the hell's the fence for?" </p>


                            An anxious Kubick wasn't sure. </p>


                            No one knew why a fence surrounded the factory.
                            It always had been there.</p>


                            "I didn't understand why it was up here either,"
                            Kubik said. "I always wanted to take it down."</p>


                            So the fence came down. Along with the guard
                            shack. It was only the start.</p>


                            Mr. Fix-it had arrived.</p>


                            To improve, not sell</p>


                            Northern intends to push his 6,000-employee
                            enterprise, a UTC auto parts division considered
                            ripe for the sales block by some financial analysts,
                            into the top tier of parts makers in America and the
                            world.</p>


                            "I was sent here on a mission to fix it. Not sell it.
                            Anyone can sell it," Northern said.</p>


                            He's starting with Iowa City and a handful of the
                            other plants in his domain, the Interiors division of
                            United Technologies' Automotive division. </p>


                            With 40,000 employees in 89 plants worldwide,
                            Dearborn-based UT Automotive ranks among the
                            nation's 25 largest auto parts makers in terms of
                            annual sales of $3.06 billion.</p>


                            Today, however, even $3-billion parts suppliers are
                            vulnerable as takeover targets. Big parts makers are
                            buying smaller ones. It's happening because car
                            companies want parts makers to cut costs. The Big
                            Three want entire component systems delivered
                            ready for installation on the vehicle assembly lines. </p>


                            UT Automotive President Norman Bodine, a
                            physicist in charge of UTC's automotive business
                            since 1992, has staked out a strategy at odds with
                            industry consolidation.</p>


                            Rather than buy, say, a seat maker in a quest for
                            economies of scale, or sell off a so-so division,
                            Bodine said UTA can thrive if it focuses on higher
                            quality and lower production costs. First, though, he
                            has reshuffled the executive ranks.</p>


                            Bodine created the position of technology director
                            to stimulate research and development. He filled it
                            with Masazumi Sone of Nissan Motor Co.
                            New managers head three of UTA's five divisions.
                            They include Edwin Buker, a former BMW
                            manufacturing executive now at the Wiring division,
                            and Kathleen Ligocki, who came to the Motors
                            division from UTC's Carrier subsidiary in Paris.</p>


                            Nowhere has the new strategy been more stark than
                            in the Interiors division. </p>


                            Interiors are key</p>


                            "For UTA to win, Interiors needs to win. My job is
                            to come here and get Interiors to be a world-class
                            business," Northern said. "But first we had to put
                            lean thinking into Automotive. Our philosophy is
                            small is better. Lean is better. Simple is better."</p>


                            Since Northern arrived in January, Interiors has
                            stepped up research on future products such as a
                            table that folds out from tailgates of sport-utility
                            vehicles, to make tailgate parties more fun.</p>


                            Aiding the research effort, Northern said, are about
                            200 engineers and technical employees hired in
                            recent months. Plans call for hiring another 150, a
                            move that would increase Interiors' salaried staff by
                            more than 20 percent in one year.</p>


                            And the division has tried to pare costs. Kevin
                            Smith, an ex-Toyota Motor Co. purchasing
                            executive joined as purchasing manager. Smith
                            intends to slim Interiors' list of 1,400 suppliers to no
                            more than 140.</p>

                            In the plants, starting in Iowa City, Northern
                            emphasized lean manufacturing, a concept that
                            seeks minimum waste to maximize profits. He
                            brought in as head of manufacturing Garrett Mikita,
                            an engineer who made his mark as a cost-cutter at
                            Pratt & Whitney.</p>


                            Northern figures lean manufacturing techniques soon
                            will leave him with surplus factory capacity. UTA
                            Interiors plants already are set to close in Howe,
                            Ind., and Morganfield, Ky., although Northern
                            expects no wholesale shutdown among Interiors' 19
                            remaining plants.</p>


                            R&D efforts soon can help fill the surplus capacity
                            with new products like the fold-out table and
                            instrument panels with built-in road maps, he said.</p>


                            "We need to be the best of the best at what we're
                            doing," Northern said.</p>


                            Write it here</p>

                            Small. Lean. Simple. It sounds easy.</p>


                            Bill Kubik found otherwise.</p>


                            Automotive engineers talked for years about getting
                            efficient. Really efficient. Tradition always interfered.</p>


                            What it came down to was this: You bought the big
                            plastic injection molding machines and stamping
                            presses. Then you ran them flat out. </p>


                            Boxes of raw material piled up everywhere. Pallets
                            of finished products filled the warehouse. That was
                            tradition.</p>


                            Everyone had heard of lean manufacturing. Iowa
                            City managers and their bosses in Dearborn even
                            tried a few lean steps, like just-in-time delivery. But
                            the steps were small. Cautious.</p>


                            "The guys at Interiors hadn't really done this before,"
                            Kubik said. "That causes you to struggle with it a bit
                            more."</p>


                            Then came Northern. He knew money was wasted
                            in the fence and the guards and especially in the
                            traditions: unopened boxes of raw material, stacks
                            of warehoused auto parts, design engineers who
                            barely consulted with toolmakers and manufacturing
                            engineers.</p>


                            And he knew who could scrub away Iowa City's
                            traditions: Shingijutisu, pronounced
                            shing-uh-juh-its-sue.</p>


                            Today, the name rolls off the tongue of workers in
                            Iowa City as smoothly as if they were saying,
                            "Budweiser." No wonder.</p>

                            Shingijutisu is a consulting firm formed by a band of
                            retired Toyota manufacturing executives. They've
                            put on nine Iowa City workshops, using Toyota's
                            efficient production system as a model for cutting
                            waste.</p>


                            "Ed had worked with the Shingijutisu people, who
                            are the key to this whole thing," Kubik said. "They
                            live the manufacturing experience."</p>


                            The 850-employee Iowa plant makes instrument
                            panels, arm rests, center consoles, door trim and
                            covers for passenger air bags. Under the Toyota
                            system, that's thought to be excess variety. Workers
                            can't focus on one part long enough to get good at
                            making it.</p>


                            So Iowa City was designated UTA's center of
                            excellence for instrument panels. The plant received
                            an instrument panel order scheduled for future
                            production at Bay Valley, Mich. It sent some door
                            panel production to Wauseon, Ohio.</p>


                            The supervisory staff was reorganized. Before, a
                            process engineer was like a firefighter, working
                            Monday on a problem on the instrument panel line,
                            Tuesday on the arm rest line.</p>


                            Now, each product line is assigned a permanent
                            engineer, accountant and manager. Instead of only
                            fighting daily fires, they can think ahead. "Probably
                            the biggest benefit is it allows you to focus
                            resources," Kubik said.</p>


                            Simple recommendations emerged. To streamline
                            manufacturing, crews moved more than 250 pieces
                            of equipment, including a 3,000-ton stamping press.
                            The work stunned some Iowa City engineers.
                            Relocating the machinery was a long task. The
                            engineers doubted Dearborn ever would have
                            permitted it in the old days.</p>

                            "People will say you don't have time to do this. I say
                            you don't have time not to do it," Northern said.
                            "My job is to be a change agent."</p>

                            Take the 34,000-square-foot welding shop at Iowa
                            City. It ran full bore as long as the machinery was up
                            to it. Shingijutisu advised otherwise.</p>
 

                            If Chrysler installs an instrument panel every 69
                            seconds in a car in Belvidere, Ill., then weld a
                            crossbeam every 69 seconds in Iowa City. Don't
                            weld as many crossbeams as you can. Weld as
                            many as you need.</p>


                            More common sense prevailed. Workers on the
                            two long welding lines worked 10 hours a day.
                            After meeting with Shingijutisu, one line was looped
                            into a tight horseshoe and the second will be.</p>

                            On the shorter line, work stations are spaced close
                            so a worker can do two or three jobs instead of the
                            one dictated by the longer welding line. Looping the
                            second line will let the shop get by with three fewer
                            welders and, at production speeds geared to
                            Belvidere, end the overtime.</p>

                            "We can reduce the cost of components by 25
                            percent for the car companies," Northern said.</p>


                            The fence and guard shack are gone. And
                            something else has changed since Mr. Fix-it arrived.</p>


                            The Sweat the Details sign disappeared.</p>


                            "Ed said, 'That's a good poster but it's not good for
                            you. What you need is something about leadership,'
                            " Kubik said.</p>


                            So Kubik found a new sign. It shows charging
                            horses and the legend: The speed of the leader
                            determines the rate of the pack. <!--footer begins here-->
