    <H2>A brief history of UT Automotive</h2>

    <p>
    The roots of UT Automotive go back to 1930, when Essex Wire Corp. was founded in
    Detroit, Mich. Essex formed its automotive division the same year and began
    manufacturing and selling automotive wire assemblies. At the time, the
    company's only manufacturing facility was located in a leased section of the
    Ford Motor Company Plant in Highland Park, Michigan. Essex was limited to
    one product - electrical wire harness for the Ford Model A.
    <p>
    In 1965 Essex became a publicly held company with its shares listed on the
    New York Stock Exchange, and in 1968 the company name was changed to Essex
    International, Inc. It was acquired by United Aircraft Corp. in 1974. In
    1975, UAC changed its name to <a href="http://www.utc.com/"> United
    Technologies Corp.</a>
    <p>
    United Technologies Automotive was formally founded in 1979, when
    <a href="http://www.utc.com/">UTC</a> combined the automotive operations of
    Essex with its Ambac subsidiary.
    <p>
    UT Automotive boasts the broadest product line of any tier-one supplier. We are the
    only major supplier capable of producing an entire interior system, from
    switches to molded components to headliners and steering wheels. This
    capability makes us uniquely suited to provide a system that guarantees
    the fit and finish of components.

<p>

