<H2>Corporate Ethics Policy</H2><p>
<B>2.1.1 Purpose<br>
</B>
<P>
This policy clarification is intended to inform UT Automotive suppliers
of UT Automotive policy regarding the acceptance of gifts or social amenities
from suppliers or potential suppliers.  It defines the limits
that are generally acceptable.  It should not, however, be used
as a substitute for good judgment.<BR>

<P>
<B>2.1.2 Scope<BR>
</B>
<P>
UT Automotive is committed to the highest standards of ethics and business
conduct.  This encompasses our relationships with our customers,
suppliers, shareholders, competitors, the communities in which
we operate, and with each other as associates at every organizational
level.<BR>

<P>
<B>2.1.3 General Policy Regarding Business Gifts<BR>
</B>
<P>
United Technologies Corporation has adopted an ethics policy which
places particular emphasis on associates who are directly involved
in procurement, supplier quality, or source selection.  UT Automotive associates
are governed by the same limits.  The following is provided as
general information for UT Automotive suppliers.<BR>

<P>
<B>2.1.3.1    Business Lunches and/or Dinners<BR>
</B>
<P>
UT Automotive associates may accept meals provided by a supplier before,
during, or after business  meetings only, provided that the normal
frequency is not more than once a calendar quarter  from any one
supplier, and not more than once a month from all suppliers in
aggregate.<BR>

<P>
<B>2.1.3.2   Gifts<BR>
</B>
<P>
UTC policy prohibits the request or acceptance of gifts by UT Automotive
associates.  This includes use  of property or facilities, gift
certificates, gift selection catalogs, food baskets, alcohol,
cash,  or favors extended to associates or their families.  The
only exceptions would be unsolicited  gifts of a promotional nature,
such as pens, calendars, or similar items, which bear a company
 logo or advertisement.<BR>

<P>
<B>2.1.3.3   Discounts<BR>
</B>
<P>
If a supplier offers a discount on services or products, it may
be accepted by a UT Automotive associate  only if the discount is made available
to employees of all customers of the supplier, or to the  public
generally.<BR>
<P>
<B>2.1.3.4   Prizes</B>
<BR>
<P>
At some events conducted by suppliers such as golf outings, dinners,
etc., door prizes or other  prizes are provided by the supplier.
 Employees approved to attend these events may accept  prizes
under the following conditions: all participants must be eligible
for the drawing or prize,  and any gift accepted must be disposed
of, in accordance with the UTC Corporate Policy.<BR>

<P>
<B>2.1.3.5  Entertainment<BR>
</B>
<P>
Acceptance of business related entertainment shall be approved
in advance by a UT Automotive  associate's
supervisor, in writing.  Business related entertainment shall
be limited to athletic,  theatrical or cultural events when accompanied
by an employee of the supplier.  Frequency  shall not be more
than once a year, with any one supplier, and not more than once
per  calendar quarter with all suppliers in aggregate.<BR>

<P>
<B>2.1.3.6   Company Events and Activities<BR>
</B>
<P>
UT Automotive associates may not solicit or accept any kind of support from
a supplier, or potential  supplier, for any UT Automotive sponsored organization
social, athletic, or recreational activity, such  as golf outings,
picnics, Christmas parties, etc.<BR>

<P>
<B>2.1.3.7   Travel and Lodging<BR>
</B>
<P>
UT Automotive associates must have approval of the UT Automotive President before
accepting the provision of  air travel or lodging by a customer
or supplier.  This applies to private aircraft or commercial 
airlines for business or non-business travel.<BR>

<P>
<B>2.1.4 Conflicts of Interest<BR>
</B>
<P>
UTC associates must deal with suppliers, customers and others
doing business with the Corporation in a manner that avoids even
the appearance of conflict between our personal interests and
those of the Corporation.  This requirement applies equally to
business relationships and personal activities.<BR>
<br>
<br>
<CENTER>Go to the <a href="sec31.htm">Next Section - Section 3.1</CENTER><p>

