<!--header ends here-->
<H2>Contracts</H2>
<BR>
</U></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B>4.1.1 Purpose<BR>
</B>
<P>
To identify the various types of contracts, as well as the governing
terms and conditions, that may be utilized by UT Automotive's purchasing community.<BR>

<P>
<B>4.1.2 Scope<BR>
</B>
<P>
Contracts for services or products will be required of any supplier
or potential supplier to UT Automotive.<BR>

<P>
<B>4.1.3 General<BR>
</B>
<P>
A contract is a legal obligation between a buyer and a seller
to perform certain duties.<BR>

<P>
Formal agreements should be used when the terms and conditions
involved in a commitment are such that a standard purchase order
is not adequate.  In addition, a formal agreement should be used
when:<BR>

<P>

<UL>
<LI> The purchase period extends beyond one year;
<P>
<LI> The value of the commitment exceeds the limits of authority granted the purchasing   manager.
</UL>

<P>
Apply QS-9000, Element 4.3.<BR>

<P>
<B>4.1.4 Blanket Orders<BR>
</B>
<P>
A blanket order is a contract covering one or more commodities
for one or more locations and is usually formalized by a purchase
order document.  After supplier bidding/negotiations on item(s)
predetermined by the buyer to be repetitive/small order buys,
the selected supplier(s) will be issued a blanket order(s).<BR>

<P>
<B>4.1.5 Construction Contracts<BR>
</B>
<P>
Construction contracts cover the construction of a plant or unit
of equipment and usually includes a labor factor.  To prevent
possible losses associated with these types of contracts, construction
contracts are developed with assistance from UT Automotive's
legal department.<BR>

<P>
<B>4.1.6 Firm Fixed Price Agreements<BR>
</B>
<P>
The supplier agrees to supply goods or services for a firmly committed
amount that is not subject to adjustment by reason of unforeseen
costs experienced by the supplier in the performance of the agreement.
<BR>

<P>

<B>4.1.7 Long Term Agreements<BR>
</B>
<P>
Long term agreements can serve to increase a supplier<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">'</FONT>s
total volume of business, thus reducing unit costs and permitting
the supplier(s) to sell at lower prices.  Long term agreements
can be written from one to three years and eliminate duplicate
yearly supplier investigations and purchasing administrative efforts.
<BR>

<P>
<B>4.1.8 Professional Services Agreement<BR>
</B>
<P>
Architects, engineers, lawyers, consultants and educational specialists
are representative of individuals and firms which provide professional
services.  Professional services agreements are developed with
assistance from UT Automotive's legal department.<BR>

<P>
<B>4.1.9 Purchase Orders<BR>
</B>
<P>
Purchase orders should clearly describe the product and/or service
ordered, and include where applicable:<BR>

<P>
<UL>
<LI> Part number and revision level;
<P>
<LI> The type, class, grade or other specific identification;
<P><LI> The title or other positive identification, and applicable issues 
of specifications,  drawings, process requirements, inspection instructions and
other relevant technical   data, including requirements for approval
or qualification of product, service,   procedures, process equipment
and personnel;
<P>
<LI> The title, number
</UL>

<P>
<B>4.1.10 Purchase Order Amendments<BR>
</B>
<P>
Purchase order amendments are issued as a result of changes and/or
cancellations to the original order.<BR>

<P>
<B>4.1.11 Spot Buy Purchase Orders<BR>
</B>
<P>
One time purchases for which a purchase order is prepared and
issued to the supplier.<BR>

<P>
<B>4.1.12 Time and Material Agreements<BR>
</B>
<P>
Time and material agreements provide for the procurement of supplies
or services on the basis of payment for a composite hourly rate
or rates which include all elements of cost, factory burden, general
and administrative expenses, the supplier's profit, and material at cost.<BR>

<P>

<B>4.1.13 Customer Verification</B>
<P>
Where specified in the contract, UT Automotive's customer or the customer's
representative shall be afforded the right to verify at the supplier's
premises and UT Automotive's premises and UT Automotive's premises that
the supplier's product conforms to specified requirements.<BR>
<br>
<br>
