<H2>Request for Quotation Guidelines</H2>
<BR>
</U></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B>5.1.1 Purpose<BR>
</B>
<P>
To communicate UT Automotive's position on the request for quotation process.<BR>

<P>
<B>5.1.2 Scope<BR>
</B>
<P>
This policy applies to all suppliers and/or potential suppliers
of products, materials and/or services to UT Automotive.<BR>

<P>
<B>5.1.3 General<BR>
</B>
<P>
Requests for Quotations are expected to be returned to UT Automotive within
the allotted time given by the buyer.  All aspects related to
the commodity should be defined in the Request for Quotation
response.  Suppliers are encouraged to provide a total cost breakdown,
ensuring a more competitive bid process.  Requests for Quotation
may also include cost saving suggestions in all areas of the
commodity, such as material substitutions, packaging, design and
service requirements, etc.  Cost saving suggestions are expected
from the supplier at the initial quote stage and during the product/service
life cycle.  All suppliers of products or materials requested
to bid must be determined in advance to be qualified suppliers,
per the requirements of the Partners in Excellence program, for
the commodity in question.  Additionally, to ensure an efficient
and effective quoting process, suppliers should follow, but are
not limited to the following guidelines:<BR>

<P>
<UL>
<LI> Suppliers shall respond
to Requests for Quotation, manufacturing problem or other such
 requests in a timely manner, and information supplied to UT Automotive
must be complete and accurate.
<LI>Suppliers shall meet, maintain and improve established and required quality levels and are expected to lend technical advice and support during initial and on-going phases of programs.
<LI>Suppliers should never commit to a project unless compliance to the specified terms and conditions are assured.
<LI>Suppliers should be sufficiently aware of UT Automotives leadtime inventory to ensure timely arrival of partial/complete deliveries to avoid "stock outs".
<LI>Suppliers should avoid dependence on contingencies as a means to inflate a deliberately low quotation.  The absence of complete specifications from UT Automotive can cause the submission of an unintentional low quote, therefore, suppliers should question completeness of specifications from UT Automotive to avoid upward cost adjustments as a response to specification additions.
<LI>Suppliers should keep UT Automotive informed of new product/service information, process improvements, cost savings, price changes, etc., to keep the buyer abreast of opportunities for better buys, changing market conditions and requirements.
<LI>Suppliers should assist in locating alternate sources for "hard to get" items and assist in standardization efforts by suggesting suitable and appropriate item, service or product substitutions.</ul><p>
<CENTER>Go to the <a href="sec61.htm">Next Section - Section 6.1</CENTER>
