<area shape="rect" coords="0,21 35,54" href="/index.htm">
</map>
<IMG SRC="doin.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="68" usemap="#doingbusiness" border="0">
</center>
<!--header ends here-->
<H2>F.O.B. Terms</H2>
<P>
<B>6.1.1     Purpose<BR></B><P>
To identify the various transportation terms as they relate to ownership, risk of loss and payment of transportation expense.
<P>
<B>6.1.2     Scope</B><P>
Applicable to all raw and/or finished goods purchased by UT Automotive; specific terms negotiated between UT Automotive and the supplier.
<P>
<P><B>6.1.3 General - Domestic Terms</B><P>
The shipping terms included in a purchase order of sales contract determine who has the legal right to specify the carrier and the routing of the goods being purchased.  Shipping terms define the point at which a buyer takes title to the goods.  This, in turn, defines who is responsible for payment of freight charges, for handling negotiations with the carrier, and for filing necessary loss or damage claims.  The "owner" of the material holds all rights and responsibilities that accompany ownership.
<P>
     <UL><B>F.O.B. Origin, Freight Collect<BR>
F.O.B. Origin, Freight Prepaid<BR>
F.O.B. Origin, Freight Prepaid and Charged Back<BR>
F.O.B. Destination, Freight Collect<BR>
F.O.B. Destination, Freight Prepaid<BR>
F.O.B. Destination, Freight Collect and Allowed<BR></B>
</UL>
<P>
At the request for quotation stage of procurement, suppliers should quote their pricing based on F.O.B. (Named) Origin, Freight Collect and F.O.B. Destination, Freight Prepaid Terms.  Freight charges under the F.O.B. (Named) Origin, Freight Collect should be obtained from the third party logistics management suppliers representative (or source identified by the business unit).  The most cost advantageous terms should then be specified.
<P>
<B>6.1.4     General - International Terms</B>
<P>
The two ways of transporting overseas material are via ocean liners and air freight.  The trade-off between the two is in time and freight rates.  Ocean vessels offer the lowest rates but transit times are longer; the opposite is true for air freight.  If the commodity has a high unit cost and it is desirable to keep inventory to a minimum, then air freight is the viable approach.
<P>
Some of the common freight terms are:
<UL>
<B>F.O.B. (Named Inland Carrier at Named Inland Point of Departure)<BR>Freight Prepaid to (Named Point of Exportation)<BR>
F.O.B. (Named Inland Carrier at Point of Exportation)<BR>
F.O.B. (Named Inland carrier at Inland Point of Departure)<BR>
F.O.B. (Named Inland Point in Country of Importation)<BR>
F.O.B. Vessel (Named Port of Shipment).</B> </ul> <p>

Under this system, the suppliers price covers all expenses up to, and including, delivery of goods on the overseas vessels provided by the buyer at the port of shipment.<p>

Under F.O.B. Terms, excepting named inland point in country of importation, the obligation to obtain ocean freight space and marine insurance rests with the buyer.  Despite this obligation, in many trades, the supplier performs this service for the buyer.
<UL>
<B>F.O.B. Airport (DAP).</B>  The supplier is required to deliver the goods to the airport.  Title passes to the buyer upon completion.<BR>
<B>Ex-Works.</B>  Under these terms, the buyer bears all risks and costs from the point of origin.  The extent of the suppliers responsibility is in obtaining documents issued in the country of origin, which may be required by the buyer for purposes of exportation or importation at destination.<BR>
<B>FAS.</B>  The supplier bears all risks until the merchandise is placed within reach of the ships tackle.  Thereafter, all transportation risks and expenses are the buyers.<BR>
<B>CIF.</B>  Under such terms, the supplier is responsible for all costs and risks until the ocean vessel ties up to the dock at the point of importation.<BR>
<B>C & F.</B>  This term is similar to CIF, except the supplier does not provide insurance or bear the risk of loss of merchandise while at sea.<BR>
</UL>
Shipping rates in international transportation are determined  in two basic ways:
<P>
<OL><LI>Conference rates are uniform, established in conferences of international carriers.  The rates quoted by these carriers are the same, or uniform, and the buyer is assured that certain routes will always be traveled, regardless of freight volume;<BR>
 <LI>Charter rates are established by independent conference carriers, usually for single movements utilizing all or most of a vessel or air carrier.  Such rates are negotiable with individual carriers and will typically be lower than conference rates.<BR>
</OL>
Similar to the domestic purchasing criteria, at the time of the request for quotation in the procurement process, suppliers should show F.O.B. Origin (Ex-Factory) and F.O.B. Destination.  This allows purchasing to evaluate the price of the material only (F.O.B. Origin), and the cost of transporting that material.<br>
<br>
