<!--header ends here-->
<H2>International Purchasing</H2>
<P>
<B>7.1.1     Purpose</B>
<P>
UT Automotive, as a global corporation, strives to meet the requirements of the market under which it is operating.
<P>
<B>7.1.2     Scope</B>
<P>
When operating in an international marketplace, UT Automotive associates and suppliers should be familiar with certain issues and/or requirements of the market.
<P>
<B>7.1.3     General</B>
<P>
There are many items which may be reviewed prior to purchasing goods outside the United States.  it is difficult to predetermine which items will be of most relevance in each transaction, but the following is a list of issues that may be consulted.  There may also be changes to laws and regulations in each country.  UT Automotive may consult its legal, finance and tax departments about particular countries prior to any significant purchasing negotiations or commitments.
<P>
<B>7.1.4     Legal Issues</B>
<P>
<B>7.1.4.1     U.N. Convention of the International Sale of Goods (CISG)</B>
<P>
a.  Applies automatically to transactions between parties in countries that have ratified it.<BR>
b.  The U.N. Convention of the International Sale of Goods is generally very similar to the Uniform   Commercial code Article 2.<BR>
c.  The CISG applies to an international and a commercial sale of goods.<BR>
d.  Applicable place of business is one which has the closest relationship to the contract and its performance.<BR>
e.  Differences between UCC and CISG
<UL><LI>If the price terms are not specified, or provided for, no contract is made.
<LI>Irrevocable offers can remain open even if they are not in writing.
<LI>A contract is created at the time the acceptance is received by the offeror.
<LI>There is no battle of the forms under the CISG - acceptance should mirror the offer or it is a counteroffer.
<LI>Few formalities of the statute of frauds are required to have a binding contract.
</UL><P>
<B>7.1.4.2     Protection of Information</B>
<P>	
Patent systems in many countries are not as protective as those of the U.S., and it is, therefore, possible to lose rights to valuable information.  Prior to release of proprietary information (material specifications, designs, process know-how, etc.), a written agreement protecting UT Automotives proprietary information may be required.
<P>
<B>7.1.4.3     Alternative Dispute Resolution</B>
<P>
In a large scale purchase contracts, a clause outlining a dispute resolution procedure, such as arbitration, avoiding a court system and allowing for a quicker settlement of issues, may be included in the contract.
<P>
<B>7.1.4.4     Local Content requirements</B>
<P>
Many countries have requirements as to the percentage of a product that must be produced locally.  This may alter sourcing requirements for UT Automotive or our customers.  Sellers should include duty free status, etc., on all documents related to purchasing material or services.
<P>
<B>7.1.5     Payment</B>
<P>
<B>7.1.5.1     Currency Exchange</B>
<P>
When products are purchased outside the U.S., a determination must be made regarding the currency of payment.  Wherever possible, contracts should be denominated in the U.S. dollar if being purchased for shipment to the U.S.
<P>
<B>7.1.5.2     Letters of Credit</B>
<P>
Suppliers are discouraged from utilizing letters of credit when doing business with UT Automotive.
<P>
<B>7.1.6     Practice</B>
<P>
<B>7.1.6.1     Quality</B>
<P>
Specifications and procedures vary in different parts of the world.  Instructions should be explicit and no assumptions made in the area of terms of art translating accurately across the borders.  Material standards are also different; quality requirements, defect parameters and warranty responsibility should be explicit.  The Partners in Excellence supplier quality system requirements incorporate the global requirements of the QS-9000.  UT Automotive encourages and recognizes suppliers who have attained ISO 9001, 9002, 9003 registration, as well as suppliers who have met the requirements of QS-9000 and all standards specified within.
<P>
<B>7.1.6.2     U.S. Regulation</B>
<P>
Products must meet OSHA space, consumer safety specifications, environmental requirements or other state or federal requirements.  Requirements should be outlined and the products inspected prior to use.
<P>
<B>7.1.7     Shipment</B>
<P>
<B>7.1.7.1     Customs</B>
<P>
U.S. Customs requires labeling for country of origin, and payment of duties, depending upon the source country and type of product.  Suppliers should be made explicitly responsible for shipment of products to the U.S., unless there is a practical reason for UT Automotive to have control.
<P>
If UT Automotive exports technology to assist the supplier in producing the product, there may also be a license required in order to export the technology.
<br>
<br>
<br>
