<H2>Quality Planning</H2>
<P>
<B>10.1.1     Purpose</B>
<P>
To assure that all UT Automotive suppliers have prevention based quality improvement plans that concentrate on continuous product and process improvements.
<P>
<B>10.1.2     Scope</B>
<P>
Quality planning and continuous improvement should be integrated into all processes and functions within the supplier organization.  The suppliers quality planning shall include related goals and objectives, with procedures and methods for planning, organizing, leading and controlling future improvements to maintain a competitive position within its industry.  Apply Advanced Product Quality Planning and Control Plan reference manual and QS-9000, Section 4.2.3, with consideration given to sub points a) through h).
<P>
<B>10.1.3     Program/Project Management</B>
<P>
Quality planning is a structured method of defining and establishing the steps necessary to assure that a product/service satisfies the customer.  The goal of quality planning is to facilitate communication in all program phases, at all organizational levels, to assure that all required steps for program completion are accomplished on time.  Successful quality planning requires executive management commitment to achieving customer satisfaction.  UT Automotive may require the supplier to submit specific program planning documents and product status, such as timelines (Gantt charts).
<P>
<B>10.1.4     Record Control</B>
<P>
All records should be maintained based on the suppliers defined document control system, unless otherwise directed by UT Automotive, UT Automotive customers, or federal mandates.  These records shall be available for review by representatives of UT Automotive, as requested.  Apply QS-9000, Element 4.16.
<P>
<B>10.1.5     Continuous Improvement</B>
<P>
Suppliers shall have continuous improvement plans which define objectives, performance targets, responsibilities and measurement systems for continuous improvement.  The continuous improvement planning should be conducted by cross-functional teams and should involve, at a minimum, the areas of quality, productivity, efficiency, prices capability, delivery, and technology.  Activities shall be documented and reviewed with appropriate management at regularly defined intervals.  Apply QS-9000, Section II, 2.1.
<P>
<B>10.1.5.1     Manufacturing Efficiencies</B>
<P>
Suppliers should consider the various aspects of Flexible Manufacturing (a strategy of continuous improvement utilizing world class manufacturing techniques, including:  Just-in-Time, Total Productive Maintenance, Total Quality Control, Employee Involvement and Simplicity), in determination of the need for focused improvement activity.
<P>
<B>10.1.5.2     Business Process Improvement</B>
<P>
Suppliers should consider the various aspects of the business process re-engineering, and office Kaizen, in determination of the need for focused improvement activity.
<P>
<B>10.1.6     Quality and Cost Improvement Proposals</B>
<P>
The suppliers planning should include the identification, development and submission of quality and cost improvement suggestions to UT Automotive.  Suggestions should be submitted in writing, to UT Automotive Purchasing, with a courtesy copy to UT Automotives plant quality management.<p>

