<H2>Sample Submission Requirements</H2><P>
<B>11.1.1     Purpose</B>
<P>
To establish guidelines for production sample submissions to United Technologies Automotive.
<P>
<B>11.1.2     Scope</B>
<P>
Sample submission requirements apply to all UT Automotive suppliers of production materials and parts.
<P>
<B>11.1.3     Responsibility</B>
<P>
Suppliers shall perform sample submissions for each part number and engineering change level revision, unless otherwise specified by UT Automotive.  Suppliers shall also perform sample submissions for changes in manufacturing processes, manufacturing location, etc., as required by UT Automotive Purchasing after providing advance notice of the change to UT Automotive, (see PIE Section 4.1.7).  UT Automotive Buyers may request Special Samples as defined in section 7.1.4.  Suppliers shall insure that sample submissions include appropriate paperwork as outlined in the Production Part Approval Process guideline, and completely conform to UT Automotive requirements on the first scheduled submission.  UT Automotive requires that initial samples be produced form production tooling and processes.
<P>
<B>11.1.3.1     Sample Submission Deviation</B>
<P>
Suppliers are responsible for investigation and correction of component discrepancies, prior to sample submission. <B> If discrepancies to sample submission requirements are detected, suppliers shall initiate corrective action prior to sample submission.</B>  In the event that all viable corrective actions have been pursued and exhausted without success, the supplier shall obtain approval of a deviation, PRIOR to the buyer sample submission deadline date.  A requested deviation does not relieve the supplier of the responsibility to meet the original sample submission date and to continue to take corrective action to meet specifications by the expiration date of the deviation.  Apply documents:
Production Part Approval Process and QS-9000, Section II, 1.1, 1.2.
<P>
<B>11.1.4     Special Samples</B>
<P>
These samples consist of component parts that are not completely fabricated on production tooling and/or not to the current print revision level (e.g., require secondary or special manual operations).  Special sample pieces shall be identified as Special Samples on the Part Submission Warrant form, in the Production Part Approval Process guide.  Special samples do not necessarily require paperwork such as layouts, material certifications, and capability studies, and therefore, CANNOT be used as salable units.  UT Automotive Purchasing or a designee may request 100% dimensional layouts to comply with customer requests.  Additional special sample submission requirements of the UT Automotive business unit may also apply.
<P>
<B>11.1.5     Production Part Layout</B><P>
Suppliers shall perform and submit full part layouts and material certifications at initial sample submission.  Requirements for layout and material certification plans shall be designated in the product control plan, and approved by UT Automotive.
<P>
<B>11.1.6     Sample Submission Identification</B><P>
Suppliers shall include the following on the packing list with all sample submissions and special sample submissions:
<UL>a)  Type of sample<BR>
b)  Quantity submitted<BR>
c)  Engineering change level of submission<BR>
d)  Tooling purchase order number<BR>
</UL>
<B>11.1.6.1     Sample Submission Shipping Labels</B><P>
Sample submission and special sample submission containers shall have a label attached with the following information indicated:
<OL>a)  Type of submission:  (buyer samples, production evaluation samples, prototype samples, special samples)<BR>
b)  Date<BR>
c)  UT Automotive part number<BR>
d)  Part name<BR>
e)  Engineering change level<BR>
f)  Quantity<BR>
g)  Lot number<BR>
</OL>
Additional sample submissions of the UT Automotive business units may also apply.
<P>
<B>11.1.7     Common Stock Components</B><P>
Suppliers who sell off the shelf components (tooling has not been specifically built for UT Automotive or its customers), and who cannot comply with the Partners in Excellence sample submission requirements may be exempted from sample submission requirements if they maintain, on file, a letter of compliance on their company letterhead stating that the component sold to us conforms to the dimensions and material certifications, given in the companys catalog or brochure, and that the letter includes both the UT Automotive and supplier part number.  Also, the UT Automotive component drawing shall be included with the submission.  These documents shall be available upon request.  <B>This is the exception and not the rule; full documentation should be procured if it is available.</B><p>

