</center>
<!--header ends here-->

<H2>Component Control</H2>
<P>
<B>12.1.1     Purpose</B><P>
To establish minimum supplier requirements for initial and ongoing control of production material, quality, manufacturing and the associated processes.  Apply documents:  QS-9000, Failure Mode Effects Analysis, Fundamental Statistical Process Control, and Advanced Product Quality Planning.
<P>
<B>12.1.2     Scope</B><P>
Applicable to all material, tooling, gaging, packaging, etc., utilized in the processing of parts or assemblies, and in the fabrication of the finished product.
<P>
<B>12.1.3     Quality Assurance</B><P>
Partners in Excellence quality system requirements incorporates QS-9000, Element 4.2.  Suppliers shall use QS-9000 (or appropriate ISO standard as required by UT Automotive customers in Europe) as part of their quality system.  UT Automotive shall verify conformance to these requirements through the use of supplier self-assessments, UT Automotive performed on-site assessments or third party registration acknowledgment per Section 16.1 of this policy guide.
<P>
<B>12.1.4    Design Control</B><P>
This element applies to suppliers who have design responsibility.  The supplier shall define, plan, document, provide adequate resources for, and regularly review each design and development activity in accordance with the following UT Automotive requirements.  Apply QS-9000, Elements 4.4 and 4.9.2.
<P>
<B>12.1.4.1    Ok-To-Tool Drawings</B><P>
UT Automotive approved Ok-To-Tool drawings serve as authorization for production tool changes, part submissions, and customer sample submissions.  Contact UT Automotive Purchasing for detailed procedures.
<P>
<B>12.1.4.2     Design Failure Mode and Effects Analysis (DFMEA)</B><P>
UT Automotive requires suppliers to submit Design Failure Mode Effects Analysis at the time of part sample approval, for supplier designed components or assemblies.  Production suppliers shall comply with the requirements of the FMEA document.  A design FMEA is an analytical technique utilized primarily by a Design Responsible Engineer/Team as a means to assure that, to the extent possible, potential failure modes and their associated causes/mechanisms have been considered and addressed.  The design FMEA does not rely on process controls to overcome potential weakness in the design...  Apply Potential Failure Mode and Effects Analysis reference manual.
<P>
<B>12.1.4.3     Tooling and Gage Design Control</B><P>
This element applies to suppliers who have responsibility for manufacturing tool and/or gage design.  The supplier shall define, plan, document, provide adequate resources for, and regularly review each design and development activity in accordance with QS-9000 Design Control and Process Control elements, and any additional UT Automotive requirements specified in the contract.  At the time of quote, suppliers must submit tool and/or gage design prints which identify significant tool and/or gage features and control characteristics, and any changes of notes developed during the quote process.  Apply documents:  QS-9000, Elements 4.4 and 4.9, and Fundamental Statistical Process Control, Chapter I (or II), Section 5.
<P>
<B>12.1.5     Process Control</B><P>
Suppliers shall identify and plan for control of any process which directly affect quality.  Plans should include documented procedures defining process flow, and use of suitable equipment and working environments.  UT Automotive may require suppliers to submit the following documentation at Part Sample Approval, as determined by the request of quotation.  Apply documents:  QS-9000, Element 4.9, Fundamental Statistical Process Control, Chapter I (or II), Section 5.
<P>
<B>12.1.5.1     Process Failure Mode Effects Analysis (PFMEA)</B><P>
Suppliers shall comply with the Potential Failure Mode Effects Analysis reference manual.  A process FMEA is an analytical technique utilized by a Manufacturing responsible Engineer/Team as a means to assure that, to the extent possible, potential failure modes and their associated causes/mechanisms have been considered and addressed.  It is assumed that the product will meet the design intent.  The process FMEA does not rely on product design changes to overcome weaknesses in the process...
<P>
<B>12.1.5.2     Process Flow Diagram</B><P>
Suppliers shall comply with Advanced Product Quality Planning, Section 3.3.  The process flow diagram shows the relationships between operations and control points.  The diagram also allows for consideration of variation factors which affect control characteristics.  This assists in the quality planning phase of new or revised products and/or processes.
<P>
<B>12.1.5.3     Process Control Plan</B><P>
The process control plan is a written description of the systems for controlling the process(es).  UT Automotive approval of the suppliers process control plan is required.  Suppliers shall comply with Advanced Product Quality Planning, Section 6.0.
<P>
<B>12.1.6     Statistical Product and/or Process Qualification</B><P>
Statistical evidence should be provided for control characteristics as outlined on the approved supplier process control plan.  UT Automotive may request additional process capability information or modification of existing process control plans.  Apply QS-9000, Element 4.20.
<P>
<B>12.1.6.1     Initial Process Capability (Variable Data)</B><P>
Process capability is the measured inherent reproducibility of specific characteristics of a product manufactured by a controlled process.  UT Automotive suppliers shall establish an initial process capability index of 1.67 Ppk prior to part sample submission, using parts produced from the tooling intended for production, under production conditions.  Specific actions are required for process that cannot obtain an initial process capability of 1.67 Ppk.  Apply QS-9000, Element 4.9.2.
<P>
<B>12.1.6.2     On-going Process Capability (Variable Data)</B><P>
On-going process capability shall be verified through the use of variable control charts (or other appropriate statistical methods), on items identified as (control or critical) characteristics on the approved process control plan.  For these characteristics, a Cpk of 1.33 or greater and a process under a state of statistical control is required.  Apply QS-9000, 4.9.3 and 4.9.4.
<P>
<B>12.1.6.3     Process Parameter Capability</B><P>
On-going process control should be verified through the use of variable control charts (or other appropriate statistical method on significant process parameters.  Process parameter control methods should be included in the suppliers control plan (for example: speed, temperature, material weight).  Apply documents:  QS-9000, Section II, Element 2.3 and Production Part Approval Process.
<P>
<B>12.1.7     Changes in Design, Material Composition, or manufacturing Process</B><P>
The supplier shall request and obtain written approval prior to any change as identified in the Production Part Approval Process reference manual.  Changes shall be controlled in accordance with QS-9000, Section 4.4.9 and reflected on the applicable control plan, Failure Mode Effects Analysis, Process Failure Mode Effects Analysis, and other associated documents.  Where requested, the supplier shall provide a part sample warrant to obtain change approval.
<P>
<B>12.1.8     Control of Inspection, Measuring and Test Equipment</B><P>
Suppliers shall maintain documented procedures and data records to control, calibrate and maintain inspection, measuring and test equipment used to insure the conformance of product to specification.  Apply QS-9000, Element 4.11.
<P>
<B>12.1.8.1     Measurement R&R Studies (Variable Data)</B><P>
Suppliers shall establish and maintain a program to determine the capability of all measurement systems, using repeatability and reproducibility (R&R) studies.  Apply Measurement System Analysis reference manual.
<P>
<B>12.1.8.2     Measurement R&R Studies (Attribute Data)</B><P>
Suppliers shall establish and maintain a program to determine the capability of measurement systems used for product validation.  Apply Measurement System Analysis reference manual.
<P>
<B>12.1.9     Material Analysis</B><P>
A material analysis will consist of physical and/or chemical tests compared to the specifications which verify the material used meets or exceeds the stated specifications.  The analysis shall be maintained and made available upon request.  Additional testing by an accredited lab may also be required based on UT Automotive  and/or UT Automotive customer specifications.  The analysis may be subcontracted; in this case the resulting documentation shall indicate:
<OL>
<LI>Name and address of the subcontractor that performed the test;
<LI>Two (2) copies of the test report from the subcontractor signed by a duly authorized officer or quality representative of the subcontractor;
<LI>Manufacturers name and model number of the equipment used
</OL>
Apply QS-9000, Element 4.10.1 and Production Part Approval Process, Section 5, G.
<P>
<B>12.1.10     Dimensional Layout with Numbered UT Automotive and/or UT Automotive Customer Print</B><P>
Suppliers shall submit a dimensional layout at the time of part sample submission.  This layout will consist of measurements for all print dimensions, unless specified otherwise in the control plan.  For engineering changes, layout dimensions will be required and are dependent on the extent of the engineering change, and should be indicated on the Part Sample Warrant (PSW).  Layouts shall include all individual cavities of a multi-cavity mold or the individual sides of multi-gang dies.  All layouts shall be accompanied by the numbered UT Automotive and/or UT Automotive customer print used to measure the samples.  The layout data shall be ordered sequentially by the UT Automotive and/or UT Automotive customer print balloon numbers.  If balloon numbers do not exist, the supplier is responsible to number the print and record measurements accordingly.  The supplier shall circle all results that are identified as out-of-print.  Apply documents:  Production Part Approval Process, Section 5D and F, QS-9000, Elements 4.9 and 4.20, and Fundamental Statistical Process Control.<p>
