<!--header ends here-->
<H2>Product Nonconformance & Corrective Action</H2><P>
<B>15.1.1     Purpose</B><P>
To establish the procedure for a suppliers response to product nonconformity and corrective action requests.
<P>
<B>15.1.2     Scope</B><P>
Supplier reports of corrective action shall be provided as requested by UT Automotive plant quality or purchasing management, or a designated UT Automotive representative.  Timely and thorough response to a notification of product nonconformity and/or a corrective action request is considered a critical component to the success  of a suppliers relationship with UT Automotive.
<P>
<B>15.1.3     Responsibility</B><P>
It is the responsibility of UT Automotives quality representative, or a designate, to initiate a request for corrective action to a supplier.  UT Automotives quality and engineering will assist in the formulation and/or implementation of supplier corrective action requests, as appropriate.  It is the responsibility of the supplier to initiate immediate and comprehensive containment action upon notification of product non-conformance.
<P>
It is the responsibility of the supplier to submit a target date for completion of interim and complete corrective and preventative action.  The target dates shall be submitted within 48 hours of receipt of the corrective action request.  Any changes in target completion dates shall be immediately communicated, in writing, to the suppliers UT Automotive quality representative.
<P>
<B>15.1.4     Corrective Action Statement Review</B><P>
Suppliers reply to a corrective action request will be reviewed by the plant quality manager, or a designate, to ensure a positive plan of corrective action has been taken to prevent recurrence of a discrepancy.  The effectiveness of corrective action will be evaluated upon receipt of subsequent material (subsequent material shall not reflect the discrepancies which prompted the request for supplier corrective action).  Once the issue is resolved to the satisfaction of the plant quality manager or designate, the report will be closed.  Suppliers are expected to review the request and state interim containment within the time period negotiated.  Apply QS-9000, Element 4.14
<P>
<B>15.1.4.1     Suggested Supplier Corrective Action Plan - Format Description</B><P>
1a)  Supplier<BR>
1b)   Part name<BR>
1c)   Part number<BR>
1d)   Blueprint (B/P), level and date<BR>
2)    Problem and/or defect description<BR>
3)    Interim and/or immediate action<BR>
4)    Material review date<BR>
5)    Build date<BR>
6)    Number of parts<BR>
7)    Number of defects<BR>
8)    Certification of subsequent shipments<BR>
9)    Root cause definition<BR>
10)  Permanent corrective action<BR>
11)  Verification of corrective action<BR>
12)  Statistical evidence<BR>
13)Signatures<BR>
<P>
<B>15.1.5     Control and Liability of Nonconforming Material</B><P>
The supplier will be notified of receipt of nonconforming material in writing, by fax, and/or telephone.  Information included about the nonconformances will include at a minimum:
<UL>
a)  Date received<BR>
b)  Quantity received<BR>
c)  Reason for rejection<BR>
d)  Request for corrective action<BR>
</UL>
<B>15.1.5.1     Return of Shipments</B><P>
In cases where nonconforming material is received by UT Automotive, and the in hand inventory of acceptable material is sufficient to meet UT Automotives immediate needs, the entire shipment may b returned to the supplier.
<P>
<B>15.1.5.2     Supplier Liability for Nonconformance</B><P>
When nonconforming material causes a delay or potential delay in UT Automotive and/or UT Automotive customer production schedules, the supplier may be liable for all sort, rework, or other incurred costs.  The supplier may be permitted the following options, at the discretion of a UT Automotive representative.
<UL>
a)  A certified replacement shipment will be allowed, providing its receipt causes no delays to production.<BR>
b)  Sorting at UT Automotive facility by supplier personnel to maintain production schedules.<BR>
c)  Sorting and/or rework by UT Automotive may be at suppliers expense.  This cost may be at a predetermined rate stated on the purchase order and can be charged to the suppliers account.<BR>
</UL>
<B>15.1.5.3     Nonconforming Product Detected by a UT Automotive Customer</B><P>
If nonconforming material reaches a UT Automotive customer, and the nonconformance is caused by a UT Automotive supplier, that supplier may be liable for all related charges, including sort and/or rework by UT Automotive or the supplier at UT Automotive, and/or UT Automotive customer plant locations.
<P>
<B>15.1.6     Internal Control of Nonconforming Product</B><P>
The supplier shall establish and maintain documented procedures to ensure that product that does not conform to specified requirements is prevented from unintended use or installation.  This control shall provide for identification, documentation, evaluation, segregation (when practical), disposition of nonconforming product, and for notification to the functions concerned.<p>

