<H2>Supplier Performance Evaluation</H2><P>
<B>16.1.1     Purpose</B><P>
UT Automotive evaluates the individual performance of its suppliers to insure compliance to UT Automotives quality, delivery and continuous improvement expectations, as outlined in this policy guide and the QS-9000 standard.
<P>
<B>16.1.2     Scope</B><P>
Supplier performance evaluations should be conducted for UT Automotive material, production and service suppliers.
<P>
<B>16.1.3     Supplier Evaluation Elements</B><P>
The effectiveness of the suppliers quality systems will be evaluated per QS-9000, with an emphasis in defect prevention and commitment to continuous improvement.  UT Automotives Partners in Excellence supplier performance evaluation consists of four basic elements:
<P>
<B>16.1.3.1     Purchasing Measurement</B><P>
a)  Profile data (Form, Appendix E)<BR>
b)  Quality and cost improvements as supported by the financial and technical aspects of the suppliers business plan.<BR>
c)  Timelines and accuracy of product deliveries.<BR>
d)  Responsiveness to engineering changes.<BR>
<P>
<B>16.1.3.2     Quality Measurement</B><P>
a)  Ability to conform to and/or exceed UT Automotive product quality requirements, including product quality requirements of UT Automotives customers.<BR>
b)  Compliance to QS-9000 (which includes ISO 9001) and/or other UT Automotive customer specific requirements, as evidenced by a supplier self-assessment, third party audit or an on-site assessment performed by a UT Automotive representative.<BR>
<P>
<B>16.1 3.3     Technology Measurement</B><P>
a)  Product design and development<BR>
b)  Applied research and development<BR>
c)  Testing capabilities<BR>
<P>
<B>16.1.3.4     Cost Improvement</B><P>
Cost improvement suggestions provided by the supplier resulting in product/process savings.
<P>
<B>16.1.4    Methods of Supplier Performance Evaluation</B><P>
All current material and production suppliers to UT Automotive shall be evaluated by any combination of the performance evaluation measurements below.  The supplier performance evaluation may be used in making sourcing decisions for existing and future purchased material.  The elements of the UT Automotive supplier performance evaluations are as follows:
<P>
<B>16.1.4.1    On-Site Supplier Evaluations</B><P>
UT Automotive Engineering, Purchasing, Quality and manufacturing facilities should jointly decide which suppliers require on site assessment.  On-site evaluations will be led by UT Automotive associates who have successfully completed QS-9000 Lead Auditor training, and will be governed by Quality System Assessment guidelines for auditing and this policy section 16.1.4.
<P>
<B>16.1.4.2     Quality and Deliver Rating Report</B><P>
UT Automotive Purchasing shall periodically provide performance reports to each major supplier.  Typically, major suppliers are those which, ranked by purchased product dollar volume, contribute to approximately 80% of a UT Automotive business units total purchased product dollar volume.
<P>
The quality performance rating (parts per million (PPM) is compiled by summing non conforming quantities for each component from all UT Automotive manufacturing locations within a business unit, and dividing by the total number of components shipped, times 1,000,000.
<P>
<B>PPM = (å PiecesNon-conforming ¸ å QuantityReceived) x 1,000,000</B>
<P>
Product will be considered non-conforming if it does not meet UT Automotives requirements for product specifications, labeling, packaging or part sample warrant approval.
<P>
The delivery performance rating is the percent of compliance to release.  Performance is compiled by summing all on time received quantities for each component part from each supplier at all UT Automotive manufacturing locations within a business unit, and dividing by the sum of all parts released by all UT Automotive manufacturing locations, times 100.
<P>
<B>Delivery (å PartsReceivedOnTime ¸ å RartsReleased) x 100</B>
<P>
<B>16.1.4.3     QSA Assessment</B>
Suppliers shall submit QSA self-assessments when requested, to both the requestor and UT Automotive Quality & Supplier Development, with the initial submission date agreed upon by UT Automotive purchasing.  This assessment, with corrective action plans, will be used to evaluate the suppliers continuous improvement activities.
<P>
<B>16.1.4.4     Cost Deviation Factor</B><P>
The cost deviation from the quoted piece price may be utilized to assess additional expenses incurred by UT Automotive.  External expenses or charges imposed directly to UT Automotive from UT Automotive customers may also be evaluated, if the charges are found to be directly related to the suppliers quality performance.
<P>
<B>16.1.4.5     Total Cost</B><P>
This is a sum of all costs that are realized in the procurement of product form a supplier.  This includes, but is not limited to:  shipping, handling, delivery, quality, inspection, corrective action, and piece price.
<P>
<B>16.1.4.6     Total Piece Price</B><P>
This is calculated by multiplying the annual total received quantity, by the negotiated piece price per part number.
<P>
<B>16.1.4.7     Rejection Notification Cost</B><P>
This is calculated by multiplying the number of rejection notifications, by a cost factor, (defined by the receiving facility).  Suppliers may be charged with this cost, as defined on the rejection notification form.
<P>
<B>16.1.4.8     Material Handling Cost</B><P>
This is calculated by multiplying the number of shipments in excess of the release schedule, by a cost factor (defined by the receiving facility).
<P>
<B>16.1.4.9     Prototype/Part Sample Warrant</B><P>
Suppliers may be reviewed for product adherence to specification, sample submission accuracy and conformance to sample schedules.
<P>
<B>16.1.4.10   Incoming Inspection</B><P>
Suppliers are evaluated on their ability to ship materials that do not require UT Automotive to perform incoming inspection.  The method for determining inspection requirements is outlined below.
<P>
<B>16.1.4.10.a     Skip Lot Sequence</B><P>
The following is a guideline only.  The actual lot quantity that results in inspection free status may vary, based on historical evidence or other rationale (e.g. new technology) to ensure defect free material entering the manufacturing system.  Each supplier part number will be measured by Receiving Inspection for six (6) successive shipments (Inspection Status), then placed on Skip Lot Status provided no manufacturing or receiving rejections occur.  The next five shipments will not be inspected.  The sixth lot will be inspected for verification, and if accepted, the supplier part number will be placed on Certified Status.  The next ten shipments will not be inspected.  The eleventh shipment will be inspected for verification, and if accepted, the supplier part number will be placed on Inspection Free status.  No shipments will be inspected for the remaining life of the program, unless significant product concerns develop.  If rejections occur at any status, the supplier part number returns to Inspection Status, and begins the skip log sequence again.  See Appendix F for a visual depiction of the skip lot process.
<P>
<B>16.1.4.10.b     Parts Free of Inspection Status</B><P>
UT Automotive Purchasing evaluates the inspection status of each suppliers part on a periodic basis.  The total quantity of a suppliers parts on Inspection Free status will be divided by the total quantity of parts supplied to establish the percent of supplier parts on Inspection Free status.
<P>
<B>16.1.5     UT Automotive Conducted Assessments</B><P>
Under certain circumstances, a trained UT Automotive QS-9000 lead auditor shall conduct a QSA assessment at the suppliers facility.  UT Automotive assessments are conducted, as outlined in QSA, Process for Second Party Assessments.  The on site assessment process includes a documentation review, on site assessment, and verification of corrective actions.  Scoring will be conducted utilizing the zero to three (0-3) point rating variable score method.  In developing suppliers, UT Automotive will conduct supplier assessments should any of the following issues arise:
<UL>
a)  Recurring relationship and/or communication concerns<BR>
b)  Consistently high number of defects (PPM)<BR>
c)  Less than satisfactory delivery performance<BR>
d)  High number of quality rejection notices<BR>
e)  New supplier<BR>
</UL>
In addition to the above criteria, consideration of the following will be weighed in the decision to conduct  an on-site assessment:
<UL>
a)  Purchased dollar volume<BR>
b)  Low percentage of parts on Inspection Free status<BR>
c)  Self-assessment and/or action plans not submitted to UT Automotive<BR>
d)  Suppliers self-assessment score does not correlate to the PPM and Delivery ratings<BR>
e)  Suppliers components and/or materials are critical to the production process.<BR>
</UL>
<B>16.1.6     New Supplier Criteria</B><P>
New supplier candidates will be evaluated, per section 16.1 of this policy guide, prior to an award of business.  An on-site facility review may be conducted with participation from UT Automotive Purchasing, Engineering and Quality representatives.
<P>
<B>16.1.7     UT Automotive Performance Awards</B><P>
Performance awards are presented annually to suppliers who demonstrate the best value to UT Automotive.  New suppliers may be eligible for the preferred supplier or Partners in Excellence award with a minimum one year history.  Two levels of nomination may be awarded to a supplier, based on the following measures of quality, delivery, and QSA point award.  Special consideration can be given for suppliers to receive a preferred status, providing they have obtained significant and consistent continuous improvement objectives related to quality, delivery and cost outlined by the nominating business unit.  All sourcing UT Automotive manufacturing facilities must concur with the award nomination.
<UL>
<U><B><I>Preferred Supplier Award</I></B></U><BR>
Compliance rating level of ³ 80%, PPM defects £ 100, and delivery ³ 98%.<BR>
<U><B><I>Partners in Excellence Award</I></B></U><BR>
Compliance rating level of ³ 85%, PPM defects £ 50, and delivery = 100%.<BR>
</UL>
<B>16.1.8     Unsatisfactory Supplier Performance</B><P>
UT Automotive is unwilling to accept poor product, service, delivery and/or relationship quality from its suppliers.  Individual concerns shall be addressed with corrective action reports.  Chronic problem suppliers (high PPM defect rate, poor delivery performance, unresponsiveness to concerns, etc.)  will be governed by the UT Automotive sourcing facilitys supplier corrective action procedure and may be desourced.

