<h2> Instrument Panel Ergonomics: <br>Designing Beyond Accessibility</h2>
<h4>by <a href="obrien.htm">Timothy O'Brien</a></h4>
<p> </P>
<h3>Introduction</h3>
<p>When most people think of ergonomics, the first thing they usually visualize is the "Oscar Layout" or "SID" the crash test dummy. We think of designing an instrument panel (I/P) so that most drivers - from the ninety-ninth-percent male through the third-percent female - can comfortably fit behind the wheel and easily access all vehicle controls. Total ergonomic design, however, goes beyond accessibility to include functionality and aesthetics.</P>
<p>Several real-world examples come to mind when we consider this concept of total ergonomic design, such as the annoyance of driving at night with the constant reflection of cluster lights hitting the driver's eyes from the windshield or side window, or the sound of that cold-weather squeak between the trim bezel and
<p><cite>"We must bear in mind that the object we are working on is going to be ridden in, sat upon, looked at, talked to, activated, operated or in some other way used by people.</P>
<p>"If the point of contact between the product and the people becomes a point of friction, the designer has failed.</p>
<p>"On the other hand, if people are made safer, more efficient more comfortable or just plain happier - by contact with the product, then the designer has succeeded."</P></cite>
<p>To succeed with an automotive instrument panel design, all forms of driver contact, desires or expectations must be considered. Controls mounted on the I/P must be visible; be located where expected, and function according to the operator's preconceived method. Matching the customer's perceptions with this given expectations will create perfect harmony between man and machine.</p>

<h3>Ergonomics' Basic Aim</h3>
<h3></h3>
<p>The basic aim of ergonomics is to measure the capabilities of the man and then to arrange the environment to fit such abilities. An attempt to "fit the job to the man" rather than to "fit the man to the job." These measured capabilities are more than simply dimensional and size constraints.</P>
<p>We receive information from the outside world from our senses - sight, hearing, taste, touch and smell. The sensory system receives stimuli and send information along the particular sensory system. This is the process. On entering the brain these nerve impulses are interpreted to produce recognizable patterns of sight, smell, sound, etc. This process is influences greatly by the individual's past experiences and expectations. This process of perception, however, is entirely subjective in nature.</P>
<p>The design criteria of an instrument panel can be considered to fall into two general areas. The first are requirements associated with the actual measured capabilities of the man. These are such items as accessibility, efforts of controls, and all safety-related items, whether federal regulations or strictly occupant protection criteria. These "hard" design criteria items make up the sets of standards for most instrument panel design requirements. Standards are required to verify that the occupant can physically, comfortably and safely operate the motor vehicle. This part of the design phase is of most interest to the engineering and design team. The actual operator, however, assumes the majority of these items to be a given. He expects to be able to see and reach all controls, to fit comfortably behind the wheel and to know that he is safe.</P>
<p>A second area of I/P design criteria may have more to do with the operator's perception of design rather than the actual standard design requirements. For starters, before anyone even touches a product, an opinion is formed based solely upon its appearance. Many people feel as though they're "looking at what they paid for" while driving down the road. The visual quality of an I/P is one of the most important features of an automobile. Obtaining consistent color and gloss, as well as maintaining excellent fit and finish between components, gives the operator that good feeling about the car. Of equal importance is that vehicle controls must function in the manner the operator expects. He finds controls located where he thinks they should be and they look and function as expected.</p>
<h3>Instrument Panel Design</h3>
<p>The instrument panel design process takes us from the styling clay model through final production drawing release (or CAD tape). A packaging drawing is constructed around three major I/P sections. First is through the steering column center which is used to verify driver fit and sight requirements. A section through the center line of vehicle is used to package all center stack controls, A/C outlets, ash receiver etc. Finally a third section through the P.A.B. door and glove box opening is used to package the airbag canister, verify glove box opening is used to package the airbag canister, verify glove box swing and evaluate fit of the passenger.</P>
<p>The starting point for any instrument panel design is the orientation of the driver and passenger relative to the vehicle interior. In Figure 2 we see the start of an I/P packaging layout showing the 95th percentile driver. The mannequin is placed in the rearmost "H" point or seating position marked "Hr." The "eyellipse," shown in Figure 3, is a standard SAE tool used by the industry to indicate the range of drivers eye location. It is designed such that any line of sight tangent to this ellipse defines a boundary that accommodates 99 percent of the drivers. In addition to verifying unobstructed viewing of all controls, the line-of-sight studies are used to predict any unwanted reflections off the vehicle windshield. Figure 4 shows a line-of-sight study predicting veiling glare, a phenomenon usually seen as an inverted ghost-like image of the I/P surface and any surface features present such as defroster grilles.</P>
<p>In addition to these dimensional and visual requirements for the I/P, there are several safety criteria. Occupant protection is a critical feature of every instrument panel design. Such requirements as head impact (FMVSS 201), knee impact (FMVSS 208) or homologations must be designed into the system. Each OEM has a set of standards (typically beyond that of the federal requirements) used to verify maximum occupant safety during a potential accident.</P>
<p>The ergonomics of physical size, shape and strength abilities of the occupant generate these sets of "hard" design criteria. Standards are created to accommodate the full range of the population relative to these physical parameters. Although of great importance, most operators of vehicle actually are unaware of these designed-in features. Again, the driver expects to be comfortable behind the wheel, to be able to see and reach all controls and generally be happy driving his new vehicle. Beyond the accessibility of all controls are the ergonomics: their movement, locations and looks.</P>

<h3>Ergonomics of Controls</h3>
<p>The number and complexity of automotive controls is increasingly dramatically as features and functions for safety, comfort and convenience are added. Cruise controls, power windows, locks, mirrors and power seat adjustments are just a few of the added features available in most cars today. These additional controls obviously result in instrument panels that are more intricate and crowded than ever before. The issues of control design, placement and looks thus presents a challenge to I/P design teams.</P>
<p>When expectancies for the preferred direction of control operation are found to be the same in a large percentage of people, the expectancies can be termed "population stereotypes." Several direction-of-motion stereotypes are shown in Figure 5. These are the SAE findings for "on" or "increasing" directions. Some of these stereotypes come from associations to controls found in the home - light switches, appliances or volume buttons on a TV, for example. Rather extensive surveys and experimentation are required to obtain these population stereotypes. Some evolve slowly as the general population becomes more familiar with a type of control. See, for example, the left and right stalk controls shown in Figure 6. People are becoming more familiar with using the steering wheel stalks to control such features as high beams, wipers and washers. Consistency in design is crucial for this type of control.</P>
<p>The general location of certain controls is another expectancy of drivers. The high-beam control, for example, previously was a foot switch and now, as mentioned, has been moved to the left stalk. The power-mirror switches shown in Figure 7 are being evaluated for door- versus console-mounting locations. Again, consistency creates location as well as direction-of-motion stereotypes.</P>
<p>The look of a particular control - or more specifically the symbol representing it - has become a standard set by SAE (J1048). The International Standardization Organization (ISO) has created 25 automotive "ISO" symbols used in the automotive interior to identify certain controls and displays. The chart in Figure 8 shows the result of a recent survey relative to ISO symbol recognition. The percentages of correct recognition, shown at the top of the chart, indicate that there are several symbols which do not yet have strong stereotypes.</p>
<p>The determination of tendencies for any of these forms of stereotypes is an ongoing study. As the direction of motion, location or symbolic look of controls becomes more and more consistent across vehicles from around the globe, these particular stereotypes will be converted into additional I/P ergonomic design standards. With new features will come new controls requiring additional surveys to establish the next evolution of stereotypes.</P><p>
<h3>Summary</h3>
<p>The complexity of future instrument panel designs increasingly will be steadily as the number of additional features become standard equipment. Such techniques as head up displays (HUD) where controls are projected onto the windshield, will definitely become standard. The focused image just over the hood can contain all control displays and symbols. just as with the manual controls, these types of controls also will require extensive customer evaluations. Looking for any advanced stereotype tendencies will help design the system so that the customer is comfortable with it.</P>
<p>Another technique to be used in future I/P designs will be the use of "virtual reality." In this totally simulated world, a designer (or potential customer) can completely drive the vehicle, operating all controls and evaluating comfort, convenience and the actual look of the vehicle interior. All of this can be accomplished through computer simulation techniques without investing the time and money required to produce prototype mock-up systems. The entire interior environment can be designed, simulated, evaluated and changed before any tooling has been started.</P>
<p>The instrument panel design, obviously, must continue to accommodate all constraints and capabilities relative to the varied population of intended occupants. To obtain the highest degree of quality of an I/P design, however, we must go beyond mere accessibility. Designing an extremely user-friendly environment will generate the greatest customer perceptions of quality, comfort and enjoyment. True customer focus is the only way to approach the perfect match of man and machine.
<p> <h3><a href="references.htm">References</a></p></h3>
<!--footer begins here-->
