<h2> Photonic Displays</h2>
<h3>Take to the Road<br>
<I>New flat-panel technologies chase liquid-crystal displays for automotive applications.</I></h3>
<p>by Silviu Palalau
as published in <cite>Photonics Spectra</cite>, April, 1996
<p>
<IMG SRC="images/fig1.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="491" HEIGHT="244">


<br><hr>
<strong>Figure 1. </strong><em>Flat-panel displays: not your father's dashboard.</em>   <hr>             
<p>Automobiles have undergone some remarkable changes since their inception. They no longer are 
just a means of transportation; they have become a home away from  home with all of the creature 
comforts to which we are accustomed. Even navigational aids, including digital maps and orbital 
satellites that monitor the precise location of a vehicle, have come of age.</p>

<p>Map navigation systems show the driver's position on a map, the route to a selected destination,
 and, if an Information Traffic System is implemented, traffic-jam areas and alternate routes. The 
 technology is mature enough to be accepted in the automotive world; several map navigation systems
  already are on the market. </p>

<p>There is an increasing number of high-information-content systems in a car (e.g., map navigation,
 collision warning/avoidance, rearview camera, etc.). These high-information-content systems have a 
 common thread: the need for a high-resolution flat-panel display.</p>

<p>In late January, UT Automotive and Planar Systems entered into a series of 
agreements focused at jointly developing electroluminescent display products for the automobile market.
 The systems could provide navigation, vehicle tracking, function controls, security, trip computing,
  mapping/routing and other features (Figure 1). The decision to focus on electroluminescent displays 
  was based on a study of mature and emerging display technologies and the specific properties needed 
  for automotive applications.</p>
<p>
<hr>
<strong>What car-makers need</strong>

<p>Flat-panel display requirements are related to the application and location in the car. The
applications include the information center in the console area shared by the driver and passenger, 
the instrument panel in front of the driver (and which the passenger may view), and so-called "head-up" 
information projected directly onto the windshield so the driver need not look down to access the 
information. The challenging automotive goal for the first two categories is high optical 
performance and automotive compliance at low cost ($2 or less per square inch of display).</p>

<p>The contrast ratio in low and high ambient light is the most important measure of optical
 performance and is measured as follows:</p>

<em>Contrast ratio = (brightness of image + reflected light)/(brightness of background + 
reflected light).</em>

<p>The brightness level specified by many display manufacturers is inadequate for use in 
automotive applications because of the ambient sunlight environment. It is generally accepted 
in automotive human-factors studies that a contrast ratio of 1.2 is the lowest value that provides 
legibility. High-contrast and low-reflectivity values are needed within the driver's optical cone 
and the passenger's field of vision.</p>

<p>Another measure of optical performance is the number of colors or hues. Full-color capability 
should be considered if the display is a TV/video monitor. However, US safety regulations prohibit 
drivers from watching TV while driving; therefore, multicolor displays with a limited number of 
colors and shades per color may be considered for information centers or instrument panels if 
they are more cost-effective.</p>

<p>Each car manufacturer sets its own environmental conditions and guidelines for testing
 electromechanical or optical parts, but they share almost the same philosophy in considering 
 environmental factors. The environmental working conditions depend on the display's mounting
  place and position in the car. Typically, the operational temperature range is from -30&#186C 
  to +80&#186C, but they may be up to +92&#186C on some of the instrument panel surfaces exposed
   to sun.</p>

<p>Temperature cycle and temperature shock tolerance (to simulate opening the car door on a very 
cold day or a very hot day) are also tested. The operational voltage range is from 9 to 16 V with
 some variations (reverse voltage, load dump fluctuation, low-voltage and high-voltage conductive 
 and inductive noise). Electromagnetic interference is another environmental condition that should
  be considered at high and low frequencies (i.e., the audio spectrum) so that the display will 
  not interfere with other electronics circuitry placed nearby.</p>

<p>The current technologies of choice for automotive applications are liquid-crystal displays
 for high-resolution needs (because of their availability) and vacuum fluorescent displays for
  low-resolution needs (because of their low price). Competing technologies for this market 
  include electroluminescent display, plasma displays and field emitter displays.</p>
<p>
<hr>
<strong>The old stand-by</strong>
<p>There are several categories of liquid-crystal displays, but the common denominator is a 
substance called liquid crystal, which maintains its properties within a temperature band between
 solidified and liquefied points.</p>

<p>Liquid-crystal displays have some basic problems, including limited operational temperature 
range, low response time, low contrast, limited viewing angle, need for an external light source,
 need for polarizers, flickering, crosstalk, and a trade-off between brightness and lifetime 
 (the higher the brightness, the shorter the lifetime). Also, like any organic material, these 
 displays need an ultraviolet- and infarred-blocking layer to protect them from sunlight and external 
 light sources.</p>

<p>Attempts to correct these problems have made the liquid-crystal display (LCD) family a tree 
with many branches:</p>
<ul>
<li>In polymer-disperse LCDs, the passage of light is controlled by the electric field without 
the use of polarizers. In polymer-stabilized cholesteric-texture LCDs, the cholesteric liquid 
crystal display reflects the light. There are two stable states (or textures): the reflecting
 planar state and the nonreflecting focal conic state. This provides a high-contrast display in 
 sunlight and does not need polarizers. Its bistability enables it to retain images without any 
 power. Disadvantages include very long response time (about 5 seconds) and only monocolor 
 (no shades).</li><p>
<li>Active-matrix LCDs have a switching element for each pixel. The active element may be either
 a two-terminal, diode kind (metal isolated metal) or a three-terminal-element thin-film transistor 
 on amorphous silicon or ploy silicon. These displays overcome the flickering problem by isolating
  each pixel in the matrix. The pixel is activated during each refresh cycle and remains activated 
  due to a stored charge.</li></ul>
<p>The main problems with active-matrix displays are their complex structure and the number of parts
 included in the display system. (Figure 2)
<P><IMG SRC="images/fig2.gif" ALT="figure 2"  ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="158" HEIGHT="422"><hr><strong>Figure 2.</strong><em> The active-matrix 
liquid-crystal display comprises many layers of materials and optical elements.</EM><hr>
 These result in the high manufacturing costs. The only 
 advantage of the simple-matrix LCD (or "passive" LCD) vs. active-matrix LCD is lower manufacturing 
 costs (about one-third of the active-matrix displays).</p>
<ul><li>Ferroelectric LCDs maintain their orientation without an applied voltage, so the inherent 
memory of the ferroelectric materials allows simpler drive electronics than an active-matrix LCD 
(i.e., no refreshing of the screen is needed). These crystals also switch more quickly and provide
 higher contrast. They are difficult to manufacture, however, because of the photosensitivity of
  the ferroelectric crystal and the very narrow spacing and tolerances of the liquid-crystal cell.</li><p>
<li>Twisted nematic molecules twist 90&#186 and use polarizers to block the light. Supertwisted 
nematic molecules twist 180&#186 to 270&#186 (typically 240&#186) and use the twisted crystals 
as a light-frequency retarder. The transmission/voltage characteristic has a much steeper slope; 
therefore, much greater contrast can be achieved.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<strong>Competing technologies</strong>
<p>Vacuum fluorescent technology comes in three basic types: character display or 5 x 7-matrix dots;
 custom-designed characters and symbols; and large, high-resolution matrix dots (300 x 200). The first
  two are low-resolution displays (about 3 x 3-mm dot size) already in use in cars. Despite their high
   brightness, the contrast is not very good in ambient sunlight. Increasing the brightness can 
   increase contrast, but this produces some temperature dissipation problems, especially for large 
   displays. Another disadvantage is the lack of shades and colors.</p>
<p>Some display manufacturers offer highly integrated, low-resolution, custom-designed displays and
 driving electronics at a very low price. But high-resolution vacuum florescent displays are still
  in the prototype stage, struggling with driving electronics and temperature dissipation problems.</p>
<p>A less-developed technology, the field-emitter display, is struggling to find a good manufacturing
 process for sharp tips or diamond layers. Also, field emitters have trouble with high operating 
 voltages and accidental discharges between pixels; this technology is not yet mature enough for 
 automotive application.</p>
<p>Another contender, the electroluminescent display, looks more promising. It offers a robust solid-state
 structure, (Figure 3) the ability to operate in harsh environments and a wide viewing angle. 
 <P><IMG SRC="images/fig3.gif" ALT="figure 3" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="235" HEIGHT="204">
 <HR><STRONG> Figure 3.</STRONG><EM>Multicolor electroluminescent display structure developed by Planar Systems</EM><hr><p>
 An emissive display, it does not need an external light source. The displayed information can 
 be multicolor (multiple shades of red and green), with high contrast in high ambient light, so 
 it is readable in sunlight.</p>
<p>Unlike the liquid-crystal display, the electroluminescent display has a quick response time 
independent of temperature.(Figure 4)
<p><IMG SRC="images/fig4.gif" ALT="figure 4" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="504" HEIGHT="216">
<hr><STRONG> Figure 4.</STRONG><EM>Electroluminescent displays respond more quickly then thin-film-transistor liquid-crystal displays, especially in cold weather.</EM><hr>
 Consequently, electroluminescent displays do not require 
extra components (e.g., heaters) to support display startup in cold weather conditions. In addition,
 electroluminescents do not require protection, as liquid-crystal displays do, from overheating in 
 direct exposure to sunlight, which can wash out the screen. The electroluminescent display also has
  a wider viewing angle than the LCD (Figure 5).</p>
  <p><IMG SRC="images/fig5.gif" ALT="figure 5" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="403" HEIGHT="216"><hr>
 <strong>Figure 5.</strong><em>Contrast is more stable across all viewing angles in electroluminescent displays than in thin-film-transistor liquid-crystal displays.</em><hr>
<p>
<strong>Color still a concern</strong>
<p>Electroluminescent technology lags behind liquid crystals in one significant area: It lacks 
full-color capability on electroluminescent displays is still complicated from a manufacturing 
standpoint (and thus costly), and full-color technology has reached only the prototype stage. 
Consequently, it is not yet an option.</p>
<p>In comparison to vacuum florescent display technology, electroluminescent technology has 
fewer problems with temperature and power dissipation in larger sizes (e.g., 300 x 200 pixels, 
where vacuum fluorescence is in prototype stages). Electroluminescent displays also offer higher
 resolution and more colors and shades per color than vacuum fluorescence.</p>  
<p> In comparison to plasma display technology, electroluminescence has a higher resolution, 
a higher contrast and more shades per color. Also, plasma displays are much larger (i.e., the 
electroluminescent is more compact) because of the size of glass required and the barrier ribs
 that are required to isolate each individual pixel.</p>
<p>The next generation of cars will need flat-panel displays. The choice of a technology will
 be determined by application, price and performance. From a technical standpoint and based 
 on its inherent characteristics, electroluminescent display technology is the most feasible 
 option for automotive high-resolution displays. Because of its simple structure, manufacturing 
 costs should be lower than those for liquid-crystal, which is by far the most significant 
 competitor.<p>
<p>
<p>
<hr>

<strong>Meet the author</strong>
<p>Silviu Palalau is Senior Engineer for flat-panel displays at UT Automotive
 in Dearborn, Michigan.</p>

