<h2> Energy Storage Technologies and Their Benefits to Hybrid Vehicles</h2>
<h4>by Evan C. Polley and Thomas W. Grudkowski <BR>United Technologies Research Center</h4>

<p>
<h3>HYBRID ELECTRIC VEHICLES</h3>

<P>Concern over the environment effects of mobile source air pollution (especially CO, NOx, and volatile organic compounds) has caused various forms of government regulation during the past twenty years.  Recently state governments in the United States, most notably, California, have begun to mandate the use of "zero-emissions" or all-electric vehicles (EV) to concentrate air pollution at more easily managed electric utility power plants.</P>
<P>To maintain customer satisfaction, automobile manufacturer must respond to these environmental concerns without substantially increasing the cost or reducing the performance (range, acceleration, availability of auxiliaries such as heat or air conditioning) of their products.  As will be developed below, there no energy storage technologies that appear to offer the ability to completely and cost-effectively replace conventional heat engines with battery-powered electric motors.  This technological limit will likely continue well into the next decade.</P>
<P>A potentially viable alternative is the hybrid electric vehicle (HEV), which combines a heat engine with electric drive and some on-board electric energy storage.  HEV's offer the opportunity to substantially reduce emissions of pollUT Automotivents while maintaining current performance.  The existing refueling infrastructure is also maintained. An additional benefit that can be expected is a significant improvement in fuel efficiency. The United States' Partnership for New Generation Vehicle (PNGV) goal is roughly 3 liters per 100 km, a level likely to be very attractive to automobile drivers and buyers.</P>
<P>Comparisons among the power train systems for a 1500 kg passenger car are shown in Table 1.</P>

<TITLE>Drive-System Comparisons</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<TABLE>
<TABLE BORDER=2>
<CAPTION><B>Table 1.</B> Drive-System Comparisons</CAPTION>


<TR>
	<TH></TH>
	<TH>Current Conventional Vehicle</TH>
	<TH>Zero Emissions Vehicle</TH>
	<TH>Hybrid-Electric Vehicle</TH>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Typical Energy Source</TD>
	<TD>100kW gasoline engine</TD>
	<TD>Electric utility</TD>
	<TD>25 kW diesel generator</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Typical Energy Storage</TD>
	<TD>Fuel Tank</TD>
	<TD>Lead-acid or ?? battery</TD>
	<TD>Fuel tank and flywheel</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Typical Drivetrain</TD>
	<TD>Mechanical</TD>
	<TD>Electric Motor</TD>
	<TD>Mechanical and electric motor</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>"Refueling" System</TD>
	<TD>Existing</TD>
	<TD>Needs battery recharge stations or similar capability</TD>
	<TD>Existing (including electric recharge from grid, only when convenient and cost-effective</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TH></TH>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Acceleration, Gradability</TD>
	<TD>Acceptable</TD>
	<TD>Reduced by 30% or more</TD>
	<TD>Unchanged</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Range Between Fueling</TD>
	<TD>Acceptable</TD>
	<TD>Reduced by 75% or more</TD>
	<TD>Unchanged</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Emissions (CO, NO<SUB>x</SUB>, VOC)</TD>
	<TD>Highest</TD>
	<TD>None on-board, some at electric utility, lowest overall</TD>
	<TD>Emissions reduced by up to 75% vs. current conventional vehicle</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Efficiency</TD>
	<TD>Lowest-9 liters/100 km</TD>
	<TD>Complicated calculation-but likely highest, after battery infrastructure is in place</TD>
	<TD>Middle-"PNGV" goal is 3 liters/100km</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TH></TH>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>*Key Issues</TD>
	<TD>*Cost and achievability of significant emissions and efficiency gains</TD>
	<TD>*Vehicle performance<BR>*Cost of batteries and battery infrastructure, including disposal</TD>
	<TD>*Cost of more complex drive system</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE><BR><BR>

<h3>HYBRID VEHICLE TYPES</h3>
<P>	HEV's  are typically divided into "parallel" and "series" types.  Parallel HEV's have both mechanical and electric drive capability, often linked by clutch mechanisms.  Serial HEV's have only electrical drive.  Here, the hear engine is employed only to power a generator to create electricity.  Both types must have electric energy storage and electric drives both are capable of using regenerated braking energy to extend range and enhance efficiency.  HEV's can be further divided by their mode of operation.  They can be either "dual mode" permitting zero emission, pure electric operation or "power assist" where both battery and heat engine power are typically applied together.
<P>	Given these system-level differences and the number of major powertrain subsystems (heat engine, generator, electric energy storage, fuel storage, mechanical drives, electric traction drive, controller (s), interfaces, etc.), the challenge of optimizing HEV designs is significant.  Bradford Bates of Ford Motor Co. has created a useful framework for discussing these design trade-offs.<B>[2]</B>. Figure 1 is adapted from his recent use of three-dimensional design space that demonstrates the variations in heat engine size, electric drive capability and electric energy storage. Fuel storage is not a design limiting factor in most cases. In Fig. 1, designs for series HEV's can be placed on the top surface of the cube. Parallel HEV's occupy the interior of the cube. Conventional vehicles and pure electric vehicles occupy the limit powers at the two of the cube's corners.</P>
<BR>

<IMG SRC="images/hev.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="431" HEIGHT="261" BORDER="0">

<HR>
Figure 1. HEV Design Trade-off
<HR>
<p>
<BR>
<P>	Figure 1 highlights some of the key issues facing HEV designers. For both parallel and series HEVs, choice of dual mode (such as points A or B in Fig. 1) operation requires equipping the vehicle with electric and heat engine drives that are each fully capable of powering the vehicle.  The on-board energy storage requirement is significant. Power-assist operation (as at point C or D in Fig. 1) sacrifices the ability to operate in pure electric mode but enables reduction in both electric drive and heat engine capability.  Modern, high efficiency components and controls are required in both cases.  However, careful energy and power management can allow smaller less capable sub-systems 
to combine to provide performances similar to conventional vehicles.  Figure 2, adapted from BMW., shows the parallel and series HEV operating strategies in power assist mode <B>[4]</B>.</P>
<P>	Figure 3 shows a specific example of each of the four possible combinations of parallel/series and dual mode power assist. The notional vehicle is a 1500 kg passenger car of approximately model year (MY) 2004. Performance should be, in general, equivalent to current conventional designs, with typical accessories. Although lighter vehicles and specific purpose vehicles may be possible, the vehicle target should embody the mainstream, high volume and low-cost technologies that provide today's high levels of customer satisfaction. For comparison, the four examples of Fig. 3 have been plotted on Fig. 1 at the point A, B, C, and D.</P>
<BR>


<IMG SRC="images/shybrid.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="495" HEIGHT="155" BORDER="0">
<HR>
Figure 2. Power Assist Operating Strategies
<HR>
<p><p>
<IMG SRC="images/power.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="470" HEIGHT="299" BORDER="0">

<HR>
Figure 3. HEV Power System Examples
<HR>
<p>

<H3>ENERGY STORAGE REQUIREMENTS</H3>
<P>The HEV energy storage goals of the PNGV program are compared to various energy storage technologies in Table 2 <B>[1], [2], [3], [5], [7-10]</B>.</p> 


<TITLE>Performance Specifications for HEV Energy Storage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<TABLE>
<TABLE BORDER=2>
<CAPTION><B>Table 2.</B> Performance Specifications for HEV Energy Storage</CAPTION>


<TR>
	<TH></TH>
	<TH>Specific Energy<BR>(whr/kg)</TH>
	<TH>Specific Power<BR>(kw/kg)</TH>
	<TH>Lifetime<BR>(Cycles)</TH>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>PNG Goals for MY 20004</TD>
	<TD><BR></TD>
	<TD><BR></TD>
	<TD><BR></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD><I>Power Assist</I></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>40</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1.20</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>5x10<SUP>5</SUP></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD><I>Dual Mode</I></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>67</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>1.10</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>5x10<SUP>5</SUP></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TH></TH>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Lead Acid</TD>
	<TD><BR></TD>
	<TD><BR></TD>
	<TD><BR></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD><I>Near-Term</I></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>40</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.15</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>~1x10<SUP>3</SUP></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD><I>MY 2004 (Horizon)</I></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>55</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.40</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>~?x10<SUP>3</SUP></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Nickel/Cadmium</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>60</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.20</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>~2x10<SUP>3</SUP></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Nickel/Metal Hydride (Ovonics)</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>80</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.20</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>~1x10<SUP>3</SUP></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Nickel/Sodium Chloride</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>100</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.15</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>~1x10<SUP>3</SUP></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD>Lithium Polymer, MY 2004+</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>130</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>0.15</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>~1x10<SUP>3</SUP></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>

<P>	All the electro-chemical batteries fall short of the HEV requirements in two areas: specific power and cycle life. Although there is sufficient energy storage available for reasonable battery weights, these batteries will neither provide sufficient power not last the lifetime of the vehicle. The 60 kW or 80 kW traction motors of Fig. 3 will be uselessly oversized unless sufficient electric power is available. Conversely, low powered vehicles that require customers to repeatedly buy expensive replacement batteries will be unresponsive to customers needs.  Further, a lack of power density will greatly reduce the energy efficiently impact of regenerative braking. Note that no battery technology promises performance equal to the United States Advanced Battery Consortium (USABC) Long-Term EV Goal. Together, with the absence of an electric vehicle recharging infrastructure, this lack of an appropriate energy storage technology will undermine any regulatory effort to use pure electric drive systems in mainstream vehicle applications.</P>
<P>	Two alternative to electrochemical batteries are now under development:  flywheel energy storage and ultracapacitors.  Both promise ample power and cycle life, but are challenged by store energy in a polarized liquid layer which forms when an electric potential is created between two electrodes in an electrolyte, seem unlikely to be developed to a level of energy density that would be useful in a vehicle. Flywheel energy storage, where energy is stored in a rotating mass of composite material connected to a motor/generator, seems most likely to find an application in HEV's. Flywheel devices can be scaled for different power requirements (by changing the motor/generator) separately from scaling for energy storage requirements through changes in the rotating structure.  
This flexibility is responsive to the large number of potential designs in Fig. 1. Additionally, unlike many chemical batteries, flywheel devices are environmentally benign and pose no disposal problems at the end of their useful life. A pre-prototype flywheel surge power unit, under development by UT Automotive with BMW A.G., is shown in Fig. 4 <B>[5]</B>.</P></P>
<BR>

<IMG SRC="images/engine.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="228" HEIGHT="251" BORDER="1">
<IMG SRC="images/flywheel.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="230" HEIGHT="253" BORDER="0"</TH>

<HR>
Figure 4. UT Automotive, Inc., Flywheel Surge Power Unit

<HR>
<p>
<IMG SRC="images/unit.GIF" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="495" HEIGHT="354" BORDER="0">
<HR>
Figure 5. Energy Storage Options for 1500 kg Passenger Car
<HR>
<p>

<H3>DESIGNING ENERGY STORAGE SYSTEM FOR HEV'S</H3> 
<P>The target 1500 kg passenger car with conventional vehicle performance and accessories shall require energy storage of at least 25 kWhr to operate pure electric. If electric operation range is 4 km/kWhr for typical drive cycles, a rather limiting 100 km range between recharging results. Unfortunately, any battery technology that will be available in the foreseeable future will require a tremendous mass of batteries to store this much energy and also deliver adequate power. Limiting the battery mass to a more realistic 200 kg provides insight into design possibilities that are more likely to be practical. </P>
<P>The electric power requirement placed on the energy storage system depends on the heat engine power available and the choice of dual mode vs. power available and the choice of dual mode vs. power assist operation. For the example power systems of Fig. 3, this electric power requirement is 50 kW to 80 kW.</P>
<P>Figure 5 applies the specifications of Table 2 to the two relevant axes of the design space cube of Fig. 1. In each case, the candidate energy storage technology is plotted for a range up to 200 kg of energy storage mass. The PNGV and USABC energy storage goals are also plotted,</P>
<P>Limitations on the design space are caused by the limitations in the energy storage technologies. Practical general use of pure electric vehicles are shown unlikely. Allowing 500 kg of the nickel metal hydride batteries may yield 40 kWhrs of energy storage and 100 kW electric power output. The cost of such a mass of batteries, and the impact on the design of the vehicle's structure, are likely to be unacceptable. Even among HEV design option, energy storage limitations will reduce the options available. Practical design points exist around the PNGV goals of 2 kWhr to 5 kWhr for energy storage and 60 kW to 80 kW electric power output. Flywheel technology is responsive here. However, flywheel technology, especially for the 5 kWhr device, is unlikely to fully meet PNGV goal for energy storage mass.</P>
<P>Advance electrochemical batteries may prove useful in providing limited range or low-power zero-emissions operations for dual mode HEV's. But unlike flywheel device where energy storage and power output are independent parameters only specific ratios of energy storage to power are available to HEV designers using electrochemical batteries.</P>
<P>Ultra capacitor applications are more limited. They are most likely to be useful for very high power output power needs that do not have substantial energy storage requirements. An example would be pre-heating of emissions-controlling catalysts to reduce start-up on conventional vehicles.</P>
<p>
<H3>KEY ISSUES: COST AND DEVELOPMENT</H3>

<P>The PNGV cost challenge for HEV energy storage technologies is significant. The 2 kWhr, 60 kW device is targeted at $1000 for MY 2004 with the 5 kWhr, 80 kW drive at $2000 ($20/kg and $27/kg respectively).  These challenging cost goals will constrain designers of electric energy storage devices to avoid exotic materials and manufacturing processes.  Designs at the limit of material allowable or with overly precise tolerances or construction techniques will be most unlikely to succeed. The PNGV goals are most likely to be met in the high-volume production environment that characterizes most automotive manufacturing.  This is a key reason for focusing development efforts on applications that are likely to be broadly appealing to customers, rather than on limited or specialty markets.</P>
<P>With the early involvement of high volume automotive manufacturers, design evolution can be undertaken now that will result in HEV's that are both environmentally beneficial and genuinely desired by the driving public early in the next decade. </P>
<p> <h3><A HREF="hybridrefs.htm">References</A></p></h3>

