<h5>Contact: Tom Andrew (<a href="mailto:tandrew@uta.com">tandrew@uta.com</a>)<BR>
Contact: Lin Cummins (<a href="mailto:lcummins@uta.com">lcummins@uta.com</a>)<br></h5> 
<H2>
UT Automotive expands electronics in Europe</H2>
<P>
<P><STRONG>
KRONACH, Germany Jan. 27, 1997</strong> - UT Automotive, a United Technologies company, signaled its expansion in the automotive electronics industry in Europe by signing an agreement to form a joint venture with Loewe Opta GmbH, a German electronics company.<p>

"This joint venture demonstrates our commitment to supporting our global customers," said Norm Bodine, president and chief executive officer of UT Automotive. "Loewe has been an excellent supplier of automotive electronics to the European automotive industry. This joint venture supports our company's efforts to quickly expand our electronic capabilities in the European market with established, high-quality products and name recognition."<p>
UT Automotive is the majority owner of the new venture, named UT Loewe Automotive, and the company will continue to operate in Kronach. Loewe Opta will concentrate on its commercial operations. 
Bodine said the joint venture with Loewe provides UT Automotive with a key opportunity to build and grow its electronics business throughout Europe, and is consistent with the company's strategy to focus on globablization, technology and focusing on its core businesses.<p>
"This acquisition in Europe is a major step in our ongoing strategic plan to further develop our capabilities in electronics and expand our technology base around the world," Bodine said. "It also offers us an opportunity to expand and grow our customer base."<p>
"With UT Automotive as a partner, we strengthen the international aspect of automotive electronics," said Dr. Rainer Hecker, Loewe manager. "It thus becomes easier to be a systems supplier for the automotive industry. Additionally, the cooperation extends our customer base and guarantees a larger volume of orders."<p>

Gunter Mecklinger, who has been responsible for Loewe's automotive electronics business, will be the head of the new company. He is one of about 180 employees who will switch to UT Loewe Automotive from Loewe Opta. Mecklinger will report to Richard Sloan, president of UT Automotive - Europe.
"Loewe will support our efforts to strengthen our relationships with key customers such as BMW, which they have had a long-term relationship with," Sloan said. "In addition, not only does this give us worldwide production of electronic components, but the sharing of technologies among our operations will make us a better supplier of innovative products and high-quality electronic components to our present and future customers."<p>

Automotive electronics that had been produced by Loewe Opta and will be produced by UT Loewe Automotive include electronics for the control of heating and air conditioning systems; power switching electronics; electronic modules to control seats, mirrors and instrument clusters; electronics for anti-lock braking systems and chassis controls; analog and digital audio amplifiers; and video modules.<p>

UT Automotive is a $3.1 billion tier-one supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers. Based in Dearborn, Mich., the company has 40,000 employees and 90 manufacturing plants in 18 countries.<p>

UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <A HREF="http://www.utc.com">United Technologies Corp.</A>, which provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.<p>

Loewe, founded in 1923 in Berlin, develops advanced products in the fields of consumer electronics, telecommunications and automotive electronics. The company is involved in the production and sales of commercial televisions, screen-based text systems and equipment, videos, stereo and tape equipment, and circuit boards and car electronics for industrial purposes.</P>
