<IMG SRC="../medi.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="68" usemap="#media" border="0">
</center>
<!--header ends here-->
<h5>Contact: Tom Andrew (<a href="mailto:tandrew@uta.com">tandrew@uta.com</a>)</h5> 
<H2>
UT Automotive to discontinue operations in Thomson, Ga.</H2><P>
<P><STRONG>THOMSON, Ga., Jan. 7, 1997 </strong>- UT Automotive, a United Technologies company, today informed employees of the company's intention to discontinue its operations in Thomson, Ga.<p>
The company plans to move production of acoustical products from Thomson to a                UT Automotive facility in Holland, Mich., during the second quarter of 1997. Approximately 175 employees are expected to be affected by the move.<p>
UT Automotive made the announcement today to provide as much advance notice as possible to its employees.
"We regret these changes will result in a downsizing of our work force, and in the closing of our Thomson facility," said Ed Northern, vice president and general manager of UT Automotive's Interiors operation. "But unfortunately, in order to survive in our highly competitive automotive business, these very difficult decisions had to be made."<p>
In June 1996, the company announced one of Thomson's product lines would be moved to the Holland facility.
"Our intent was to allow the Thomson plant the opportunity to return to profitability," Northern said. "Unfortunately, the business and the plant's financial performance has remained at an unacceptable level."<p>
In an effort to support its work force in Thomson, UT Automotive is developing plans for its associates that include some special separation and insurance coverage benefits.
UT Automotive, with headquarters in Dearborn, Mich., is a major supplier of electrical and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers.<p>
UT Automotive is a unit of Hartford, Conn.-based <A HREF="http://www.utc.com">United Technologies Corp.</A>, which provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.</P>
