(<a href="mailto:mscholl@uta.com">mscholl@uta.com</a>)<br>
(313) 593-9672</h5><h2>UT Automotive Develops Advanced 'Smart' Junction Box Technology 
 </h2><p>
 
                                 
  <strong>DEARBORN, Mich., Oct. 21 </strong> - In an effort to increase efficiency
and improve upon today's automotive electrical distribution systems (EDS), UT
Automotive, a United Technologies Company, has developed an advanced concept
called "Smart" Junction Box (SJB) technology. <p>

  Thanks to the high level of integration found in SJB technology, engineers
 will soon be able to develop EDS with reduced wire harness bulk, less
complexity and fewer interconnections.  SJB.0 technology offers automakers a
fully integrated, multifunctional, electronic and electromechanical management
system.<p>
 
  The UT Automotive SJB completely integrates current systems through its
advanced design and integration and consolidation of 14 separate electrical
modules. <p>

  "SJB technology represents an evolutionary step in the development of
junction boxes because we can integrate both the electronic functions and the
existing power functions into a single unit," said William Floyd, manager of
electronic products for UT Automotive's Input Controls business unit. "Another
important advantage of SJBs is the ability to make quick and less-costly
design changes when necessary." <p>
  SJBs can provide a number of benefits in control and performance improvement
functions within the EDS.  Among these are:  <ul>
  <li>a reduced number of interconnections 
<li>reduced packaging size and weight 
  <li>a decreased amount of parts to assemble 
  <li>shorter design and lead times 
<li>elimination of additional electronic modules 
 <li>improved reliability  </ul><p>

  UT Automotive's SJB technology utilizes printed circuit boards (PCB) instead
of traditional metal fret assemblies.  An advantage of this technology is its
ability to create very complex circuit interconnects through the use of
photo-lithographic processes.  UT Automotive's SJB consists of two PCB layers
covered by copper traces and separated by a plastic isolator.  Current
junction boxes require as many as 13 separate layers that must each be custom
stamped or molded and assembled. <p>

  "With SJB technology, a microcontroller can be integrated with the junction
box to offer programmable options that can expand the EDS functionality with
minimal additional hardware," said Floyd.  "It also supports expanded
diagnostic capability that will enhance the serviceability of the EDS." <p>

  UT Automotive is a $3.1 billion tier-one supplier of electrical, electronic
and interior trim systems and components to car and light-truck manufacturers.
 Based in Dearborn, Mich., it has 40,000 employees at 90 manufacturing plants
in 17 countries. 
<p>
  UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based United Technologies
Corp. (NYSE: UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology products
and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.  
 
