<h2>UT Automotive Develops Integrated Liftgate Multiplexed Module</h2>

<p>
<strong>DEARBORN, Mich., Oct. 21 </strong> -- Teamwork among three units of UT
Automotive, a United Technologies Company, has resulted in a new product that
consolidates parts, cuts cost, reduces weight and puts control of six separate
functions into one component. <p>
 
  The integrated liftgate multiplexed module -- designed for vans, wagons and
sport utility vehicles -- incorporates controls for liftgate lock/unlock,
liftglass release, liftgate wiper, heated backlight, license plate lamps and
the center high-mounted stop lamp.  <p>

  The module uses electronics, multiplexing, a small motor and a special
device called a "Geneva mechanism."  Operation of the six functions previously
required three motors and a series of wires, relays and electronics.  <p>

  "The new integrated multiplexed module is the result of combining research
and technology from three of UT Automotive's product areas -- motors, wiring
systems and electronics," said Masazumi Sone, UT Automotive's director of
technology.  <p>

  "This cross-functional system design and development strategy is being
increasingly utilized at UT Automotive to combine technologies and add value
for our customers."  <p>

  The Geneva mechanism, a key to the module's operation, consists of a central
cam and three shafts that turn using a series of cam followers.  Each shaft
 controls one of three mechanical functions: the liftgate wiper, the
lock/unlock and liftglass release.  The mechanism is driven by a single,
permanent-magnet DC motor.  <p>

  UT Automotive projects significant vehicle manufacturer cost-saving
opportunities with the new mechanism and improved end-user satisfaction.  Some
of the cost-saving advantages, according to Sone, include weight reduction,
reduced customer assembly labor, improved reliability, system integration and
parts consolidation.  <p>

  The systems approach is a key part of the company's long-term new product
development and business strategy.  That strategy is led by UT Automotive's
Technical Council, comprised of company technical leaders, under the direction
of Sone.  <p>
  "Our expertise in electronics, DC motors, wiring systems and interior trim
positions UT Automotive as a strategic partner in developing future systems
for the auto industry," said Norm Bodine, UT Automotive president.  <p>

  UT Automotive is a $3.1 billion tier-one supplier of electrical, electronic
and interior trim systems and components to car and light-truck manufacturers.
 Based in Dearborn, Mich., it has 40,000 employees at 90 manufacturing plants
in 17 countries.  <p>
  UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based United Technologies
Corp. (NYSE: UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology products
and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries. <!--footer begins here-->
