(313) 593-9672</h5><h2>UT Automotive and Planar Systems Announce Development of Fully
Integrated Flat-Panel Display Systems</h2>

<p>
<strong>DEARBORN, Mich., Oct. 21, 1996</strong>-- UT Automotive, a United
Technologies Company, and Planar Systems, Inc. have jointly developed a
prototype electroluminescent display (ELD) for automotive applications.  The
announcement was made today at the Convergence '96 Automotive Technology
Exposition. </p>

  The UT Automotive/Planar flat-panel display, which is intended to replace
conventional instrument clusters, can provide all pertinent driver control
information, such as vehicle speed, engine RPM, fuel level and other
information in one convenient location.  The display can also be used as a
stand-alone information center for specific features such as a navigation
system. </p>

  "We partnered with Planar to develop these products for the automotive
market because of the unique attributes of their electroluminescent technology
for this difficult environment," said UT Automotive President and CEO Norm
Bodine.  "In Planar, we have a partner that has a proven capability of moving
core display technologies into high-quality products." </p>
  ELDs offer automakers several advantages, including wide viewing angle,
operation over broad temperature ranges, low electromagnetic interference and
high reliability.  And ELDs do not require a supplementary light source.</p>
Current liquid-crystal displays have been criticized for their limited
operational temperature range, low contrast, need for external light source
and flickering. </p>

  A key advantage of the UT Automotive/Planar flat panel display is the
potential for enhanced driver safety and convenience, and improved
accessibility to other features and information.</p> 
  "One important aspect of our ELD flat-panel display is its quick response
time, regardless of ambient temperature," said Masazumi Sone, UT Automotive's
director of technology.  "Consequently, our unit does not require additional
components, such as heaters, to support display startup in cold weather
conditions." </p>

  According to Sone, this application will revolutionize the concept of
man-machine interface and demonstrate the system's integration of UT
Automotive's interior trim, electrical distribution system, electronics and
other products. </p>

  "Planar is pleased to be teamed with UT Automotive in this effort," said Jim
Hurd, Planar's President and CEO.  "UT Automotive brings a great deal of
experience in dealing with the automakers and has been tremendously helpful in
navigating this partnership as we engage in this new and exciting market
opportunity." </p>

  UT Automotive is a $3.1 billion tier-one supplier of electrical, electronic
and interior trim systems and components to car and light-truck manufacturers.
 Based in Dearborn, Mich., it has 40,000 employees at 90 manufacturing plants
in 17 countries. </p>

  UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United
Technologies Corp.</a> (NYSE: UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology products
and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries. </p>
  Planar Systems, Inc. (Nasdaq: PLNR) is a worldwide leader in the
development, manufacture and marketing of high-performance flat-panel and
CRT-based display products.  The primary market sectors that Planar serves
today are medical, industrial, instrumentation, defense, communications,
transportation and business/office.  The Company competes on a global basis
with full development, manufacturing and marketing operations in both the
United States and Europe.  <!--footer begins here-->
