<h2>
UT Automotive to close facility in Niles, Michigan</h2><P>	<STRONG>NILES, Mich., Sept. 20, 1996 </STRONG>- UT Automotive today informed employees of the company's intention to consolidate its Steering Wheels operations in Grabill, Ind., and to discontinue operations at its plant in Niles, Mich. <P>The closing of the Niles facility, which will be completed in the first quarter of 1997, will affect approximately 290 employees.The closing is part of ongoing cost and productivity improvement activities throughout the company. The company made the announcement today to provide as much advance notice as possible to its employees.<P>We regret these changes will result in a downsizing of our work force, and in the closing of our Niles facility,said John Lahiff, vice president of UT Automotive's Steering Wheels business unit. "But unfortunately, we are faced with excess manufacturing capacity. In order to survive in our highly competitive business, these very difficult decisions had to be made.<P>The manufacture of steering wheels at Niles will be consolidated at the UT Automotive facility in Grabill over the next several months. During that time the company will determine the size of the work force needed in Grabill.<P>In an effort to support its work force in Niles, UT Automotive is developing plans to offer some special services to employees affected by the change. Employees will be informed of such services as they become available.<P>UT Automotive, with headquarters in Dearborn, Mich., is a major supplier of electrical and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers.<P>UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based United Technologies Corp., which provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.<!--footer begins here-->
<p>
