<h2>UT Automotive, Siam Motors Company sign Thai joint venture agreement</h2>
<IMG SRC="../images/wolanczyk.jpg" ALIGN=BOTTOM BORDER="0">
<P></P><h6>Photo: President of Siam Motors Phornthep Phornprapha, left,
          and Vice President and General Manager, Input Controls of UT
          Automotive Thomas C. Wolanzyk (<I>Business Day</I>, Thailand, 1996)</h6>

<P>	<STRONG>DEARBORN, Mich., Aug. 21, 1996 </strong>- To support its strategic expansion into the Asian automotive components market, UT Automotive today announced it has signed an agreement with Siam Motors Company (SMC) to form Siam UT Automotive Co., Ltd.  The joint venture company will manufacture electromechanical and electronic components for the Thai domestic market and for UT Automotive's global customers.
<P>	"SMC and UT Automotive established this joint venture in Thailand to support the rapid growth of the automotive industry in the region, and especially Thailand," said Thomas C. Wolanzyk, vice president and general manager of UT Automotive's Input Controls business unit. "Currently, Thailand and much of the ASEAN automotive market depend on electromechanical and electronic components imported primarily from Japan."
<P>	The new joint venture, to be located near Bangkok, will manufacture heater fan switches, relays, multifunction switches, door lock switches, remote entry systems and door lock control modules.  UT Automotive is the majority partner in the venture.</P>
<P>	"Entering Thailand demonstrates our commitment to and support of our customers in the Asian region," said Norman R. Bodine, president and chief executive officer of UT Automotive. "We view Thailand as an excellent manufacturing location, offering opportunities to establish UT Automotive as a key supplier to other southeast Asian markets.  It also will allow UT Automotive to participate more quickly and with lower investment to support our automotive customers."</P>
<P>	Lower shipping costs, other economic incentives offered by the government of Thailand and strong partners like SMC will help UT Automotive realize many opportunities to pursue additional business in the future, he added. </P>
<P>	SMC, founded in 1952, is one of the major conglomerates in Thailand.  It has grown significantly, due to a strong demand for motor vehicles in the country.  Its 26 joint ventures include automotive engines, spark plugs, batteries, automotive air conditioners and elevators.  It manufactures Nissan motor vehicles through a joint venture, Siam Nissan Automotive Co., Ltd., with Nissan Motors of Japan.</P>
	<p>UT Automotive, based in Dearborn, Mich., is a major supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers.  Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America, Europe, and an increasing number in Asia.	</P>
	<p>UT Automotive is a subsidiary of <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a> of Hartford, Conn. (NYSE: UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.

