<p>
<h2>UT Automotive Enters Argentina</h2>

<P>	<STRONG>DEARBORN, Mich., July 17, 1996 </strong>-  UT Automotive recently closed an agreement to acquire an Argentine supplier of automotive wire harnesses, Talleres Electricos San Isidro (TESI), beginning the company's expansion process into South America. 
	Conversion of the plant, located in Buenos Aires, into a UT Automotive facility is under way and is expected to be completed by the first of  the year. 
	<p>"South America is one of the fastest growing markets in the world," said Ed Buker, UT Automotive's vice president of wiring systems. "In order to successfully continue our global expansion process, UT Automotive had to become part of that viable market."
	<p>UT Automotive acquired the existing 48,000-square feet plant because of  TESI's strong management team and their understanding of the government and the marketplace.  The company plans to keep the current management and 130 line workers in place.
	"The existing asset of the work force was a prime reason for acquiring the facility," Buker said. 
	<p>UT Automotive's Argentine expansions will meet the needs of key customers who presently have automotive assembly facilities in South America. Every major Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM) is present or in the process of establishing itself in the flourishing country. 	
	"OEMs are focusing on these opportunities - and we must do the same. We must follow our customers to these new markets," said UT Automotive President Norm Bodine. 
	<p>UT Automotive, which has operations in Europe, Asia and North America,  is continuing to expand in locations around the globe.  
	"This move firmly establishes UT Automotive as a global player ready and able to move into emerging markets in the world," said James Garcia, director of South American operations. 
	"We hope to be able to serve 25 percent of the total market in the region," Buker said.
	<p>UT Automotive expects its expansion will continue throughout South America. 
	 "Once we are established, we will pursue other expansion possibilities in the region," Buker said. 
	UT Automotive, based in Dearborn, Mich., is a major supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers.  Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America, Europe, and an increasing number in Asia.	
	<p>UT Automotive is a subsidiary of <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a> of Hartford, Conn. (NYSE: UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.

