<h2>UT Automotive 'Steers' Automakers Toward Consumer Preferences</h2>
<IMG SRC="../images/steer.gif" ALT="steering wheel" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="385" HEIGHT="252">
	<P></P>
<P>	<STRONG>DEARBORN, Mich. July 15, 1996 </STRONG>- When it comes to pleasing its automaker customers, UT Automotive's Steering Wheels group is taking a turn in the right direction. 
	The group has accepted UT Automotive's role as an OEM supplier whole heartly by assuming some of the automakers' consumer research burden.   <p>Engineers from the group have created a traveling display of steering wheels and developed a comprehensive survey to learn more about consumers' opinions of  steering wheel features.
	"Our main goal is to say to our customers, 'We've studied car buyers and - when it comes to steering wheels - we know what automotive consumers want," said Steering Wheels Engineer Kevin Nehilla, who created and administers the survey.
	<p>In June, Nehilla took the display containing a variety of Ford, Chrysler and other steering wheels to Fairlane Ford, an auto dealership in Dearborn, Mich., to survey consumers on their preferences.
	Those surveyed were asked for their preferences on wheel features such as rim thickness, leather wrapping, speed control design and placement, horn switch design and actuation and overall appearance.  Customers were encouraged to take a "hands-on" approach -- to touch and examine the different wheels to determine their favorite features.
		"Most people had a definite opinion on what they liked and what they did not," Nehilla said. "Surprisingly, one man we surveyed said he just hated leather wrapped steering wheels."<p>
		The survey conducted at Fairlane Ford is the first of many to be administered throughout the metro area, he said.  Plans are to conduct additional polls at shopping malls, car washes and other dealerships.
		"The ultimate goal is to design steering wheels with the features customers prefer," Nehilla said.  "Accumulating this information shows automotive consumers their opinions matter and makes automakers aware that we are willing to take on a larger role as a supplier."
		<p>In early 1996, UT Automotive became the world's first steering wheel supplier to receive Ford Motor Company's Full Service Supplier designation.  In attaining this status, UT Automotive underwent a rigorous, nine-month evaluation during 1994 and 1995, to prove it could meet Ford's high standards.
		UT Automotive is a major supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America and Europe, and an increasing number in Asia.
		 <P>
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based 
<a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>,
(NYSE:UTX) which provides a broad range of high-technology
products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive
industries.<p>
