<H2>UT Automotive to consolidate operations at Holland, Mich., facility
</H2><P><STRONG>HOLLAND, Mich., June 27, 1996</STRONG> - UT Automotive 
 today informed employees of the company's intention to continue operation of its Holland, Mich.,
  facility.</P>
<P>The company last December told employees it planned to discontinue operations in Holland by the 
third quarter of 1997. Mike Ryan, director of manufacturing for UT Automotive's Interior Systems operations, 
said the company's strategy changed because of the cost of moving some of the operations out of 
Holland, and because of improved performance and strong technical resources at the Holland facility.
</p><p>"This decision is part of ongoing cost and productivity improvement activities throughout the 
company," Ryan said. "We decided it would be best to continue operations in Holland after closely
 examining all of the issues, including the improved performance of our Holland facility."</P>
<P>UT Automotive plans to consolidate production of its acoustical products, moving some operations to Holland 
from UT Automotive facilities in Indiana and Georgia. In addition, production of some headliners may move 
from Holland to a UT Automotive facility in Port Huron, Mich.</P>
<P>UT Automotive, with headquarters in Dearborn, Mich., is a major supplier of electrical and interior trim 
systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part of nearly 
every passenger vehicle built in North America and Europe.
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>, which provides a broad
 range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive 
 industries.

