<H2>UT Automotive, West Virginia University 'Charged Up' for the Cleveland Grand Prix's Formula E Race
</H2>
<IMG SRC="../images/wvirginia.gif" ALT="electric car" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="313" HEIGHT="214">
<HR><EM>UT Automotive is charging ahead to provide automakers with innovative but cost efficient products for their 
electric vehicle.  And what better venue to test new products than on the road - in race cars. 
 UT Automotive is one of the sponsors of the race car developed and built by students at West Virginia 
 University's college of engineering and Mineral Resources.  Dave Berels, content leader, 
 UT Automotive's global electric vehicle programs, takes a seat in the Formula E race car, which will
  make its debut at the Cleveland Grand Prix next month.  </EM>
<HR>
	<STRONG>DEARBORN, Mich., June 27, 1996</STRONG> -   UT Automotive (UT Automotive) and 
	<A HREF="http://www.wvu.edu/" NAME="West Virginia University">West Virginia University</A> are teaming up to create a successful Formula E (electric) car for the Cleveland
	 Grand Prix. UT Automotive has donated $10,000 to West Virginia University to help sponsor an electric car that 
was designed and built by over 20 students and three faculty members.	</P>
<P>	The school's car, named Formula Lightening, is a high-performance race vehicle that is scheduled 
to compete in five races this year.  The car, which is driven by a professional driver, is capable of
 traveling up to 140 m.p.h. West Virginia University's electric car will compete against 12 American universities in 
the Cleveland Grand Prix's Formula E car race at the Burke Lakefront Airport June 28-30.
</P>	
<P>	The Formula E racing series was created to encourage the development and increase public
 awareness of electric vehicles. Students who participate in the races gain valuable, hands-on,
  educational experience while advancing the technology of electric vehicles. 
	"It is widely understood in the automotive industry that racing provides one of the best test 
	beds for product development," said Ted Bott, manager of UT Automotive's global electric vehicle programs. 
	"The demands of racing have helped to produce some of the lightest, most efficient, 
	highest-performing systems found on today's passenger cars and trucks."</P>
<P>	"UT Automotive plans to continue the partnership with West Virginia University next year," Dave Berels, content leader, UT Automotive global electric vehicle programs said.  "We will be working with 
the students to 
incorporate our electrical distribution system components in their race 
car this fall." West Virginia University's car will be on display at UT Automotive's Dearborn headquarters July 
8-15 for both visitors and employees to get an up-close look at the electric car. 
<P>	UT Automotive is a major supplier of electric, electronic and interior trim systems and components to car
 and light truck manufacturers.  Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in 
 North America, Europe and an increasing number in Asia.</P></P>
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based 
<a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>,
(NYSE:UTX) which provides a broad range of high-technology
products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive
industries.
