<H2>Ford Names UT Automotive World's First Full Service Supplier for Steering Wheels</H2>

<P>	<STRONG>DEARBORN, Mich., June 24, 1996</STRONG> - UT Automotive (UT Automotive) is the world's first steering wheel supplier to receive Ford Motor Company's Full Service Supplier (FSS) designation.
<P>	In attaining full-service supplier status, UT Automotive underwent a rigorous, nine-month evaluation process in 1994 and 1995 that required it to meet Ford's high standards in areas such as product design, development, product testing, manufacturing engineering, manufacturing support, service support and CAD/CAE data capability.</P>
<P>  	A steering wheel system includes a die-cast or steel-stamped armature molded in eurethane or PVC (sometimes leather wrapped); air bag cover, horn, speed control and other switches; and electrical slip rings.</P></P>
<P>	"This designation as a Ford Full Service Supplier recognizes the years of dedication that our team has invested in setting and meeting customer satisfaction and quality goals," said John Lahiff, vice president and general manager of UT Automotive's steering wheel group.  "We're as proud of this high accomplishment as we are of the world-class-quality steering wheel systems we provide daily to Ford."</P>


<P>	Attaining FSS status was no easy task, according to Leo Hagan, program manager for UT Automotive's Ford steering wheel business.  The effort involved hundreds of UT Automotive associates across our Steering Wheels organization.  
	"We fundamentally reinvented our business," Hagan said.  "Our associates had to change the way they think, from a supplier's frame of mind to a customer's.  An associate in charge of a certain responsibility now had to act as 'Mr. Ford' would."</P>
<P>	Hagan said a recent restructuring of the Steering Wheels organization in which associates and departments are now aligned along customer lines enables associates to act as the customer's advocate.  Customer teams now set targets in areas that matter most in developing, defining and validating the product, he added.
<P>	UT Automotive provides a variety of steering wheels and steering wheel systems for Ford vehicles worldwide.  These include the new 1997 F-Series pickup trucks, Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable, Crown Victoria, Grand Marquis, Thunderbird, Cougar, Mercury Villager and Nissan Quest minivans and a variety of Ford medium- and heavy-duty commercial trucks.</P></P>
<P>	UT Automotive is a major supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers.  Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America and Europe and an increasing number in Asia.
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based 
<a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>,
(NYSE:UTX) which provides a broad range of high-technology
products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive
industries.

