<H2>UT Automotive reduces work force at Newton, Ill., facility

</H2><P><STRONG>NEWTON, Ill., June 20, 1996 </strong>- UT Automotive earlier 
this week informed employees of the company's intention to reduce its work force by about 150 
employees in Newton, Ill. </p>
<P>UT Automotive's Newton plant, located on Marshall Drive, manufactures wiring harnesses for cars, trucks and
 sport utility vehicles. Production at the facility is being reduced because the company is 
 consolidating production of one of its lines of wire harnesses at a UT Automotive facility in Mexico. </P>
<P>This consolidation is part of ongoing cost and productivity improvement activities throughout 
the company. The work-force reduction in Newton was based on the need to realign the facility's 
work force to meet its production requirements, said Greg Clark, plant manager.</P>
<P>The layoffs will occur in two phases; the first will take place in early August and the second 
about a month later. Approximately one-third of plant's current work force will be affected. </P>
<P>UT Automotive, with headquarters in Dearborn, Mich., is a major supplier of electrical and interior trim 
systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part of nearly every 
passenger vehicle built in North America and Europe.
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>,
 which provides a broad 
range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive
 industries.
