<H2>UT Automotive Names O'Day Vice President, Quality and Enterprise Productivity</H2>
<IMG SRC="../images/oday.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="192" HEIGHT="279">
<P>	<STRONG>DEARBORN, June 19, 1996</STRONG> - Michael J. O'Day has been named vice president, Quality and Enterprise Productivity at UT Automotive  in Dearborn.
<P>	O'Day's duties will include leading the development of quality systems and improvement processes throughout UT Automotive worldwide. In addition, he will be responsible for implementation of QS-9000, business process reengineering, and many productivity initiatives already underway.   O'Day reports to Norman Bodine, president and CEO of UT Automotive.</P>
<P>	Previously, O'Day had served as director of sales and marketing at UT Automotive Europe, focusing on electronics and switch products.  Prior to his European assignment, O'Day was manager of UT Automotive's electronics manufacturing plant in Tampa, Fla. </P>
<P>	Before joining UT Automotive in 1986, he was employed at General Electric (GE)  in its Motor Business Group.  At GE,  he aided in obtaining supplier certification to General Motors, Ford, and utility market suppliers. </P></P>
<P>O'Day has a bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering and a master's degree in finance, both from the University of Michigan. </P>
<P>	UT Automotive is a major supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America, Europe, and an increasing number in Asia. 
<P>	UT Automotive is a subsidiary of United Technologies Corporation of Hartford, Conn. (NYSE:UTX) , which provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries. </P></P>

<P>
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based 
<a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>,
(NYSE:UTX) which provides a broad range of high-technology
products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive
industries.

