<h2>Honda of America Mfg. Presents UT Automotive With Quality Performance Award</h2>		
<P></P>
<P>	<STRONG>DEARBORN, MICH., June 17, 1996</STRONG> - The associates of UT Automotive's (UT Automotive) electronics plant in Tampa received a supplier award for outstanding achievement in Quality Performance from officials of <A HREF="http://www.honda.com/" NAME="Honda">Honda America Mfg.</A> (HAM) today. 	
<P>	UT Automotive was one of 13 of HAM's 353 North American suppliers to receive the Quality Performance Award at the company's 14th-annual Supplier Conference in April. UT Automotive's Tampa plant manufactures numerous components for the Honda Civic, Accord, and the Odyssey mini-van. UT Automotive began supplying parts to HAM in Oct. 1991.		</P>
	"The quality level, competitiveness and development capability of suppliers is an essential part of Honda's growth in North America," said Dave Nelson, senior vice president of HAM Purchasing and Corporate Affairs. "That's why we honor companies like UT Automotive. Their commitment and quality focus is absolutely critical to our future success together. As we 
develop and manufacture new products for new markets, we plan for our suppliers to play an ever-increasing role in their development."</p>
<P>	The Quality Performance award places UT Automotive in the top 8 percent of its commodity type for all Honda suppliers, said Chris Saleski, senior sales engineer for UT Automotive. "This is the most coveted award a supplier can win from Honda."
<P>	"We have an unprecedented number of active development programs for exclusive new North American vehicles and powertrains," added Nelson.  "It's a very full plate - one rich in opportunities for suppliers to provide new parts and increase their production volume with Honda in North America.</P></P>
<P>	Honda also emphasized its plans to increase exports of finished vehicles, as well as parts and components for other Honda manufacturing facilities in the Americas.  Exports of U.S.-built cars will increase by 50 percent to 150,000 in 1999.  HAM and its suppliers also will begin shipping their engines and other parts to the Honda do Brazil auto plant in Brazil for production of civics in 1997. "We must continue to think globally and act locally," said Nelson.
<P>	To qualify for the Quality Performance Award, a supplier must be in the top 15 percent of their commodity type, as measured by quality rejects in parts per million (PPM) and meet the Delivery average.</p>
	UT Automotive is a major supplier of electrical, electronic, and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North 
America, Europe, and an increasing number in Asia.</P>
<P>
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based 
<a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>,
(NYSE:UTX) which provides a broad range of high-technology
products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive
industries.
