<H2>UT Automotive and Lawrence Tech Are Racing Ahead Together</H2>

<P>	<STRONG>Dearborn, Mich. June 14, 1996</STRONG> -  UT Automotive and Lawrence Technological University in Southfield Mich. have teamed up in developing a hybrid electric vehicle that Lawrence Tech will enter in the Future Car Challenge, sponsored by the United States Council for Automotive Research and the U.S. Department of Energy.</P>
<P>	UT Automotive contributed $15,000 and 200 hours of engineering to Lawrence Tech for preparation of its hybrid electrical vehicle for the competition on June 17-24 at the Ford Motor Co. proving grounds in Dearborn, Mich.
<P>	"Lawrence Tech has earned great respect in auto engineering, so it made perfect sense to collaborate with this group on its hybrid electric vehicle," Ted Bott, manager UT Automotive global electrical vehicle programs said.</P>

<P>	Lawrence Tech's team of 60 students has converted a conventional Ford Taurus into a hybrid electric vehicle.  The hybrid electric car combines an electric motor with a combustion engine.
<P>	UT Automotive will supply some of the components to make the car perform successfully.  A high voltage electrical distribution system, connectors, 
and prismatic mirrors made by UT Automotive will all be part of the car.
	"By participating in electric vehicle racing, we have the advantage over our traditional competition in experiencing what works and what doesn't work in more than a lab environment," Bott said.
<P>	Last year, the Lawrence Tech team won the "Greatest Range," award and finished fifth overall at the Hybrid Challenge against 11 other colleges. </P>
<P>	In addition, the 1995 Lawrence Tech hybrid vehicle was featured at the White House during an energy efficient vehicles presentation. "These students are the brightest and most motivated budding automotive electrical engineers in the United States," Bott said.</P></P>
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based 
<a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>,
(NYSE:UTX) which provides a broad range of high-technology
products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive
industries.

