<H2>UT Automotive Honors Suppliers for Exceptional Performance</H2>

	<STRONG>DEARBORN, Mich., Mar. 18, 1995</STRONG> - UT Automotive (UT Automotive) has recognized 18 U.S. suppliers for exceptional performance in 1995 as part of the company's annual Partner's in Excellence program.
	"The Partners in Excellence program challenges our suppliers to be the best they can be, and it enables us to recognize those suppliers that are helping UT Automotive attain its goals," UT Automotive President Norm Bodine said. "The companies we honor have earned their marks among the best suppliers in the industry."
	Five suppliers earned UT Automotive's highest honor, the Partners in Excellence award:
<UL>
		<LI>Norton Sealant, of Wayne, N.J., which supplies foam gaskets to UT Automotive's Wiring Systems
		 operations in North America.
		<LI>NSK Corp., of Ann Arbor, Mich., which supplies ball bearings to UT Automotive operations to 
		Brownsville, Texas and Columbus, Miss. NSK also won a 1994 Partners in Excellence award
		from UT Automotive.
		<LI>PPG Industries, Inc., of Pittsburgh, which supplies adhesives to UT Automotive operations 
		in Wauseon, Ohio.
		<LI>Spirol International Corp., of Danielson, Conn., which supplies steel parts to
		UT Automotive operations in Traverse City, Mich., and Zanesville, Ohio.
		Taracorp, of Granite City, Ill., which supplies solder to UT Automotive's Wiring Systems 
		operations in North America.</ul>
<P>		To qualify for a Partners in Excellence award, suppliers had to achieve quality levels 
		equal to or less than 50 parts per million for a minimum of six months; a continuous 
		delivery rating equal to 100 percent; 
		and commercial/technological and system ratings of 85 percent or better.</P>
		<UL>
		<LI>In addition to the four Partners in Excellence awards, 13 other companies received 
		Preferred Supplier awards from UT Automotive:
		<LI>Abbott Ball Company, of West Hartford, Conn., which supplies steel parts to UT Automotive 
		operations in Traverse City, Mich., and St. Matthews,  S.C.
		<LI>C.W. Tool and Mold Company, of Stratford, Conn., which supplies plastic parts 
		and products to UT Automotive operations in Columbus, Miss., and Matamoros, Mexico. UT Automotive recognized
		 C.W. Tool and Mold for the second consecutive year.
		<LI>El Paso Wire (Group Dekko), of Kendallville, Ind., which supplies wire to UT Automotive's 
		Wiring Systems operations in North America.
		<LI>Elgin Die Mold, of Pinetree Grove, Ill., which supplies injected molded parts and 
		connectors to UT Automotive's Wiring Systems and Input Controls operations in North America.
		<LI>Gemini Plastics Company, of Ubly, Mich., which supplies plastic parts to UT Automotive's
		 Wiring Systems operations in North America.
		<LI>Industrial Devices, Canton, Mass., which supplies wire subassemblies to UT Automotive's  
		Wiring Systems operations in North America.
		<LI>Kemet Electronic Corp., of Orlando, Fla., which supplies electronic parts to UT Automotive 
		operations in Tampa, Fla. This is the third consecutive year Kemet Electronics has been
		 recognized by UT Automotive's supplier recognition program.
		<LI>Littlefuse, of Des Plaines, Ill., which supplies fuses to UT Automotive's Wiring Systems 
		operations in North America.
		<LI>Mayfair Plastics, Inc., of Gaylord, Mich., which supplies plastic parts to UT Automotive 
		operations in Traverse City, Mich., and St. Matthews, S.C.
		<LI>OR Plastics, Inc., which supplies plastic parts to UT Automotive operations in Tampa, Fla.
		<LI>TDK Corp. of America, of Shawnee, Okla., which supplies ceramic magnets to UT Automotive 
		operations in Columbus, Miss., and Matamoros, Mexico. TDK also won a supplier recognition
		 award from UT Automotive last year.
		<LI>The Torrington Company, of Torrington, Conn., which supplies needle bearings to 
		UT Automotive operations in Columbus, Miss.
</UL>
	To qualify for a Preferred Supplier award, companies had to achieve quality levels equal 
	to or less than 250 parts per million for a minimum of six months; continuous delivery rating 
	equal to 98 percent; and commercial/technological and system ratings of 80 percent or better.
	Suppliers received their awards March 18 at UT Automotive's annual Partners in Excellence dinner in 
	Dearborn.
	UT Automotive is a major supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems and components 
	to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle 
	built in North America and Europe.
	UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corporation</a> (NYSE:UTX), which 
	provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building 
	systems and automotive industries.

