  <head>
    <title>
      UTA to Reduce Plymouth, Ind., Operations
    </title>
  </head>

  <body bgcolor="#ffffff">

    <p align="center">
    <img src="/images/heads/about.head.gif" width="550" height="150"
    alt="[about uta]">
    </p>


    <h5>
      Contact: Brian Shuler
      <a href="shuler@uta.com">
        shuler@uta.com
      </a>
      <br>
      (219) 936-2141
      <br>
      (313) 593-9685
    </h5>

    <h2>
      United Technologies Automotive to Reduce Plymouth, Ind., Operations
    </h2>

    <stron>DEARBORN, Mich., January 19, 1996</strong> - United Technologies
    Automotive (UTA) today informed employees at its operations in Plymouth,
    Ind., of the company's intention to significantly reduce and consolidate
    manufacturing operations by mid-May 1996. The S. Liberty wire harness
    assembly plant will be phased down during this period and consolidated into
    UTA's Plymouth Industrial Park warehouse facility, affecting 190 employees.
    <p>
    The Plymouth plant was originally scheduled to close in late 1991; however,
    it remained open because of an unexpected increase in business at that time.
    The decision to close the plant now is based on a softening automotive
    market due to lower than anticipated auto sales, combined with the age and
    condition of the plant, said Art Nelson, UTA's director of North American
    wire assembly operations.
    <p>
    "We regret the need to reduce operations in Plymouth," Nelson said.
    "However, we're currently faced with excess manufacturing capacity and
    rising maintenance costs for the 104-year-old facility. In an ever-changing
    and challenging automotive supply market, these measures are necessary to
    continue to be competitive."
    <p>
    The manufacture of wire harnesses for Ford Motor Co. at Plymouth will be
    transferred to UTA facilities in Newton, Ill., and Chihuahua, Mexico.
    Warehousing and distribution operations will remain in the Industrial Park,
    along with a limited amount of wire harness production for the North
    American automotive market. "The high quality of work at Plymouth is a
    credit to all of the plant's employees," Nelson said. "It's only through
    their hard work that we were able to open a warehouse facility in mid-1994
    and can now retain 130 jobs in Plymouth. We'll continue to look for other
    work that fits into Plymouth's competitive position and place it there."
    <p>
    The 190 affected employees will be from all levels of the hourly and
    salaried work force. "This is not an easy action to take and the company
    will do all it can to help find employment for the displaced employees,"
    Nelson added.
    <p>
    UTA, headquartered in Dearborn, Mich., is a major supplier of electrical
    and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck
    manufacturers worldwide.
    <p>
    It is a unit of <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.,</a>
    based in Hartford, Conn., which provides a broad range of high-technology
    products and support services to the aerospace, building systems and
    automotive industries.

    <hr>

    <p align="center">
