  <head>
    <title>
      UTA, Ford Develop Innovative New Steering Wheel
    </title>
  </head>

  <body bgcolor="#ffffff">

    <p align="center">
    <img src="/images/heads/about.head.gif" width="550" height="150"
    alt="[about uta]">
    </p>

    <h5>
      Contact: Michael Scholl
      <a href="mailto:mscholl@uta.com">
        mscholl@uta.com
      </a>
      <br>
      (313) 593-9672
    </h5>

    <h2>
      United Technologies Automotive, Ford Develop Innovative New Steering
      Wheel
    </h2>

    <strong>DEARBORN, Mich., Jan. 22, 1996</strong> - A new, state-of-the-art
    steering wheel, that utilizes advanced materials technology to minimize
    cost, reduce weight, and improve steering performance, has been developed by
    United Technologies Automotive (UTA) and Ford Motor Company. 
    <p>
    The new wheel, which was developed for the new F-Series pick-up, Bronco
    truck and Econoline van, provides significant cost savings for both Ford
    and UTA and is half the weight of the wheel it will replace. 
    <p>
    The new wheel is manufactured by UTA from soft feel urethane over a
    magnesium base, which makes it lighter and helps it meet steering column
    objectives, while allowing the support structure to be minimized. 
    <p>
    "I believe this wheel will become popular because of its light weight, cost
    effectiveness, and the way it performs by minimizing steering column
    vibrations," said John Lahiff, UTA's vice president and general manager,
    steering wheels. "Our customer also tells us the new wheel also rates
    extremely well in terms of overall steering wheel performance. 
    <p>
    "The wheel not only met all performance requirements, but its aesthetics
    also were well received."
    <p>
    UTA also developed the airbag cover to match the wheel, allowing for easier
    assembly at the plant.
    <p>
    The new wheel was recognized recently through Ford's annual internal
    Truck Achievement Award. The award was in recognition for the wheel's light
    weight, cost effectiveness, and technological innovation.
    <p>
    "The genuine partnership, as displayed by UTA lead engineer Scott Dershem
    and the Ford styling group, made this program a success," said Leo R. Hagan,
    UTA's sales manager, steering wheels. "The combination of UTA's program
    management, design capabilities and manufacturing leadership has served as
    an example for all future steering wheel programs."
    <p>
    UTA is a major supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems
    and components to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part
    of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America and Europe, and a
    growing number in Asia.
    <p>
    UTA is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based
    <a href="http://www.utc.com/"> United Technologies Corp.</a> (NYSE:UTX),
    which provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the
    aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.

    <p>

    <a href="ftp://www.uta.com/pub/primages/pn96.jpg">
      <img src="/general/pr/images/pn96.small.jpg">
      Click here
    </a>
    to download a high-resolution image.

