(<a href="mailto:mscholl@uta.com">mscholl@uta.com</a>) (313) 593-9672</h5>

<H2>UT Automotive Plans Manufacturing Facility In Poland</H2>

<P>	<STRONG>DEARBORN, Mich., Dec. 19, 1995</STRONG> - UT Automotive (UT Automotive) will open a 38,000-square-foot manufacturing facility for electrical distribution systems on Plonsk, Poland.</P>
<P>	UT Automotive will house its new manufacturing operation within a Ford Motor Company assembly plant, and will manufacture wiring harnesses for Ford's small cars. UT Automotive initially will lease floorspace for its operations from Ford.</P>
<P>	"This is a tremendous opportunity for UT Automotive to better serve its customer, and expand our manufacturing capabilities in Eastern Europe," said UT Automotive-Europe President Richard Sloan.</P>
<P>	UT Automotive plans to employ 350 workers at Plonsk and will begin production in January.
<P>	Sloan said the establishment of a manufacturing plant in Plonsk takes UT Automotive back to its roots in the automotive industry. The company began making wiring harnesses for Ford in 1930 in a leased section of the automaker's Highland Park, Michigan, facility.</P></P>
<P>	UT Automotive is a major supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America and Europe and an increasing number in Asia.</P>
<P>	UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corporation</a> (NYSE:UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.</P>

