  <head>
    <title>
      UTA Develops Rear Integrated Liftgate Node
    </title>
  </head>

  <body bgcolor="#ffffff">

    <p align="center">
      <img src="/images/heads/about.head.gif" alt="[about uta]">
    </p>

    <h5>Contact: Michael Scholl
      <a href="mailto:mscholl@uta.com">
        mscholl@uta.com
      </a>
      <br>
      (313) 593-9672
    </h5>

    <h2>United Technologies Automotive Develops Rear Integrated Liftgate Node For
Vans and Sport Utility Vehicles</h2>

    <strong>Dearborn, Mich., Nov. 14, 1995</strong> - A revolutionary, 
    state-of-the-art, rear integrated liftgate node for vans and sport-utility 
    vehicles, which cuts cost, consolidates components and reduces weight, has 
    been developed by United Technologies Automotive.
    <p>
    The multiplexed liftgate node incorporates six separate functions, including 
    liftgate lock/unlock, liftglass release, liftgate wiper, heated backlight, 
    license plate lamps and center high-mounted stop lamp, all into a single 
    unit. By using sophisticated electronics, multiplexing technology, a single 
    DC motor and a special device called a "Geneva mechanism," the node is able 
    to perform functions that previously had required three separate motors and a
    series of wires, relays and electronics. 
    <p>
    The Geneva mechanism, the key to the node¹s integration, consists of a 
    central cam and three shafts that turn using a series of cam followers. The 
    unit is powered by a single, permanent-magnet motor. Each section of the 
    mechanism is responsible for one of the three moving functions: liftgate 
    wiper, liftgate lock/unlock and liftglass release.
    <p>
    "The Geneva mechanism is an integration of research and technology from three
    of UTA's product areas - Motor Systems, Wiring Systems and Input Controls," 
    said Masazumi Sone, UTA's director of technology. "This cross-divisional 
    system development is a strategy being increasingly utilized at UTA to 
    integrate technologies and add value for our customers." 
    <p>
    UTA projects significant cost-saving opportunities with the new mechanism and
    improved customer satisfaction. Some of the cost-saving advantages, according
    to Sone, will include weight reduction, reduced customer assembly labor, 
    improved reliability, system integration, robust design and part number 
    reduction. 
    <p>
    UTA President <a href="/people/norm.html">Norm Bodine</a> believes that the 
    rear integrated node is an example of the technology and system-integration 
    capabilities automakers expect from their tier-one, full-service suppliers.
    <p>
    "Our experience in electronics, DC motors, interior trim and wiring systems 
    positions UTA as a strategic partner in developing future systems for the 
    auto industry," Bodine said. "I believe this and similar projects will result
    in new business opportunities for UTA with customers worldwide."
    <p>
    UTA is a major supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems 
    and components to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part of
    nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America and Europe.
    <p>
    UTA is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based 
    <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>
    (NYSE:UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology products and 
    services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.

    <p>

    <a href="ftp://www.uta.com/pub/primages/rearnode.jpg">
      <img src="images/rn.thumbnail.jpg" border=0 alt="[Rear Node Image]">
      Click here
    </a>
    to download a high-resolution (300dpi) image.

