<h2>UT Automotive Reduces Work Force by 52 at Peru Plant</h2>

<p>
<strong>Peru, Ind., Aug. 9, 1995</strong> - UT Automotive (UT Automotive) is
reducing its work force by 52 salaried and hourly associates at its Wiring
Systems facility in Peru.

<p>
Plant Manager Greg Comoglio said the reductions affect 12 salaried and
40 hourly associates and are the result of decreased production volumes
at the plant. The plant had reduced its work force by 60 associates in
June.

<p>
The Peru facility still employs more than 300 associates. 
The plant manufactures terminals, conductors and connectors. Its
primary customers are two North American automakers.

<p>
The 150,000-square-foot facility is one of the oldest manufacturers of
plastic products in the United States. It opened in 1941 as Bryan
Manufacturing, producing wire harnesses for World War II aircraft. It was
acquired by Essex in the late 1940's, switched production to plastic
components in the early 1950's and was acquired by <a href="http://www.utc.com/">
United Technologies Corp.</a> in 1974. It became part of UT Automotive in 1979.

<p>
UT Automotive, headquartered in Dearborn, Mich., is a major supplier of electrical,
electronic and interior trim systems and components to car and light
truck manufacturers worldwide.

