<h2>UT Automotive Names Edwin L. Buker to Head Wiring Systems</h2>

<p>
DEARBORN, Aug. 28, 1995 - Edwin L. Buker, a former
manufacturing executive with BMW and Honda of America, has joined
UT Automotive (UT Automotive) as vice president and general
manager of UT Automotive's wiring systems business.

<p>
Buker's appointment  was announced today by UT Automotive President
<a href="/../general/people/norm.htm">Norman R. Bodine</a>.   

<p>
"We are very fortunate to have Ed join us. He is an experienced
industry leader," Bodine said, "and the manufacturing knowledge he
brings with him from the OEM-level will help UT Automotive to become more
keenly focused on serving our customers' needs."

<p>
Buker has been associated with BMW for three years, most
recently as vice president-Munich Office for BMW Manufacturing
Corp. in  Germany.  Before that he was vice president-Manufacturing
at BMW's U. S. vehicle plant in Spartanburg, South Carolina, during its startup.

<p>
Prior to joining BMW in 1992, Buker worked eight years in
various executive-level positions with Honda of America
Manufacturing, Inc.  He joined Honda in 1984 as manager of its
motorcycle plant, and in 1985 was appointed manager of Honda's
auto assembly plant in Marysville, Ohio.  He subsequently held the
positions of vice president and plant manager for the East Liberty
assembly plant, and vice president-Auto Quality.

<p>
Buker received his bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering
in 1976 from Tri-State University, Angola, Indiana, and his master
of business administration degree from <a href="http://www.ohiou.edu">
Ohio University</a> in Athens.
<p>
Buker succeeds Richard L. Barrett, who has been appointed vice
president, Worldwide Manufacturing and Technical Integration.  In
this new position, Barrett will direct and coordinate the global
integration of advanced manufacturing processes and new
technological capabilities.

<p>
"Barrett's experience and knowledge of North America, Europe,
Latin America and the Pacific Rim make him ideally suited to lead
UT Automotive's global manufacturing planning effort, so necessary in serving
our customers' global needs," Bodine said.	  

<p>
UT Automotive is a major supplier of electrical and interior trim
systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers.  Its
products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North
America and Europe.

<p>
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corporation</a> of
Hartford, Connecticut, which provides a broad range of high
technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems
and automotive industries.
