<h2>UT Automotive Named Remote Entry Supplier 
for Acura TL Luxury Sedan</h2>

<p>
<strong>DEARBORN, Mich., July 12, 1995</strong> - UT Automotive has been named by Honda as
supplier for remote entry systems for Acura's TL luxury sedan, announced
<a href="/general/people/wol.htm">Thomas C.  Wolanzyk</a>, vice president and general
manager, Input Controls for UT Automotive.

<p>
The remote entry systems, manufactured by UT Automotive in Tampa, Fla., are
supplied to Honda's Acura manufacturing plant in Sayama, Japan.  The TL
currently is sold both in Japan and in North America.

<p>
"We've shown that we can compete with Japanese suppliers - even
in electronics - in supplying feature-rich, quality components at
competitive prices to Japanese assembly plants," said Wolanzyk.  "Our
full-service, global approach to component supply has helped establish
UT Automotive as an important supplier to Honda." 

<p>
The TL's UT Automotive-developed remote entry system, comprising an
electronic receiver module and two remote transmitters (key fobs),
permits keyless entry by unlocking the vehicle's doors with a single press
of a key fob button.  For security, the driver can lock all doors with a
single touch of a second button.

<p>
UT Automotive's relationship with Honda began in 1987, when the company
began manufacturing switches and relays for the Honda Accord.  Soon, UT Automotive
began supplying components for Honda's popular Civic model.  Currently,
UT Automotive also supplies remote entry systems, electrical distribution systems
and other components to Honda for other car lines that are manufactured
in Japan for the Japanese domestic and export markets.  UT Automotive began
working with Acura on development of the TL remote entry system in
1993.

<p>
UT Automotive is a full-service supplier of electrical, electronic and interior
trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers.  Its
products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America
and Europe.  

<p>
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">
United Technologies Corp.</a>  (NYSE:UTX), which provides a broad range of
high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building systems
and automotive industries.
