<h2>UT Automotive Expands Interior Trim Plant</h2>

<P>
<strong>BERNE, Ind., July 18, 1995</strong> - UT Automotive (UT Automotive) has expanded
its interior trim facility in Berne, Ind., by 65,000 square feet. The expansion was 
made to accommodate UT Automotive's growing business in injection molded, painted and 
assembled exterior automotive mirrors and grilles. 

<P>
The new building will house mirror assembly, incoming material, and 
finished goods. 
       
<p>
"This expansion provides tremendous opportunities for cost 
savings," said Mike Talaga, Berne's plant manager. "We've consolidated
four warehouses that were spread over a 40-mile radius down to two buildings 
operating side by side. This has simplified our inventory management and 
reduced transportation cost."

<p>
UT Automotive obtained the Berne plant from Sheller-Globe in 1989.
With its product line constantly increasing, the existing facility became too 
small to meet the volume demands of its customers.

<p>
"Our mirror business has experienced phenomenal growth over the last
18 months," said Leon Goolsby, UT Automotive's vice president and general manager,
mirrors. "We anticipate further growth in the near future."           
  
<p>
UT Automotive's Berne and Dayton, Tenn., plants currently supply mirrors and
other trim products to <a href="http://www.ford.com/">Ford</a>, General Motors, 
<a href="http://www.chryslercorp.com/">Chrysler</a>, Nissan, Toyota, NUMMI, 
Diamond Star and Saturn.            

<p>
UT Automotive is a major supplier of electrical and interior trim systems and 
components to car and light truck manufactures. Its products are part of nearly
every passenger vehicle built in North America and Europe. 
      
<p>
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>,
which provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the 
aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.   
