<h2>United Technologies Automotive Named Remote Entry Supplier 
for  Odyssey Minivan by Honda</h2>


<p>
<strong>DEARBORN, Mich., July 19, 1995</strong> - United Technologies Automotive
(UTA) has been named supplier of remote entry systems for Honda's new
Odyssey minivan.  The remote entry systems, manufactured by UTA in
Tampa, Fla., are supplied to Honda's manufacturing plant in Sayama, Japan. 
The Odyssey currently is sold in Japan, Europe and North America.

<p>
Odyssey's UTA-developed remote entry system, comprising an
electronic receiver module and two remote transmitters (key fobs),
permits keyless entry by unlocking the vehicle's door with a single press
of a key fob button.  For security, the driver also can lock all doors with a
single touch of a second button.

<p>
UTA's relationship with Honda began in 1987, when the company
began manufacturing switches and relays for the Honda Accord.  Soon, UTA
began supplying components for Honda's popular Civic model.  Currently,
UTA also supplies remote entry systems and other components to Honda's
Acura division for the TL luxury sedan, which is sold both in Japan and in
North America.

<p>
Honda recently <a href="/general/pr/zville_rel.html">recognized</a> 
UTA's Zanesville, Ohio, manufacturing
plant with an award for outstanding component delivery performance.  The
plant achieved 100-percent on-time delivery of components (none early,
none late).  UTA's Zanesville plant manufactures relays, door lock
switches and fan switches for Honda's vehicle manufacturing plants in
East Liberty and Marysville, Ohio, and in Japan.

<p>
UTA is a full-service supplier of electrical, electronic and interior
trim systems and components to car and light truck manufacturers.  Its
products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America
and Europe.

<p>
UTA is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United
Technologies
Corp.</a>  (NYSE:UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology
products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive
industries.
