<h2>United Technologies Automotive Wins Honda Award</h2>

<p>
<strong>Zanesville, Ohio, June 13, 1995</strong> - Associates at United Technologies
Automotive's Linden Avenue plant in Zanesville really deliver, and as a result, today were
presented with a supplier award for outstanding delivery from Honda of America Manufacturing
(HAM).

<P>
UTA was one of only 38 of HAM's 322 North American suppliers to receive a delivery award at
the company's recent annual supplier conference. To earn the award, the plant had to achieve 100-
percent on-time delivery of all components (none early, none late) and meet the quality average.

<P>
UTA's Linden Avenue facility supplies relays, door-lock switches and fan switches for Honda's
Accord and Civic models, which are manufactured domestically at the automaker's Marysville
and East Liberty, Ohio manufacturing plants.

<P>
"This award to our associates illustrates their absolute commitment to serving our customers in a
very competitive industry," said Jeff Lunsford, plant manager of UTA's Linden Avenue pant. "The
depth of this customer commitment is evidenced in the continued growth of our business with
Honda, a very demanding customer and a recognized leader in building quality vehicles."

<p>
"UTA's commitment to outstanding performance is an important part of increasing our
competitiveness in the global marketplace," said Dave Nelson, vice president of purchasing for
HAM. "Achieving the level of performance reached by UTA and its associates is possible only
when there is management commitment, associate involvement and dedication to continuous
improvement by the total team."

<p>
UTA's relationship with Honda began in 1987, when the company began manufacturing switches
and relays for the Honda Accord. Soon, the company began supplying components for Honda's
popular Civic models. Currently, UTA also exports remote entry systems and other components
to Honda for the North American versions of the company's new <a
href="/general/pr/odyssey_rel.html">Odyssey minivan</a> and its <a
href="/general/pr/acura_tl_rel.html">Acura division's TL luxury sedan</a>.


<P>
The 500,000-sq.-ft. Linden manufacturing facility, built in 1892, employs nearly 1,100 associates.

<P>
UTA is a full-service supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems and components
to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in
North America and Europe.

<P>
UTA is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United
Technologies Corp.</a> (NYSE: UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology
products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.

