<h2>UT Automotive Signs Licensing, Supply Agreements with Korean
Engineering Company</h2>

<P>
<strong>Dearborn, Mich., June 30, 1995</strong> - UT Automotive has
licensed its new patented mirror actuator technology to Jaeil Engineering, a Korean based
manufacturing company, located in Seoul. The company also signed a supply agreement with Jaeil
for future automotive models.

<P>
With the agreement, Jaeil will use UT Automotive's patented design to manufacture mirror actuators and
will have restricted distribution rights for passenger car and truck mirrors.

<P>
"The key difference in the UT Automotive design, when compared to existing mirror actuators currently
available in the market, is the geometric positioning of the pivot, allowing less vibration," said
Michael D. Faloon, UT Automotive's director of research and development, mirrors. "The new feature will
virtually eliminate all vibration when the vehicle is in motion, enabling the driver to make more
precise mirror adjustment."

<p>
Jaeil's main products include precision tools, automotive parts, radio and telecommunications
products, and precision and insert molding. Jaeil currently supplies both Korean based and foreign
companies, including Samsung, Gold Star, Eaton, Siemens and Daewoo and Packard Electronics.
Jaeil recently purchased Daeseung Mirrors, one of only three mirror companies in Korea, to expand
its business into the automotive field. Daeseung is a supplier to Hyundai, Daewoo, Kia and Ssang
Yong auto companies in Korea.

<P>
"Jaeil is an excellent technology partner for the commercialization of this new design," said Leon
Goolsby, UT Automotive's vice president and general manager, mirrors. "The combination of UT Automotive's world-
class technology, and Jaeil's manufacturing expertise, promise outstanding global growth
potential."

<p>
UT Automotive is a major supplier of electrical and interior trim systems and 
components to car and light truck manufactures. Its products are part of nearly
every passenger vehicle built in North America and Europe. 
      
<p>
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United
Technologies Corp.</a>,
which provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the 
aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.   

