<h2>UT Automotive Named Full-Service Supplier 
for Switches by Ford Motor Company Body, Chassis Engineering
Groups</h2>

<p>
<strong>DEARBORN, Mich., April 3, 1995</strong> - UT Automotive 
has been named a full-service supplier for switch products by both the Body
Engineering and Chassis Engineering organizations of <a href="http://www.ford.com">Ford Motor Co.</a>  UT Automotive is the
first switch supplier to simultaneously receive the designation from two Ford
engineering organizations.

<p>
In attaining full-service supplier status with Ford, UT Automotive underwent a rigorous
13-month evaluation process that required it to meet Ford's high standards in
areas such as product design, development, product testing, manufacturing
engineering, manufacturing support, service support and CAD/CAM data
capability.

<p>
"Ford's recognition of UT Automotive as a full-service supplier acknowledges our
world-class concept-to-production capabilities for switch products," said <a href="/../general/people/wol.htm">
Thomas C. Wolanzyk</a>, vice president and general 
manager of UT Automotive's Input Controls business
unit, which manufactures electromechanical switches and electronic components
for light vehicles.  "We look to automakers such as Ford, who recognize our full-
service capabilities, to increasingly utilize them as competition in the global
automotive marketplace becomes more fierce."

<p>
Ford's full-service supplier certification is built on the requirements of the
automakers's Total Quality Excellence program.  Its goal is to increase product
quality and customer satisfaction, improve engineering and manufacturing cost
efficiencies, minimize engineering changes, shorten product development time and
increase advanced technology development.

<p>
"A key outcome of our full-service supplier status is that UT Automotive's product
development cycle for switches now is synchronized to Ford's program model,"
said William Floyd, engineering manager for electromechanical switches for UT Automotive,
who managed a cross-functional team appointed to oversee the certification
process.  "That model is driving how Ford develops its products into the future, so
this recognition will help us compete for future development opportunities."

<p>
UT Automotive manufactures a broad range of electromechanical switches and
electronic modules for the automotive industry.  These include multifunction turn
signal switches, ignition switches, keyless entry switches, brake shift interlock
solenoids, headlamp switches, relays, transmission connectors, rheostats, transfer
case modules, seat switches, memory modules, wiper modules, keyless entry
modules and other instrument panel switches.

<p>
UT Automotive is a major, full-service supplier of electrical and interior trim systems
and components to car and light truck manufacturers.  Its products are part of
nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America and Europe.

<p>
UT Automotive is a subsidiary of Hartford Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corp.</a>
(NYSE:UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology products and
services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.

