<h2>UTA-Port Huron Employees Reject Unionization Vote</h2>

<p>
<strong>Port Huron, Mich., March 22, 1995</strong> - United Technologies Automotive (UTA)
hourly employees at the company's Port Huron manufacturing facility today rejected a bid for
United Auto Workers union representation.

<P>
"We appreciate the support our employees have shown by rejecting the union's attempts to organize
at our Port Huron plant," said Jim Haney, general plants manager for Unite Technologies
Automotive. "The company has a history of providing good jobs in a safe environment at a fair
wage."

<p>
UTA's Port Huron manufacturing facility, which employs more than 200 associates, makes
automotive headliners for UTA's North American customers. The plant, which began operation in
1971, became part of UTA in 1979.

<P>
UTA is a major supplier of electrical and interior trim systems and components to car and light
truck manufacturers. Its products are part of nearly every passenger vehicle built in North America
and Europe.

<P>
UTA is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United
Technologies Corp.</a> (NYSE: UTX), which provides a broad range of high-technology
products and services to the aerospace, building systems and automotive industries.

