<h2>United Technologies Automotive, Niles Cooperate on Auto
Components in Europe</h2>

<p>
<strong>DEARBORN, Mich., Feb. 7, 1995</strong> - Automotive
suppliers United Technologies Automotive (UTA), and NIles Parts Co.,
Ltd., of Japan have announced a cooperative agreement for development
of automotive components in Europe. The two companies will share
technology for the development of electromechanical switches and
electronic components for European automotive manufacturers.

<p>
The companies will open a joint office in the United Kingdom during
the first quarter of 1995 to provide sales, marketing and engineering
services for the production of components for European automakers.

<P>
"This agreement will provide a complete range of product capabilities to
our mutual European customers," said Thomas C. Wolanzykk, vice
president and general manager of UTA's Input Controls business unit.

<P>
"Sharing technologies will alow us to support global vehicle
development as a team," said T. Suzuki, president of Niles Parts Co., Ltd.
"This is mutually beneficial, both to us and to our customers, because it
allows us to apply lessons learned in the European market to customer
programs in other markets, as well."

<p>
"The combination of both companies' complementary technologies,
coupled with UTA's manufacturing presence, should enhance our
competetive position in Europe," said Richard J. Sloan, president of
UTA-Europe.

<P>
UTA and Niles have worked together in similar technical relationships
in North America since 1988. The companies have shared technologies
for the design of multifunction switches and electronic products.

<P>
Niles Parts Company is headquartered in Tokyo, Japan, and is a major
supplier of electronic and electromechanical automotive components,
having R & D, engineering, assembly, marketing and sales facilities
primarily in japan and extending to the automotive market worldwide.

<P>
UTA, headquartered in Dearborn, Mich., is a subsidiary of Hartford,
Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies
Corporation</a> (NYSE: UTX). It is a major supplier of electrical and
interior trim systems and components to car and light truck
manufacturers worldwide.

