<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN"><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>UTA Licenses Revolutionary Prismatic Mirror Technology</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#ffffff">    <p align="center">    <img src="/images/heads/about.head.gif" width="550" height="150"    alt="[about uta]">    </p>    <h5>Contact: Michael Scholl      <a href="mailto:mscholl@uta.com">        mscholl@uta.com      </a>      <br>      (313) 593-9672    </h5><H2>UT Automotive Licenses Revolutionary Prismatic Mirror Technology</H2><IMG SRC="rear2.gif" ALT="mirror 1" ALIGN=TEXTTOP WIDTH="239" HEIGHT="240"><P>	<STRONG>DEARBORN, Mich., Feb. 23, 1995</STRONG> - UT Automotive (UTA) has licensed a revolutionary 	prismatic side-view exterior mirror technology for North American production from de Montfort 	Management Ltd., of England.</P><P>	The Prismatic mirror utilizes Fresnel prisms and a reflective mirror surface mounted inside 	the passenger compartment on the center line of the door to allow the driver to easily view 	objects along side and behind the vehicle.</P><P>	"Side-view mirror technology has gone essentially unchanged for 70 years," said Richard E. Berg, manager,	 marketing, advanced technology, Interior Systems & Components for UT Automotive.</P><P>"This innovative technology promises a wider range of styling and design freedom, while incorporating all of the functionality found in today's mirrors."</P><P>	"Prismatic mirror technology, with its many advantages over conventional mirrors, is the first	 step in a new generation of vision systems that will increase visibility and enhance the safety 	 of vehicles into the 21st century," said Michael D. Faloon, director, research and development, Mirrors,	  for UTA.</P><P>	The technology's performance advantages over traditional exterior side-view mirrors include:</P><UL TYPE=DISC>		<LI>Improved aerodynamics - In wind tunnel testing, the low profile of the prismatic mirror, 		which protrudes 60 percent less than conventional mirrors, virtually eliminates mirror and 		wind drag. It also eliminates wind noise caused by turbulent air passing by the mirror at 		high speeds.		<LI>Improved side vision - the stabilizing action of mounting the mirror over the door's 		center line reduces vibration, contributing to improved side/rear vision for the driver.		<LI>Ease of use in inclement weather - because the reflective surface of the mirror actually 		is located inside the vehicle, the driver does not look through a dirty side window to see 		images in the mirror.		<LI>"Driver friendly" performance - Has the look, feel, and function of a traditional side 		mirror to the driver.		<LI>Increased safety - Because the mirror does not protrude, it does not present an injury 		hazard to pedestrians or bicyclists.		<LI>Reduced mirror damage - The mirror's low-profile design greatly reduces incidents of 		mirror damage that can occur while the vehicle is parked or in automatic car washes.</UL><P>	The prismatic mirror's wedge-shaped design offers numerous advantages to automakers, as well 	as motorists. Because the mirror eliminates coefficient of drag penalties associated with 	conventional designs, it can help OEMs meet federal corporate average fuel economy (CAFE) 	standards. The cost of the prismatic mirror is expected to compare favorably with foldable 	mirrors currently on most upscale car and light truck models.</P><P>	Styling flexibility also is improved. The mirror can be designed into the window area 	traditionally used for side-view mirror placement or in the door panel below the vehicle's 	belt line.</P><P>	According to Leon R. Goolsby, vice president and general manager of UTA's Mirrors group, the license	 agreement allows UTA to use all levels of de Montfort's Milner prismatic technology to produce 	 side-view exterior mirrors for North American-made domestic and export vehicles.</P><P>	Based in Lichfield, England, de Montfort is an international automotive consultancy with clients 	that include governments, vehicle manufacturers and distributors and component suppliers. The 	company also develops innovative automotive products for licensing to others.</P><P>		UTA is a major supplier of electrical, electronic and interior trim systems and components		 to car and light truck manufacturers. Its products are part of nearly every passenger 		 vehicle built in North America and Europe.</P><P>	UTA is a subsidiary of Hartford, Conn.-based <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corporation</a> (NYSE:UTX), which	 provides a broad range of high-technology products and services to the aerospace, building 	 systems and automotive industries.</P>	    <hr>    <p align="center">      <img src="/images/footers/about.footer.rev.gif">      <a href="/people/people.html">        <img src="/images/footers/people.footer.gif" border="0">      </a>      <a href="/products/products.html">        <img src="/images/footers/products.footer.gif" border="0">      </a>      <a href="/locations/locations.html">        <img src="/images/footers/locations.footer.gif" border="0">      </a>      <a href="/jobs/jobs.html">        <img src="/images/footers/jobs.footer.gif" border="0">      </a>      <a href="/technology/technology.html">        <img src="/images/footers/technology.footer.gif" border="0">      </a>    </p>    <hr>    <h6>All information Copyright &#169; 1994, 1995, 1996 United Technologies    Automotive, unless stated otherwise.</h6></BODY></HTML>
