<P>

<A HREF="juarez.htm">JUAREZ EARNS ISO-9002</A>

<P>

<A HREF="women.htm">INTERIORS' WOMEN'S  GROUP ASKS THE QUESTION: <BR>'WHAT IF?'</A>

<p>

<A HREF="around.htm">AROUND UT AUTOMOTIVE</A>


</FONT>



</TD>






<TD WIDTH=350ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN="TOP">







<!---##########STORY STARTS HERE##########--->





<h1>Sloan seeks growth in European market</h1>

<p>


In a recent interview, Dick Sloan, president of United Technologies Automotive (Europe) cited the challenges 
of working with and among several trade regulations, cultures, languages and currencies. With a presence in 
every major European market, Sloan's operation must maneuver among various customer needs while 
meeting governmental and geographic requirements.<P>

<STRONG>Q.  Recently, United Technologies Automotive (Europe) has implemented 
the "lead-unit" concept. What is this?</STRONG> <BR>
<STRONG>A.</STRONG>  Since we powered up this concept in 1993, our penetration in Europe has increased 
dramatically. Because we service so many automakers in Europe -- which has many different requirements, 
cultures and languages -- we developed the lead-unit concept where engineering, product, finance, quality 
and sales responsibilities are directed from a single operation. This concept supports our efforts to provide the best 
customer service. It's similar to the product development teams concept in the U.S.<p>

<STRONG>Q. Who are our key customers in Europe?</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>A.</STRONG> Our customer base has really grown. PSA, Fiat and Renault have always been our 
key customers, but we have added GM Opel, Saab and Jaguar. We are the first outside supplier Opel has 
contracted. And we are a key supplier for GM's new Astra and Omega car programs.
PSA continues to be our No. 1 customer. We supply two products to PSA -- cooling fans and electrical 
distribution systems.  We supply 75 percent of the wiring for the new Citroen Saxo, which produces 
about 1,250 cars a day. We also supply cooling fans and 75 percent of the wiring system to Citroen 
for the  Xantia; 100 percent of wiring systems to SAAB; and 100 percent of the junction boxes and 
some wiring systems for the Land Rover.<p>

<STRONG>Q.  How do you plan to grow United Technologies Automotive (Europe) business?</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>A.</STRONG> Our long-term goal is to increase our market penetration and assume the leadership 
position with all of the major European product lines. There are two ways we will accomplish this:  first, by being awarded 
new contracts for new products with our present customers, as well as acquiring new customers and second, by actively pursuing acquisitions and joint ventures. <P>

<STRONG>Q. Quality is a major issue today.  How is United Technologies Automotive (Europe) doing in this area?</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>A.</STRONG> Overall, our quality levels in Europe are very good. Our plants in Hungary and Portugal
 have the best customer PPM records.  We recently implemented a new and innovative automated quality 
system throughout Europe. This is a computer data base that allows us to input information from the plant's 
first-run capability to facts about customer rejects, warranties and reliability.<p>

<STRONG>Q. What are some of your future challenges?</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>A.</STRONG> Western Europe will continue to be a competitive fight.  For the first time, European car makers are 
dealing with a world-class pricing structure. The pressure is on for European automakers to lower car prices, 
and as they lower their prices, they come to us to lower our prices. <p>

<STRONG>Q. What are some of the opportunities you see?</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>A.</STRONG> Our real opportunities will be in Eastern Europe, where the industry is growing 
at a rapid rate. There will be tremendous growth in vehicle sales in that market, and we want to be part of 
that growth.  We're getting organized to support our automotive customers in that market.  
We already have operations in Hungary and Poland. <p>

<STRONG>Q. How do you see the business changing?</STRONG><BR>
<STRONG>A.</STRONG> In Europe, car companies are doing more outsourcing. This offers us an opportunity to grow our business. 
Europe is ahead of the U.S. in moving in the direction of suppliers providing car makers with 
integrated systems and external modular assembly.<P> 



<TD WIDTH="130" VALIGN=TOP>


</TD></TR></TABLE>
<BR>


