    <h2>Norm Bodine</h2>
    <h3>President and CEO</h3>
    <IMG SRC="pics/norm.gif" ALT="Bodine" ALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="200" HEIGHT="263">


    <P>
    <STRONG>Norman R. Bodine</STRONG> is president and CEO of UT Automotive.</p>
<P>	Prior to being appointed president and CEO in January 1992, Bodine served as president of
	 UT Automotive's electrical systems unit from June 1991 to January 1992, where he was responsible
	  for managing the company's North American electrical products -- including wiring systems, 
	  input controls, connectors and motor systems -- at 36 manufacturing plants.</P>
<P>	Bodine joined UT Automotive in 1984 as president of its former Automotive Products Division,
	 with broad, global responsibilities.  Before joining UT Automotive, Bodine was president of 
	 Prestolite Co., then a unit of Allied's Bendix Division.</P>
<P>	A native of Schenectedy, N.Y., Bodine received a bachelor of science degree in physics from 
	the <A HREF=http://www.umich.edu>University of Michigan</A>, and a master of science degree and
	 doctorate in physics from the
	 <A HREF=http://www.washington.edu>University of Washington</A>.  He also completed <A HREF="http://www.cornell.edu/" NAME="Cornell University">Cornell
	  University's</A> <A HREF="http://www.gsm.cornell.edu/Catalog/execEd.html" NAME="Executive Development Program">Executive Development Program</A>.</P>
<P>	He is a member of the Citizens Advisory Committee for the <A HREF="http://www.umd.umich.edu/" NAME="University of Michigan Dearborn">University of Michigan-Dearborn</A>, 
	the Presidents Council for the <A HREF=http://www.umich.edu>University of Michigan</A> in Ann Arbor, Mich., the board of 
	trustees for the <A HREF="http://www.dia.org/" NAME="DIA">Detroit Institute of Arts</A> and the Automotive Original Equipment Manufacturers,
	 where he serves as treasurer.</P>
<p>
   



    
