<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>UT Automotive Design and Engineering</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#173973" VLINK="#777777" ALINK="#C8D838" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<map name="general">
<area shape="rect" coords="362,23 ,449,54" href="/jobs/jobs.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="273,24, 363,54" href="/doing/doin.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="198,23,274,53" href="/protech/prod.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="122,24, 199,53" href="/media/medi.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="47,00, 122,67" href="../gene.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="01,23, 34,54" href="/index.htm">
</map>
<IMG SRC="../gene.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="73" usemap="#general" border="0">
</center>
<!--header ends here-->    <h2>4. Design and engineering capabilities/technology</h2>



    <p>
    From initial concept through production and beyond, UT Automotive carries projects
    through all stages of development using the most modern design and
    engineering tools and techniques.
    <P>
    UT Automotive can provide a full range of design and styling capabilities, including
    concept development through sketches and renderings, and full-sized styling
    models, graphic design and layout design.
    <P>
    Our designers and engineers are experts in their fields. When involved
    early in the concept phase, UT Automotive often has introduced new ideas and options
    to customers that add value or lower the cost of products and streamline the
    manufacturing process. In fact, UT Automotive has the capability to work as a
    customer's engineering and design department, providing cost-effective
    program management and allowing customers to devote more time to final
    vehicle assembly.
    <P>
    UT Automotive uses such engineering hardware and software as advanced Catia and PDGS
    computer-aided design and computer-aided engineering (ACD/CAE) systems. We
    emphasize the exchange of design and process technology and information
    among our U.S., European and Japanese engineering centers to better serve
    our customers' needs. To further improve this exchange, all of UT Automotive's
    engineering centers are linked via global satellite.
    <P>
    In addition, UT Automotive draws on the knowledge and expertise of nearly 1,000
    engineers and scientists at the <a href="http://www.utrc.utc.com/">United
    Technologies Research Center</a>. Many dedicated research projects -
    including rapid prototyping, materials testing and composites testing - are
    under way there and at local universities.
    <P>
    We're also working with other United Technologies divisions to transfer
    their technology to automotive applications. For example, UT Automotive is teaming
    with Carrier, the world's largest manufacturer of heating and air
    conditioning systems, to develop air distribution systems that route air
    through a vehicle's headliner and door panels.
    <P>
    UT Automotive continues working to reduce design and engineering time, accommodate
    changes easier and decrease concept-to-market cycle time. Through
    innovation, technology transfer and extensive research and development,
    we're constantly finding ways to improve our products and introduce new
    concepts to the automotive industry.

<p>

    <p align="center">
      <a href="/general/info/cust.htm">[back]</a>
      <a href="/general/info/closer.htm">[top]</a>
      <a href="/general/info/test.htm">[next]</a>
      </p>

