<!--header ends here-->

    <h2>Significant Events in UT Automotive History</h2>


    <table>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1930<br>
        <td>Essex Wire Corporation of Detroit, Michigan establishes the
        Automotive Products Division and begins manufacture and sale of
        automotive wire assemblies. <br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1931<br>
        <td>Essex begins manufacture of automotive switches.<br> 
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1932<br>
        <td>Essex begins manufacturing wire and cable for automotive and
        construction industries. <br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1934<br>
        <td>Sheller introduces steering wheels with a spray painted finish.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1936<br>
        <td>Essex began producing magnet wire. <br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1939<br>
        <td>Amos-Thompson Corporation buys a plastic injection molding machine
        for its plant in Edinburgh, Ind.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1941-1945<br>
        <td>Essex supplies the military with electrical wire assemblies, field
        telephone wire, and transformers. <br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1950s<br>
        <td>Sheller introduces plastic steering wheels.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1954<br>
        <td>American Bosch Corp. and its subsidiary, Arma Corp., form a single
        company: American Bosch Arma Corp. The company opens a 125,000 square
        foot facility in Columbus, Miss. Early products include automobile
        voltage regulators and ignition equipment for commercial stationary
        engines.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1957<br>
        <td>Globe-Wernicke Company is merged into The City Auto Stamping
        Company.  The new company is named Globe-Wernicke Industries, Inc.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1965<br>
        <td>Essex becomes a publicly held company with its shares listed on the
        New York Stock Exchange. <br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1966<br>
        <td>Sheller Manufacturing Corporation merges into Globe-Wenicke
        Industries, Inc. The new company is named Sheller-Globe Corporation.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1967<br>
        <td>Essex begins manufacturing automotive turn signals.<br> 
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1968<br>
        <td>Essex Wire Corporation changes its name to Essex International,
        Inc.
        <p>
        American Bosch Arma Corp. changes its name to Ambac Industries.
        <p>
        Sheller-Globe introduces the first urethane wheel for automobile
        use.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1969<br>
        <td>Essex establishes operations in the United Kingdom to manufacture
        and sell wire harnesses in Europe. <br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1969<br>
        <td>Essex establishes an integrated circuit research and manufacturing
        Facility in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. <br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1970<br>
        <td>Essex opens first Mexican plant in Juarez.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1971<br>
        <td>Essex licenses Tokai Rika to manufacture turn signals using APD
        patented technology. <br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1971-1972<br>
        <td>Essex receives two of the first U.S. patents in multiplex
        technology. <br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1973<br>
        <td>Essex conceives steering column POD switching concept as the
        Divinci car proposal.<br> 
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1973<br>
        <td>Essex establishes electronics manufacturing facility near
        Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. <br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1974<br>
        <td><a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corporation</a>
        acquires Essex International, Inc.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1977<br>
        <td>Alma Plastics Company buys Edinburgh, Ind. plant.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1978<br>
        <td>MAISA, a Spanish manufacturer of automotive wire harnesses,
        electromechanical products, electronics and terminals and connectors,
        is acquired by Essex as a wholly owned subsidiary.
        <P>
        Ambac becomes a wholly owned subsidiary of
        <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corporation</a>.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1979<br>
        <td><a href="http://www.utc.com/">UTC</a> organizes United Technologies
        Automotive by combining Ambac Industries and the electrical and
        electronics operations of Essex. UT Automotive establishes its headquarters in
        Dearborn, Mich.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1983<br>
        <td>UT Automotive purchases a majority interest in Gate, S.p.A., an Italian
        manufacturer of fractional horsepower DC electric motors and other
        components for the European automotive industry.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1982<br>
        <td>Sheller-Globe acquires certain assets of TRW-Clifford Limited
        (England).<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1984<br>
        <td>UT Automotive enters into joint venture agreements with Renault to manufacture
        automotive wire harnesses and terminals and connectors in Europe.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1984<br>
        <td>UT Automotive is awarded Board of Director's Trophy by
        <a href="http://www.utc.com/">United Technologies Corporation</a> for
        successful development of multiplex technology.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1984<br>
        <td>UT Automotive enters into joint venture agreement with Grundig (Germany) for
        manufacture of wire harnesses.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1985<br>
        <td><a href="http://www.utc.com/">UTC</a> buys Alma Plastics.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1987<br>
        <td>UT Automotive forms joint venture with Furukawa Electric Co., called United
        Technologies Furukawa to produce wiring systems.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1988<br>
        <td><a href="http://www.utc.com/">UTC</a> purchases a 46 percent
        interest in Sheller-Globe, a Detroit-based producer of steering wheels,
        door panels and other automotive interior trim products.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1989<br>
        <td><a href="http://www.utc.com/">UTC</a> buys an additional 46 percent
        in Sheller-Globe and combines the supplier with UT Automotive's operations.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1991<br>
        <td>UT Automotive's first plant in Eastern Europe opens in G&#246;d&#246;ll&#246;,
        Hungary.<br>
      <Tr>
        <th align="right" valign="top">1994<br>
        <td>UT Automotive signs joint-venture agreements with two Chinese companies to
        produce wire harnesses, engine cooling modules and other related
        components. <br>
      <Tr>
         <th align="right" valign="top">1997<br>
        <td>UT Automotive signaled its expansion in the automotive electronics 
	industry in Europe by signing an agreement to form a joint venture with Loewe 
	Opta GmbH, a German electronics company.<br>
    </Table>

    <!--footer begins here-->
