<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>

    <TITLE>Francis J. Macielak</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#173973" VLINK="#777777" ALINK="#C8D838" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<map name="general">
<area shape="rect" coords="362,23, 449,54" href="/jobs/jobs.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="273,24, 363,54" href="/doing/doin.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="198,23, 274,53" href="/protech/prod.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="122,24, 199,53" href="/media/medi.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="47,00, 122,67" href="../gene.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="01,23, 34,54" href="/index.htm">
</map>
<IMG SRC="../gene.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="73" usemap="#general" border="0">
</center>
<!--header ends here-->
    <h2>Tom Wolanzyk</h2>
    <h3>Vice President &amp; General Manager,<br>Input Controls</h3>
    <IMG SRC="pics/wol.gif">

  

    <P>

    <STRONG>Thomas C. Wolanzyk</STRONG> was named vice president &amp; general
    manager, Input Controls, on Jan. 7 1992 as part of UT Automotive's reorganization 
    into business units. Wolanzyk had served since 1989 as vice president and 
    general manager of UT Automotive's electromechanical and electronics group, which was 
    renamed Input Controls.
    <P>
    Wolanzyk is responsible for the business unit that designs and manufactures
    a wide range of electric and electronic controls for automotive
    applications, including single-use and muliti-function switches, electronic
    modules, brake/shift interlock solenoids and remote/keyless entry systems.
    <P>
    Wolanzyk joined UT Automotive in 1980 as manager of advanced systems in the 
    automotive products division. He became chief engineer of advanced 
    engineering and electronics in 1982, and later that year was named manager
    of advanced engineering and electronics. He became vice president of 
    engineering in 1984, and became a senior vice president in 1987.
    <P>
    Before coming to UT Automotive, Wolanzyk spent nine years with <A HREF="http://www.gm.com">General Motors</A>.
    Before GM, he held positions with General Dynamics and <A HREF="http://www.wmich.edu">Western Michigan
    University</A>.
    <P>
    Wolanzyk holds an associate's degree in applied science from Devry
    Institute of Technology, a bachelor's degree in electrical engineering
    from <a href="http://www.wmich.edu">Western Michigan University</a> and a
    master's degree in electrical engineering from the
    <a href="http://www.umich.edu">University of Michigan.</a>
