<!--header ends here-->

    <h3>Timothy F. O'Brien</h3>

<h4>Product Engineering Manager</h4>

<p>Tim O'Brien has been involved in the design of instrument panels and other interior trim components since he began his automotive career with <a href="http://www.ford.com/">Ford Motor Company</a> 13 years ago. He joined UT Automotive in 1986 as senior product design engineer responsible for product design direction and manufacturing feasability for several interior trim assemblies.</p>
<p>As product engineering manager for UT Automotive's padded trim products group, a position he has held since 1989, O'Brien directs the engineering staff in the development of instrument panels, consoles and door trim panels for such customers as <a href="http://www.toyota.com/">Toyota</a>, Diamond-Star, <a href="http://www.chryslercars.com/">Chrysler</a>, NUMMI and <a href="http://www.ford.com/">Ford</a>. He was instrumental in the successful launch of the instrument panel and door trim panels for Chrysler's exciting new <a href="http://www.4adodge.com/neon/">Neon</a>.</p>
<p>O'Brien holds a master's degree in physics from <a href="http://www.emich.edu/">Eastern Michigan University</a> and a bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering from the <a href="http://www.utoledo.edu/">University of Toledo.</a></p>

