<TD WIDTH=610 ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN="TOP">







<!---##########STORY STARTS HERE##########--->





<h1>QS-9000: It's your job</h1>

<p>


How do you spell quality?  For automotive suppliers who wish to remain suppliers in the next millennium, 
it's spelled QS-9000. <p>

QS-9000 is an industrywide quality system encompassing the fundamental quality expectations of 
automakers, truck manufacturers and other subscribing companies.  <p>

The system is a tool designed to provide the discipline required to effectively manage quality throughout business while eliminating redundant requirements and their 
associated costs.<p>

"QS-9000 is the way we're expected to run our business," said Ray Colley, corporate manager of quality 
systems, who was brought to UT Automotive from Carrier last year to spearhead the company's QS-9000 
certification effort.<p>

All Tier 1 suppliers to the automotive industry are required by their customers -- 
Ford, General Motors and Chrysler -- to obtain QS-9000 certification.  While each customer has its own deadline, 
the expectation is the same.<p>

In fact, Ford set the tone regarding the importance of achieving quality standards recently when it removed 
44 component supplier plants who had not earned Q1 status from its list of suppliers. Losing the Q1 
designation means losing Ford's business.<p>

Ed Hagenlocker, Ford Automotive Operations president, said this marks the first withdrawal in Q1's history.
"It's one example of what our higher expectations are," said Hagenlocker, who was quoted in a 
Detroit Free Press article.<p>

Colley put it this way.  "If we don't achieve QS-9000 status, then we won't be able to quote on new 
business.  It's that simple," he said.<p>

<IMG SRC="graph2.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH="340" HEIGHT="196" BORDER="0" HSPACE="6" VSPACE="3">

Achieving certification in all of the functions a company's employees perform -- in the office to the 
plant floor -- is not simple.  The first step involves documenting procedures and agreeing on how current 
business procedures are performed.  Then, further reviews of every process and procedure determine if the 
work is done in the most efficient or effective manner. If  associates determine if the function can be improved,
the appropriate changes are made. <p> 

<HR>
<I>The chart, right, illustrates the months in 1997 that UT Automotive needs to achieve QS-9000 status for various OEMs.</I><p>
<HR>

An audit process follows in which processes or procedures  not in conformance with sound business 
practices are identified and corrective action suggested.  A  corporate audit and/or a third-party audit by an 
outside, objective source followed by a third-party initial audit is required.   Management reviews the suggested 
action, then assigns personnel, machinery and materials -- whatever it takes -- to make the necessary 
improvements.<p>

The real "value added" part of the process comes during implementation of QS-9000, according to Colley.  
"The part I like most is taking off my auditor's hat and putting on my 'how can I help' hat.  This is where 
working together with people, sharing best practices, and re-audits will assist in improving our overall 
business systems."<p>

Many work groups throughout UT Automotive are in the process of achieving 
QS-9000.  Some are in the audit stage, while others are in the corrective action phase.<p>

While plants and offices are busy assessing their processes and procedures, Colley and his staff -- 
Karen Dupon and Mike Thomas -- have been busy spreading the QS-9000 word.  To date, more than 
2,500 employees worldwide have been trained on QS-9000.  <p>

As deadlines near for QS-9000 certification, Colley's staff is working hard to turn the goal into reality.<p>

"We have put out a call for qualified auditors through our UT Automotive QS-9000 Forum and from 
all over UTC to assist in our overall audit efforts," Colley said.  "This will help us share best practices while 
allowing qualified associates to obtain auditor days required for their registration as an auditor or lead auditor 
with the Registration Accreditation Board."<p>

Qualified associates needing audit assistance or wishing to participate in audits should obtain approval 
from their supervisors, and contact their QS-9000 management representative and Colley.<p>

"If we are to achieve QS-9000 registration in 1997, we must have management 
support of this audit activity," Colley said.<p>

Meanwhile, associates can expect to live QS-9000 in the coming months, Colley added.  
Even after initial certification, third-party audits will be repeated every six months to ensure quality systems 
remain in place.<p>

"Our customers are requiring that we establish, document and implement effective quality management 
systems based upon QS-9000," he said. <p> 

"We must learn the art of 'saying what we do and doing what we say.'  This new process may be more 
work initially, but in the long run it will pay off.  As we continue along the path of 
continuous improvement, the quality systems we set in place today will become the 
foundation we build upon tomorrow."<p>

<p><p><p>

<center><A HREF="QS9000.htm">TOP OF PAGE</A><p>

