<h1>Around UT Automotive</h1>


<H4>Zanesville, Ohio</H4>
Some 20 employees from the Zanesville, Ohio, Input Controls plant are hitting the books 
to earn their MBAs. Students attend the University of Findlay via video conference technology.  
The program, consisting of 33 credit hours, will take roughly two years to complete.
Jeff Lunsford, plant manager, said the on-site educational program is a first for the plant.  
"We're used to making switches here, not MBA graduates," he said. 

<H4>Detroit, Michigan</H4>
<IMG SRC="round.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH="205" HEIGHT="140" BORDER="0" HSPACE="6" VSPACE="3">
Car enthusiasts at the  Porter Street office didn't have to walk too far to catch a glimpse of some hot rods.  
The first annual Porter Street Auto Show was held in the building's 
parking lot. Associates who own treasured vehicles drove them into work for a day to share their passion with 
fellow workers.  The cars -- ranging from a 1966 AC Cobra 427 and Triumph Spitfire to a 1985 SS Monte Carlo -- 
were parked outside the building's front door so associates could browse during their lunch hour.
Peter Raciti, product engineer, Steering Wheels, who spearheaded the show, said the event provided associates 
with the opportunity to share their passion. "It was a great networking opportunity," he said. <p>

