<h1>UT Automotive enters Thailand market</h1>

<p>

<IMG SRC="thai.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="275" HEIGHT="209" BORDER="0" HSPACE="5" VSPACE="2">

To support its strategic expansion into the Asian automotive components market, United Technologies 
Automotive, Inc.  has signed an agreement with Siam Motors Co., Ltd. (SMC) to form Siam UT Automotive Co., 
Ltd.  The joint venture company will manufacture electromechanical and electronic components for the Thai 
domestic market and for UT Automotive's global customers.  UT Automotive is the majority partner in the 
venture.<p>

"We established this joint venture with SMC in Thailand to support the rapid growth of the automotive industry 
in the region, and especially Thailand," said Tom Wolanzyk, vice president and general manager, Input Controls. 
"Right now, Thailand and much of the Asian automotive market depend on electromechanical and electronic 
components imported primarily from Japan."<p>

The new joint venture, to be located near Bangkok, will manufacture heater fan switches, relays, multifunction 
switches, door lock switches, remote entry systems and door lock modules. <p>

"Entering Thailand demonstrates our commitment to and support of our customers in the Asian region," 
said  President Norm Bodine. "We view Thailand as an excellent manufacturing location, offering opportunities 
to establish our company as a key supplier to other southeast Asian markets.  It also will allow us to participate 
more quickly and with lower investment to support our automotive customers."<p>

Lower shipping costs, other economic incentives offered by the government of Thailand, and strong partners like SMC will help us realize many 
opportunities to pursue additional business in the future, he added.<p>

SMC, founded in 1952, is the largest automotive components manufacturer 
in Thailand.  It also manufactures Nissan motor vehicles through a joint venture, Siam Nissan
Automotive Co., Ltd., with Nissan Motors of Japan.<p>


