<TD WIDTH="110" VALIGN="TOP">


<FONT SIZE=2 >
<A HREF="thai.htm">UT AUTOMOTIVE ENTERS THAILAND</A>

<P>


<A HREF="breed.htm">BREED PURCHASES STEERING WHEELS</A>

<P>

<A HREF="QS9000.htm">QS-9000: IT'S YOUR JOB</A>

<P>

<A HREF="major.htm">BODINE: AUTO SUPPLIERS FACING MAJOR CHALLENGES</A>

<P>

<A HREF="cebu.htm">CEBU WINS PRESIDENT'S AWARD</A>

<P>

<A HREF="around.htm">AROUND UT AUTOMOTIVE</A>

<P>

<A HREF="utc.htm">AROUND UTC</A>

</FONT>



</TD>



<TD WIDTH="25">

</TD>



<TD WIDTH=610 ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN="TOP">







<!---##########STORY STARTS HERE##########--->





<h1>Bodine: Auto Suppliers Facing Major Challenges</h1>

<p>



<IMG SRC="aiag2.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH="226" HEIGHT="286" BORDER="0" HSPACE="2" VSPACE="2"> 


Automotive suppliers -- UT Automotive included -- are facing major challenges in today's rapidly changing business 
environment.<p>

That's the message UT Automotive President Norm Bodine told a crowd of some 600 at the Automotive Industry Action 
Group's (AIAG) annual Achievement Awards dinner Sept. 17 in Detroit.<p>

"Our industry is undergoing dramatic change, especially as it relates to the cost and capital structure of major tier one 
suppliers," said Bodine, who was the keynote speaker. <p>

Bodine preceded his remarks to automakers and suppliers with a two-minute videotape illustrating the technological 
resources of United Technologies Corp., including visual highlights of UT Automotive, Pratt & Whitney, Sikorsky, Hamilton 
Standard, Otis and Carrier.<p>

Bodine cited several issues facing auto suppliers in today's marketplace.  For example:<p>


	<LI>Tier one suppliers, in general, think they need to be big in order to survive.  Should this growth be accomplished by 
	merger or acquisition?  Bodine said UT Automotive aims "not necessarily to be the biggest, but to be the very best at 
	what it does . . . on a global basis."<p>

	<LI>Systems integration is the future, but do the automakers want or need an integrated systems supplier in every case, 
	and how much of an integrator should suppliers be?   "I believe our customers will be better served if we offer quality 
	systems that perhaps don't provide everything in one bundle, but are better suited to their special product wants and needs," 
	Bodine said.<p>

	<LI>The increased challenges to meet accountability, responsibility, product reliability and warranty costs demands. 
	Bodine said UT Automotive was one of the first auto suppliers to deliver report cards on itself to customers on field 
	reliability.<p>

	<LI>Should or can every tier two or three supplier develop a global presence? According to Bodine, "going global" can stretch a company's financial and human resources to the breaking point.
Bodine praised AIAG as "an organization that helps each of us meet and manage challenges that face our industry."<p>

AIAG assists automakers and suppliers in their cooperative effort  to increase productivity, reduce costs, improve 
quality and make the U.S. industry more competitive in the global marketplace.<p>

Examples of AIAG efforts are programs to eliminate redundancies in computer-aided design systems and to implement 
deployment and training programs for quality systems.<p>


<TD WIDTH="130" VALIGN=TOP>







<!--##########START RIGHT PROMOS HERE##########-->







