<h2>Aspen-Developed Site for the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's Business Responds to AIDS and Labor Responds to AIDS Programs (BRTA/LRTA) Now On the Web</h2>

The <a href="http://www.brta-lrta.org">BRTA/LRTA site</a> gives an overview of BRTA/LRTA programs that help
businesses and labor organizations meet the challenges of HIV/AIDS in the workplace and in the community. Among the site's features are timely information and recent publications on issues related to HIV/AIDS in the workplace; actual statements from business and labor leaders
detailing successful workplace programs; real life scenarios addressing HIV/AIDS issues that
may arise in the workplace; and an extensive list of links to related Web sites. The site also
features several animated GIF (graphic interchange format) images and a QuickTime clip of a
TV Public Service Announcement.
<p><br>

<h2>Kudos for the CDC NAC Web Site</h2>

"Your Tax Dollars At Work . . . The <a href="http://www.cdcnac.org">National AIDS Clearinghouse</a> is just what it says -- a thorough, well-organized site for HIV news, research, funding sources and databases."<p>

-- <i>Reprinted from</i> Fast Forward, The Washington Post's <i>monthly guide to video, music, and computers</i><p>

"On sci.med.aids, one of the most important regular posts is the AIDS Daily Summary from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). The National AIDS Clearinghouse makes available this information as a public service, and it is definitely worth a look."<p>

-- <i>Reprinted from</i> Yahoo! Internet Life<p>

"The Internet has a vast array of sites that help in keeping up with study findings, medical conferences and policy matters. A good place to start is the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's National AIDS Clearinghouse . . . it is the most reliable source of accurate and up-to-date information on AIDS research."<p>

-- <i>Reprinted from the</i> Atlanta Journal/Atlanta Constitution, Living <i>section</i> 

<p><br>

<h2>Aspen Completes First Year of Operating The FEMA Map Service Center</h2>
On October 1, 1996, Aspen completed the first full year of operation for the Map Service Center (MSC) under a 4 option year contract from the Federal Emergency Management Agency.  The MSC was designated a "Reinvention Laboratory" under the National Perfor
mance Review (NPR) prior to the procurement.  MSC supports the National Flood Insurance Program (NFIP) by providing one-stop service for all NFIP-related material.  This support includes a customer service center to receive orders for products and provide
 technical assistance for flood concerns; processing orders, collecting payments, distributing map products and NFIP materials; providing customer follow up; and implementing a new inventory management system utilizing commercial off-the-shelf software.<p
>
Aspen continually seeks to implement performance improvements that are consistent with the MSC's concept as a "Reinvention Laboratory."  For example, customer service performance at MSC was established to conform to NPR's "equal to the best in the busines
s" standards.  Call wait time has been reduced by 150 percent, and the abandonment rate has been reduced by 50 percent over prior contract performance.  Customer Service Representatives also have become very knowledgeable in their subject matter through t
raining from many supporting FEMA representatives; this has further enhanced the quality and accuracy of information provided to callers.  The call center operates from 8:00 a.m. to 8:00 p.m. with 8 to 10 operators and receives approximately 100,000 calls
 annually. 
<p>
During the first year of operation, the MSC distributed over 7.8 million products, an increase of 88 percent over the prior year's rate. Despite this significant increase, Aspen maintained order delivery times at 40 percent less than in the prior year. Fu
rther, we have maintained this performance even though the number of flood disaster orders increased by an unprecedented 524 percent during the first half of FY 1996 and required the shipment of more than 500,000 map panels to flood disaster sites. <p>
For more information about the MSC, contact Linda Kiess at <a
href="mailto:lkiess@aspensys.com"><b>lkiess@aspensys.com.</b></a>
<P><BR>

<h2>Aspen Wins National Health Information Awards</h2>
In October it was announced that Aspen won one silver and one bronze National Health Information Awards. In 1994 this program was initiated to recognize the nation's best consumer health information programs and materials. This recognition program is pres
ented by the Health Information Resource Center, the only private sector clearinghouse for consumer health information. More than 700 entries for the 1996 National Health Information Awards were judged by a specially selected panel of health information e
xperts during this past July and August.<p>

The projects awarded are as follows:<p>
<UL>
<LI>For a total Health Information Program in the category of Consumer Decision-Making Information (Silver):  <i>HIV/AIDS Clinical Trials: Knowing your Options</i> (video,discussion guides and brochures) funded by NIAD/FDA/NLM/CDC.<p>

<LI>For a World Wide Web/Internet Page in the category of Health Promotion/Disease and Injury Prevention Information (Bronze):  <a href="http://www.cdcnac.org"><i>CDC National AIDS Clearinghouse</i></a> WWW Site Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</UL>  
<P><BR>

<H2>HCC Begins Operating IVR System for HUD</H2>
On October 25, the <a href="http://www.aspensys.com/hcc"><i>Housing Counseling Clearinghouse</i></a> (HCC) began operating the Interactive Voice Response (IVR) Counselor Referral System for HUD. With this technology, callers seeking the names of local age
ncies to help them with housing questions and problems just enter their zip code and a code for the type of counseling they desire. The system automatically searches HCCs database and supplies the caller with at least three appropriate local agency names
 and phone numbers. HCC currently maintains a database of over 1,200 pre-purchase, rental issue, default foreclosure, and home equity conversion mortgage counselors.<p>
During the first week of operation, 9,319 individuals were helped by this system and the numbers are expected to grow. The IVR technology could potentially be used to help other Aspen-run clearinghouses handle higher volumes of calls without increasing st
aff size or the workload for current staff.<br>


