<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Aspen Timeline</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FF0000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#3B17FF" VLINK="#FF0900">

<!-- System: Aspen Home Page -->
<!-- Author: Aspen Systems Corporation (www.aspensys.com) -->
<!-- Editor: David -->
<!-- Last Update: 5/13/96 10:00am-->
<!-- Source File: timel2.html -->
<BR>


<CENTER><H1><B>Timeline</B></H1></CENTER>

<HR WIDTH=75% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center>



<FONT SIZE=4><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><B>1958</B><BR>
Aspen was founded as part of the University of Pittsburgh to
publish and use computer technology for storing and retrieving legal data.<P>

<B>1969</B><BR>

Aspen introduces System 50 -- the first full-text database that captures the laws of all 50 states.<P>

<B>1973</B><BR>
Aspen pioneers the full-service litigation support industry with Instant Index -- a tool to index daily court transcripts.<P>

<B>1974</B><BR>

Aspen establishes a document coding center for the Federal Trade Commission. We also win our first major commercial litigation support contract.<P>

<B>1977</B><BR>
Aspen begins operating the National Criminal Justice Reference Service for the Department of Justice, helping to establish our current status as the leading provider of clearinghouse services for the Federal government.<P>

<B>1986</B><BR>
Aspen introduces the first PC-based workstation for litigation support. The Aspen Litigation Workstation combines document searching, word processing, and local file management. <P>

<B>1987</B><BR>
Aspen establishes the National AIDS Clearinghouse for the 
U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.<P>

<B>1989</B><BR>
Aspen acquires Applied Management Sciences (AMS), enabling the corporation to offer data survey and analysis as well as business process reengineering. The AMS Computer-<BR>
Assisted Telephone Interviewing (CATI) Center provides Aspen's clients with a full range of computer-assisted survey services.<P>

<B>1992</B><BR>

Aspen develops bulletin board systems for several federally
sponsored information centers, thus initiating our provision of electronic dissemination services to the public. For Access ERIC (Educational Resources Information Center), Aspen also establishes electronic networking capabilities offered through a commercial online service vendor.<P>

<B>1993</B><BR>
Aspen becomes an employee-owned company. <P>

<B>1994</B><BR>
Aspen expands its electronic dissemination capabilities to
include new fax technologies and Internet services. We offer World Wide Web site development and other services through
our high-speed Internet connection.<P>

<B>1995</B><BR>
AspenView 2.0(R) is introduced. This image-enhanced document retrieval software package combines full-text and fielded searching capabilities, searchable annotations, and dynamic links to Windows applications.<P>

Aspen's Navigator(TM) is brought to the energy market, enabling organizations to track and integrate customer information for marketing, billing, and project management efforts.<P>

<B>1996</B><BR>
Aspen launches HousingLink(SM), a subscription-based World Wide Web service for housing and community development professionals.<P>


</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="http://www.aspensys.com/cgi/aspbtbr.map">
<IMG SRC="aspbtbr.gif" Border=0 ISMAP></CENTER></A>

<BR>



</BODY>
