<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>REBEL</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#3B17FF" VLINK="#FF0900">

<!-- System: Aspen Home Page -->
<!-- Author: Aspen Systems Corporation (www.aspensys.com) -->
<!-- Editor: Greg -->
<!-- Last Update: 5/8/96 2:00pm-->
<!-- Source File: rebel.html -->

<!-- Generation of PM publication page 1 -->


<IMG ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 SRC="asplogo.gif"><P><P>
<BR>

<FONT SIZE=7><B>REBEL&#153</B></FONT><BR>




<FONT SIZE=5><I>Reconciled Bills, Engineering, and Load Research Hourly End-Use Model</I></FONT><P><BR CLEAR=RIGHT><P><BR>







<HR>
<P>






<FONT SIZE=4>Aspen Systems Corporation,with recognized expertise in the field 
of load research, has now combined state-of-the-art 
engineering, statistical, and programming techniques to develop REBEL&#153, 
a load research hourly end-use model, that gives clients:
<P>

<!-- List Tag -->
<UL>
<LI>Low Cost; Due to  the Absence of Metering Requirements

<LI>Flexibility; Written for the Commercial Sector, but Easily
Modified for Residential

<LI>Proven Track Record; Successfully Applied in the Field
</UL>

<P>Aspen's Reconciled Bills, Engineering, and Load Research (REBEL&#153) hourly 
end-use model offers several advantages over other analytical designs, including 
maximum leverage of load research data, low cost due to the absence of metering 
requirements, the accuracy of on-site engineering data and local weather conditions, and 
intelligent engineering and statistical techniques that provide defensible results.

<P><BR>
<B>Market Position</B>
<P>
Aspen markets REBEL&#153 as a powerful tool used as part of our load research 
services, rather than as a stand-alone software kit available as a commodity on the open market. 
 Written in SAS&#174;, we license the uncompiled code to customers for their future use 
if desired, unlike some of our competitors.  REBEL&#153 is written for the 
commercial sector, but can be easily modified to perform residential evaluation as well.  Aspen 
is also in a position to market the services (sample design, data collection, 
preliminary analysis) that accompany REBEL&#153 analysis.
<P><BR>

<B>Results</B>
<P>
The software has already been successfully applied to a project for a major 
North-Eastern utility.
<P><BR>

<B>Data Input</B>
<P>
The model draws upon these data resources:  (1) premise level hourly load data 
from load research buildings; (2) on-site engineering data; (3) weather data; and (4) 
billing data.  REBEL&#153 can be configured to receive either billing data alone or load 
research data alone if only one or the other is available.
<P><BR>

<B>Data Output</B>
<P>
The core output of REBEL&#153 is hourly load by end-use, fuel type, day type, and 
month for each surveyed building and building type.  Annual EUIs are a byproduct of 
the developed load shapes.  The choice of end-uses, fuel type, and day types can 
be adjusted for a particular customer.  Our current configuration includes ten 
end-uses (lighting, water heating, cooking, refrigeration, office equipment, 
miscellaneous, outdoor lighting, ventilation, heating, and cooling), three fuel types (electricity, 
natural gas, and other fossil fuel), four day types (week day, peak day, Saturday, and 
Sunday), ten building types (warehouse, office, retail, restaurant, foodstore, school, 
college, hotel, hospital, and miscellaneous), and twelve months.
<P><BR>

<B>Internal Calculations</B>
<P>
The REBEL&#153 model employs a four step computational procedure.  First, 
engineering data for each building is applied to calculate hourly demand by end-use.  Second, 
end-use level results are reconciled with premise level data for load research buildings 
in the sample.  Third, the reconcilation is performed against billed data for 
non-load research buildings in the sample.  Fourth, the data is aggregated by building type 
based on the sample design to produce building type load shapes and EUIs.<P>



<B>For More Information Contact:</B>
<P>
Aspen Systems Corporation<BR>

Energy & Technology Services Division<BR>

962 Wayne Avenue, Suite 701<BR>

Silver Spring, MD  20910<BR>

<P>
<B>Telephone:</B>  (800) 638-2784     
<P>
<P><B>            Fax:</B>  (301) 495-8562</FONT>

</FONT><P>
