<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>End-Use Load Shapes</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<!-- System: Aspen Systems Corporation -->
<!-- Author: Aspen Systems Corporation (www.aspensys.com) -->
<!-- Editor: Greg -->
<!-- Last Update: 5/14/96  -->
<!-- Source File: load.html -->

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000" LINK="#3B17FF" VLINK="#FF0900">


<IMG align=left hspace=10 SRC="aspnbug3.gif">
<H2><A Name="load">End-Use Load Shapes From Appliance Saturation Survey Data</A></H2><P>


     <FONT SIZE=4>End-use load models that explain residential end-use 
hourly loads as functions of weather, building, appliance, and 
household characteristics were developed by Aspen as part of the 
EPRI-managed Missouri Data Transferability Project. 
 In most cases, these residential models can be applied to 
estimate end-use load shapes for any utility with available weather and 
appliance survey data.  In addition to providing accurate load shapes, 
these characteristics-based models meet the needs of utility 
marketing professionals.  The models can be used for marketing research 
and "what-if" analysis since the model variables explicitly account for 
the effects that housing and demographic characteristics have on 
appliance hourly energy use.  Knowing how different lifestyle and 
demographic characteristics affect energy use allows marketing analysts to 
perform economic analysis of the effects of marketing key end-use 
loads, identifying and targeting specific products to profitable segments.<P>

<IMG SRC="heater.gif"><BR>


<I>Water Heater Average Weekday Load Shapes for February</I>

<P>      In the Missouri project, econometric models that explain 
both the probability of an appliance being &quot;on,&quot; and the hourly load given 
that the appliance is &quot;on&quot; were 
developed for ten end-uses using end-use metered data, weather variables, and 
building, appliance, and household demographic and behavioral characteristics 
that were readily available from each utility's appliance saturation 
survey data. These models were then used to develop load shapes for five utilities 
by 
applying the models to each utility's appliance saturation survey 
and weather data. The resulting  load shapes revealed the differences 
in weather patterns, and housing, appliance, and 
demographic characteristics across the different service areas. For example, 
hourly loads were larger for those utilities with older appliance and 
housing stock and higher average occupancy levels.<P>




<IMG SRC="pump.gif"><BR>


<I>Heat Pump Predicted Average Weekday Load Shapes for August</I>



<P>      One of the most exciting features of this modeling approach is that 
it allows for intra-utility as well as inter-utility analysis. For 
instance, end-use load shapes can be developed for intra-utility 
service areas, market segments and combinations of service areas 
and segments. In conjunction with other projects and data sets, Aspen 
is continuing to refine the methodology and expand the applications of 
this important tool.
<P><B>For More Information</B><P>
<I>If you would like more information on potential applications of the 
models, please contact Dr. Thomas Yoder at (423) 482-2721.</I></FONT><P>


<A HREF = "jan1996.html#inthis"><IMG align=left border=0 hspace=0 vspace=5 SRC="redbar.gif"><BR clear=left>

