<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Market Research and Competition</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<!-- System: Aspen Systems Corporation -->
<!-- Author: Aspen Systems Corporation (www.aspensys.com) -->
<!-- Editor: Greg -->
<!-- Last Update: 5/14/96  -->
<!-- Source File: market.html -->

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#00000" LINK="#3B17FF" VLINK="#FF0900">


<IMG align=left hspace=10 SRC="aspnbug3.gif">


<H2>Market Research and Competition</A></H2><P>


     <FONT SIZE=4>What are customers buying?
What do customers perceive as a value-added service?  How 
should products and services be priced?  How can we identify and 
reach customers who are willing and able to buy?  How much do 
customers know about my competitors and their products and services?  (How 
much do I know about my competitors' products, services, and prices?)
<P>     In the era of deregulation and evolving competition in the 
utility industry, these are the types of questions many industry 
executives are asking. Of course, the first part 
of the challenge was substituting the word "customer" for "ratepayer." 
 Progress has been made.  Now we ask ourselves the above 
questions about what our "customers" want 
to buy, for an old axiom of marketing is to sell customers what they want 
to buy, not what we happen to have on the shelf to sell. Therefore, 
the challenge now becomes finding out about what our customers want 
to buy and how we can position ourselves to profitably sell 
these 
products and services to them. In an era of competition, utilities will 
have to aggressively research, bring to market, and price products 
and services that customers in very different segments will be looking for. 
 Many of these products and services have not yet even been thought of 
by utility planners, but will be defined by customers.
<P>     Utilities are therefore reinventing market research, and applying it in new applications.  
For example, recent market research- related projects which Aspen has been engaged in include: developing customer desired features of two-way communications systems to deliver rate information and manage customer loads, identify threats and opportunities resulting from customer consideration of on-site generation, analyzing customer  recognition and response to multi-media promotional campaigns, and developing approaches to analyze the profitability and return on investment of marketing selected loads to different customer segments.
	<P>

If your utility is not asking the above questions and performing the associated customer research, then beware, because your competitors, both within and outside the traditional utility industry, are!  In recognition of the importance of this type of research in the competitive era, Aspen has developed multidisciplinary teams specializing in the application of market research and marketing intelligence systems in the customer-driven utility of the future.<P>


<B>For More Information</B><P>


<I>Aspen's strategic market research teams stand ready to help utilities prepare 
for competition.  For more information, please contact Patrick McCarthy at 
(800) 638&#173;2784 or <!-- MailTo Tag -->
<A HREF="MAILTO:pmccarthy@aspensys.com">pmccarthy@aspensys.com</A>.</I></FONT><P>


<A HREF = "jan1996.html#inthis"><IMG align=left border=0 hspace=0 vspace=5 SRC="redbar.gif"><BR clear=left>

