<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Quality Data: An Important Product</TITLE></HEAD> 
<!-- System: Aspen Systems Corporation -->
<!-- Author: Aspen Systems Corporation (www.aspensys.com) -->
<!-- Editor: Linda -->
<!-- Last Update: 09/16/96  -->
<!-- Source File: QDProd.html -->
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<IMG align=left hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif">

<H2>Quality Data: An Important Product</H2>

<H3>Data Collection</H3>
<B><FONT SIZE=4><P>Data are collected by many health care organizations from hospitals to physician group practices, and by a wide variety of health care-related entities such as State data organizations and pharmaceutical companies. Hospitals and other health care providers collect clinical and administrative data to assess patient outcomes, identify processes for improvement, and assist in managerial decisionmaking and planning. State data organizations collect data for hospital rate setting, public health planning and assessment, and business and labor health care cost control. Recently, pharmaceutical companies have produced disease management protocols. They are now collecting clinical data to monitor and assess patient outcomes under the disease management protocols.</P></FONT></B>


<H3>The Importance of <A HREF="dqplan.html">Data Quality</A></H3>
<P>It is important to recognize that collecting data is not an end in itself. Assuring and assessing the quality of the data is part of the data collection process, but it is frequently overlooked by those who generate and collect data. The integrity and credibility of a database is dependent on the reliability, validity, and completeness of the data collected. Increasingly, organizations that collect data are realizing that objective data validation studies are needed to assure the soundness of the conclusions and the decisionmaking that results from their data collection and analysis.</P>


<H3>Assessing Data Quality</H3>
<P>Aspen's Health Information Services division has conducted data validation studies for a variety of organizations, including the Maryland and Connecticut State data agencies, the Health Care Financing Administration, and a number of hospitals and health maintenance organizations. </P>

<P>Aspen has designed studies that assess validity, accuracy, and reliability of coded or abstracted data elements, as well as the validity of diagnosis-related groups. Aspen's methodology includes a scientific sample selection that meets the unique goals of each study and uses statistical analysis to validate the results. Aspen's data collection staff are credentialed health information management professionals and certified coding specialists whose work is subject to rigorous quality controls throughout every project.</P>

<P>Aspen understands the importance of quality data as an organization's most significant product, and Aspen's methodology for assessing the quality of an organization's data assures that the significance of the product is suitably recognized.</P>

<P>See the related articles in this issue about <A HREF="surveys.html">survey design</A> and <A HREF="dqstudy.html">data quality studies</A>.</P>

<P><I>For more information about Aspen's services, contact Ben Betzer at 1-800-395-5055.</I><P>

<br>
<center>
<font size=4>
<b><a href="hcinfo.html">Next Article</a> | 
Previous Article | 
<a href="sum1996.html#inthis">Contents of Summer 1996 Issue</a><BR>
<a href="hismain.html">HIS FOCUS Home Page</a></b></font></center>
<BR><BR>

