<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Surveys? Call Aspen</TITLE></HEAD> 
<!-- System: Aspen Systems Corporation -->
<!-- Author: Aspen Systems Corporation (www.aspensys.com) -->
<!-- Editor: Linda -->
<!-- Last Update: 09/16/96  -->
<!-- Source File: surveys.html -->
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<IMG align=left hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif">

<H2>Surveys? Call Aspen . . . One of the Services That Makes Aspen Unique</H2>

<H3>Survey Design and Implementation</H3>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><P>The Survey and Evaluation Services (SES) Division of Aspen has been conducting multiple instrument surveys, using computer-assisted telephone interviewing (CATI) and computer-assisted data entry (CADE) systems for over 15 years. Our approach to designing a survey instrument begins with a definition of the objectives of the survey and a detailed plan describing exactly how the variables will be measured. The identification of key informants is the first step in planning the data collection process. We also conduct a comprehensive literature review of survey instruments.</P></B></FONT>

<H3>Using Computers</H3>
<P>Aspen incorporates the development of software for laptop computer-assisted data entry, particularly for medical record abstractors. Computer-assisted data entry provides an opportunity to create and edit the data set simultaneously, thereby eliminating the need for retrospective editing or repeat data collection.</P>



<H3>Establishing the Methodology</H3>
<P>Aspen pretests the survey with a small group of appropriate individuals to review the content and format of the instruments, tests the procedures to be used during the survey, then tests the data that will be stored by the CATI or CADE systems.</P>

<P>Sampling statisticians design and implement the study sampling plan. Well-established procedures are used to recruit and train interviewers, and medical record abstractors are trained in the use of computer-assisted data entry. </P>

<H3>Maintaining Quality</H3>
<P>Data storage, tabulation and analysis of study data, data transmission, and documentation are subjected to the most stringent quality control procedures to ensure quality data management. Interviews and record reviews are coded directly into either CATI or CADE systems whenever possible, with a random sample from each batch reviewed by a supervisor. The CATI system will automatically track and log all calls.</P>

<H3>Assuring Confidentiality</H3>
<P>The data and information handled by SES have included Privacy Act data, government financial data, technical research data, and classified military data. SES confidentiality provisions include instructing all individuals involved in a study about the confidentiality of the responses, then providing signed confidentiality statements as required. Working files with identifiers are maintained on the computer network, thereby limiting access to the data. Aspen's SES Division also incorporates the use of automated data processing security programs and software that are in compliance with government and industry security standards.</P>

<P><I>For more information about the Survey and Evaluation Services (SES) Division, contact Meryl Bloomrosen at 1-800-395-5055.</I></P>

<br>
