<HEAD><TITLE>Data Quality Studies</TITLE></HEAD> 
<!-- System: Aspen Systems Corporation -->
<!-- Author: Aspen Systems Corporation (www.aspensys.com) -->
<!-- Editor: Linda -->
<!-- Last Update: 09/16/96  -->
<!-- Source File: dqstudy.html -->
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<IMG align=left hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif">

<H2>Data Quality Studies</H2>

<H3>Objectives</H3>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><P>There are a number of issues to be considered in performing a <a href="dataqual.html">data quality study</a>. The first consideration is the objective of the study. For example, one data quality study may be initiated to assess the accuracy of coded and abstracted data that are submitted for third party reimbursement by a health care provider, while another study may assess coded and abstracted data that are used by a health care provider for quality improvement, service or facility planning, or for medical effectiveness research. Another study may assess the accuracy of a database that is used for comparative analyses that result in some kind of public disclosure or policy that affects all the health care providers in a State.</P></B></FONT>

<P>Most data quality studies are performed by comparing the original coded and abstracted data collected from the source document (most frequently a health record) with the same data that have been recoded and reabstracted, usually by another data abstractor who is considered to be objective and is preferably an expert. </P>

<P>The ultimate objective of the data quality study and the size of the database to be assessed will help determine the study size, the sampling methodology to be used, and whether clinical, demographic, or billing data elements are assessed.</P>

 
<H3>Sampling Methodology</H3>
<P>The sampling methodology is significant in that it will determine whether the results of the data quality assessment can be reported as descriptive findings, or as individual accuracy rates. For example, if a random sample of a randomly chosen number of health records is selected (such as 100 inpatient records), the only conclusions that could be drawn from the assessment would be descriptive. For example, the assessment might say, "Of the 100 records reabstracted or recoded, 10 records or 10% of the records had errors."</P>

<P>If the study objective is to determine the accuracy of all billing data submitted by a health care provider to Medicare, or to determine the accuracy of coding myocardial infarctions in all hospitals that submit coded data to a statewide database, the sample would need to be statistically determined in order to calculate accuracy rates for the specified populations. That is, to calculate a coding accuracy rate, the selected sample would need to be statistically determined as a random sample, based on the total population. The study results could then state, for example, "Of all bills submitted, the accuracy rate for coding the principal diagnosis was 87% &#177 3.2%."</P>


<H3>Defining Data Quality</H3>

<P>Another important issue in conducting a data quality study involves defining what data quality means according to the objectives of the study. Usually data quality means accuracy. However, accuracy implies not only the attribute of correctness, but also completeness, consistency, and validity. </P>

<P>The methodology for conducting a data quality study should describe how each attribute of quality is to be assessed for each of the coded data elements and the abstracted data elements. Data element definitions used in the original data collection should also be carefully followed in the data quality study. 
</P>


<P><I>For more information about how Aspen can help you with a data quality study, call Zoe Metcalf at 
1-800-395-5055.</I></P>

<br>
