<title>Data Quality Plans: Key Components</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Data Quality Plans: Key Components</H2>
<H3>In our last issue, we talked about the benefits of performing routine data quality reviews in your facility to assess and improve the quality of data being collected. We would like to now discuss the key components of a <A HREF = "dataqual.html">data quality plan</A> and how you can design and implement your own. This issue will be addressed over a series of articles during 1996.</H3>

There are several key components in a total data quality plan: coder development and training, coding policies and guidelines, data quality reviews, physician education, and information management. Here is a brief look at each of these areas and how they fit into a total data quality plan for your facility.<P>

<H3>Coder Development and Training</H3>
How much time do you spend developing and training your coding staff? How in tune is your coding staff with their role in the health care delivery system? Often, coders are well versed in their own tasks and the tasks of their department, but they lack basic knowledge of what happens after they have completed their job functions.<P>

Will your facility support the development of an in-house education and in-service program to ensure that the coding staff has access to the wealth of clinical information that is available? Educated coders make educated coding decisions that will have positive long-term effects on your facility's overall data quality.<P>

<H3>Coding Policies and Guidelines</H3>
The first question to ask about coding policies and guidelines is: "Do you have any?" If you do, then you must ask the following questions: When was the last time you updated your policy and procedure manual? Does each coding staff member have access to the manual and provide input into its contents? Do you follow nationally recognized coding guidelines such as those found in Coding Clinic and CPT Assistant, as well as your own facility-specific guidelines? Coding guidelines, developed with input from coders, coding references, and clinical staff, are key to the execution of an effective data quality plan.

<H3>Data Quality Reviews</H3>
Data quality reviews allow you to assess medical record documentation, physician education needs, and the quality and relevance of coding practices. As part of an overall data quality plan, routine random and focused reviews provide valuable information that will help direct your educational efforts.<P>

The key to effective data quality is feedback. How will you direct education and re-education efforts when needs are identified during review? How will findings be incorporated into your coding policies and guidelines?  A data quality review in a vacuum benefits no one.<P>

<H3>Physician Education</H3>
A certain percentage of the data quality issues identified result from a lack of physician understanding of the coder's needs. Obtaining medical staff buy-in for your data quality improvement efforts is very important. Developing and maintaining lines of communication with the medical staff will give you access to one of your most valuable resources.<P>

<H3>Information Management</H3>
The coordination of information dissemination in your facility is an important issue. Who is responsible for processing requests for clinical information? What is the role of the health information management (HIM) professional in your facility in this key area? Frequently, two or more people may request similar information from different sources. At times, this may result in two different interpretations of the same clinical data, resulting in questions of data integrity. As a HIM professional, you can assess user needs and help focus clinical data extraction efforts.<P>

Working with your facility's information services personnel, you can emphasize your expertise in clinical data collection and evaluation. How clinical data will be displayed as information and disseminated throughout the organization is a key component of your clinical data quality plan.<P>

<H3>Putting It All Together</H3>
You all will be asking yourselves when you will find the time to develop and implement a data quality plan.  In the changing health environment, with managed health plans scrutinizing clinical data, facilities can no longer put off looking at the quality of their clinical data and making plans for the future.  An investment in data quality in the short term will reap long-term benefits for all members of the health care team.<P>

A health information management firm such as Aspen Systems Corporation can assist you in the development and execution of a data quality plan, providing services ranging from a single data quality review to a complete evaluation of your current data quality efforts and recommendations for improvement in all component areas. Quality data is the foundation of health care services, allowing insurers, consumers, and regulatory agencies to assess the quality of care and services and make informed decisions regarding health care consumption. Start contributing now to your facility's future success through the development and implementation of a data quality plan.<P>

<I>For more information, contact Ms. Zoe Metcalf at (800) 395-5055.</I><P>

