<title>Focus On: ICD-9-CM November Meeting</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2><A HREF = "focus97.html">FOCUS ON</A>: ICD-9-CM Coordination and Maintenance Committee November Meeting</H2>
<H3>The ICD-9-CM Coordination and Maintenance Committee met in Washington, D.C., on November 30, 1995, to discuss proposals for the 1997 fiscal year. The comment period for all proposed code changes, deletions, and additions discussed at both the May and November meetings ended in mid-January. Final recommendations will be forwarded to the Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA) in February.</H3>

Several physicians representing various specialty medical societies were on hand to give detailed presentations of proposed additions and/or changes to pediatric urological codes, mental health codes, and child and adult abuse codes, as well as to discuss the addition of one or more V-codes for patients with a terminal illness who are admitted to the acute care setting for "palliative" care in their end-of-life stage.<P>

New codes were proposed for the insertion of noncoronary stent(s), the coding of bypass grafts using arteries other than the mammary artery, the performance of endometrial ablation, and pancreatic islet cell transplantation. Multiple changes to the procedure section were introduced regarding the performance of various procedures via laparoscopic approach. The bulk of these changes were recommended in the Female Genital section, specifically relating to procedures performed for ovarian and fallopian tube conditions.<P>

In addition to the diagnosis codes recommended during the physician presentations, other recommendations include adding a code for Factitious Disorder by Proxy (Munchausen Syndrome by Proxy), a specific code identifying fetal alcohol syndrome, an addition to the postoperative complication codes to identify infected and noninfected seromas, and codes to identify mitochondrial chromosomal abnormalities. Codes were also proposed to address disseminated superficial actinic porokeratosis (DSAP) and pruritic urticarial papules and plaques of pregnancy (PUPPP), as presented by the American Academy of Dermatology.<P>

An additional presentation was made on the proposed ICD-10 Procedures Coding System. 3M Healthcare has almost completed the design of the new system and is prepared to release it for phase II of its 3-year HCFA contract in March 1996. Year Two of the contract will involve testing the new system in the field and at 3M, as well as receiving and considering comments from health care organizations providing beta testing. During Year Three, HCFA will contract with an independent evaluator to assess the proposed software and its efficacy in the field.<P> 

Finally, announcements were made regarding staffing, and to address changes for the Coordination and Maintenance Committee members. Sue Meads has resigned her position as cochair of the committee, replaced by Donna Pickett, formerly with the American Hospital Association and <I>Coding Clinic.</I> The new mailing address for comments and suggestions regarding potential coding changes is:<P>

<DL><DT> <B>Health Care Financing Administration</B>
<DT> BPD, OHP, Division of Prospective Payment
<DT> Mail Stop C5-06-27
<DT> 7500 Security Boulevard
<DT> Baltimore, MD 21244-1850
<DT> Fax: (410) 786-0594
</DL>

You can also contact the following committee members directly:<P>

<DL><DT> <B>Patricia Brooks</B>
<DT> Phone: (410) 786-5318
<DT> E-mail: <a href=mailto:pbrooks@hcfa.gov><B>pbrooks@hcfa.gov</B></a><P>
<DT> <B>Ann Fagan</B>
<DT> Phone: (410) 786-5662
<DT> E-mail: <a href=mailto:afagan@hcfa.gov><B>afagan@hcfa.gov</B></a><P>
<DT> <B>Amy Gruber</B>
<DT> Phone: (410) 786-1542
<DT> E-mail: <a href=mailto:agruber@hcfa.gov><B>agruber@hcfa.gov</B></a><P>
</DL>

<I>For more information on the ICD-10 Procedures Coding System, or to arrange an educational session for physicians and allied health professionals, contact Aspen Systems Corporation, Health Information Services at (800) 395-5055.</I><P>

