<title>Data Quality Studies: Some Commonly Asked Questions</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left 
hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Data Quality Studies: Some Commonly Asked 
Questions</H2>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>As the health information needs of our Nation change, there is 
increased attention on the availability of high quality information. Health care 
organizations striving to meet the challenges of generating and maintaining high quality 
data are increasingly turning to <A HREF = "chime.html">health information data quality studies</A> for help.<P>
Below are answers to some commonly asked questions about health information data 
quality studies and some facts on how they can benefit a health care 
organization.</B></FONT><P>

<H3>What is a <A HREF = "dqplan.html">data quality study?</A></H3> 

A typical health information data quality study involves either the concurrent or 
retrospective review of data maintained in a sample of an organization's medical records 
or claims. The process determines the caliber of administrative and/or clinical 
information maintained in an organization's medical records or financial/billing systems. 
The study can be conducted prior to the billing function, or after, depending on the 
specific facility goals.<P>

<H3>Why do a data quality study?</H3>

A data quality study will give managers valuable information about the reliability, 
validity, completeness, timeliness, and/or accessibility of the clinical and administrative 
data an organization maintains. Sometimes studies are undertaken because of noted 
changes in a facility's case mix, revenue, or accounts receivable.<P>

<H3>Why is this important?</H3>

Health care managers make decisions. Some of those decisions are based on information 
that evolves around the administrative and clinical data of a specific patient. Others are 
based on trends in administrative or clinical data. Either way, if health care managers 
cannot be sure whether the data on which they are basing a decision is sound, the decision 
made may not be the best one for an organization.
Furthermore, since much of a health care organization's reimbursement is based on 
clinical and financial data submitted to payers, the submission of accurate, timely, and 
complete information to those payers assures optimal reimbursement.<P>

<H3>What will the results of the data quality study tell an organization?</H3>

Depending on the particular goals of the study and the kinds of data examined, the study 
can provide an organization with valuable information on the consistency of similar kinds 
of data, on whether or not data are measuring what they intend to measure, or if all the 
data that should be present are available. In particular, depending on how samples of 
records or claims are selected, the results of a data quality study can allow the facility to 
determine the level of accuracy for all records and claims.<P>

<H3>Who should perform a health information data  quality study?</H3>

Either trained coders from the health information services department of an organization 
or outside consultants can perform the study. Although there are advantages to having an 
organization's personnel perform the study, having external, unbiased professionals 
perform the study has advantages as well. A data quality study performed by a health 
information management firm such as <A HREF = 
"http://www.aspensys.com/"><B>Aspen Systems Corporation</B></A> offers detailed, 
comprehensive information on the status of the organization's data as well as specific 
recommendations on how to improve the data, its collection process, and its usability. 
With this information, managers can have confidence that their data will not only 
optimize reimbursement for their organization, but will help them make better, more 
informed decisions. Organizations are well advised to select their sample of records or 
claims for review, according to appropriate sampling techniques. Be sure to define how 
accuracy rates will be determined.<P>

<I>For more information, contact <B>Linda Frey</B> at (800) 395-5055.</I><P>

