<H3>Ophthalmic Ofloxacin -- New Indication</H3><P>The FDA has approved ofloxacin ophthalmic 0.3% solution (Allergan's <I>Ocuflox</I>) for the treatment of corneal ulcers. <I>Ocuflox</I> is currently indicated for the treatment of bacterial conjunctivitis.</P><H3>Allopurinol Sodium Injection -- New Dose Form</H3><P>Glaxo Wellcome's <I>Zyloprim</I> (allopurinol sodium equiv 500 mg base/vial) is approved for management of cancer patients whose therapy causes uric acid levels to rise and who cannot tolerate oral <I>Zyloprim</I>.</P><H2>Recommended for Approval</H2><H3>Irinotecan</H3><P>An FDA advisory committee recommended accelerated approval of irinotecan (CPT-11; Pharmacia & Upjohn's <I>Camptosar</I>) for second-line treatment of patients with metastatic carcinoma of  the colon or rectum whose cancer has recurred or progressed following a 5-fluorouracil-based regimen.</P><H3>Nevirapine</H3><P>Accelerated approval has been recommended by the FDA's Antiviral Drugs Advisory Committee for <I>Viramune</I> (nevirapine) by Boehringer-Ingelheim for treatment of HIV infection. If approved, <I>Viramune</I> will be the first marketed non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor.</P><H3>Alteplase -- New Indication Recommended</H3><P>The FDA's Peripheral and CNS Drugs Advisory Committee has recommended approval for Genentech's <I>Activase</I> (alteplase; tPA) for treatment of acute ischemic stroke within 3 hours of symptoms if patient does not show intracranial bleeding on computed tomography scan. If approved, alteplase will be the first drug indicated for treatment of ischemic stroke.</P><H3>Etoposide Phosphate IV (<I>Etopophos</I> by Bristol-Myers Squibb) -- Approved</H3><P>Etoposide phosphate IV is indicated for treatment of small-cell lung cancer and first-line and refractory testicular tumors. Its greater solubility than <I>VePesid</I> (etoposide) means it can be given in smaller volumes of saline (e.g., 400 ml).</P></TD><TD><H2>New Drugs</H2><H3>Adapalene (<I>Differin</I> by Galderma)</H3><P>Adapalene, a retinoid-like compound, is approved for the treatment of acne vulgaris. Treatment results are seen in 8 to 12 weeks compared with 2 to 6 weeks for Ortho's<I> Retin-A</I> (tretinoin) or 4 weeks for Allergan's <I>Azelex</I> (azelaic acid 20% cream). Unlike these treatments, <I>Differin</I> does not carry a warning of hypopigmentation. <I>Differin</I>'s price will be comparable to that of <I>Retin-A</I> and will be available as a once-daily 0.1% solution and gel.</P><H3>Albendazole (<I>Albenza</I> by SmithKline Beecham)</H3><P><I>Albendazole</I> is approved for treatment of hydatid cyst disease of the liver, lung, and peritoneum due to dog tapeworm larvae <I>Echinococcus granulosis</I> and neurocysticercosis due to pork tapeworm larvae <I>Taenia solium</I>. Dosing for hydatid is 400 mg twice daily for 3 cycles of 28 days followed by a 14-day drug-free interval after each cycle. For neurocysticercosis, recommended dosing is 400 mg twice daily for 8 to 30 days.</P><H3>Corticorellin Ovine Triflutate IV (<I>Acthrel</I> by Ferrin Labs)</H3><P><I>Acthrel</I> is approved for use in differentiating pituitary and ectopic production of ACTH in patients with ACTH-dependent Cushing's syndrome. <I>Acthrel</I> has greater sensitivity and specificity than older diagnostics such as an insulin shock test and dexamethasone suppression tests.</P><H3>Latanoprost (<I>Xalatan</I> by Pharmacia & Upjohn)</H3><P>The FDA-approved <I>Xalatan</I> opthalmic solution for the treatment of open-angle glaucoma and ocular hypertension in patients who are either intolerant of or insufficiently responsive to other intraocular pressure-lowering medications. As a once-daily treatment, <I>Xalatan</I> showed reductions similar to twice-daily treatment with timolol in intraocular pressure.</P><H3>Topotecan (<I>Hycamtin</I> by SmithKline Beecham)</H3><P><I>Hycamtin</I> has received FDA approval for treatment of ovarian cancer that has not responded to other treatments. A member of the camptothecin drug class, topotecan stops tumor growth by inhibiting essential enzymes. The response rate for <I>Hycamtin</I> is relatively similar to that of paclitaxel (Bristol-Myers Squibb's <I>Taxol</I>).</P><br><center><font size=4><b>Next Article | <a href="dqstudy.html">Previous Article</a> | <a href="sum1996.html#inthis">Contents of Summer 1996 Issue</a><BR><a href="hismain.html">HIS FOCUS Home Page</a></b></font></center><BR><BR></BODY> </HTML> 
