<title>Aspen's Contract Management Services: Creating "Win-Win" Solutions</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Aspen's Contract Management Services:<BR>Creating "Win-Win" Solutions</H2><BR clear=left><BR>

<H3>Why Choose Contract Management Services?</H3>
<A HREF = "contract.html"><B>Contract management services</B></A> give a health care facility access to the best of two worlds -- experienced and innovative managers to direct day-to-day departmental operations onsite, and the resources and technical expertise of a nationally recognized health care information services firm, such as Aspen Systems Corporation, to provide the analytical and evaluative services that so often get "lost in the shuffle" of hospital administration. Contract management services are clearly a viable option for health information management (HIM) departments in today's health care environment. HIM managers are looking for creative support and direction. Hospital administrators want a HIM department that is cost-effective, efficient, respected, and responsive to the diverse clinical and financial needs of its customers. Departmental employees want to see and participate in improvement efforts and not just "be improved." Can these varied outcomes be achieved in a positive and progressive way for all players? Aspen has the answer, and the answer is: Yes!<P>

<H3>Contract Management Case Study</H3>
St. Anywhere Hospital's Medical Record Services Department has developed a chronic, debilitating condition: it forgot to move into the 1990's! The director, in place for many years, couldn't understand what all the fuss was about when the American Medical Record Association changed its name to American Health Information Management Association! Although respected by peers and colleagues, this director was not well known for an innovative approach to health information management. This director did not encourage employees to interact with their "customers," contributing to a poor internal and external department image. Performance evaluations were long overdue and were cursory at best when delivered. Employees appeared to be in a rut, with no motivational activities, no continuing education, and no chance for upward mobility. Everything remained the same.<P>

Hospital administrators despaired over decreasing receivables and lack of improvements in the Medical Record Services Department's processes and outputs. Coding was routinely 10 to 20 days behind. It seemed that no one in the department understood the intertwining of clinical and financial information that is necessary in today's competitive health care market.  Even the purchase of automated equipment several years ago failed to produce expected efficiencies; it appeared that many processes continued to be carried out manually.<P>

<H3>Aspen's Contract Management Services</H3>
During negotiations, Aspen put everyone at ease about the decision to opt for contract management services. Aspen worked with hospital administrators to clearly define the expected benefits and outcomes of a contract management engagement. Together, they focused on the two key areas through which Aspen could bring about the "win-win" solution everyone sought to achieve. To call this "experiment" a success, Aspen would have to meet mandated performance standards and provide the hospital with access to our full complement of technical expertise.<P>

<H3>Meet Mandated Performance Standards</H3>
After obtaining approval, Aspen placed an extremely qualified and experienced medical records director at St. Anywhere. The director evaluated work flow and work processes. Input was solicited from all employees. Hard work, dedication, and a willingness to participate in proposed improvements resulted in a 37-percent reduction in backlogs in the department. Evaluation of services provided by outside vendors yielded a significant problem with overbilling and steps were taken to correct the situation. Finally, the director provided deserving employees with career advancement possibilities, promoting one long-term employee to a supervisory position. Job descriptions were streamlined and updated. Performance evaluations were brought up to date, and were meaningful and objective, with goal-setting opportunities and recognition of abilities. Staff members saw that efforts to improve would be well worth the time and effort. As staff began to feel better about their environment, customer service and customer perception of the department improved. All employees were trained on the department's commercial medical records abstracting system. Employees could now run ad hoc reports to aid in job performance. Responsibility and ownership, for the job and the output, were readily apparent.<P>

<H3>Provide Access to the Full Complement of Technical Expertise</H3>
An Aspen contract management engagement involves more than just the placement of a qualified director or other management personnel; our value-added services make it an extremely attractive and cost-effective option for hospitals. Aspen's information systems personnel were able to help St. Anywhere develop a fully functional interface between the department's clinical system and the hospital's financial system. Additionally, they were instrumental in the development of a 5-year Information Resources Management Strategic Plan for St. Anywhere prior to the 1995 JCAHO survey. Because Aspen is not affiliated with any commercial hardware or software vendors, hospital administrators felt comfortable that access to Aspen's highly specialized technical expertise and advice would not come with additional product purchase proposals.<P>

<H3>. . . And Then What Happened?</H3>
Now well into its second year under Aspen's contract management services, the department is moving towards updating and revising its departmental policies and procedures and continuing to further employee training and development. Data quality studies are also scheduled to commence shortly, which will more specifically assess current coding expertise and skills and enable Aspen to develop training programs targeted to unique facility needs.<P>

<H3>Where Do We Go From Here?</H3>
The case study provided is an actual account of a current contract management engagement, perhaps in a facility very much like your own. If you feel unable to meet and support your facility's mission and goals with a responsive, cutting-edge health information management initiative, why not investigate Aspen's contract management service offerings? Together, we can create a "win-win" solution for your health care organization!<P>

<I>For more information, contact Ms. Barbara Stevens at (800) 395-5055.</I><P>

