<title>Are You Ready for APGs?</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Are You Ready for APGs?</H2>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>Hospitals and other health care facilities have experienced numerous changes over the years as Congress and <A HREF = "hcfapubs.html">Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA)</A> have enacted laws and regulations governing payment for health care services provided to Federal beneficiaries. The data reporting requirements and information management complexities facing physicians, hospitals, and other health care providers in the 1990's are well recognized. In particular, recordkeeping and data reporting requirements to meet the demands of insurers, attorneys, third-party payers, patients, and Federal and State government agencies have increased. And now, payment by Ambulatory Payment Groups (APGs) is expected.</B></FONT><P>

Facilities currently handle ambulatory coding in a variety of ways. In some cases, hospitals have centralized coding for outpatients (emergency room/department; outpatient ancillary services [laboratory, radiology]; outpatient clinics; and ambulatory surgery). Typically, when coding is centralized, it is often performed in the medical records or billing departments. When coding is entirely decentralized, it is performed by each outpatient care area. If coding is partially decentralized, the medical records department may be responsible for emergency room/department and ambulatory surgery coding, with the outpatient clinics and ancillary service areas responsible for their own coding. In addition, when hospitals have multiple outpatient clinics, it is often common for each clinic (i.e., internal medicine, pediatrics, OB/GYN) to perform its own coding. In these cases, the number of areas with responsibility for coding frequently depends on the number of separately administered clinics.<P>

The following questions need to be answered by health care facilities preparing for APGs:<P>

<UL><LI>Who is performing outpatient coding?
<LI>What is the volume of cases coded by each outpatient area?
<LI>What source documents are used (medical records; checklists)?
<LI>When are signs or symptoms coded?
<LI>When are V codes used?
<LI>What kinds of coding guidelines are used?
<LI>Who issues these guidelines?
<LI>How many diagnoses and procedures are coded?
<LI>What rules are used to determine the sequencing of these codes?
<LI>What are the qualifications of outpatient coders?
<LI>What kind of training is available?
<LI>What types of quality controls are used to measure coding accuracy?
</UL>

Clearly, outpatient areas should identify resources, such as the code books used for coding. The ease with which the books are updated should also be explored. Sometimes outpatient service units do not use any code books at all. They use preprinted (coded) encounter forms or have outdated code books. Often encoders or other computerized software are used to support coding; these should be identified as well. Sometimes, outpatient coding is performed as a byproduct of the chargemaster function. If so, the chargemaster must be reviewed annually for accuracy and completeness. There should also be a procedure for uniform annual updating of all coding books with official errata or addendum.<P>

It is by no means trivial to ask what is state of the art in outpatient coding. Once descriptive information about the coding process is collected and analyzed, facilities will be in a better position to look at alternatives to the current decentralized approaches. One option is to centralize some or all of the coding activities under one department. In this case, the staff's ability and qualifications to handle additional activity needs to be explored. Resources (budget considerations; training; work space; quality assurance/control mechanisms) required to appropriately address these issues should not be underestimated. Institutional politics, medical staff relationships, and administrative policies and procedures will undoubtedly also need to be considered. It may also be necessary for facilities to re-evaluate the various positions, their formal position descriptions, salary classifications, and other human resource-related issues in their assessment process.<P>

<I>For more information on how to prepare for APGs and assessment of coding accuracy, contact Meryl Bloomrosen, <a href=mailto:mbloomrosen@aspensys.com><B>mbloomrosen@aspensys.com,</B></a> phone: (800) 395-5055.</I><P> 

<br><center><font size=4><b><a href="intronet.html">Next Article</a> | Previous Article | <a href="fall1995.html#inthis">Contents of Fall 1995 Issue</a> | <a href="hismain.html">HIS FOCUS Home Page</a></b></font></center><BR><BR>

