<title>Rx For Success: An Introduction to the Internet</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>RX For Success: An Introduction to the <A HREF = "shortcop3.html#onweb">Internet</A></H2>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>Health care managers use a variety of information referral sources to get answers to common every-day questions that affect their jobs and operations. The abundance of information can be overwhelming with hundreds of journals, reference books, specialty guides, and inservice training courses. If only there was one place we could all go to get the exact information we needed. With the rapid expansion of the information superhighway with literally thousands of new roads and bridges, a one-stop shopping mall is evolving that can provide health care managers with the tools and information they need on virtually any subject area: the Internet.</B></FONT><P>

However, this new technology also brings with it a certain amount of confusion and intimidation. As more and more health care managers are beginning to "get their feet wet" (surfing the net), we at Aspen thought it appropriate to take what we have learned of this vast information resource and pass it along in a three part article designed to introduce our readers to some common protocols, definitions, and road maps to assist you in your early travel adventures.<P>

Evolving from a small group of government computer hubs over 30 years ago, the Internet has expanded into a global supernetwork of services and information sources. While the Internet owes much of its recent glory to online pop culture icons like the Rolling Stones and die-hard Trekkies, health care managers, faculty, students, and executives will find more serious fare on the system. If you can find a local and cost-effective entry point to jump on, you will discover a wealth of health care information just a few keystrokes away. But let's take this journey one step at a time. First we'll offer a brief history of the Internet, with some personal insights and a few tips for first-time users.<P>

As the Internet grew, it developed its own culture and its own language. If you thought GUI, WYSIWYG, and SCSI were tough to decipher, wait until you try to interpret standard Internet road signs. We will provide a brief guide that will help demystify some of the most common terms in part two of our article. In part three of the Internet article, we'll discuss some specific stopping points for health care managers and staff as well as look at some of the Internet's social grace conventions, called "netiquette"-- a must for first time users.<P>

<H3>Some History</H3>

<IMG Align=Left hspace=6 SRC="workstn.gif">The Internet offers just about everyone unparalleled access to information on just about everything from anywhere in the world. But just what is the Internet about and how do you get a freeway pass? First of all, the Internet doesn't really exist in any one place. Instead, it is a loosely linked network of major computer hubs that crisscross the globe. It really got its start in the middle of the Cold War, when the Department of Defense sought to develop a communications system it could rely on if other systems were damaged. This need, coupled with the emerging technology that allowed computers of all types to "talk" with one another over phone lines, gave birth in the 1960's to what is now called the Internet.<P>

The Internet quickly gained favor with government researchers who recognized the benefits of exchanging information electronically. With the National Science Foundation in the lead, the Internet became a "telecommunications backbone" to enhance research and education through open data exchange. The tremendous surge in the availability and use of personal computers really spurred the Internet's growth in popularity in the 1990's. As modem-equipped PCs became common features at home and at work, users looked for ways to use this new technology to improve and enhance their lives. Commercial on-line services (Prodigy, CompuServe, America Online, and others) gained large popularity, providing millions of people from all walks of life with new information, ideas, and opportunities within a few keystrokes.<P>

<A HREF = "http://www.aspensys.com/"><IMG Align=Right border=0 SRC="aspnhome.gif"></A>Today the Internet offers just about everything from census data, government reports, and congressional bills to music reviews, on-line chats, and David Letterman fan clubs. For many corporations the Internet is becoming a primary means of communication with employees and customers via electronic mail. (Aspen's Home Page, which will be discussed in more detail in part two, can be found at the following Internet address, <A HREF = "http://www.aspensys.com/"><B>http://www.aspensys.com</B></A>) Health information managers can find their own bulletin board and information road stop at the Health Information Management-List service (HIM-L). Other places of interest to the health care community include numerous universities, the National Library of Medicine, the National Institutes of Health, and the Health Sciences Library. But just as in a library, it is easy to get lost and frustrated on the Internet if you do not know what you want or where to look. In the meantime, read as much as you can and look for advertisements for "front-ends" for your PC that will help you get to where you are going. Graphical interfaces, such as Mosaic (available in most computer stores) and World Wide Web Browser (offered free to Prodigy members), will help you navigate the Internet easily.<P>

<br><center><font size=4><b><a href="focus97.html">Next Article</a> | <a href="areyou.html">Previous Article</a> | <a href="fall1995.html#inthis">Contents of Fall 1995 Issue</a> | <a href="hismain.html">HIS FOCUS Home Page</a></b></font></center><BR><BR>

