<title>FOCUS ON: ICD-9-CM Coordination and Maintenance Committee</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2><A HREF = "novmtg.html">FOCUS ON</A>: ICD-9-CM Coordination and Maintenance Committee May Meeting</H2>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>The <A HREF = "vcodes.html">ICD-9-CM</A> Coordination and Maintenance Committee met in Washington, DC on May 5, 1995 to discuss proposals for the 1997 Fiscal year. The FY 1996 recommendations have already been finalized and will be published in early June in the Federal Register.</B></FONT><P>

A detailed presentation of laparoscopic appendectomies preceded the proposal for new codes for this procedure. A fourth digit would be added to the present code to distinguish the laparoscopic approach. 47.01 & 47.11 for open appendectomy and 47.02 & 47.12 for laparoscopic appendectomy. This was the only new procedure presented.<P>

There were several diagnosis additions and revisions proposed. Two conditions were presented by the American Academy of Dermatology. The first was a new code for disseminated superficial actinic poro-keratosis (DSAP), often a precursor to squamous cell skin cancer, was proposed in the solar radiation category, 692.75.  The second was pruritic urticarial papules and plaques of pregnancy (PUPPP), which is a common inflammatory skin condition late in pregnancy but has no specific code in the pregnancy category.<P>

The effects of smoking on various diseases was again discussed. Modifications to the tabular index were recommended to better capture this relationship.<P> 

The dilemma of how to code the self removal of a feeding tube was also discussed. 
Further refinement of the atherosclerosis fifth digits were proposed for internal mammary and other specified bypass grafts.<P>

Due to expanded neurological testing possibilities, new fifth digits were proposed in category 315.4 coordination disorders to separate specific syndromes.<P>

New fifth digits were also proposed with tabular modifications to specify whether or not an aneurysm of the internal carotid artery is intracranial.<P>

Code 483.1 is proposed for chlamydial pneumonia.<P>
 
A new code (079.6) and tabular modifications were suggested for respiratory syncytial virus, often the cause of bronchiolitis in children.<P>

A request was discussed for non-menopausal hot flashes. No conclusion was drawn and comments will be considered.<P>

Tabular modifications and coding guidelines were requested for the problem of redundancy in the use of concussion with head injury. Basically code 854 should not be used with any conditions classifiable to 850-853.<P>

A new code 519.5 was proposed for mechanical complication of the respiratory ventilator.<P>
 
Code 997.6 was revised to clarify the use of the amputation stump complication code. The word "late" will be deleted so the code should be used regardless of the time since the amputation.<P>

Also in the complication category a fifth digit specification has been proposed for "non-healing wound," code 997.92.<P>

<IMG Align=Right SRC="meeting.gif">A modification was presented to simplify the multiple coding of cholelithiasis of multiple sites.<P>

Further proposals will be made in December 1995 and finalized in June 1996. Detail and comments on the specifics of these proposals can be made by contacting the following:<P>

<CENTER><B>The National Center for Health Statistics</B><BR>
<B>Morbidity Classification Branch, Rm. 954</B><BR>
<B>6525 Belcrest Road</B><BR>
<B>Hyattsville, MD 20782</B><P></CENTER>

In addition to the regular agenda, a presentation was made on the proposed ICD-10 Procedures Coding System (PCS). This contract has been awarded to 3M Healthcare as a new coding system for inpatient procedures. A three year project term has begun, but no proposed date of implementation has been set. The system will be based on a seven digit alphanumeric code with each character having specific meaning such as body system, site, approach, and device.<P>

The codes will be extremely specific and require exact documentation in the record to define all digits accurately. A site specific index will likely be in table format and require precise anatomy and medical/surgical terminology skills. Because of the huge amount of codes being proposed, computerization of the system will be essential.<P>


<br><center><font size=4><b><a href="medicare.html">Next Article</a> | <a href="intronet.html">Previous Article</a> | <a href="fall1995.html#inthis">Contents of Fall 1995 Issue</a> | <a href="hismain.html">HIS FOCUS Home Page</a></b></font></center><BR><BR>

