<title>In Other News...</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><A NAME="onweb"><IMG align=left border=0 hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"></A>
<H2>HIS FOCUS Now Available on the World Wide Web</H2>
The <I>HIS FOCUS</I> newsletter can now be accessed electronically via the World Wide Web (WWW) on the <A HREF = "intronet.html">Internet.</A> The WWW is a rapidly expanding hypertext-based information system that combines text, graphics, audio, and video. <I>HIS FOCUS</I> has its own WWW home page, which features current as well as past issues of the newsletter. Users who wish to view a particular issue of <I>FOCUS</I> need only to "click" on the issue they want to access, then select articles through a menu of titles. Users can also download portions of articles, complete articles, or entire newsletters for future reference.<P>
 
The <I>HIS FOCUS</I> WWW home page can be viewed at <A HREF = "http://www.aspensys.com/hisfocus/hismain.html/"><B>http://www.aspensys.com/hisfocus/hismain.html.</B></A><P>

<IMG border=0 SRC="redbar.gif"><BR><BR>

<A NAME="aspnlink"><IMG align=left border=0 hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"></A>
<H2>AspenLINK Announced</H2>

Aspen Publishers, Inc., of Gaithersburg, Maryland, recently announced AspenLINK, a new online network for health care professionals offering various features, including Federal and State health agency directories and glossaries, a searchable Aspen Publishers catalog, and daily postings of Federal Register health care-related regulatory activity.<P> 

<I>For more information, contact <B>Audrey Hudiburgh, <a href=mailto:audrey.hudiburgh@aspenpub.com>audrey.hudiburgh@aspenpub.com,</a></B> phone: (301) 417-7500.</I><P>

<IMG border=0 SRC="redbar.gif"><BR><BR>

<A NAME="infoexch"><IMG align=left border=0 hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"></A>
<H2>Information Exchange<BR>
new drugs......</H2>

Facts and Comparison, Inc. -- publishers of drug information -- are regular contributors to this column. Call Facts and Comparisons' Customer Service at (800) 223-0554 for more information.<P>

<IMG Align=Right SRC="rxpill.gif"><FONT SIZE=4><B>Moexipril HCI </B>(<I>Univasc</I> by Schwarz Pharma)</FONT><P>
The FDA has approved moexipril HCI, another ACE inhibitor, for the treatment of hypertension. <I>Univasc</I> reduces blood pressure within 2 hours after the initial dose taken 1 hour before a meal. A higher dose of 15 mg/day may produce a greater antihypertensive effect, but if greater control of blood pressure is desired, the addition of a low-dose diuretic, hydrochlorothiazide (eg., <I>Esidrix</I>), has an additive effect. Like other drugs in its class, cough is a common side effect in moexipril.<P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>Dexrazoxane</B> (<I>Zinecard</I> by Pharmacia)</FONT><P>
The FDA has approved <I>Zinecard</I>, which can reduce the incidence and severity of cardiomyopathy associated with doxorubicin. Dexrazoxane injection is to   be taken by women with metastatic breast cancer   who have received 300 mg/m2 of doxorubicin and who would benefit from continued therapy with doxorubicin.<P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>Nalmefene HCI </B>(<I>Revex</I> by Ohmeda)</FONT><P>
The FDA has approved Ohmeda's opioid antagonist, nalmefene HCI (<I>Revex</I>). Nalmafene HCI is indicated for the complete or partial reversal of opioid drug effects, including respiratory depression, induced by either natural or synthetic opioids and for the management of known or suspected opioid overdose.
<P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>Mycophenolate Mofetil</B> (<I>CellCept</I> by Syntex)</FONT><P>
Mycophenolate mofetil (<I>CellCept</I> by Syntex) has been approved by the FDA for the prevention of kidney transplant rejection. Mycophenolate, in combination with cyclosporine and corticosteroids, reduces the incidence of treatment failure within the first 6 months following transplantation.<P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>Lansoprazole</B> (<I>Prevacid</I> by TAP Pharm)</FONT><P>
The FDA has approved lansoprazole (<I>Prevacid</I>), the second proton pump inhibitor for treatment of duodenal ulcers and esophagitis. It will be available as capsules with enteric coated granules.<P>

<FONT SIZE=5><B>update......</b></font><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>Schedule Change</B><BR>
<B><I>Famotidine</I></B> (<I>Pepcid AC</I> by Johnson and Johnson  /Merck)</FONT><P>

The FDA has approved the histamine H2 antagonist famotidine (<I>Pepcid AC</I>) as a nonprescription medicine for prevention of heartburn and acid indigestion. <I>Pepcid AC</I> is a lower-dose version of Merck's prescription anti-ulcer drug (<I>Pepcid</I>) and is the first of its class to be sold <I>over the counter (otc).</I><P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>Imitrex</I></B>--New Doseform</FONT><P>

Glaxo Wellcome received FDA approval to market <I>Imitrex</I> (sumatriptan succinate) in a tablet form. The drug is used for the treatment of migraines and is currently sold as an injection.<P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>Tagamet HB</I></B>--otc Status Approved</FONT><P>

<I>Tagamet HB</I> (cimetidine) has received FDA approval for <I>otc</I> use for relief of heartburn, acid indigestion, and sour stomach. The drug joins <I>Pepcid AC</I> (famotidine) as the second <I>otc</I> H2 antagonist on the market.<P>

