<title>Contracted Services...</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Contracted Services for Medical Records Departments</H2>
<H3>It is becoming increasingly common for health care organizations 
to use outside contractors to manage their operations, especially 
their patient accounts and medical records. Contractors are also 
being used in the area of information systems. What factors have 
led to the increased use of management contractors? </H3>

One factor is that health care facilities are placing greater 
emphasis on cost containment. Administrators are under increasing 
pressure to reduce staffing levels, and as a result, personnel 
costs (salaries and associate benefits) are a likely target when 
mandates for savings are given. The shortage of qualified, 
seasoned professionals presents another staffing problem. <A HREF = "winwin.html">Contract 
management companies</A> are frequently able to attract and compete 
more successfully than individual facilities for persons with top-level expertise. Additionally, larger, more established contract 
management firms such as <A HREF = "hospbene.html">Aspen Systems Corporation</A> can provide 
backup services and additional technical support for the 
recruitment process that are often not available to a single 
facility. Moreover, Aspen is able to apply what it learns from one 
account or client to improve service to other clients.
<P>

Another reason a health care organization may decide to use a 
contractor is that a contracted management company can help the 
organization determine its information management needs. For 
example, before negotiating a contract for medical records 
services, administrators must obtain critical information about 
the existing department or functional area benefitting from the 
services. Often, having these departments managed by an outside 
contractor is justified when issues of cost and quality are 
considered. However, to make an informed decision about the true 
need for a contractor, your organization must collect objective 
information about the current volume and level of services 
provided and the costs of providing these services. It is 
important to carefully document the costs of providing existing 
medical record services in order to complete an accurate cost-benefit analysis of the option to "contract out." Additionally, 
once the decision is made to hire a management contractor, an 
analysis of alternative proposals from qualified firms should be 
conducted.
<P>

Administrators who are considering hiring a contractor to manage 
their medical records departments, or selected areas within these 
departments, should decide what the minimum services to be 
provided by the management company are; what the duties and 
responsibilities of the facility and the management firm will be; 
and what the economic limitations of the relationship are. It is 
also vital to clearly delineate cost and quality performance 
indicators. In assessing proposals, you should at the very least 
consider the reputation, performance, and resources of the 
management company and review the resumes for key onsite and 
offsite management personnel. And of course, a careful analysis of 
the financial aspects of the proposals is always necessary.<P>

<IMG Align=Left SRC="handshak.gif">At Aspen we see ourselves as a partner with each of our clients. 
When running your department or functional area, we are an 
extension of your staff. Additionally, we keep our clients 
informed of exactly what we are doing to improve medical record 
services and how we are implementing improvements. 
<P>

<I>For more information or for assistance in developing your request 
for proposal, please contact Meryl Bloomrosen at (800) 395-5055.</I><P>

