<title>Rx For Success: Optical Imaging</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Rx FOR SUCCESS: Optical <A HREF = "shortcopy.html#docimag">Imaging:</A><BR>
Getting the Right System</H2>
<H3>Is your health care organization considering purchasing an 
optical imaging system to manage its clinical or administrative 
records? If so, you must decide which system, among the many 
available, to purchase. An organization needs a proven, fail-safe 
method of finding a system that meets its information management 
needs and can accommodate or be integrated with its current level 
of automation. The structured analysis approach, the 
method Aspen recommends its clients use for choosing a system, takes these needs into consideration.</H3>

Health care organizations typically use two methods to select 
optical imaging systems: colleague recommendations and vendor 
demonstrations. While these two methods are inexpensive and easy 
to employ in the short term, they are often unreliable.<P>

The structured analysis approach is the most objective way 
for your health care organization to analyze the functional and 
economic value of the information systems available to it. When 
considering how to use an optical imaging system in a health care 
facility, the organization should ask the following questions:<P>

<UL><LI> Who needs the information?
<LI> What information is needed?
<LI> Where does the information come from?
<LI> When is the information needed?
<LI> Why is this information needed?
</UL>

It is only after these questions are answered from the 
perspective of all of the potential users of the optical imaging 
system that the organization can identify the features (referred 
to as functional and technical requirements) it needs in the 
system. Armed with this information, the organization will be 
better prepared to select the <I>right</I> system. The organization can 
then determine if purchasing a system with these features is 
economically feasible.<P> 

<I>For more information, contact Linda A. Frey at (800) 395-5055.</I><P>

