<title>Maybe It's Time To Redesign</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Maybe It's <A HREF = "intrview.html">Time To Redesign</A></H2>
<H3>You've reengineered and restructured. You've established continuous quality improvement programs and quality circles, trained your staff in the principles of total quality management, upgraded your information systems, and studied up on change management. Yet, you still find yourself struggling with process bottlenecks, exploding costs, and incessant pressure to become "more efficient." Your hospital may be a candidate for <A HREF = "aspoffrs.html">operational redesign.</A></H3>
			
Operational redesign emphasizes the functioning of the hospital as a whole rather 
than as a set of separate, specialized departments or disciplines. By adopting this 
simple change in perspective and conducting thorough, systematic evaluations, 
hospital managers can make hospital operations more cost-effective and bring about dramatic improvements in patient and employee satisfaction.<P>

Operational redesign challenges the conventional assumption that most problems 
in the organization are caused by a lack of adequate resources. If the available 
resources are believed to be inadequate, then each department will fight for its share of them. The available resources may, in fact, be perfectly adequate to support the functions of the hospital--there may even be a surplus of some resources--but they must be distributed and managed appropriately.<P> 

Consider the typical hospital in which resources and personnel are organized 
around specialized clinical and administrative departments. In an effort to make the 
organization more cost-effective, hospital executives often "challenge" department 
managers to improve service, reduce staffing, and increase productivity, while 
cutting costs. The financial performance of each department is inevitably compared 
to that of other departments within the hospital. In this atmosphere, it is difficult to 
initiate creative solutions outside the boundaries of the department. For example, a 
manager from one department who suggests that changes should be made in other 
departments will usually get a hostile response from the managers of those 
departments. Thus, the traditional, department-focused structure of a hospital 
encourages competition for resources, but does not necessarily promote the optimal distribution of those resources.<P>

But what if there truly is not enough money, staff, equipment, space, or information 
to meet the hospital's needs? Operational redesign can help in two ways. First, by 
redistributing the available resources to maximize their impact, operational 
redesign can improve the functioning of a struggling organization. Second, by 
determining which resources are most urgently needed, operational redesign can be used to set priorities for making potential improvements or acquisitions, or to make choices between essential resources and less critical ones.<P>

<IMG Align=Right SRC="watch.gif">Some hospitals have introduced patient-focused care initiatives to shift the emphasis from the department to the patient. Decentralization of services, cross-training of staff, and point-of-care data collection and delivery systems are some of the methods used to provide patients with the best possible care. In patient-focused care models, the patient, as the customer, is the ultimate judge of the quality of the service provided.<P>

In truth, patients are not the only customers you need to be concerned about. 
Patients, third-party payors, insurance companies, employer coalitions, and 
employees each have different requirements, expectations, and perspectives that 
must be accommodated. Through an operational redesign initiative, the hospital 
staff can learn to systematically determine the true source of problems and devise 
creative approaches for handling them that take into account the needs of all 
customers.<P>

An operational redesign project may be conducted by your hospital staff or with the 
help of a redesign consultant. In the most successful redesign efforts, the consultant is a facilitator who guides the hospital staff in developing and implementing a redesign plan rather than a mysterious figure who shows up to collect data and reappears months later with a final report. Of course, operational redesign cannot solve all the problems in the hospital; some problems are confined to a single department, procedure, or system, and must be addressed at those levels. But for persistent, complex problems that seem to defy solution, operational redesign may be the strategy that enables your staff to develop the problem-solving skills they need to keep your hospital competitive.<P>

<I>For more information about operational redesign and how it can benefit your 
healthcare organization, contact Kathleen Strouse at (800) 395-5055.</I><P>

<br><center><font size=4><b><a href="cpt1995.html">Next Article</a> | <a href="optical.html">Previous Article</a> | <a href="spri1995.html#inthis">Contents of Spring 1995 Issue</a> | <a href="hismain.html">HIS FOCUS Home Page</a></b></font></center><BR><BR>

