<title>Coding Corner: AMA Publishes 1995 CPT Manual</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Coding Corner: AMA Publishes 1995 CPT Manual</H2>
<H3>The American Medical Association (AMA) has released the <I>1995 
Physicians' Current Procedural Terminology Manual,</I> effective for 
most payors on January 1, 1995. The manual features a new dual 
column layout on 8 1/2" x 11" pages. It also includes additional 
clinical examples, which are located in Appendix D. More 
importantly, the editors have revised the descriptions of many 
codes in hopes of improving clarity and consistency in use. Other 
revisions reflect new technology or prevailing terminology, such 
as the change of the term "radionuclide" to "radiopharmaceutical." 
In addition, more procedures are now designated as "Separate 
Procedures" and should not be coded when carried out in 
conjunction with other more complex procedures.</H3>

Throughout the Surgical Section, terms that reflected the reason 
for a particular procedure (that is, the diagnosis) have been 
deleted or are given only as examples of diagnoses. In some cases, 
codes are designated for general use. (See, for example, code 
25000, Release of deQuervain's Disease.)<P>

Another general trend is the change in the use of key phrases such 
as "with biopsy." In this phrase, the word "for" was often 
replaced by "with." Health care providers should carefully read 
each description, noting the position of the semicolon, to 
determine what is included with some basic procedure "packages."<P>

In the Respiratory System Section, codes pertaining to sinus 
endoscopy surgery have been completely revised. The guidelines 
preceding the section remain the same, but multiple codes have 
been deleted and consolidated into single codes. Careful review of 
the operative report, thorough understanding of the anatomy of the 
nasal area, and communication with surgeons is essential for 
accurate reporting of these procedures.<P>

There are very few changes to the Radiology, Pathology, and 
Laboratory Sections this year. However, the Physical Medicine and 
Rehabilitation Section (formerly called the EEG and Physical 
Medicine Section) has major changes to reflect current practice. 
Look for new definitions and new codes for procedures that were 
not included in the old manual. For example, time variables for 
physical therapy have been revised. In addition, mislabeled 
procedures have been moved under their correct categories. 
According to presenters at this year's AMA CPT Update Workshop in 
Chicago, editors of the manual will continue to make long overdue 
revisions of this type over the next couple of years.<P>

Guidelines in several subsections (the History, Examination, and 
Complexity of Decisionmaking subsections) of the Evaluation and 
Management Section that were vague and misleading have also been 
rewritten. Details of the changes in the Preventive Medicine 
Section are included in winter 1994 volume of <I>CPT Assistant.</I> 
According to this publication, a patient's age determines how 
often he or she will make preventive medicine visits to the 
doctor. When a problem or abnormality is found during such a 
visit, two Evaluation and Management codes may be required to 
fully describe the complex process leading to the diagnosis. 
Modifier 25 has been revised to include this scenario.<P>

Without a new CPT '95, you cannot accurately bill patients, 
insurance companies, etc., for services rendered. Only a brief 
list of the additions, deletions, and revisions to last year's 
codes are provided in Appendix B of the 1994 CPT manual.<P>

When assigning codes to services you provide, read and apply the 
complete text of each guideline and code description. Coding staff 
and medical staff must work together to make sure medical record 
documentation accurately reflects the service provided, 
particularly in these first few months when the new codes are 
being implemented.<P>

The start of a new year is an ideal time to make sure your CPT 
coding staff is coding accurately and consistently. Aspen Systems 
Corporation can help you evaluate coding quality and train your 
staff in all aspects of CPT and <A HREF = "shortcopy.html#compendi">ICD-9CM</A> coding.<P>

<I>For more information, contact our Health Information Services 
group at (800) 395-5055.</I><P>

