<title>Aspen To Conduct Data Quality Reviews for CHA</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Aspen To Conduct Data Quality Reviews for CHA</H2>
<H3>Aspen was awarded a contract from the Connecticut Hospital Association (CHA) to conduct <A HREF = "dataqual.html">data quality studies</A> at hospitals throughout the State. Aspen will assist the CHA's Clinical Information Task Force, which is appointed by and includes Health Information Management directors of the State's hospitals, in assessing the accuracy, uniformity, and validity of coded and abstracted patient information. Hospitals submit this information to the Connecticut Health Information Management & Exchange Program (CHIME), an affiliate of CHA, where it is entered into a statewide data base.</H3>

In a "white paper" about the planned release of CHIME hospital data to the public, 
CHA's Clinical Information Task Force expressed concern about data accuracy. 
Among the issues addressed in the paper were the effects that medical record 
documentation, fiscal pressures, and institutional information systems and 
procedures have on data quality.<P>

<IMG Align=Right SRC="reports.gif">The paper outlined three CHA task force initiatives intended to improve the 
reliability of hospital discharge data:<P> 

<UL><LI>The formation of a CHIME Data Quality Task Force to recommend improvements in the procedure for editing the hospital data received by CHIME.
<LI>The implementation of a statewide external review process.
<LI>The development of a statewide coder education program to promote uniformity in hospital coding and abstracting of patient information.
</UL>

After obtaining the support of Connecticut hospitals for these initiatives, CHIME 
issued a Request For Proposal (RFP) for assistance with the external reviews of data quality. Aspen responded to the RFP with a proposal outlining how it would 
conduct coding and abstracting quality reviews in Connecticut hospitals and was 
selected for the job.<P>

CHIME sent letters to the administrators of the 31 CHA member hospitals describing the project and encouraging each hospital to participate in semiannual reviews of data quality to be performed by Aspen. To date, most of the hospitals have agreed to participate and to pay for the reviews. Reviews will be conducted on a carefully selected sample of patient records, thereby permitting statistically reliable results. From these reviews, reports will be generated that describe the findings in each facility, identify any differences found between hospital-coded and Aspen-coded data, and explain the apparent reasons for those differences.
<P>

It is expected that the hospitals will use findings from the reviews to improve not 
only the quality of the data sample reviewed, but also of data submitted to CHIME in 
the future. Findings will also be used in statewide coder education efforts and may 
result in revisions to the procedure for reporting and editing CHIME data.<P>

<I>For more information, contact Meryl Bloomrosen at (800) 395-5055.</I><P>

