<title>Blind Spots?</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Are There Blind Spots in Your Patient Satisfaction Data?</H2>
<H3>In recent years, greater emphasis has been placed on measuring patient satisfaction with health care services. Patient satisfaction data help management determine the direction for change and encourage health care organizations to be accountable for their operations. Health care professionals in hospital settings, HMOs, and physician offices understand the need to listen to patients closely and regularly and collect data on the their perceptions about service. Surveys are the primary instrument used for measuring patient satisfaction levels and determining future needs. They may be conducted by mail, telephone, or in person immediately after the service is provided.</H3>

Health care organizations that conduct patient satisfaction surveys want to learn how patients feel about their services and staff. Satisfaction scales are frequently used to measure patient satisfaction with specific services, such as medical care, nursing care, laboratory services, and housekeeping. Surveys are also used to find out what patients think of more general services, such as how staff explain procedures and treatments and length of waiting time. <P>

<IMG Align=left SRC="handcirc.gif">In most situations, management can predict survey results. Although patient satisfaction data may provide a few "surprises," they tend to confirm and quantify what health care managers already know about the operations of their organizations. In their desire to appear informed of patient needs and opinions, health care professionals are sometimes reluctant to admit that certain aspects of the survey results were unexpected.<P>  

For this reason, and to be as accurate and objective as possible, the survey should be periodically administered to the managers--in other words, managers should be asked how well they think the organization is performing. The survey results from both parties--managers and patients--can then be compared to point out any discrepancies. If the discrepancy exceeds 20 percent, there is a "blind spot" that requires closer examination. The results of this blind spot analysis can focus the change effort on the appropriate service or staff, rather than on an inappropriate area.<P>
	
<I>For more information on patient satisfaction surveys, contact Dr. Lilly B. Gardner, Vice President of Survey and Evaluation Services, Aspen Systems Corporation, at (800) 638-2784.</I><P>

<br><center><font size=4><b><a href="shortcop2.html">Next Article</a> | <a href="chime.html">Previous Article</a> | <a href="spri1995.html#inthis">Contents of Spring 1995 Issue</a> | <a href="hismain.html">HIS FOCUS Home Page</a></b></font></center><BR><BR>

