<IMG align=left hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2><A 
NAME="infoexch">Information Exchange</A></H2>
<P>
Facts and Comparisons, Inc.--publishers of drug information--are regular contributors of this column to FOCUS. Call Facts and Comparisons' Customer Service at (800) 223-0554 for more information.</P>
<IMG align=left hspace=3 SRC="rxlogo.gif"><H2>New Drugs</H2>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>Cysteamine Bitartrate (Cystagon by Mylan)</B></FONT><BR>

Cysteamine bitartrate has been approved for treatment of 
nephropathic cystinosis. About 200 children in the United States 
suffer from this disease, in which the amino acid cystine 
accumulates in kidney tubules, leading to progressive kidney 
failure, weak bones, and stunted growth. In studies early 
treatment with cysteamine reduced the incidence of kidney failure. 
Children treated with the drug continue to grow but do not reach a 
normal height.<P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>Abciximab (ReoPro by Centocor)</B></FONT><BR>

Centocor received FDA approval for ReoPro (abciximab), a 
monoclonal antibody, for reduction of acute cardiac complications 
in angioplasty patients at high risk for abrupt artery closure. 
The antibody inhibits platelet aggregation by binding to a 
specific receptor on platelets. ReoPro, Centocor's first product, 
was expected to be available in February 1995.<P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>Vinorelbine Tartrate (Navelbine by Burroughs Wellcome)</B></FONT><BR>

Vinorelbine Tartrate will be available for first-line treatment of 
ambulatory patients with unrespectable, advanced non-small cell 
lung cancer (NSCLC). Navelbine is indicated for use as a single 
agent in the treatment of stage IV NSCLC and in combination with 
cisplatin for stage III or IV NSCLC. It is approved as an IV 
treatment on an outpatient basis. Burroughs Wellcome expected the 
product to be available by mid-January 1995. This approval marks 
the first new treatment for NSCLC in 20 years.<P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>Lamotrigine (Lamictal by Burroughs Wellcome)</B></FONT><BR>

Lamotrigine, a phenyltriazine compound, has received FDA approval 
as an adjunctive therapy for the treatment of partial seizures in 
adults with epilepsy. The drug may be given in combination with 
carbamazepine (Tegretol) and phenytoin (Dilantin).<P>

