<title>Rx for Success...</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Rx 
FOR SUCCESS: Scale Your Systems Security Level To Value and Content</H2>
<H3>The level of security established for a system or group of systems, and 
the effort and cost expended to maintain that level of security should be 
scaled to the value of the system and its contents to the organization. For 
example, it may not be cost effective to apply a security program suitable 
for a large mainframe computer room to a small, PC-based office 
automation system supporting a non-critical operation.</H3>
<P>
Therefore, one of the first elements in developing a successful security 
program is the analysis of existing systems, data, and security practices. 
After information on these components is understood, an approach and plan 
can be developed to move the system(s) to an appropriate level of 
security.
<P>
Information that may be considered during this evaluation includes: 1) the 
nature of the systems, the criticality of the data to the organization, and 
the impact of system damage or data loss; 2) the adequacy of the administrative, 
management, and technical approaches used to protect the 
systems; 3) organizational and individual responsibility, and accountability for security; 
and 4) requirements for additional security, standards, training, and updated technology. 
At this point, a list of security requirements and policies can be developed.
<P>
A second step is the evaluation of the organization, policies, system, and 
physical plant to identify and document potential vulnerabilities and 
threats. Probabilities of occurrence and impact estimate are developed for 
each risk. Recommendations can then be made and costs estimated to eliminate or reduce 
these risks.
<P>
The third step in the development of a system security plan is the 
development of an outline of tasks, objectives, and schedules required to 
meet the requirements identified and implement the recommendations to 
reduce identified risks and threats. This may include topics such as new 
programs required, security software to be implemented, as well as 
specific procedures to be implemented, such as password assignment and 
update, control of application additions, system management, network 
access, and physical security.
<P>
The results of these steps are then collected into a comprehensive 
security plan for approval, funding, and implementation. The final plan 
should also include the assignment of specific responsibilities and 
mechanisms for review, updating, and reevaluation of requirements and 
risks.
<P>
One additional aspect of system security is that of contingency planning 
and the establishment of mechanisms for continuing operations in the 
event that critical automated systems are unavailable for use. This topic 
will be discussed in the next issue of this newsletter.</p>
<H4><I>For more information about security initiatives, contact Edwin Morgan at (800) 
395-5055.</I>
</H4>

