<title>1994 JCAHO Information Management...</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>1994 JCAHO Information Management Standards 
Announced</H2>
<H3><I>Part Three: The New Information Management (IM) JCAHO 
Standards</I></H3>
<H3>In Parts One and Two of this article, we mentioned that information management 
standards are now part of Section 2 of the AHM, <i>Organizational Functions</i>, along 
with leadership and improving organizational performance. According to the Joint 
Commission's preamble and principles for this new set of standards, "the goal of 
information management is to obtain, manage, and use information to enhance and 
improve individual and organizational performance in patient care, governance, 
management, and support processes."</H3>
<P>
This set of new and newly regrouped standards describe a vision of effective and 
continuously improving information management in health care organizations. The 
objectives related to achieving this vision are:
<DIR>
<LI>more timely and easier access to complete information throughout the organization;
<LI>improved data accuracy;
<LI>demonstrated balance of proper levels of security versus ease of access;
<LI>use of aggregate data, along with external knowledge bases and comparative data, to 
pursue opportunities for improvement;
<LI>redesign of important information-related processes to improve efficiency; and
<li>greater collaboration and information sharing to enhance patient care.
</DIR>
<P>
The new IM standards focus on the key IM areas of Planning, Patient-Specific Data, 
Aggregate Data, Knowledge-based Data and Comparative 
Performance Data and Information. The standards are broken down into six 
key processes:
<DIR>
<LI>identification of the organization's information needs;
<LI>structural design of the information management system;
<LI>definition and capture of data/information;
<LI>data analysis and transformation of data into information;
<LI>transmission and reporting of information; and
<li>assimilation and use of information.
</DIR>
<P>
From these six key processes, the JCAHO has developed ten major 
standards for the Management of Information. Each of the respective 
standards are broken down into substandard categories of proficiency. The 
organization's leaders have important roles and responsibilities if an 
organization-wide approach to IM will be achieved, maintained, and 
improved. The "Improving Organizational Performance" chapter of the AMH 
will be used to design, measure, assess, and improve the organization's 
performance of the JCAHO IM standards. These standards are used to apply 
dimensions of performance which are "Doing the Right Things" and "Doing 
the Right Things Well" in the six key IM processes described above.
<P>
The management of information standards survey process will involve a 
combination of group and individual interviews, document review, 
performance outcome measurement, and observations. As the IM standards 
are focused on every aspect of health care, the interviews will take place 
in every hospital department. The majority of the new IM standards affect 
the information management and medical record departments.
<P>
The above IM processes, which are used by the Joint Commission to 
establish the new and regrouped IM standards, will require additional 
planning and preparation for the next JCAHO inspection. The new IM 
functional area will present new challenges for virtually every 
department within your health care organization.</p>
<H4><I>Aspen functional and technical experts can help your organization or hospital 
department prepare for an upcoming JCAHO inspection. For more information contact 
Len Fogelsonger at (800) 395-5055.</I>
</H4>

