<title>Coding Corner...</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Coding Corner: Focus on V-Codes</H2>
<H3>Numerous health information statistical reports are generated in hospitals and 
government agencies across the nation on a daily basis. To the non-Medical Record 
practitioner, the <A HREF = "focus97.html">ICD-9-CM</A> codes used in these reports may look more like alphabet soup 
than statistical information. Why are there V and E's in front of some of the codes? 
Hospitals and physicians are instructed to follow "V-code" reporting guidelines for 
outpatient services yet insurance providers may or may not "accept" V-codes. What 
exactly is a V-code anyway?</H3>
<P>
Within ICD-9-CM are two supplementary classifications that are used as "diagnosis" 
codes. The first is called the "Supplementary Classification of 
Factors Influencing Health Status and Contact with Health Services." Each 
code in this supplement begins with a V. The second supplement is a 
classification of External Causes of Injury and Poisoning (E800-E999). In 
this issue we will focus on the V-code definitions and basic guidelines.
<P>
The V-code classification provides codes for patient encounters or 
situations that are not injuries or diseases. The use of V-codes generally 
fall into three types of circumstance:
<DL>
<DD><P>
1. When a person is currently not ill but requires health services for another purpose such 
as to act as a donor, receive a prophylactic vaccination, well visit, counseling, or special 
screening. These services would generally be provided in the outpatient setting. Inpatient 
newborns are also categorized with a V-code.
<DD><P>
2. When a problem or circumstance impacts the patient's care in either inpatient or 
outpatient settings, but are not current diseases or injuries. Many times the presence of a 
history of certain conditions such as cancer or previous surgery may require additional 
tests, monitoring, etc. V-codes describe these health factors. Per coding guidelines, these 
codes would not be acceptable as principle diagnoses.
<DD><P>
3. When a person encounters health care services in follow-up to a current or healing 
condition for specific treatment. Examples include admission for chemotherapy, 
admission for dialysis, attention to dressings, and admission for removal of orthopedic 
devices.
</DL>
<P>
Generally, these codes are listed as principal diagnoses in either the 
outpatient or inpatient setting.
<P>
These are the most confusing V-codes because the patient's current disease or injury is 
also coded as a secondary "diagnosis" code, as well as a procedure code for the service 
provided. The codes are designed to distinguish between encounters solely for primarily 
non-surgical specialized treatment and more complex encounters to diagnose or otherwise 
medically or surgically care for the patient. For example, an admission for chemotherapy 
(V58. 1) is generally 
short and predictable in patient resource consumption and outcome. Whereas the 
admission to work-up and originally treat a cancer patient would be much more extensive 
and varied depending on the type of cancer and surgical involvement.
<P>
Reporting guidelines for V-codes are the same as for other diagnosis 
codes. The definitions of principal and secondary diagnoses apply. If a V-
code is the reason chiefly responsible for the patient's encounter it should 
be used as the principal diagnosis (exceptions are noted in code books). For 
patients receiving ancillary diagnostic services only, the appropriate V-code is sequenced 
first, such as V72.5, Radiologic Examination. For further 
use of V-codes in the outpatient setting, see <I>Coding Clinic</I>, First Quarter 
1990.
<P>
To be reported as a secondary diagnosis, V-codes must meet the criteria 
for all secondary diagnoses and impact the patient's current encounter. 
Many V-codes for previous or family history may apply to the patient, but 
not impact the current admission.
<P>
Coders may find the proper V-codes by looking in the ICD-9-CM index 
under headings such as Aftercare, Carrier, Checkup, Counseling, 
Examination, Follow-up, History, Observation, Screening, Status or 
Supervision. Generally the supplemental classification is short enough 
that the experienced coder can quickly find an applicable V-code by 
perusing the main headings.
<P>
Coders should be particularly aware of those V-codes that are 
complication/co-morbidity (CC) codes possibly impacting the DRG 
assignment. These include some of the status post organs replaced by 
transplant (V42.0-V42.8), insufficient prenatal care (V23.7), and 
respirator dependence (V46.1).</p>
<H4><I>Aspen Systems can design coding services for your staff that focus on your 
particular health care setting and training needs. Contact Meryl Bloomrosen at (800) 395-
5055 for more information.</I></H4>

