<title>1995 Coding and DRG Changes</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=5 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>HCFA Publishes 1995 Coding and DRG Changes</H2>
<H3>The <A HREF = "areyou.html">Health Care Financing Administration</A> has published its proposed rules 
for FY 1995. On May 27, 1994, the <I>Federal Register</I> included several ICD-9-CM 
coding changes for the upcoming year. These proposed codes 
typically become finalized without any major revisions and are published 
in early September with an effective date of October 1, 1994.</H3>
<H3>As in previous years, most of the new codes involve the addition of a new 
fourth or fifth digit to provide greater specificity. Examples of this type 
of change include:</H3>
<IMG SRC="hcfatabl.gif"><BR>
<P>
In an unusual change, specificity has been decreased in the coding of HIV 
disease. Code 042 will now replace code 042.0-044.9. This should provide 
greater consistency in HIV reporting. A new code, V08 has been added for 
asymptomatic HIV infection status and 795.71 for nonspecific serologic evidence of HIV. 
Look for <I>Coding Clinic</I> guidelines on the use of these new codes soon after the 
Final Rule is published.
<P>
Other conditions with new codes include: Late effect of complication of 
obstetrical conditions, Fragile X syndrome, benign shuddering attacks, 
late effect of adverse effect of drug, amputation status, prophylactic 
organ removal, and problems related to lifestyle.
<P>
Three new procedure codes have been added: Creation of pleuroperitoneal 
shunt 34.05, Autologous hematopoietic stem cell transplant 41.04, and 
infusion of biological response modifier 99.28.
<P>
Each year there are adjustments to the DRG classifications to reflect 
changes in treatment patterns, technology or other factors. For FY '95 only 
minor revisions have been proposed involving moving code 694.1 to DRG's 
283/284 and changing the surgical hierarchy for MDC 2 and 3. A limited 
number of revisions to the CC exclusion list involving related or new 
codes are also proposed. Lastly, a few procedures such as excision of 
lymph structures, lower limb amputations and pacemaker codes included 
in DRG's 468, 476 and 477 were shifted to more pertinent DRG's where 
indicated.</p>

<H4><I>Detailed coding changes with explanations will be published separately by 
Aspen and can be obtained by contacting Michelle Watson at (800) 395-
5055.</I></H4>

