<title>Aspen Offers...</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><IMG align=left hspace=3 
SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2>Aspen Offers <A HREF = "redesign.html">Operations Analysis</A> Services to Clients</H2>
<H3>Health information management departments must continually cope with 
change. As Congress finalizes what version of health care reform we will 
see, one of the first questions many will ask about the plan is how will it 
affect my job? My organization? As the Joint Commission on 
Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations develops and refines its newest 
information management standards, health care facilities will wonder 
how they will respond to ever changing health data reporting 
requirements. As state health care organizations structure new 
regulations governing costs and access to health care, health care 
facilities will once again face additional demands to release patient 
information.</H3>
<P>
On top of this, today's administrators face increasing pressures to operate 
their facilities and departments with restraint. They're often faced with 
staff vacancies, budget cuts, hiring freezes, and staff reductions. <I>How to 
do more with less?</I> The demands for outstanding, client/patient-oriented 
services are evident even in the face of these pressures. The need to 
provide efficient and effective health information management services is 
strong and the consequences of failing to provide such services are 
dramatic. Consequently, many institutions are looking for guidance in 
conducting internal departmental evaluations and analysis to review and 
improve their current business practices.</p>
<P>
For health information management (HIM) departments, conducting a 
management audit and operations evaluation involves a review of all 
activities conducted within the HIM department but also requires a review 
of the records and information processing functions throughout the entire 
organization. Effective HIM departments cannot operate in isolation from 
the activities of the organization as a whole. At the very least, successful 
HIM services require sound principles of administration and information 
management, clear understanding of the mission of the organization, and 
established lines of responsibility and authority. HIM departments require 
extensive and detailed policies and procedures that govern the operations 
of the department and promote the objectives of the facility. 
Nevertheless, there are wide variations in practice in implementing the 
basic HIM functions, and the quality and productivity measures used to 
monitor compliance with standards. In this article, we address achieving 
efficiencies in the HIM department while gaining greater control and 
management of HIM functions.</p>
<P>
To begin, let's start with some basic questions:</p>
<DIR>
<LI>What is your organizational mission? Who are your clients? How can you serve 
them better?
<LI>What are the fundamental operational, functional, and performance characteristics of 
the HIM processes that can be identified as candidates for improvements? How and 
where in the process can changes be made? What are the strengths and weaknesses of 
current operations?
<li>What resources are available to help with this activity?
</DIR>
<P>
Once you have answered these questions, the next step is to identify the 
goals of your evaluation. Once you have refined your goals, you can begin to 
implement a series of activities to meet them.
<P>
Determining what you need to accomplish will help you set the scope of 
your project, given your budget and time constraints, as well as personnel 
limitations. To begin, identify any problem areas by analyzing your 
operations and the existing organization. This includes a review of 
existing operating policies and procedures, data and work flows, reporting 
systems, quality controls, and performance standards. This is frequently 
done by conducting a series of data gathering activities (such as 
observation, interviews, job analysis questionnaires, work flow 
assessments and activity reporting). Once problems are described, 
quantify and prioritize them.
<P>
The next step is to develop solutions to those problems. You must identify 
ways to improve departmental functions and capabilities in response to 
expected functional changes in order to enhance services and meet 
organizational requirements. The end result of this assessment may 
include recommendations for amendments or updates to existing policies, 
the development of new procedures, and a restructuring of work flow 
through the department.</P>
<H4><I>Aspen has compiled a selected bibliography on HIM department evaluation 
and productivity measurement. To receive your free copy of this 
bibliography, or for more information on how Aspen can help you assess 
your department, call Meryl Bloomrosen at (800)-395-5055.</I></H4>

<br><center><font size=4><b><a href="shortcopy.html">Next Article</a> | <a href="hcfapubs.html">Previous Article</a> | <a href="fall1994.html#inthis">Contents of Fall 1994 Issue</a> | <a href="hismain.html">HIS FOCUS Home Page</a></b></font></center><br><br>

