<IMG align=left hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2><A NAME="infotool">Electronic 
Information Tool Provides Code Conversion</A></H2>
<P>
The Department of Health and Human Services has recently developed and 
released a computerized information tool which provides users with 
conversions of ICD-9-CM codes from calendar years 1985 to 1993 (fiscal 
years 1986 to 1994). The system is intended to help users track annual 
changes in diagnosis and procedure codes.
<P>
The system (the official electronic version of code changes) was jointly 
developed and approved by the National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS) 
and the Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA). The purpose of the 
system is to provide an automated and systematic approach to tracking 
code modifications. The system is updated after the publication of the 
final rule on code changes in the Federal register.
<P>
<I>The software is available on diskette for $265.00. For more information 
contact: HCFA, Bureau of Data Management and Strategy, Office of 
Statistics and Data Management, 6325 Security Blvd., 3-A-10, 7008 
Security Office Park, Baltimore, Maryland 21207. To order this public use 
file (PUF), address your order to: HCFA, PUF, Accounting Division, P.O. Box 
7520, Baltimore, Maryland 21207-0520.</I></p>
</H3>

<IMG border=0 SRC="redbar.gif"><BR>

<IMG align=left hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2><A NAME="enterococ">Coding 
Update: Classification of Enterococcus</A></H2>
<P>
<I>Cecil's Textbook of Medicine</I> classifies enterococci to Group D streptococcus 
infections. This grouping, according to the <I>Merck Manual</I>, is based on the 
Lancefield Groups A-K and K-T. Group D consists of two major categories: enterococcus 
<I>(Enterococcus faecalis, E. durans, E. faecium)</I> and nonenterococcus <I>(S. bovis, 
S. equinus)</I>. Enterococci are inhabitants of human intestinal flora and are a major 
cause of nosocomial and community-acquired sepsis. <I>Enterococcus faecalis (S. 
faecalis)</I>, in particular, causes urinary tract infections, peritonitis, cellulitis, wound 
infection, bacteremia and endocarditis.
<P>
Although medical reference books such as <i>Cecil's Textbook</i> classify enterococcus 
to Group D streptococcus, the ICD-9-CM indexes it to 041.4 
(E. coli). A call to Delray Green at the National Center for Health Statistics revealed that 
this was an indexing error. The correct code should be 041.04. We expect that a 
correction will be made with the 10/l/94 ICD-9-CM addenda.

<H3>References</H3>
<H4><I>Cecil's Textbook of Medicine,</I> 19th edition, p. 1626.</h4>
<h4><I>Merck Manual,</I> edition, p. 90.</H3>
<H4>Green, Delray. Telephone interview. 1 August 1994.</I></H4>

<H4><I>For more information on updated coding information, contact Meryl 
Bloomrosen at (800) 395-5055.</I></H4>

<IMG border=0 SRC="redbar.gif"><BR><BR>

<IMG align=left hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"><H2><A 
NAME="outsourc">Outsourcing Your Transcription Services</A></H2>
<P>
Accurate and timely documentation is vital for quality patient care and 
accurate reimbursement. Many providers have turned to contract 
management support and outsourcing some medical record functions. If 
you are currently evaluating transcription services, Aspen suggests you 
consider the following questions:
<DIR>
<LI>Do you have equipment that needs to be updated? Look at what the service has to 
offer. You can have the doctors call a number which will connect them to equipment 
outside the hospital, provided by the service.
<LI>If you have an up-to-date digital system, how will the service hook-up to it and 
manage it? Who pays for the phone lines and monthly service? Is this included in a rate?
<LI>Do you want the service to pick up cassettes? When and how will this be 
accomplished?
<LI>How will the transcribed reports be delivered? Will the proper number of copies be 
included? 
<LI>Can reports be printed in your facility? How can you get a computer hook-up?
<LI>Do we pay by the line or the page?
<LI>How often will we be invoiced?
<LI>What are the terms and conditions of the contract languages?
<LI>What constitutes a line of transcription? What is the number of characters? How 
many lines make up a page? How are they counted?
<LI>What about <I>stat</I> work? Can reports be provided within two hours?
<LI>Routine turnaround must be within 24 hours. Will this occur?
<li>How does the company monitor the quality of its work?
</DIR>
<P>
The more information you ask up front, the fewer surprises you will 
encounter once you start the service.</P>
For more information on how Aspen can help you evaluate outsourcing transcription 
services, please call Paul Gustafson at (800) 395-5055.<p>

<IMG border=0 SRC="redbar.gif"><BR><BR>

