<title>In Other News...</title><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><A NAME="aidsinfo"><IMG align=left border=0 hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"></A>
<H2>HIV/AIDS Information on the Internet</H2>
Through the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) National AIDS Clearinghouse (NAC), health care professionals can keep abreast of HIV/AIDS-related trends. The Clearinghouse, operated by Aspen under a contract with CDC, provides information to people and organizations working in prevention, health care, research, and support services. With the expansion of the Internet as an information source, many of the Clearinghouse resources are now available online:

<UL><LI><B>The CDC NAC World Wide Web site</B> contains information about Clearinghouse services, new CDC guidelines and publications, current statistics, and links to other HIV/AIDS-related Web and gopher sites. Free CDC NAC inventory publications may be ordered through the Internet. The address is <A HREF = "http://www.cdcnac.org/"><B>http://www.cdcnac.org</A>.</B>
<P>
<LI><B>The AIDS News Listserv</B> sends HIV/AIDS-related messages to subscribers. It includes the <I>AIDS Daily Summary</I>, a daily news clipping service; selected <I>Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report</I> articles; <I>CDC National AIDS Hotline Training Bulletins</I>; and press releases. The address is <a href=mailto:listserv@cdcnac.aspensys.com><B>listserv@cdcnac.aspensys.com</a>.
</B> To subscribe, send the message "subscribe aidsnews yourfirstname yourlastname" to the above address.<P>
<LI><B>The CDC NAC gopher</B> provides a simple menu that enables users to find a wide variety of documents on HIV and AIDS. Basic HIV/AIDS-related information is available, as well as information about prevention, treatment, and living with HIV. The gopher address is <A HREF = "gopher://cdcnac.aspensys.com:72"><B>gopher://cdcnac.aspensys.com:72</A>.
</B>
</UL>

<I>If you have questions about accessing any of CDC NAC's Internet resources, e-mail the Clearinghouse at <a href=mailto:aidsinfo@cdcnac.aspensys.com><B>aidsinfo@cdcnac.aspensys.com
</a>
</B>  or call (800) 458-5231.</I><P>

<IMG border=0 SRC="redbar.gif"><BR><BR>

<A NAME="newcombo"><IMG align=left border=0 hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"></A>
<H2>New Correct Coding Combinations</H2>

The Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA) recently released guidelines that define correct coding practices for Current Procedural Terminology (CPT). The coding practices will be the basis of national Medicare policy for payment of physician claims using CPT, effective with claims received on or after January 1, 1996. There are two main types of coding edits/combinations that have been implemented: comprehensive and component coding combinations and mutually exclusive coding combinations that represent services and/or procedures that would not or could not be performed concurrently based on the CPT code description or standard medical practice. A copy of this information can be obtained on paper or electronically from the National Technical Information Service (NTIS) at (703) 487-4650.<P> 


<IMG border=0 SRC="redbar.gif"><BR><BR>

<A NAME="infoexch"><IMG align=left border=0 hspace=3 SRC="aspnbug2.gif"></A>
<H2>Information Exchange<BR>
new drugs......</H2>

Facts and Comparisons, Inc. -- publishers of drug information -- are regular contributors to this column of FOCUS. Call Facts and Comparisons' Customer Service at (800) 223-0554 for more information.<P>

<IMG Align=left SRC="rxpill.gif"><B>Lamivudine.</B> The FDA approved lamivudine (3TC; <I>Epivir</I> by Glaxo Wellcome) for use in combination with zidovudine (AZT; <I>Retrovir</I> by Glaxo Wellcome) under its accelerated approval process for treatment of HIV infection when therapy is warranted based on clinical or immunological evidence of disease progression. Clinical trials have shown the combination therapy to increase CD4 cell counts; however, there are no data on lamivudine's potential effects on clinical outcome of HIV, such as the incidence of opportunistic infection or survival. Lamivudine is the first HIV indication approved by the FDA for initial therapy since zidovudine monotherapy was approved in 1987. The dosage is 150 mg twice daily in combination with zidovudine.<P>

<B>Saquinavir.</B> Also approved by the FDA for HIV infection was saquinavir (<I>Invirase</I> by Hoffman-LaRoche), which received the fastest approval of any antiviral agent for HIV with only 3 months passing between the drug's NDA filing and its approval. It is indicated for use in combination with nucleoside analogs such as zidovudine (AZT; <I>Retrovir</I> by Glaxo Wellcome) and zalcitabine (ddC; <I>Hivid</I> by Hoffman-LaRoche) for the treatment of advanced HIV. Saquinavir is a protease inhibitor (it disables the enzyme protease, which is necessary for HIV reproduction). Combination therapy has proven to increase CD4 cell counts, and best results were shown when used with a nucleoside analog the patient hadn't tried before. The dosage is 600 mg 3 times daily in combination with a nucleoside analog.<P>

<B>Glimepiride.</B> The FDA approved the Type II diabetes (non-insulin-dependent) drug glimepiride (<I>Amaryl</I> by Hoechst Marion Roussel) for once-daily use as monotherapy or in combination with insulin to lower blood glucose in diabetes patients who cannot control their glucose level through diet and exercise.<P>

<B>Amifostine.</B> The FDA approved US Bioscience's cytoprotective agent <I>Ethyol</I> (amifostine) for the reduction of cumulative renal toxicity associated with repeated cisplatin (<I>Platinol</I>) use in advanced ovarian cancer patients.<P>

<B>Cetirizine.</B> The FDA approved Pfizer's antihistamine <I>Zyrtec</I> (cetirizine) for treatment of perennial allergic rhinitis (year-round allergies), seasonal allergic rhinitis, and chronic urticaria (itching and hives). Although Pfizer maintains <I>Zyrtec</I> is the most widely prescribed antihistamine in Europe, FDA approval took 7 years. The once-daily tablet will be available in 5 and 10 mg.<P>

<B>Ibutilide.</B> (<I>Corvert</I> by Pharmacia and Upjohn.) <I>Corvert</I> is approved by the FDA for rapid conversion of atrial fibrillation or atrial flutter to normal sinus rhythms. Other drugs used to treat fibrillation and flutter are not rapidly effective, and treatment often requires titration and close observation for 1 to 3 days.<P>

<B>Riluzole.</B> The FDA approved riluzole (<I>Rilutek</I> by Rhone-Poulenc Rorer), making it the first approved drug for the treatment of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS; Lou Gehrig's disease). In one trial, riluzole patients lived an average of 3 months longer than placebo patients. The drug is neither a cure for ALS nor is it able to stop the muscle paralysis that leads to progressive nerve damage. But the drug has shown some effect on the fatal disease for which there has previously been no treatment.<P>

