<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Health Information Management</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#3B17FF" VLINK="#FF0900">

<!-- System: Aspen Home Page -->
<!-- Author: Aspen Systems Corporation (www.aspensys.com) -->
<!-- Editor: David -->
<!-- Last Update: 7/15/96 10:00pm-->
<!-- Source File: servhlth.htm -->


<BR><CENTER><!-- Header Tag -->
<H2>Health Information Management</H2><BR>
</CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=4>
<H3>Health Information Services</H3>

Aspen's Health Information Services (HIS) division assists Federal Government agencies; health care providers, users, and employers; and third-party payers with maintaining health information systems. Aspen ensures that the systems accurately reflect the quality of care provided and the costs of services rendered and that they are in full compliance with reporting requirements. In addition, the HIS Division, through the  <!-- Link Tag -->
Program Management Integration Contract, provides technical, administrative, and managerial support to the Health Affairs community.<P>

Our highly skilled staff provide a broad spectrum of services, including coding and abstracting of health records or claims data, auditing previously coded records or claims, assisting with the management of accounts receivables, and developing medical information systems and health care databases. Moreover, through the identification of coding mistakes or incomplete data, we assist our clients with recapturing revenues otherwise lost due to these errors.<P>

Other services that Aspen offers its health provider clients include the development of programs and approaches to improve employee and organizational productivity;  implementation and evaluation of health information systems; and the identification and implementation of cost-efficient state-of-the-art systems, such as optical disc technology.<P>

Internet services supported by Health Information Services include:<P>

<UL>
<LI> <A HREF = "http://www.aspensys.com/hisfocus/">Web site for Health Information Services (HIS) FOCUS</A>
</UL>

For more information about Health Information Services, contact Meryl Bloomrosen at
<a href=mailto:mbloomrosen@aspensys.com>mbloomrosen@aspensys.com</A><P>

<HR>
<H3>Health Communication and Patient Education</H3> 

Communication plays an essential role in disease prevention and health promotion. Health communication programs can raise awareness of a health issue, problem, or solution; increase demand for health services; and reinforce knowledge, attitudes, and behaviors. However, effective communication is a challenge for many reasons. Information about health issues is often complex and technical in nature. Many diseases arouse fear in patients and interfere with their ability to receive messages. Health information may be inconclusive, controversial, and subject to change as new research findings are released.<P>

<B>Twenty years of health communications experience.</B> More than two decades of working in the health communication and information dissemination fields has helped Aspen Systems develop sharp technical skills and a keen sensitivity to the information needs of users. Aspen's approach to print and electronic publishing emphasizes the company's experience in translating research results and health promotion messages into user-friendly information products for patients and health professionals. Use of state-of-the-art technology allows Aspen to respond to new research findings by rapidly creating new products or modifying existing ones.  In the past 5 years, Aspen has collected 10 top awards for writing, layout and design, achievement of purpose, and cost-effectiveness of products developed for Federal health agencies. Recently, our World Wide Web (WWW) sites have begun to garner awards as well. The Aspen-developed Web site for the CDC National AIDS Clearinghouse was judged to be among the top 5 percent of sites reviewed by Point Communications.<P>

<B>Aspen's experienced and talented staff of communication professionals.</B> Health information projects constitute one of Aspen's major lines of business, employing seasoned WWW designers, writers, editors, and graphic artists. These professionals work closely with other Aspen staff, including physicians, nurses, public health workers, and case managers, to produce materials that bring tailored health promotion messages to a wide variety of audiences. Complementing their academic training, these subject experts gain valuable knowledge by answering questions posed by patients and health professionals over the phone and through the mail. Through this experience, they learn about patients' information needs at different stages in their disease process and determine their preferred channels of communication. This awareness has immeasurably enhanced the patient education materials developed by Aspen. In addition, Aspen's multicultural, multilingual staff bring their understanding of the cultures of various population groups to bear on health communication tasks, ensuring that printed and electronic materials will speak to targeted audiences in the most convincing way. <P>

<B>Partnerships strengthen project results.</B> Aspen staff work in close partnership with health-related organizations such as the American Medical Association, American Public Health Association, National Black Nurses Association, National Council of La Raza, American Cancer Society, Kaiser Family Foundation, and American Red Cross as well as many State and local groups. These working alliances result in the enhancement of projects by drawing upon the strengths of each partner.<P>

<B>Examples of Aspen's health communication and patient education projects.</B> The print- and electronic-based projects described below illustrate Aspen's range and depth of experience in the health communications arena. <P>

<UL>
<LI>Design, production, and maintenance of award-winning World Wide Web site for the <BR>
<A HREF = "http://www.cdcnac.org/">CDC National AIDS Clearinghouse</A> and Web sites for the <A HREF = "http://www.actis.org/">AIDS Clinical Trials Information Service</A> and the <A HREF = "http://www.hivatis.org/">HIV/AIDS Treatment Information Service</A>.<P>

<LI>Design and production of FOCUS, a quarterly newsletter for health care professionals available on the Internet that covers health information systems management, patient account and coding
news, pharmacy topics, and other products and services designed to manage health care information.<P>

<LI>Design of materials and promotion of major national mass media health communications campaigns for the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the Food and Drug Administration, and the National Cancer Institute: the 8-year America Responds to AIDS Program, FDA Mammography Information Service, and the National Governors' Association, Governors' Spouses Program, Breast Cancer Awareness Campaign.<P>

<LI>Writing, design, and production of fact sheets and patient education pamphlets in lay language on cancer and HIV infection and AIDS.<P>

<LI>Provision of tailored responses to thousands of queries received by phone and through the mail from people with cancer and HIV/AIDS.<P>

<LI>Production, promotion, and dissemination of a videotape and training package to educate patients about HIV/AIDS clinical trials.<P>

<LI>Participation in the development and design of the award-winning print and electronic Libraries as Gateways project to reach consumers with federally produced health information through public libraries.<P>

<LI>Creation of a 14,000-item database and archival collection of HIV/AIDS prevention and patient education materials. The database provides health educators with examples of successful brochures, posters, videotapes, and training curricula that they can adapt for local use. <P>

<LI>Production of databases and CD-ROM products, bibliographies, and resource guides in a wide variety of health-related areas, including cancer, diabetes, epilepsy, HIV/AIDS, mammography, worksite health promotion, special health concerns of aging and ethnic populations, clinical trials, alternative medicine, substance abuse, and child abuse.<P>

<LI>Production of the AIDS Daily Summary, a news clipping service that highlights HIV/AIDS-related research findings and important events reported in major newspapers and journals.<P>
</UL>

<HR>
For more information about Health Communication and Patient Education, contact Ruthann Bates at <a href=mailto:rbates@aspensys.com>rbates@aspensys.com</a><P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Aspen Systems Corporation<BR>
1600 Research Boulevard<BR>
Rockville, MD 20850<P>

Phone: (301) 251-5000<BR>
<A HREF = "http://www.aspensys.com/">http://www.aspensys.com</A><P>
