<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Document Scanning</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#3B17FF" VLINK="#FF0900">

<!-- System: Aspen Home Page -->
<!-- Author: Aspen Systems Corporation (www.aspensys.com) -->
<!-- Editor: David -->
<!-- Last Update: 3/19/96 10:00pm-->
<!-- Source File: servscan.htm -->


<BR><CENTER><!-- Header Tag -->
<H2>Document Scanning</H2><BR>
</CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=4>
We operate an image scanning facility in our headquarters in Rockville, Maryland. This state-of-the-art facility has the capacity to scan up to 200,000 pages per day and to provide quality control, document indexing, OCR/ICR, and CD-ROM burning functions. We can provide image scanning or microfilming services at our conversion facility or onsite. We can also convert microfilm to image format, and with our production capacity printers, we can generate paper blowback from image and/or microfilm.<P>

Drawing on our experience with imaging systems, we work with you to select the vendors, applications, and products most suited to your project needs. We can also recommend scanning, printing, and storage subsystems; and network components required to support your applications.<P>

Aspen offers extensive experience in advanced optical imaging technology. For example, for one of our clients, more than 1.7 million pages were scanned in 6 months, including 400,000 pages converted from microfilm.<P>

<B>Onsite scanning and scanning to ASCII file.</B> Aspen's 3,000-square-foot Imaging Center located at corporate headquarters allows Aspen to meet extremely tight deadlines with comprehensiveness and accuracy. Aspen has significant experience converting source documents to full-text ASCII file format using high-speed scanning systems. When performing scanning services, Aspen uses document control procedures developed and refined over many years of experience reproducing evidentiary materials.<P>

Aspen-owned hardcopy scanning equipment includes two Photomatrix 6000 scanners, one high-speed Kodak Imagelink 900 scanner, and three Ricoh IS-400 flatbed scanners. Aspen-owned film digitizing equipment includes a Mekel scanner with specialized enhancement technology from IPT.<P>

In terms of image storage, Aspen currently has 45 Gb of magnetic media storage on its optical imaging LAN. Aspen either archives the stored images to a 4-mil digital audiotape or "burns" or writes the stored images to WORM disks or CD-ROM's.<P>

<B>Offsite scanning.</B> Aspen also has the capability to scan source documents at field locations nationwide and overseas. Source document images are captured at offsite locations, and the resulting image files are sent to Aspen's image processing facility in Rockville for subsequent processing that includes optical character recognition conversion, editing, and loading of ASCII files to output media.<P>

<B>Digital image printing.</B> The Imaging Center includes a Xerox Docutech, a Ricoh laser printer, and a Hewlett Packard printer. This system, which can be placed on our existing optical imaging LAN, is a combination high-volume laser printer and xerography machine with the capability to accept the originals in paper or electronic form.<P>

<HR>
For more information, contact Bob Look at <a href=mailto:blook@aspensys.com>blook@aspensys.com</a><P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Aspen Systems Corporation<BR>
1600 Research Boulevard<BR>
Rockville, MD 20850<P>

Phone: (301) 251-5000<BR>
<A HREF = "http://www.aspensys.com/">http://www.aspensys.com</A><P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>


